<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WILLIAMS-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' OWNER TELLS AGENT: SHOW ME THE OFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The agent for outfielder Bernie Williams says there
is a lively market for the services of his client, that he has
offers of seven and eight years in hand. George Steinbrenner, the
Yankees' principal owner, does not believe him.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees offered Williams a five-year, $60-million deal
within the last week, a package that the center fielder initially
rebuffed. On Thursday evening, Steinbrenner met with Scott Boras,
Williams' agent, for more than two hours in Cleveland. As he
recalled their conversation Friday, Steinbrenner said he asked
Boras to reveal the specifics of the offers and to tell him which
teams were interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a Boras basher, but I know his game,'' Steinbrenner
said. ``He says he has a lot of bids. But when I say, `What have
you got?' he can't answer me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner was asked if he believes Boras' silence is a result
of a devotion to confidentiality, or if he believes Boras does not
have the offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he can answer because he doesn't have the
offers,'' Steinbrenner said. ``I don't think he has anything really
concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner said the meeting was cordial and friendly, a
meeting that could lead to further discussions before Thanksgiving.
In fact, Steinbrenner has the impression that Boras is ready to
negotiate with alacrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept on saying he had all these offers,'' Steinbrenner
said. ``I said: `Fine, what are they? What are they?' And that's
when that part of the conversation stops.''
</P>
<P>
   A baseball official said that Steinbrenner wanted Boras to tell
him what it would take to re-sign Williams, but that was not the
agent's style of negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boras has declined to identify the teams from which he
has received offers for Williams _ the player has paid a visit to
Arizona to talk to the Diamondbacks and is expected to go to Boston
to talk to the Red Sox _ Jim Bowden, general manager of the
Cincinnati Reds, confirmed Friday that he had offered Williams a
seven-year contract _ for $1 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is true,'' the creative Bowden said when asked about the
offer. And how did Boras react?
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott laughed and said, `You're unbelievable,''' Bowden said.
``I said we're just trying to be competitive. We want our fans to
know we're bidding for some of the best free agents at prices we
can afford, although we don't necessarily like to do it for that
many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said he made a similar offer for another Boras client,
Kevin Brown, for six years. The Reds, of course, are no more likely
to sign Williams or Brown than they are Albert Belle or Brian
Jordan, two other good-hitting outfielders who are free agents.
</P>
<P>
   A major-league executive indicated that the Yankees have placed
an initial bid on Belle; Steinbrenner said he was aware of no such
offer. But Steinbrenner, who may be playing a negotiating game of
his own as he tries to clinch a deal with Williams, said he had
given General Manager Brian Cashman and Manager Joe Torre the
go-ahead to pursue the petulant All-Star if that was the route they
chose to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe really likes him,'' Steinbrenner said of Belle. ``He
really feels like he would fit in. You know, I really get ticked
off when I hear all this stuff about whether he might be a problem.
There was a lot of that kind of talk when we signed Reggie Jackson,
and Reggie came here and fit right in and helped us win a couple of
championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Arn Tellem, Belle's agent, said he did not expect any
developments during the weekend. ``I think we'll have a clearer
idea of what we're going to do next week,'' he said, adding that he
had continued to talk with the Yankees and the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Belle has until Dec. 2 to decide whether he wants to sign with
another team or remain with the White Sox.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Yankees and Darryl Strawberry have a new deadline for their
attempts to continue their relationship. They agreed to yet another
extension of the deadline, from midnight Friday to midnight next
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to work diligently to finalize an agreement which
will fit within the framework of the basic agreement,'' Cashman
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees want to sign Strawberry, who is undergoing treatment
for colon cancer, to a contract. Because they are not certain that
he will be able to play next season, they do not want his salary to
count against their 1999 payroll for luxury-tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman said he spoke Friday with Boras about Williams, Tellem
about Belle, Alan Nero about Randy Johnson and Tony Tanzer about
Steve Finley, a free-agent center fielder. He said he was having
serious conversations with all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jordan, who is being wooed by the Yankees, Mets,
Baltimore and Atlanta, said Friday that he hoped to decide which
team he will sign with by Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one team has an advantage right now,'' he said. ``I'm just
sitting back with my family trying to make the decision. I'm happy
to be in this situation now. You can tell the kids, hard work pays
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who was born and raised in Maryland, spoke at a news
conference at Camden Yards, where message boards flashed, ``Welcome
Home Brian Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   Another significant free agent, pitcher Todd Stottlemyre, has
apparently agreed to a $32-million, four-year contract with the
Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, 33, went 9-9 with a 3.51 ERA in 23 starts for St.
Louis before he was traded to Texas on July 31 along with infielder
Royce Clayton for pitcher Darren Oliver and third baseman Fernando
Tatis. He then went 5-4 with a 4.33 ERA in 10 starts for the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   While Arizona made no announcement, the agreement was confirmed
Thursday by Jerry Colangelo, the Diamondbacks' chief executive
officer. ``We've agreed to agree,'' Colangelo said. ``We have the
formality of getting the contract completed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
