<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLAIBORNE-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THIS CLAIBORNE'S LAST CHAPTER?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chris Claiborne can't help himself, it just sort
of happens when he talks about college football. Ask him a
question, and you tend to get an answer in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   When USC sealed up a bowl bid two weeks ago with a victory over
Stanford, it meant Claiborne would be making his first postseason
appearance since becoming a Trojan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just closes another chapter in my career,'' Claiborne said.
</P>
<P>
   Get the hint? It's become obvious that Claiborne will leave USC
after this season and make himself available for the NFL draft. All
that's left is the press conference, which should come sometime in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of finding reasons to turn pro, Claiborne is getting to
the point where he needs a reason, any reason, to remain at USC for
another season.
</P>
<P>
   This week's selling point involves UCLA. But Chris: You wouldn't
want to turn pro if you lost to UCLA today, would you? Wouldn't it
just make your college career seem unfulfilled without at least one
victory over your cross-town rival?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah,'' Claiborne said. ``You have to take the wins with the
losses. And just have fun. The worst thing you can do is put one
team ahead of another. I'm looking forward to playing Notre Dame as
much.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, scratch that theory.
</P>
<P>
   Today's UCLA game is important to Claiborne. It's just not
getting in the way of his ultimate goal: the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   He's considered no worse than a top 10 pick, a 6-foot-3,
250-pound linebacker who won't need to come out on passing
situations. Someone who can play inside or outside.
</P>
<P>
   His future is something that weighs heavily on his mind. Not
just in five years, but 50 years from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about the future a lot,'' Claiborne said. ``I want to
take care of my kids and my kids' kids. I want my grandkids to say,
`Yeah, we got old money.' It's up to me to establish that.''
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be much of a problem. His national profile has
skyrocketed this season and will continue to rise since being named
one of three finalists for the Butkus Award.
</P>
<P>
   After USC played Florida State, Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden
said, ``(Ohio State linebacker) Andy Katzenmoyer is a great player,
but Chris Claiborne was even more impressive. We had a couple plays
we thought would break out big, but all you saw was No.55 swallow
somebody up.''
</P>
<P>
   There's little on an individual basis left for Claiborne to
accomplish, if he returns to USC for his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one thing missing, it's an elusive victory over the
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an individual, I felt I played really good in those
games,'' Claiborne said. ``We just had some bad breaks and they
took advantage of it. Personally, it hasn't been painful. As an
individual, I felt I played really good.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments may sound slightly detached, but Claiborne has
always been more interested in expressing himself through his play
than with words.
</P>
<P>
   He'd rather try to sack Cade McNown than spend 10 minutes
explaining what it would feel like.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is real easy to get along with,'' said USC linebackers
coach Shawn Slocum. ``He interesting from that standpoint. He's not
real vocal. He just prepares himself and plays with intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne has changed this year, however. He is no longer just a
lead-by-example linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   When USC's offense sputtered in the first half against Oregon,
he went up to an offensive assistant and asked, ``OK, what are you
going to show us in the second half?''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, that might sound like player challenging a
coach, but those within the USC program understand his burning
desire to win, and expect those kind of remarks.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Claiborne has refrained from getting too emotional
talking about UCLA this week. He doesn't just want to beat the
Bruins, he wants to beat every team just as badly.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne's dominance this season was borne during a meeting
with Slocum shortly after he was hired in January.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne, unsure of the new coaching staff, considered
transferring to Colorado or Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first day here, we sat in my office and talked about his
thoughts of going elsewhere,'' Slocum said. ``He was upset with the
coaching change. It was a natural reaction. But once he realized
what would take place and that he was at the best possible place,
he got excited.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also developed a tight relationship with Slocum, who at
33, is young enough for Claiborne to relate to on a personal level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a fun year,'' Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   But as Claiborne admits, it would be a lot nicer with a victory
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a few times I've thought about last year's UCLA game,''
Claiborne said. ``It's going through my mind. I think this will be
a close game. We just can't feel like we're the underdog. If you
think that, why even come out?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
