<HEADER>
A2603 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEUTSCHE-BANK-ACQUIRE     11-21 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-BANK-ACQUIRE-630(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., GERMANY) 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Deutsche Bank A.G., Germany's biggest bank, is on the
verge of signing an agreement to acquire Bankers Trust Corp., the
eighth-largest U.S. bank, for somewhere between $7.5 billion and $8
billion, executives involved in the talks said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Deutsche Bank deal for Bankers Trust, which could be
announced as early as next week, would be the biggest takeover of a
U.S. financial institution by a foreign bank.
</P>
<P>
   The $7.5 billion to $8 billion purchase price would represent
only a small premium to the total value of Bankers Trust's shares
in the stock market. As final details of the planned deal are
negotiated, the price could possibly go higher.
</P>
<P>
   In a year that has already witnessed a flurry of massive global
mergers, including German automobile giant Daimler-Benz's
acquisition of Chrysler Corp. and the merger of U.S. financial
services titans Citicorp and Travelers Group Inc., this deal is yet
another reminder of both the scale and the geographic reach of
these newly hatched transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations have shown an increasing willingness to merge
regardless of the nationalities of the partners involved as
executives around the world take advantage of a less restrictive
trading environment and a growing desire to tap into global
business expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, such large deals are never simple to carry out and the
complexity of managing tens of thousands of employees while making
sound business decisions is a challenge for even the most talented
business executives _ especially when the corporation created by a
megamerger spans the globe.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Deutsche Bank, a commercial banking powerhouse
which has already had a difficult time with other recent forays
into the investment banking world, will face an enormous challenge
in making the acquisition of Bankers Trust a success.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust, having survived a series of financial scandals
that tarnished the vaunted trading house's reputation and hurt its
bottom line in recent years, has been refashioning itself as
investment banker to the nation's _ indeed, the world's _ smaller,
fast-growth companies. It has also carved out a niche underwriting
and trading high-yield debt, or so-called `junk bonds.'
</P>
<P>
   But Bankers Trust has lacked the heft needed to compete with
such vaunted Wall Street competitors as Morgan Stanley, Goldman
Sachs, and Merrill Lynch. Many analysts have believed for some time
that the bank face difficulty going it alone.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is also certain to raise new speculation about
the future of J.P. Morgan and Co., the fourth largest bank in the
country. Like Bankers Trust, J.P. Morgan has worked hard to
transform itself from a commercial bank into an investment bank but
analysts are skeptical that J.P. Morgan has the ability to remain
competitive on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Deutsche Bank, which has openly been seeking an
acquisition in the United States in order to make a breakthrough
into investment banking, had unsuccessfully been courting J.P.
Morgan and was said to be considering Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc.
as another acquisition target.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Bankers Trust will certainly raise Deutsche
Bank's visibility on Wall Street, but it does not immediately grant
it a commanding presence in the investment banking market. Bankers
Trust is not a leader in overall stock and bond underwriting, nor
is it in the top ranks of providing advice on mergers and
acquisitions, both of which provide some of the most lucrative
profits on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that banking consolidation is moving into a higher
level but there aren't that many deep-pocketed buyers out there,''
said Judah Kraushaar, an analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``The other
issue is how good a vehicle Bankers Trust will be for creating an
investment banking presence in the U.S. Anybody buying this
business is going to have to work very hard to make an adequate
return.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that Deutsche will try to recruit a team of U.S.
executives who can bring added talent to Bankers Trust. Wall Street
executives have said that the German giant has made overtures to
James Dimon, the recently departed president of Citigroup, about
joining the company. Dimon has access to a well-regarded network of
dealmakers, some of whom still work for his old employer.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup, the company formed by the merger of Citicorp and
Travelers, has been hurt by disorder in its investment banking
business. It could suffer from a further outflow of much-need
talent if Dimon took command at Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how Deutsche decides to manage Bankers Trust, the
future of its current chief executive, Frank Newman, appears to be
uncertain. Newman said in an interview earlier this year that his
bank was not for sale, but recent trading losses and weak support
from his board of directors may have contributed to his inability
to avoid a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank could not be reached for comment and a Bankers
Trust spokesman declined to comment on the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are proponents of the idea that bigger is not necessarily
better,'' Newman in a recent interview. Newman became the bank's
chief executive nearly three years ago as the company began
recovering from its trading scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, a former official of the U.S. Treasury Department, was
hired to bring regulatory credibility to Bankers Trust and to help
rein in its image as a home for free-wheeling traders who took
outsized risks. But Bankers Trust, which has $156.3 billion in
assets, suffered a $488 million loss in the third quarter due to
trading problems in Russia and in other financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   There may be other losses in store, making the purchase of
Bankers Trust risky. In its most recent filing with the Securities
and Exchange Commission, Bankers Trust acknowledged that its risk
management models essentially broke down during the unanticipated
financial upheavals of the third quarter. J.P. Morgan made a
similar disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers Trust's shares have fallen precipitously recently,
although they rose sharply Friday, , climbing $5.25 or 7.3 percent
to $77.25, amid merger speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche, which has been trying to expand on its staid
foundation as a conservative and somewhat plodding financial
behemoth, recently said its profits for the quarter that ended on
Sept. 30 plunged 83.5 percent, to about $89 million, due to heavy
trading losses in emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Frankfurt-based bank already has been badly burned by an
expensive, but badly flawed, foray into investment banking through
the its Deutsche Morgan Grenfell unit. But Deutsche is still
determined to build a presence on Wall Street because it is worried
that it will be outmaneuvered on its home turf as European
financial markets, in part of monetary union there, shift to stocks
and away from the traditional bank lending that has been Deutsche's
mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   The exact terms of how Deutsche's acquisition of Bankers Trust
will be financed could not be determined, but the financing will be
arranged in Germany. Deutsche owns a large block of Daimler shares
but it is uncertain what the fate of that holding will be in light
of this deal.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs is representing Deutsche Bank in the talks; Morgan
Stanley is advising Bankers Trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
