<HEADLINE>
KINGS TO USE WEEK OFF TO REGROUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Little by little, the pieces of the Los Angeles
Kings' broken puzzle are coming back together, and not a moment too
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Goaltender Jamie Storr, who hasn't played since suffering a
groin strain on Oct. 18, is expected to start in goal tonight when
the Kings play host to the Chicago Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   After tonight, the Kings (5-12-3) don't play again for a week,
but when they do step on the ice again they may be a vastly
different team, which can't be a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Doug Bodger may be back from his broken hand in a
week. Goalie Stephane Fiset should be ready to play after missing
six weeks with two groin strains. And No. 1 center Jozef Stumpel is
expected back from his latest sprained right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Storr's return aside, though, the Kings will have to make do
with what they've got for one more game. The good news for the
Kings is that they'll be facing an opponent struggling just as
badly as they are.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have lost six games in a row and are 1-9-1 in their
past 11. The Blackhawks won their last game, at Nashville, but were
0-8-2 before that.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Storr, the Kings also should have 24-year-old
center Brandon Convery in the lineup tonight. He is expected to
play on one of the top two lines. The Kings claimed Convery on
Thursday after he was waived by the Vancouver Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Legace is scheduled to be Storr's backup, and Ryan Bach
has been assigned to the Long Beach Ice Dogs of the IHL.
</P>
<P>
   Possible suspension: One player the Kings probably won't have
for a while is enforcer Matt Johnson, whose blind-side hit knocked
Jeff Beukeboom semiconscious late in Thursday night's 5-1 loss to
the New York Rangers. Johnson and general manager Dave Taylor will
attend a hearing Monday in New York with NHL vice president Colin
Campbell, at which point Johnson is expected to be hit with a
suspension. He is not available to play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Itinerary: Following tonight's game, the Kings are slated to be
off Sunday and Tuesday, but will practice the other four days
leading up to next Saturday night's game against the Phoenix
Coyotes at the Forum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 0118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
