<DOCNO> NYT19981121.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2624 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      11-21 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY KEEPS ON PLUGGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ When he signed his three-year contract
extension in June, Cortez Kennedy talked about the Seahawks finally
having the talent to be the top team in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   During training camp in August, the Pro Bowl defensive tackle
talked about the Seahawks finally getting to the playoffs for the
first time in his nine-year career.
</P>
<P>
   As the man they call Tez sat in front of his locker this week,
all he could do was shake his head. And that said it all. Another
year. Another wasted opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have lost five of their past seven games to slip to
the outer fringe of the playoff picture. Another loss in Dallas
Sunday against the Cowboys and this season will just about be
repeated history, even with five games left to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rocky right now,'' Kennedy said. ``It's just been a rocky
road.''
</P>
<P>
   As with most of the defensive players, it is difficult to lay
the blame on Kennedy. While his statistics are not impressive (25
tackles and one sack), his effort has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Cortez is playing as well as he has since we've
been here,'' said Greg McMackin, the Seahawks' fourth-year
defensive coordinator. ``He has really shown up in the last four or
five ball games.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Raiders Pro Bowl guard Steve Wisniewski put it after last
week's game, ``Cortez is still Cortez, and that's still pretty damn
good.''
</P>
<P>
   A better indication of Kennedy's contributions to the Seahawks'
big-play defense can be found in the numbers being compiled by
linebackers Chad Brown, Darrin Smith and Dean Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has 7{ sacks among his team-leading 96 tackles and remains
on pace to challenge the club record of 153 tackles by Terry Beeson
in 1978. Smith has 53 tackles, five sacks and has returned two
interceptions for TDs, despite missing 2{ games because of
injuries. Wells is coming off a career-best game against the
Raiders in which he intercepted a pass, forced a fumble and had
seven solo tackles.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those plays started with Kennedy's disruptive push tying
up two blockers to alter what the offense was intending to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cortez is keeping people off of people, and other guys are
benefiting because of his play,'' McMackin said.
</P>
<P>
   Nice words. So why does Kennedy feel so numbingly normal?
Because the norm for him has been playing very well on teams that
don't. Since making Kennedy their first-round draft choice in 1990,
the Seahawks are 58-80. He was named NFL defensive player of the
year in 1992 and Kennedy's string of six straight Pro Bowls ended
last year when he missed the first eight starts of his career with
ankle and knee injuries. But his teams have never been to the
playoffs and have posted only one winning season (9-7 in his rookie
year).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to count us out yet,'' Kennedy said of the
postseason. ``We still can get there. It's not going to be easy,
but I can't give up. I still have to believe we can do this. I want
it too badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse for Kennedy has been the gradual disbanding
of the Rookie Club, the other members of the '90 draft _ linebacker
Terry Wooden, strong safety Robert Blackmon and running back Chris
Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden and Blackmon left in free agency last year, Warren this
year. Wooden is now starting for the 7-3 Raiders. Warren is a
valuable role player for the 7-3 Cowboys. Blackmon is playing for
the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see them doing well, but I miss those guys,''
said Kennedy, who still talks with Warren and Wooden once a week
and Blackmon every other week. ``They weren't only my teammates,
they were my best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   And right now, Wooden and Warren are a lot closer to obtaining
that ultimate goal of reaching the playoffs than Kennedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
