<HEADLINE>
STARS MAKE RIGHT MOVES IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The two major changes Stars coach Ken Hitchcock made to
his lineup Friday night ended up being the two players who most
affected the game.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Sergey Gusev scored his first NHL points, registering
a goal and an assist, in his first game of the season. And
defenseman Darryl Sydor had a goal and assist while playing forward
full time for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   That combination helped the Stars to a 4-2 win over the New York
Islanders and kept the Stars atop the Western Conference with a
10-3-2 record. It was the third consecutive victory for the Stars
and also improved their NHL-best home record to 7-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good hockey game for us the first game back \Rafter a
five-day layoff\S,'' Hitchcock said. ``It was a good balanced
effort from everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to two points apiece from Gusev and Sydor, there
were more good signs: Brett Hull added two pretty assists to push
his team-leading point total to 15; Pat Verbeek broke a seven-game
goal drought; the Stars' power play went 2-for-6 and the defensive
pair of Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk combined for 13 hits
and six blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Gusev, however, was clearly a standout. After scoring seven
points during the preseason, the 22-year-old rookie has been forced
to sit through 14 games, waiting for a chance to play. He was
shuffled into the lineup last night because Jere Lehtinen is out
with a broken thumb. Hitchcock moved Sydor from defense to the left
wing on a line with Mike Modano and Hull and inserted Gusev as
Sergei Zubov's defensive partner.
</P>
<P>
   Gusev said he has been waiting for a chance to impress someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of hard,'' Gusev said. ``I really wanted to play
great today and try to have my best game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gusev, who was playing his 10th NHL game after getting into nine
games last season, said he wasn't nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zubie helped me a lot with that,'' Gusev said.
</P>
</TEXT>
