<HEADLINE>
UNLIKELY QUARTERBACKS' TALES UNFOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two quarterbacks playing in games today on opposite ends of the
country could have a major impact on this year's national
championship race. And neither player expected to be in that
position.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State sophomore Marcus Outzen will lead the Seminoles'
offense against in-state rival Florida. Southern California
freshman Carson Palmer will be running the Trojans' offense when
they play cross-town rival UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   ``If \RFlorida thinks\S they're just going to show up and be
able to win the game, that's not going to happen,'' Outzen said.
``Actually, I hope they do think that. We've got all the tools. The
only thing different is me, and I feel I can get the ball to the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Outzen, who is nicknamed Rooster, made his first start last week
against Wake Forest. It was a victory, but unimpressive. Outzen was
11-of-19 for 184 yards as the Seminoles had a season-low 347 yards
of total offense.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State has won 10 of 11 games thanks to a big-play
offense that has produced 35 plays of 25 or more yards. Coach Bobby
Bowden was downbeat this week. Before Outzen replaced the injured
Chris Weinke, Florida State's offense was starting to become
dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked so futile on offense,'' Bowden said. ``With the
biggest game of the year coming up, we really have got to go back
to square one offensively and get some things done.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Florida-Florida State game is still in the
running for the national championship. While USC is headed to a
bowl game, its main focus will be ruining the Bruins' national
championship hopes. To do that, the Trojans will need a solid game
from their 18-year-old quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at this time, Palmer was leading Santa Margarita High
School to the Southern Section (Calif.) Division V football
championship game. He is approaching today's game with Gen-X
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been getting nervous at all lately,'' said Palmer,
who has won both his games as a starter. ``You can't approach it
any differently, whether you're playing the worst team in the
league or the best team in the nation. You have to focus the same
way, look at the game the same way, practice the same way and play
the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett has been impressed with Palmer's mature
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is he has a calmness,'' Hackett said.
``He is a very composed, very poised 18-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are valuable attributes when faced with playing the
high-profile position in a big game.  &LR; tagtop:Wendell Barnhouse,
(817) 390-7238
Bowl talk The Aloha would like to match Colorado as an at-large
team against a Pacific-10 Conference team, perhaps USC. Aloha
officials want to make that deal soon. Colorado wants to wait until
after next Saturday's game against Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The Gator would like a Georgia Tech-Notre Dame contest (The Gold
Helmet Bowl?). For that to happen, Georgia Tech must beat Wake
Forest to tie for first place in the Atlantic Coast Conference and
Notre Dame must lose either to LSU today or to USC next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Tulane, if it finishes 11-0, could wind up with an at-large
berth in the Bowl Championship Series. The Orange Bowl would love a
Tulane-Florida State game (Bobby Bowden vs. his son Tommy, the
Green Wave coach).
</P>
<P>
   The Western Athletic Conference champion, currently homeless,
could find a bowl haven in the Liberty. If that happens, Wyoming
could wind up in the Las Vegas Bowl and BYU could play in the Oahu
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten is guaranteed six bowl slots. Five teams have
qualified for the postseason. The only other team with a chance to
do so is Michigan State, which must beat Illinois and Penn State to
become eligible for a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In the Pacific-10 Conference, California, Washington and Arizona
State all are 5-5 and need to win their final game to become bowl
eligible. If UCLA winds up in the Fiesta Bowl, Arizona will hope
for a Rose Bowl bid. The Sun Bowl is leaning toward Oregon, the
Oahu Bowl would like Washington and the Las Vegas would like Cal.
</P>
<P>
   The Micron PC Bowl, formerly the Carquest, is interested in
Central Florida. The Micron PC has tie-ins with the ACC and the Big
Ten. If the Big Ten doesn't have enough bowl-eligible teams, the
bowl could invite Central Florida.
Fry plays it coy The coaching carousel has started spinning. There
are openings at Auburn, Nevada-Las Vegas, Southwestern Louisiana
and Clemson. And there will be more.
</P>
<P>
   There continues to be speculation that one of those coaching
openings will be at Iowa. The Hawkeyes are 3-7 and since the team's
last Rose Bowl trip in 1990, Iowa is 53-38-2.
</P>
<P>
   But Hayden Fry, the man who led the renaissance of the Iowa
program, is noncommittal about his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a real long year,'' said Fry, who turns 70 in
February. ``I would imagine that somewhere down along the way I'll
have to make a decision. I've said I'd like to coach until I'm 70,
but \RPenn State's Joe\S Paterno and LaVell Edwards \Rof Brigham
Young\S are going to outlive me.''
Davie looks ahead Notre Dame is 8-1 with games against LSU (today
in South Bend) and at Southern California next Saturday. If Notre
Dame goes 10-1, it likely will wind up with a berth in the Bowl
Championship Series and $12 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   However, second-year coach Bob Davie is not declaring his
program ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a long way to go before we start talking about
preseason rankings and the national championship hunt,'' he said.
``I see this program _ and I may upset some people _ I see it two
years down the road, three years down the road, before this program
is built back up with a strong foundation. We're still a building
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame should return 31 of its top 44 players next season,
including quarterback Jarious Jackson. If the Irish finish 10-1
this season, they're likely to be a top-five team next season.
Briefly Arkansas defensive coordinator Keith Burns on Tennessee
running back Travis Henry: ``I don't know what he weighs. But if
he's 220, 200 of it's from the waist down.''
</P>
<P>
   Interceptions were in the air last week in the Atlantic Coast
Conference. Duke quarterback Bobby Campbell set an ACC record by
throwing seven interceptions against Maryland. Florida State
cornerback Mario Edwards set a league record with four
interceptions against Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The seat occupied by Kim Helton is pretty toasty. The University
of Houston football coach is 17-48-1 in six seasons. Helton has
three years remaining on a contract worth $900,000. The school
probably doesn't have the money to buy out the contract. Athletic
director Chet Gladchuck said there is a ``high level of
disappointment and anxiety'' about the football program.
</P>
<P>
   After Indiana plays Purdue today, Hoosiers quarterback Antwaan
Randle El will depart Sunday for Maui. Vacation? Hardly. He'll be
on his way to join Indiana's basketball team in the Maui Classic.
Randle El won't be playing, but he wants to join the team so he can
speed his transition from football to hoops.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State linebacker Jerry Rudzinski on the annual meeting with
rival Michigan: ``Someone asked me a couple of weeks ago, `Do you
think about Michigan all season?' I told him, `No, I think about
Michigan 365 days a year. I've been thinking about Ohio
State-Michigan since grade school.' ''
Bowl projections The likely matchups for the Bowl Championship
Series and the Cotton Bowl. The top two teams in the BCS rankings
will play in the national championship game in the Fiesta Bowl. The
other BCS bowls will be the Rose, Sugar and Orange. Champions of
the Big 12, Big Ten, Big East, Atlantic Coast, Southeastern and
Pacific-10 conferences are assured berths in BCS bowls. Two other
at-large teams will be selected. Fiesta, Jan. 4 Tennessee vs.
Kansas State Sugar, Jan. 1 Florida State vs. Notre Dame Rose, Jan.
1 UCLA vs. Michigan Orange, Jan. 1 Florida vs. Syracuse Cotton,
Jan. 1) Nebraska vs. Arkansas
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
