<HEADLINE>
OILERS BEAT DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ For five years the Edmonton Oilers provided
the Anaheim Mighty Ducks with an easy target. The Ducks beat the
Oilers 16 times in 26 games, including three overtime victories.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, however, the Oilers got some payback as Andrei
Kovalenko scored 39 seconds into overtime to beat Anaheim 3-2
before 16,367 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   The victory snapped the Ducks' three-game winning streak and
overshadowed a brilliant effort from Paul Kariya, who scored his
10th goal of the season and set up Antti Aalto's first NHL goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had rallied twice to tie, but Kovalenko caught two
Ducks in the corner, cut to the net and easily beat Guy Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya had tied the game and moved into second in the NHL
scoring race with 24 points when he took a centering pass from
Marty McInnis in the slot and ripped a shot past Mikhail Shtalenkov
with 6:11 left in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever momentum the Ducks had going into the dressing room
after tying the game late in the first period didn't last long.
They took three consecutive penalties and the Oilers took a 2-1
lead early in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Haller was already in the penalty box for closing his hand
on the puck when McInnis pulled down Roman Hamrlik in the Edmonton
zone. The Ducks killed off 77 seconds of the two-man advantage, but
with one second left Kovalenko deflected Hamrlik's point shot past
Hebert at 5:48.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim then was forced to kill off the final 43 seconds of
McInnis' penalty and two more minutes when Haller was called for
high-sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the period, Jason Marshall gave the Oilers yet another
chance when he cross-checked Kovalenko, but Edmonton was unable to
take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The penalties left the Ducks little time to generate shots, let
alone good scoring chances against Shtalenkov. Anaheim managed only
one shot in the first 10 minutes and its only decent scoring chance
came in the final minute on a backhander by Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   With Oilers ahead 1-0 on the strength of Pat Fallon's goal at
3:37 of the first period, the unlikely combination of Kariya, Johan
Davidsson and Antti Aalto got the Ducks even at 14:07.
</P>
<P>
   After the Oilers had bottled up the Anaheim power play unit for
almost the entire two minutes, Davidsson chipped the puck along the
boards to Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks captain turned on the speed, raced up the left side
and lifted a perfect pass over the stick of defenseman Frank Musil.
Aalto simply tipped it home for his first NHL goal.
</P>
<P>
   While the goal was historic for the 23-year old Aalto, Kariya,
at the ripe old age of 24 and playing in just his 238th NHL game,
notched his 300th career point with the assist.
</P>
<P>
   The power play goal was the Ducks' 10th in the last nine games,
after scoring only four in the first nine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 0157EST &QL; 
