<HEADLINE>
SANDERS' STATUS STILL UP IN THE AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When Deion Sanders was tackled on the 1-yard
line after picking off a Jake Plummer pass last week, not only did
Sanders fall one yard short of scoring, he was inches short of
tying an NFL record.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has eight interception returns for touchdowns. The
record is nine, set by Kenny Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders was hobbled by a sprained left big toe. He missed
practice again yesterday, but has said he expects to play this week
against Seattle. Coach Chan Gailey said he won't know about
Sanders' status for the game until right before Sunday's noon
kickoff against the Seattle Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Said Sanders about falling just short in Arizona: ``I knew it
was something wrong with me when I couldn't take that one to the
house.'' Injury update Center Clay Shiver practiced yesterday for
the first time since spraining his big toe two weeks ago against
the Giants. But reserve Mike Kiselak will make his second
consecutive start on Sunday against the Seattle Seahawks, Gailey
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's going to start _ he's taken all the reps in practice
this week,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Everett McIver also practiced again yesterday without pain in
his knee, and all indications are that he will start in place of
rookie Flozell Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be back in there,'' McIver said. ``Now I've got
to get behind the wheel and play. Football is football. I'm not
going to do anything differently than what I was doing before I got
hurt.'' Tough test Cowboys left tackle Larry Allen has not allowed
a sack this year. Tomorrow, he'll be matched primarily against
Seahawks right defensive end Phillip Daniels, who has four sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has already nullified Arizona's Simeon Rice,
Philadelphia's Hugh Douglas, and Carolina's Sean Gilbert in a
manner that amazes quarterback Troy Aikman, who doesn't get to
really appreciate Allen's talent until he watches the game film the
day after games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He dominates his position more so than any other player at
their position,'' Aikman said. ``In this league, you just don't see
people taken off the \Rvideo\S screen. If you get a guy moving back
a bit, then you've done your job as an offensive lineman. But when
you get a guy who's not even showing up on the video screen, that's
unthinkable.'' Welcome back Jimmy The league has released its
formula for scheduling games next year. The Cowboys play the AFC
East, and have home games against the Jets and Dolphins, which will
mark Jimmy Johnson's return to Texas Stadium as a coach. The
Cowboys travel to Indianapolis and New England.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys go on to win the division this season, they would
host the NFC West division winner, and the NFC Central second-place
finisher. They would travel to play the NFC Central champion, and
the NFC West third place finisher.
</P>
<P>
   If the season ended today, they would host Atlanta and Green
Bay, and travel to Minnesota and New Orleans.
</P>
</TEXT>
