<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCHIONE'S BLUEPRINT HAS TURNED FROGS AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twelve months ago, as the ultra-top-secret,
undercover-covert-if-we-tell-you-we'll-have-to-kill-you search for
a new TCU football coach was taking place, the future was dark.
</P>
<P>
   Darker than dark, actually.
</P>
<P>
   When you're 1-and-10, and half your league has just deserted
you, and you don't know if the next big Division I shuffle will
find you playing Northwestern or Nicholls State, that's dark.
</P>
<P>
   We can now say with reasonable affirmation, however, that rumors
of TCU's football demise were only that _ just rumors. The football
Frogs will go for a winning record today in Las Vegas. And if that
isn't one of the most stupefying sports stories of 1998, you
haven't been paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids have been amazing,'' head coach Dennis Franchione
said, before his team flew off to end its season against UNLV. ``My
coaching staff and the players have done a wonderful job.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've stayed together. They've looked forward. They have
remained positive. And they never really quit believing that they
were going to accomplish some things.''
</P>
<P>
   Astoundingly, but for the spank of an errant bounce or a
final-quarter breakdown, TCU would go into today's game nursing
bowl hopes. You can add it up.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the Frogs' five losses were by the margin of a touchdown
or less. They could well be 8-2 ... or 2-8.
</P>
<P>
   If the season has taught TCU fans anything, it is that coaching
does make all the difference in the world. Franchione's credentials
were auspicious, but he proved to be even better than advertised.
</P>
<P>
   His players seem to respect him. They play hard for him. TCU
football is family again, even as so many old faces depart the
athletic department.
</P>
<P>
   The intriguing thing is that Franchione has poured a new
foundation even without a solid quarterback. Patrick Batteaux,
converted from receiver, has had his moments, but failed to be the
all-around threat that the coaches hoped he would be.
</P>
<P>
   The turnovers that Batteaux avoided in the first half of the
season have lately shadowed him, prompting him to lose confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The end result is that Batteaux could well end up back at wide
receiver next season _ he caught 27 passes in 1997 _ and the
starting quarterback job could be up for grabs among transfer Matt
Schobel, redshirt freshman Sean Stilley of Lake Highlands and
highly touted likely-incoming freshman Casey Printers of DeSoto.
</P>
<P>
   Printers is so good, his weekly journal has been one of the ones
featured on an Internet web site titled Texas 100, devoted to
statewide recruiting. A recent entry noted, ``My commitment to TCU
is real strong. I'm just trying to get other players to come as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   If neither Schobel nor Stilley seize the No. 1 spot next year,
it's not that much of a stretch to imagine Franchione turning over
the job to the teenager Printers. If he didn't, the new staff would
face going into its third season, the 2000 season, still without
its quarterback in place.
</P>
<P>
   For Franchione's spread-option system, the quarterback is
everything. At New Mexico, the system helped turn Stoney Case and
Graham Lee into Western Athletic Conference offensive players of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   TCU will lose 16 seniors, but a sound understructure appears to
be in place. Four freshman offensive linemen, all weighing 300
pounds, were redshirted and are expected to return in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Running back LaDanian Tomlinson, who had an outstanding season,
will be only a junior. But he will be pushed by nearly forgotten
Charles Jones and by LaTarence Dunbar of South Oak Cliff, one of
the redshirted freshmen, who may be the best of them all.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione redshirted 20 players, 15 of them freshmen, avoiding
the former regime's habit of rushing first-year players into
action. Three junior-college transfers that the staff recruited
were also redshirted.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many new head coaches who feel a mandate to hit the
ground winning, Franchione had the self-confidence to be patient.
The redshirts will give the 1999 Frogs rare depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' Franchione said, ``that's how you build a program.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year's still-unannounced schedule begins in daunting
fashion _ Arizona at Amon Carter Stadium, followed by a road game
at Northwestern. But it is also not a stretch to imagine TCU _ the
eternal Underfrogs _ being voted as the preseason favorite to win
the trimmed-down 1999 WAC.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what the weather holds for TCU today in Las Vegas,
it won't be dark.
</P>
<P>
   (Gil LeBreton is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
