<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-LAND (Qabatiya, West Bank) _ The Israelis yielded some
land and prisoners as the new peace deal got under way. By Deborah
Sontag. (With photo and map.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ In the latest twist in the dispute
between the United Nations and Iraq over prohibited arms, Iraq
balked at handing over documents on chemical and biological weapons
and missile systems. U.S. and British officials have warned that
air strikes remain an immediate option if Iraq does not honor its
pledge to renew cooperation with inspectors. By Barbara Crossette.
(With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   MOTHER-TERESA (Calcutta, India) _ In the year since the death of
Mother Teresa, her successor, Sister Nirmala, has gladly cast
herself in the inimitable, stooped shadow of the woman who began
the Roman Catholic order almost half a century ago to succor the
poorest of the poor. By Celia W. Dugger. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASIA (Tokyo) _ President Clinton and Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi of Japan ended two days of talk and ceremony here
Friday night with an affirmation of their national partnership but
no evidence of progress on trade and other economic disputes that
are festering between their countries.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-UNREST (Jakarta) _ Despite the military's insistence
that soldiers had been issued only blanks and rubber bullets before
the shooting deaths of 16 students last Friday, reports have
emerged that metal bullet fragments had been found in some victims'
bodies. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN-TERROR (Washington) _ Afghanistan's Taliban rulers
said Osama bin Laden is innocent of all terrorist charges and will
remain a welcome guest in Afghanistan. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-TURKEY (Rome) _ An Italian court of appeals on Friday
rejected Turkey's request for the extradition of a Kurdish rebel
leader, deepening tensions between Italy and Turkey. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Dublin) _ The Irish prime minister and a top
Northern Ireland leader announced significant progress on the
creation of a new North-South council. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-STATES (Undated) _ The largest legal and financial
threat to the tobacco industry ended Friday when 46 states accepted
a $206 billion plan to settle state lawsuits filed against
cigarette makers to recover Medicaid money spent treating diseases
related to smoking. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHOOLS-SPECIALED (New York) _ The U.S. Education
Department's Office of Civil Rights has challenged N.Y. Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew to show evidence that thousands of black and
Hispanic students are being properly placed in special education
programs, saying that a federal analysis shows evidence of
discrimination that Crew has failed to report or investigate. by
Anemona Hartocollis.
</P>
<P>
   TOM-WOLFE-ATLANTA (Atlanta) _ Tom Wolfe made a three-day
publicity tour of the city that he used as the setting for his
latest novel, about the feeble condition of American morality at
the turn of the millennium. Despite the reviews characterizing
Wolfe as a modern-day Sherman, Atlantans turned his visit into a
citywide sensation that the amused author himself likened to the
Beatles' first trip to America. By Kevin Sack. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CELL-ETHICS (Undated) _ The Ethics Advisory Council
responded to President Clinton's letter to them regarding his
concerns over the cow egg and human cell project. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SHEPARD-MURDER _ More details emerge on the murder in Wyoming of
Matthew Shepard, the college student thought to be the victim of
anti-gay violence. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STARR (Washington) _ Sam Dash, Kenneth Starr's ethics
adviser, quit in protest of Starr's appearance before the Judiciary
Committee, saying his testimony as an ``aggressive advocate'' for
the proposition that Clinton committed impeachable offenses
violated obligations of the independent counsel statute. By Don Van
Natta.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: Democrats were
arguing that Clinton had been ``exonerated'' on non-Monica Lewinsky
issues: Whitewater, travel office, FBI files. But did Starr really
clear him, or just find that he couldn't make a case he stills
believes is there? By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ Republicans on the House Judiciary
Committee sent subpoenas Friday to four witnesses in the expanding
impeachment inquiry, setting up possible new conflicts with lawyers
over privilege claims even as panel members planned a firmer
timetable that could result in a full House vote on impeachment by
mid-December. By Eric Schmitt. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-SMUGGLING (Washington) _ Federal agents have cracked an
international ring that made hundreds of millions of dollars
smuggling thousands of Indians and other Asians into the United
States over the last three years, the government announced Friday.
By David E. Rosenbaum. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE-BANK-ACQUIRE (New York) _ Deutsche Bank A.G., Germany's
biggest bank, is on the verge of signing an agreement to acquire
Bankers Trust Corp., the eighth-largest U.S. bank, for somewhere
between $7.5 billion and $8 billion, executives involved in the
talks said Friday. By Timothy L. O'Brien and Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   FEDEX-PILOTS (Undated) _ Leaders of the pilots union at Federal
Express crumbled under intense pressure from the company on Friday
and withdrew their threat to strike during the peak holiday season.
By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST-CONTINENTAL (Undated) _ Northwest Airlines acquired a
controlling stake in the rival Continental Airlines for $430
million in cash and stock Friday, despite a lawsuit by the Justice
Department that says the deal violates federal antitrust laws. By
Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   EMERGING-MARKETS (Undated) _ The door to the global bond market
has opened a crack, and Argentina and some Latin American companies
are starting to slip through. Their success in borrowing money in
the last few weeks is a sign that the financial crisis that seemed
so severe in emerging markets and elsewhere just two months ago is
easing. By Jonathan Fuerbringer. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Undated) _ After a yearlong antitrust
investigation, Japan's Fair Trade Commission told Microsoft Corp.
on Friday to change permanently one of its marketing practices, and
pointedly warned the company to watch its step in the Internet
browser market. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Japanese banks, having reported meager
half-year earnings, are beginning to request money from the
government's $500 billion bailout fund to boost their weak capital
bases. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA-EARNINGS (Tokyo) _ Toyota Motor, Japan's biggest auto
maker, said group earnings slumped 20 percent in the fiscal first
half as shrinking sales in Japan offset strong demand in the United
States and Europe. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Its love affair with Monica at long last
over, TV has turned nasty. Only 15 minutes into Kenneth Starr's
two-hour-plus monologue the NBC affiliate in New York pulled the
plug and switched to Sally Jessy Raphael. The same happened on
other channels, in other cities, including Washington itself. By
Frank Rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on
lingering bad feelings from the Hampton University coach arrests in
Texas. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBA-LABOR (New York) _ Another negotiating session between
the NBA and its players. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM (Hartford, Conn.) _ Folo on the announced
move from Foxboro to Hartford. by Nick Ravo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DUKE-ENGLISH (Durham, N.C.) _ Once the hottest English
Department around, Duke University's has fallen on hard times: it's
now in a sort of receivership, professors are leaving in droves,
and it's plagued by vicious backbiting and petty squabbles. By
Janny Scott. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   GILMAN-STEREOTYPES (Undated) _ A profile of the scholar Sander
Gilman, an expert on stereotypes who has written 58 books on a
variety of topics. By Dinitia Smith. (With photo.)
</P>
