<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_SHARKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES MAINTAIN UNBEATEN STREAK  
 DRAKE'S GOAL SINKS SHARKS IN OT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ There was a lot of streaking going on Friday night at
San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't just a frantic Curt Keilback, the Coyotes' veteran
radio voice, who got lost in the upper bowels of the stadium and
was late for the opening moments of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes kept streaking, too. They kept four streaks alive by
outracing San Jose, 2-1, in overtime. The most important: their
league-leading unbeaten streak, which has climbed to 10 (8-0-2).
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Dallas Drake scored the game winner, taking assists
from Tkachuk and Jeremy Roenick and beating backup goalie Steve
Shields with a top-shelf shot on an odd-man rush 37 seconds into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Keith and J.R. did a super job getting the puck to me in
that situation,'' Drake said. ``They both showed a hell of a lot of
patience, and when it got to me, I knew I was going to shoot high
because he's a butterfly goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say? The streak's alive. But I think the difference
was (goalie) Nikolai Khabibulin. He just played fantastic for us
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Coyotes' first victory in their past 20 overtime
games, which cover a span of two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' winning streak is at four. Captain Keith Tkachuk's
point-scoring streak, the longest in the NHL, is at 10. And their
streak of allowing only two goals or fewer is at 13, which sets an
NHL post-expansion record.
</P>
<P>
   Not since there were only six teams in the league has a club
managed such a viselike defensive grip on opponents. The 1958-59
Montreal Canadiens did it 18 times. The NHL began its first wave of
expansion eight years later.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes (10-2-2) stayed even with Dallas in the race for
first place in the Pacific Division, and they were racing in front
of their own net during the final few minutes of regulation and
overtime. They played stellar defense reminiscent of their work on
the penalty kill, which also did the job.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix thwarted four San Jose power plays, running that streak
to a perfect 21 for 21 in its past five games.
</P>
<P>
   Khabibulin, back in the lineup after a four-game hiatus, seemed
relaxed and looked sharp in turning back 20 of 21 shots after
regulation. He didn't show any rust or any glitches with his right
stick hand, which was badly bruised a week ago in practice.
</P>
<P>
   He made a huge save on a Bernie Nicholls shot in the final
minute of the third period that saved the day.
</P>
<P>
   But San Jose center Marco Sturm foiled him midway through the
first period while the Coyotes were on their first power play.
Defenseman Mike Rathje, clearing out the puck from behind the
Sharks' net, made a long pass out to Sturm at the blue line, and he
raced in and fired one past Khabibulin at the 12:45 mark for a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk tied it 11 seconds after Stephane Matteau went to the
penalty box for hooking Rick Tocchet. Tkachuk stick-handled a
rebound in front of the net and with Shields down, he wristed an
easy shot into the back of the net at 14:49.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks and their fans probably knew it was coming. Tkachuk
is a virtual Shark killer. Better even than actor Roy Schieder in
the movies. It was the Phoenix left wing's 23 goal and 43rd point
in 30 career games against the Sharks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
