<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA_GREER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART OF UA DEFENSE LEARNS FROM ADVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Handicapped kids surrounded him as he sat near a corner
of Arizona's practice field with a slightly sprained ankle wrapped
in ice. They held onto his shoe as though it provided life support.
They warily eyed anybody who approached as though they were there
to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Greer smiled. He felt grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, sometimes we wake up, look around and see how easy
we have it,'' Greer said. ``Look at these kids. They know what it
is to work. They have to work and work for any little thing they
get. It's a privilege for me to be with them. From them, I learn.''
</P>
<P>
   From them, and from everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Greer's four-plus years as an Arizona defensive lineman have
been nothing if not a learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons have not always been easy. One was about as
difficult as any could be. In 1996, Greer was caught in the middle
of a maelstrom that turned a rivalry ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the cameras and football, Greer was hit in the back by
Arizona State's Glen Gable. The incident during a 56-14 ASU victory
at Arizona Stadium resulted in a brawl, player ejections, angry
comments, editorial-page commentary and an exchange of letters
between Arizona Coach Dick Tomey and ASU's Bruce Synder.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has had an important impact on the ASU-Arizona
series as it returns to Tucson next Friday for the first time since
then. The coaches say they are taking a measured approach to the
volatile emotions that often precede kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the effort and intensity without the hate,'' Tomey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey never has to look further than Greer to know what can
happen.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Cochise in August, Tomey once lectured the media for not
giving Greer credit for growing beyond that angry moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all that garbage, look at what he has done,'' Tomey
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, not even Tomey could have imagined how important
Greer would become. He has emerged as the centerpiece of a
defensive line on a team that is only one win away from Arizona's
first 11-victory season ever. It's a defensive line that was so
unknown in August that it was predicted to be a major weakness. But
it has emerged to be the biggest surprise in a surprising season.
Greer's leadership has been a key, Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to separate the steady, evident maturity of
today's Greer, 22, from the one who was blindsided a couple of
years ago. But Greer chalks it up as just another experience, a
battle in the education of a warrior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just football,'' said the 6-foot-2, 265-pound lineman,
who suffered a serious ankle injury as a result of Gable's hit. ``I
learned from it, but I've learned from a lot things. If you play
football, you accept that those kind of things can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Greer says, he doesn't have time to wallow in the
past. His wife wouldn't let him. Greer, a native of Salinas,
Calif., married his high school sweetheart, Candace, before the
1996 ASU game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candace helps me out a lot mentally,'' said Greer, who has a
degree in political science and is studying for a master's. ``She
has been with me through the trenches.''
</P>
<P>
   Candace, a student in veterinary medicine, also has thrown some
verbal shots to get her husband moving when he appears to be mired
in those trenches. Greer has often heard the verbal lash from
Wildcats defensive coordinator Rich Ellerson. But next to Coach
Candace, Ellerson is the big easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a tougher critic than the coaches,'' said Greer, who
leads the Wildcats with eight sacks. ``She always tells me when I'm
not running fast enough or working hard enough.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that Greer won't accept any congratulations on
Arizona's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' he said. ``We lost to UCLA. But the
important thing is that we've been applying lessons from that one
ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, a horn blew. It was time for the Wildcats to meet
at midfield. He got his shoe and promised another one to the kid
who had been hugging it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be back with one, and I'll help you put it on,'' Greer
said as he left one lesson and headed for another. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
