<HEADLINE>
COME ON, THROW THE FLAG  
 KEY PLAYS HEIGHTEN SCRUTINY OF OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was fourth and 8 with only 2:40 remaining in the game.
</P>
<P>
   No. 11-ranked Nebraska had possession at its own 32-yard line,
driving for what the Huskers hoped could be a game-winning
touchdown last Saturday in Manhattan, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   But quarterback Eric Crouch was sacked for a 12-yard loss by
Kansas State linebacker Travis Ochs. Television replays and photos
clearly showed that Ochs yanked down Crouch by the face mask.
</P>
<P>
   Oops.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no whistle and no penalty, and No. 2 Kansas State
held on to win.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   In other college and NFL games, notably in the waning seconds of
the Cardinals-Cowboys game Sunday, hankies are being left in
officials' back pockets. Controversial calls are dotting this
football season like chickenpox on a child.
</P>
<P>
   Is college and NFL officiating at its worst? Do the best teams
receive the best calls?
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday in Knoxville, Tenn., top-ranked Tennessee was on
the verge of being upset by Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   With Arkansas leading, 24-22, with less than two minutes to go,
quarterback Clint Stoerner faked a handoff and rolled left, where
he stumbled and fell. Stoerner's right hand, with the ball in it,
reached the ground first, causing the ball to squirt free.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee recovered and later scored the winning touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Did the referees err? Should they have ruled Stoerner down,
saying the ground cannot cause a fumble?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' SEC supervisor of officials Bobby Gaston said. ``The
college rule is for the ball to be ruled dead, some part of the
body other than the foot or the hand must touch the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are (missed calls) in every game at every level. But
this wasn't one of them. And we haven't missed anything that's
affected the outcome of a game this season. But it's not unusual
for us to sit an official down if there are several instances of
poor judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there such an instance in Sunday's controversial finish at
Sun Devil Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   To angry Cardinals fans, it appeared that quarterback Jake
Plummer's short incomplete pass to wide receiver Rob Moore in the
end zone on the final play of the game should have been ruled pass
interference against Dallas cornerback Kevin Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Fox television announcer John Madden and studio commentator
Terry Bradshaw agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was no flag, and the Cardinals lost, 35-28.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Seeman, the NFL's senior director of officiating, would
not directly address the play. Seeman, however, talked about other
topics, including what happens to referees who fail to measure up
to NFL standards and the so-called ``best team, best call'' myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, when you're working a football game, you don't
even think of who's playing,'' Seeman said. ``You better think
about your job and making the correct judgment call, because if you
miss one, you'll be downgraded in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We constantly analyze and evaluate all the officials. It's
very competitive out there, and if someone does not perform or
shows no improvement, they're not asked back in the subsequent
year.''
</P>
<P>
   And that has happened quite often under Seeman over the past
eight years. Since retiring as a referee eight years ago, Seeman
has hired 64 officials for a staff of 112.
</P>
<P>
   Seeman said that before officials are promoted to the NFL, they
must serve a three-year stint in NFL Europe. To get to Europe,
officials must receive passing marks from Seeman's staff of 50
college scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scout 150 to 175 of the top college officials every year in
the country,'' Seeman said. ``Every year we take about the top 30
and send them to Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The very best make it to the NFL, where they are required to
partake in weekly four-hour training sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put together a training tape every week of about 45 to 50
plays that every (seven-man) crew must study,'' Seeman said. ``My
staff here (in New York) will spend six hours on a game going over
every play, and there are about 155 in every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll critique every official's previous week's game. And we
rate all of them. At the end of the year, the top-rated people get
postseason assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the scrutiny, why are seemingly obvious mistakes still
made?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about 155 plays a game and a tight judgment call
going one way or another . . . people have to understand how
quickly things happen on the football field,'' Seeman said. ``You
don't have any idea until you're down there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, there's a (questionable call) or two here or there,
but you're talking about a lot of games. Nothing's perfect. It's
not a perfect game. But the number of errors this season has been
extremely rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaston admitted Wednesday that the Tennessee-Arkansas
officiating crew made a mistake by awarding a safety to Tennessee
when the Vols should have had the option of taking the ball deep in
Arkansas territory.
</P>
<P>
   The play in question occurred with about three minutes left and
Arkansas leading, 24-20. The center snap sailed over the punter,
who turned and chased the ball down. But while the ball was still
rolling inside the Arkansas 10-yard line, he kicked it out of his
own end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this for 42 years, and I've never seen that
play before,'' Gaston said. ``I'm not trying to defend the
officials. We're paid to know it, we're supposed to know it, and we
just didn't come up with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Tim Millis, Big 12 supervisor of football
officials, to clarify the non-call against Kansas State were
unsuccessful. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
