<HEADLINE>
5-YEAR-OLD POKER FINAL: QUALITY TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trouble with all-sports networks is that they have 24 hours
to fill. You don't normally find college basketball games or NASCAR
races scheduled for the middle of a weekday afternoon, and you can
only broadcast so many exercise shows, no matter how many buff
bodies you squeeze into tight-fitting Lycra outfits.
</P>
<P>
   Which must be the explanation for how I wound up watching the
World Series of Poker on ESPN2 last week. The ``1993'' World Series
of Poker. (In case you somehow got confused and thought this was a
live broadcast, the interview with Telly Savalas _ noted dead
person _ set you straight.)
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the World Series of Cockfighting, immortalized on
``The Simpsons,'' but it was in the same general neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in its way, it was . . . fascinating, the same grisly way
watching Up With People sing a rock and roll song can be. And the
parallels between this and ``normal'' sports broadcasts were . . .
Wait, I'm getting ahead of myself.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament took place at Binion's Horseshoe, which you
couldn't miss; the beginning of the broadcast included a country
Binion's song playing as various Las Vegas scenes were shown. A bad
song, yes, but nothing worse than what Hank Jr. warbles before
``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   You know you're in for top-quality sports programming when your
host is Dick Van Patten. He spoke in a golf analyst's whisper as a
camera panned across the various tables set up for the tournament.
We would be watching the ``premiere event'' of the World Series,
the $10,000 no-limit Texas hold 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Albrecht, the tournament director, was introduced, and Van
Patten announced that he and Albrecht would be calling _ and this
is how they described it _ the play-by-play action. Madden and
Summerall they ain't, but the idea was the same.
</P>
<P>
   We were then introduced to the finalists, six men from all over
the world, including one fellow who wore a sweat suit jacket with
the sleeves rolled up past the elbows _ always a classy look _ and
Jim Bechtel, the defending champion, who hailed from Coolidge.
</P>
<P>
   Albrecht explained the game and the terms _ the button, the
small blind, the big blind, the flop, etc. _ which doesn't happen
in, say, a baseball game. But there have been times when I've
wished I had an explanation for what Tim McCarver was trying to
tell me.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible for a novice such as myself to keep up with
what was going on (despite all that, ahem, expert commentary), but
gradually, players were eliminated. Along the way, we heard the
same cliches we hear during every NBA broadcast (remember those?)
when a player nails a couple of free throws with the game on the
line, including the old favorite, ``He looks like he has ice water
in his veins.''
</P>
<P>
   Loathe as I am to admit it, when you see a guy bet $120,000 on
one hand _ that's a house! _ you can't help but get sucked in and .
. . THIS IS 5-YEAR OLD POKER! GET A HOBBY, MAN!
</P>
<P>
   A man named Mansour Matloubi lost and wouldn't shake hands with
anyone. Then he bolted from the casino (he later returned) with the
camera following him. It looked just like an NFL game, when the
camera lingers on a distraught defensive back who blew his coverage
on a game-losing touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   Between hands, members of the crowd talked about a new, younger
generation of players coming up. Remind you of anything? The
talking heads at NBC hoping _ praying _ that somewhere out there,
the new Michael Jordan is lacing up his sneakers?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Bechtel won the $1 million first prize. Afterward,
he could have been Jeff Gordon when he said, ``I came in today to
win. Would have been disappointed if I hadn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Maybe it's not that coverage of the World Series of Poker
was just like that of every other sport. Maybe coverage of every
other sport is just like that of the World Series of Poker. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
