<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK WANTS 2002 OLYMPIC SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk hopes to participate in
the Winter Olympics again, despite Team USA's disappointing finish
in Nagano, Japan, and the fallout from a dorm room trashing
incident.
</P>
<P>
   After the United States was eliminated from the medal round,
Tkachuk was quoted as saying, ``This was a total waste of time.''
The comment made headlines, but for all the wrong reasons, Tkachuk
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to go back,'' Tkachuk said this week during a
conference call with reporters. ``I think a lot of people obviously
took that quote out of context. Most of the people who know about
hockey knew what I meant. I said if we didn't win, it was a waste
of time. Maybe it came out differently, but that's the way I felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I loved being over there. It wasn't a waste of time being
over there. . . . That was a great experience. I want to go back to
Salt Lake (in 2002) so we can redeem ourselves, because we're a
much better hockey team.''
</P>
<P>
   NHL Commissioner Gary Bettman has not announced whether the
league will suspend part of the 2001-2002 season to allow NHL
players to compete for their respective countries. A decision could
come by February. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Still sitting &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight game, Coyotes enforcer Jim Cummins was a
healthy scratch, and the club played without a true ``heavyweight''
to handle any potential rough stuff by the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the decision to sit Cummins has to do with getting
second-year pro Brad Isbister more ice time. But the Coyotes also
feel they have enough team toughness to counter Cummins' absence.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk said the Coyotes best players ``can handle themselves,
more or less.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
