<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT SIGNING PERIOD AFFECTS PIPPEN QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When or if the NBA's labor war ends, a mad scramble to sign the
best free agents will ensue before the shortened season begins. The
signing period could be as little as two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But if that time comes, don't be surprised if the Suns decide to
pass on small forward Scottie Pippen, who was atop their wish list
at the end of last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns could be cooling on Pippen for several reasons. First,
he had off-season back surgery, and because of the lockout, teams
are unable to communicate with players or their representatives.
The Suns may not have time to fully evaluate Pippen's health before
they must make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Pippen turned 33 in September, which plays into the
third factor _ the length of contract he will seek or that will be
needed to pay Pippen what he is worth.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of the contract could be preordained by the labor
agreement that's being negotiated. If the base number is limited,
that means it will take more years to make the average reach what
Pippen is thinking.
</P>
<P>
   It's always possible that the Suns may find out when the lockout
ends that Pippen's back is fine and that his contract demands are
not outrageous. But it's doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, expect the Suns to address their size problem first.
The free agent most likely to move to the top of the list is
forward Tom Gugliotta, who played for Minnesota last season.
Gugliotta, at 6-feet-10 and 240 pounds, has the flexibility in his
game to play all three frontcourt positions.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta, 28, was drafted out of North Carolina State by the
Washington Bullets with the sixth pick of the first round in 1992.
In six NBA seasons with the Bullets, Golden State Warriors and
Minnesota Timberwolves, Gugliotta has averaged 16.6 points and 8.8
rebounds a game. He averaged more than 20 points and 8.7 rebounds a
game in two seasons with Minnesota and made his first All-Star Game
appearance in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the team can keep forward Antonio McDyess _ which is no
small assumption, given Houston's interest in him _ the Suns could
have two of the league's best, most versatile forwards in the game.
</P>
<P>
   It also could leave the Suns with enough money to go after a
free-agent center such as Luc Longley. Or another free agent. If
Minnesota hangs on to Gugliotta, the Suns could pursue a center
such as Vlade Divac.
</P>
<P>
   But, as a league source familiar with the free-agent situation
put it, ``Don't expect to see Scottie Pippen in a Suns uniform.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Others to watch &QL; 
 &QL; 
Even with a major signing, the team has a lot of work to do to fill
out the roster. In particular, the club will likely need another
point guard, or at least a player who can work at either guard
position off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Some players who are likely to be considered include:
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Williams, a 6-5 second-round pick of the Portland Trail
Blazers in 1997 who finished his rookie season with Toronto. He had
a solid season and scored a season high 19 points against Phoenix.
He was traded to Toronto as part of the Damon Stoudamire deal.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Cory Alexander, a 6-1 veteran of three seasons. He
was waived by San Antonio last season and picked up by the Denver
Nuggets. Alexander is a 37.7 percent career three-point shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Respert, the eighth player taken in the 1995 draft, who
already has been with four teams and played with three. He was
drafted by Portland, which sent his rights to Milwaukee. The Bucks
traded him to Toronto, which released him in March.
</P>
<P>
   He was signed to a pair of 10-day contract late last season by
the Dallas Mavericks. At 6-2, Respert is in between shooting-guard
and point-guard sizes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Places to play &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Players Association and some agents have said they might
organize charity ``All-Star'' games featuring NBA players if the
lockout continues.
</P>
<P>
   The first was to be in Las Vegas, but no site has been booked.
Phoenix is a city that has been mentioned, with Veterans Memorial
Coliseum the venue.
</P>
<P>
   Danny McCall, the booking director at the Coliseum, said he has
had a conversation with one person, whom he would not identify,
about hosting such a game. However, the talks didn't go far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never got past the first stage,'' McCall said. ``We would
like to have it, though. If they're interested in having a game in
Phoenix, my phone line is open.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
