<HEADLINE>
WILL STOTTLEMYRE HELP LURE JOHNSON? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that free-agent right-hander Todd Stottlemyre has agreed to
sign with the Diamondbacks, what's next?
</P>
<P>
   Will the fact that Stottlemyre is coming aboard send enough of a
signal to left-hander &QL; 
Randy Johnson that the team is serious about upgrades?
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know how the spirit could move Randy, or when,''
Diamondbacks General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hoping that he would view this as a pretty tangible
piece of evidence about us being competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola also cited the recent signings of left-handed middle
reliever Greg Swindell and first baseman Greg Colbrunn and the
trade for young outfielder Dante Powell as reasons for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some, those are less obvious examples, but to us, they are
significant,'' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   To ascertain if there were any hints of a direction toward which
Johnson might be leaning, The Republic attempted to contact his
agents, Alan Nero and Barry Meiser, on Friday, but they did not
return phone messages.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has offers from his previous team, the Houston
Astros, and the Texas Rangers, was due to meet with officials from
the Anaheim Angels and Los Angeles Dodgers in California and might
announce his decision before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if Randy doesn't sign, we've still got a solid rotation
in Stottlemyre, Andy Benes, Omar Daal and Brian Anderson,''
Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential member of the rotation, right-hander Armando
Reynoso, is scheduled to get an evaluation from the Diamondbacks'
medical staff today. It was to have been done Friday, but it was
pushed back a day because of a family commitment. If the team
receives medical approval, a contract likely will be offered to
Reynoso, who was 7-3 for the New York Mets in 1998. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Bernie watch &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reports out of New York had center fielder Bernie Williams
turning down a five-year, $60 million offer from the Yankees. The
Diamondbacks remain in contention, but it is uncertain where they
stand in his mind, or perhaps more to the point, in the mind of
agent Scott Boras.
</P>
<P>
   Managing General Partner Jerry Colangelo spoke with Boras on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks deny they have made an offer to Williams.
Initial reports had them proposing a deal at seven years for $100
million, and recent rumors have pared those figures to four years
at around $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every player is a moving target, and there are a lot of teams
laying in the weeds,'' Garagiola said. ``It's one of the more
fascinating times of the year _ the dynamics of it all.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trade talks &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks also are taking the trade route to reshape
their roster.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola said the team had conversations going with at least a
couple of clubs at the recent general managers' meetings in Naples,
Fla., that could resume at the annual winter meetings in
mid-December in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something could very well come together by then,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
