<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-RECRUIT_PROMISES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA SETTLES WITH PLAYER IN SCHOLARSHIP FLAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN VAN DER WERF  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rather than face trial, the University of Arizona has decided to
pay $125,000 to a former baseball player who alleges that the
school defrauded him by promising him a scholarship and then
kicking him off the team after two years.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is an isolated case, the announcement of a
settlement sent shivers through university athletic departments and
threatened to further complicate the already complex world of
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the case, UA has instituted an extensive training
program with coaches involved in recruiting to help prevent them
from making promises that they cannot keep.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State, after hearing of the case, also said it will take
precautions to assure the same thing doesn't happen there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be precedent-setting because the court might have
been about to decide that there was a verbal contract,'' said Betsy
Mosher, senior associate athletic director for compliance and
administration at ASU. ``It could send a shock wave across
departments like mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick McMillin, a seldom-used right-handed pitcher on the 1994
and '95 UA teams, was dismissed from the squad in the fall of 1995,
his junior year. He was able to keep his scholarship for the rest
of the year but was told it would not be renewed after that.
</P>
<P>
   McMillin alleged in his claim that former UA Coach Jerry Kindall
promised him that his scholarship would be renewed every year as
long as he made progress toward getting his degree, avoided
``significant disciplinary problems and continued to go out for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillin asserted that based on Kindall's assurances of a
scholarship for up to five years, he gave up significant bonuses he
could have received if he had signed to play professional baseball.
</P>
<P>
   UA did not admit wrongdoing, but school attorneys said they
decided to settle because they would have faced significant costs
if the case had gone on to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (McMillin) alleges that he was promised he would get a
four-year scholarship, whether he played or not,'' said Judith
Leonard, UA's general counsel. ``We don't believe this happened,
but sometimes you have to make a business decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Under NCAA rules, athletic scholarships are guaranteed for one
year only. A coaches is allowed to say that he or she will
recommend to the financial aid office that the scholarship be
renewed every year, and that the financial aid office always has
followed that recommendation in the past, said Michael Proctor, a
UA attorney who works on athletic compliance issues.
</P>
<P>
   The new UA training program for coaches will stress ``a uniform
format to recruiting techniques . . . discouraging approaches which
might lead to ambiguous interpretations as to the terms of
scholarship offers,'' according to a summary of the litigation
released to the state Board of Regents. The regents approved the
settlement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mosher was not familiar with details of the McMillin case, but
she recognized the name. She said his parents, Pat and Freda
McMillin of Lakeside, Calif., ``papered the Pac-10 with letters for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The family was seeking to get NCAA rules changed so scholarships
automatically would cover four years instead of one, Mosher said.
She said she doesn't believe the NCAA has taken up the issue.
</P>
<P>
   McMillin and his parents could not be reached for comment
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mosher said ASU coaches are constantly reminded of the rules on
recruiting, and she said she will use this case as a cautionary
tale. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 0309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
