r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-REDSKIN     11-21 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-REDSKINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS PREPARE FOR CLIFFHANGER VS. REDSKINS  
 GAMES SELDOM END IN BLOWOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cardinals defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis describes games
against the Washington Redskins the past few years as
``cliffhangers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not just close games,'' he said. ``They're pacemaker
games, and that's a big difference to me.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis was clutching his heart as Joe Nedney kicked a 47-yard
field goal with two seconds left to beat the Redskins, 29-27, two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Kevin Butler kicked a 47-yarder for the Cardinals
with two seconds left to send the game in Washington into overtime.
The Redskins wound up winning, 19-13, the third overtime game
between the two teams in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it happens once or twice, I think you just say it
happened that way,'' Redskins Coach Norv Turner said. ``But the way
it has happened over the last five years, the teams have been
evenly matched, whether it has been low-scoring games or whether we
had some games pretty interesting and high-scoring. Both teams play
with confidence. Both teams feel they can win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are 6-3 against Turner going into Sunday's game
against the Redskins at Jack Kent Cooke Stadium. But only one of
the games has been a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the Cardinals' four victories over Turner's Redskins
at Sun Devil Stadium, all were decided in the final minute by a
total of nine points. Each of the Cardinals' two wins in Washington
came on a field goal in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The most thrilling victory was two years ago, when the
Cardinals, 3-6 at the time, went to RFK Stadium to play a
Washington team that was 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thought we'd get slaughtered,'' said wide receiver
Anthony Edwards, who is on injured reserve this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins led, 34-20, early in the fourth quarter when former
Cardinals quarterback Boomer Esiason put on a passing show. He
wound up throwing for a team-record 522 yards, third most in NFL
history.
</P>
<P>
   He tossed three touchdown passes, including a 12-yarder to
Edwards with 20 seconds left in regulation to send the game into
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams missed field goals in overtime. Then Butler hit a
shaky 32-yarder, giving the Cardinals a 37-34 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ```It was one of the most exciting games I've ever been involved
in,'' fullback Larry Centers said. ``It was one of the wackiest
games I've ever played. We went tit for tat, back and forth. I'll
never forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that season, the Cardinals had to come from behind again
to win.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kent Graham drove them 69 yards in 15 plays to set
up a Butler field goal try on the game's final play. He hit from 28
yards to give the Cardinals a 27-26 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play them, we're up, but then they play harder and
come back,'' center Mike Devlin said. ``Then they're up, and we do
the same thing and come back. It's crazy. One team is up, the other
comes roaring back.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedney said his game-winner two weeks ago was the biggest kick
of his career, bigger than his personal-best 53-yarder to win at
Detroit the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is No. 1 because it was at home,'' he said. ``It was my
first ever game-winner at home. It was the first time I heard the
crowd cheer instead of shutting up.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback J.J. McCleskey, who blocked a punt for a touchdown at
Washington a year ago, said he is tired of the close calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was at Tennessee,'' he said, ``we had a saying that
when you get ants on the ground, don't tap your feet and kill them.
Get a sledgehammer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game I've played against them has come down to the last
play. Two weeks ago, that was incredible for the fans. As a player,
I can't deal with those types of games.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
