<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SOMERS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS STATE COACH EASES MEDIA BAN ON QB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Wizard pulled back the curtains in Oz the other day and
showed the world that he's human.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State Coach Bill Snyder admitted earlier this week that
he was wrong for preventing quarterback Michael Bishop from
speaking to the media after the Wildcats' monumental victory last
Saturday over Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder hadn't allowed Bishop to speak with print reporters since
early October. Before playing Colorado, Bishop made some comments
that Snyder found bothersome.
</P>
<P>
   That started a cute little post-game dance with the media.
Reporters, who are not allowed into Kansas State's locker room,
were allowed to request interviews with Bishop. And Snyder would
deny them.
</P>
<P>
   But Snyder loosened the muzzle some last week, allowing ESPN to
interview Bishop. And after the Nebraska game, he let Bishop talk
to Sports Illustrated, but not to the other 500 or so media at the
game.
</P>
<P>
   This prompted much criticism in the press that Snyder was acting
like a dictator and costing his senior quarterback a chance at the
Heisman Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Never before had such a large contingent of media gathered in
Manhattan, Kan. It was the finest moment in Kansas State's football
history, and Snyder came across as both a genius and a dictator.
</P>
<P>
   But last Tuesday, Snyder apologized and made Bishop available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I offer no excuses,'' Snyder said. ``It was a mistake on my
part. I've apologized to Michael, and I apologize to you and I will
apologize to the other media who were here at the time and didn't
have the opportunities I afforded one magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder deserves credit for admitting his mistake.
</P>
<P>
   But shielding Bishop is something that probably would have ended
anyway the week of the bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   The participating teams in the four Bowl Championship Series
bowls will receive $11 million to $13 million apiece. For that kind
of money, bowl officials and sponsors expect to see a team's
starting quarterback at interview sessions. &QL;  &QL; 
Tomey's deal &QL;  &QL; 
Dick Tomey, 60, often says he can see himself coaching into his
late 60s or early 70s. The question the last few years, however,
has been whether Tomey will last that long at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It now appears likely that he will. Tomey, in the last year of
his current deal, was given a five-year contract earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a difficult decision by UA officials. The Wildcats are
10-1 and ranked eighth in the country, and any fan of the school
who thinks Arizona can do better than Tomey is mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona fans also shouldn't forget where the school ranks in
college football's pecking order. The Wildcats are never going to
be able to compete nationally for the country's best players. And
in Southern California, they won't win many recruiting battles with
UCLA and Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   What Arizona has to do, and what Tomey is good at, is
identifying prospects who are overlooked by others because of
slight imperfections. That's what Tomey has done in signing players
such as quarterback Keith Smith and former defensive lineman Tedy
Bruschi.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, he is going to reach and miss. There are going to
be seasons like 1995 and '96, when the Wildcats won a total of 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   And there are going to be seasons like this one, where the
recruiting chances pay off and everyone stays healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The program is stocked with young talent, particularly on
defense, and capable of contending for Pac-10 titles over the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   It's only fitting that Tomey stays in Tucson to see it. &QL;  &QL; 
Bizarre finish &QL;  &QL; 
After the Cardinals came from behind in the closing seconds to beat
Washington two weeks ago, defensive end Andre Wadsworth was asked
whether that was the most amazing game in which he had played.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite, Wadsworth said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Wadsworth's Florida State Seminoles were trailing
Florida, 31-3, heading into the fourth quarter at Doak Campbell
Stadium in Tallahassee. The Seminoles rallied to a 31-31 tie in a
game that's known in Florida as ``The Choke at Doak.''
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry will be renewed today in Tallahassee, where Florida
Coach Steve Spurrier has never won and where the Gators haven't won
since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The winner still has a legitimate shot at the national title.
But the fourth-ranked Gators and fifth-rated Seminoles will need at
least one of the top three teams _ Tennessee, UCLA or Kansas State
_ to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're thinking about is, `Just beat those guys to put
ourselves in position in case some of those other guys lose,' ''
Spurrier said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three undefeated teams keep squeaking by each week, but
all of them have a bunch of games left that they've got to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida is in the unique position of possibly winning a national
title but losing the Southeastern Conference crown. The Gators
likely are shut out of the SEC title game because of their loss to
Tennessee. But if the Vols and another undefeated team lose,
Florida probably will jump ahead of them in the BCS polls. &QL;  &QL; 
Quick kicks &QL;  &QL; 
Quick quiz: What graduate of a Phoenix high school is a leading
contender for some coach of the year honors? Answer below.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State is in familiar territory. Last year, the
Bulldogs could have advanced to the SEC title game by winning their
last two games against Arkansas and Mississippi. They lost both
games. They are in the same position this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Brannon of Mansfield (Pa.) University finished the season
with 1,024 rushing yards. So what, you say? He's the first running
back in school history to go over 1,000 yards, breaking a 105-year
streak.
</P>
<P>
   Quiz answer: Massachusetts Coach Mark Whipple, who graduated
from Camelback in 1975. Whipple is in his first season at UMass
after going 24-16 the previous four years at Brown. The Minutemen,
2-9 last year, are 8-2 and can clinch a Division I-AA playoff berth
with a victory today over Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   UMass is ranked seventh in the country and is sixth in total
offense and 10th in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   In two games against Michigan, Ohio State quarterback Joe
Germaine has completed just 17 of 48 passes for 232 yards and a
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Germaine, from Mesa Mountain View, has completed 61 percent of
his passes this season and thrown for 21 touchdowns. A fine year,
but Germaine knows his legacy as a Buckeyes quarterback is on the
line today.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people's memories are going to be predicated on
whether we're successful against Michigan and how I play,'' he
said. ``And I understand that.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Kent Somers can be reached at kent.somers(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
