<HEADLINE>
YELEY EYES NASCAR  
 MAY ALSO BE OFFERED FULL-TIME IRL POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Could J.J. Yeley be next to bolt the open-wheel campground?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But not tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Yeley will attempt to qualify for Manzanita Speedway's first
U.S. Auto Club National Midget Series race in 17 years and past
history suggests he will be one of the drivers to beat in the
30-lap main event.
</P>
<P>
   Then what?
</P>
<P>
   Yeley, who stuck the equivalent of his big toe in Indy Racing
League waters this season, is looking down the road and what he
sees has six big letters _ NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``In January or February, I'm going through the Buck Baker
Driving School (in Atlanta),'' said Yeley, who attended Apollo High
School. ``I'm talking to a couple of (NASCAR) Busch teams, and
something might be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRL is definitely getting stronger every year, and either
(NASCAR or IRL) would be great to be with. But right now, NASCAR is
the premier division to be running with. And I don't want to limit
myself to doing one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Yeley, who nurtured his home-grown talents on Valley
racetracks such as Manzy and Canyon Raceway, isn't likely to
completely turn his back on open-wheel racing.
</P>
<P>
   Not like Jeff Gordon. Or Kenny Irwin Jr.
</P>
<P>
   At age 22, with a trunk full of talent, Yeley doesn't need to
rush the future. Not now. And not even next year or the year after.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Yeley still may be offered a full-time IRL position
next year, which some members of his camp believe is a ``95
percent'' certainty.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, Yeley also will drive a Gary
Zarounian-owned USAC Silver Crown machine in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going for the points championship,'' said Yeley, the
1997 USAC sprint car rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Zarounian can hardly wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sold my new car dealership (in Visalia, Calif.) and we're
going racing full time,'' Zarounian said. ``I'm excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zarounian, whose car formerly was driven by Donnie Beechler,
hired Yeley late this season and the Glendale driver produced two
wins in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``J.J. caught my attention earlier this year, but I didn't think
he was ready yet,'' Zarounian said. ``Then I saw him some more, and
when we decided to make the (driver) change, I thought (Yeley) was
the guy to put in the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like his attitude, his personality and his talents. He's
done a real good job.''
</P>
<P>
   IRL car owner John Menard also gives Yeley a thumbs up. Yeley's
IRL debut was earlier this season at Phoenix International Raceway,
where Menard put him in a third car. Yeley qualified 10th.
</P>
<P>
   At the Indianapolis 500, Yeley qualified 13th and finished a
season-high ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Although Menard was considered Yeley to replace Tony Stewart,
who is pursuing a NASCAR Winston Cup career, he recently chose Greg
Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought J.J. did real well and it was a difficult
decision,'' Menard said. ``But I hired Thomas Knapp to be general
manager of my race team and his background is with (Ray). That was
one of the overriding factors in choosing Greg over J.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still think (Yeley) has a future in the IRL. It just
probably won't be with us at this time. The timing is off.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeley believes he might have warranted a closer inspection had
his IRL performance not tailed off the final three races.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first two races went really good, but I had the (Nissan)
Infiniti engine the last three races and I don't know if that hurt
my performance or not,'' Yeley said. ``I felt like it might have
because here I was trying to do engine testing instead of
concentrating on jump-starting my career.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the experience I gained doesn't hurt at all. I definitely
needed all the laps I could get. I'm just happy I was even
considered. Just the publicity of being in the IRL and the Indy 500
has to help.''
</P>
<P>
   So, no, Yeley wasn't surprised when Ray was officially announced
as Menard's new driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``After (Menard) hired Tom Knapp, the writing was pretty much on
the wall,'' Yeley said. It was known last year that Greg Ray didn't
really want to drive for someone like an A.J. Foyt. He wanted his
own deal, where he could have some control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John is giving them that option.''
</P>
<P>
   What Menard's decision gave Yeley was the freedom to pursue
other avenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``For young, up and coming drivers, I think the IRL or NASCAR is
the way to go,'' Yeley said. ``(Championship Auto Racing Teams)
isn't even an option for most of us. So that's what I'm looking at.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm going to do so some sprint and midget races next year,
along with the Silver Crown. I'll still be busy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
