<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-ARMIJO-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE NEEDS TO BRING BEST BACK TO INDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An open letter to Indianapolis Motor Speedway President Tony
George:
</P>
<P>
   Dear Tony,
</P>
<P>
   First, I must applaud you for seemingly having your heart in the
right place.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the philosophy behind your creation of the Indy Racing
League is admirable.
</P>
<P>
   Providing an avenue for top young open-wheel talent in this
country is something the sport desperately needs. While it has been
a slow and not entirely successful process at this point, it's good
to see the intent is there to allow future Steve Kinsers an
opportunity to prove or disprove their Indy car worthiness.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to come up with playing rules to help contain costs also
is a noble cause. Who wouldn't be in the market to try to save a
buck?
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is this:
</P>
<P>
   By changing the playing rules, you've also changed the
Indianapolis 500. That's my only regret. You've transformed the
greatest spectacle in racing to the greatest non-spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Tony, but it's the truth. And I know you don't sense
that.
</P>
<P>
   If you did, you would have done more than what you did regarding
this week's engine rule change. You would have made it practical
for Championship Auto Racing Teams officials and engine
manufacturers to warrant seeking a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Since you were the one to change the Indy 500 rules, you should
be the one to mend the fence. But you won't. We know that now more
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   From what I can extrapolate, you are convinced the IRL and CART
should go their separate ways. You believe the IRL doesn't need
CART, and maybe it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   But what you need to realize is even the Kentucky Derby is
nothing without all the top horses in the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, you don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't matter how many fans fill your seats at the Indy
500. It's still not the same. There's no electricity, no sizzle in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Indy 500 is supposed to be about the greatest
drivers in the land attempting to crack a 33-car starting lineup.
At the moment, that's not happening.
</P>
<P>
   And the argument that the race is open to anyone is laughable.
</P>
<P>
   CART owners' pockets aren't so deep that they can invest in IRL
equipment to run in one race and one race only.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if rules governing both sanctioning bodies were identical,
you could have your IRL and CART still could have its series.
</P>
<P>
   The best news of all, however, would be that everyone again
would gather at Indy in May.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of the Indy 500, I hope it happens soon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sincerely, &QR; 
Mark Armijo &QR; 
No surrender &QL; 
 &QL; 
IRL fans didn't appreciate the printed matter in this space a week
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of 22 e-mails and a half-dozen telephone calls, 95 percent
disagreed, some vehemently, with my opinion that the Indy 500 no
longer is the greatest race in the world.
</P>
<P>
   One called me an idiot and two suggested I was a CART shill. One
even referred to me as a sycophant. Yikes.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader suggested that ``Indianapolis Star'' columnist
Robin Miller and I are the two biggest boneheads in America. Hey,
anytime I can be mentioned in the same sentence as Miller, who is
one of the sport's top reporters, I'm happy.
</P>
<P>
   But my view hasn't changed. Tony George changed the rules, and
when he did, he changed the Indy 500 for the worst. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hold the sushi &QL; 
 &QL; 
If anyone needs a bolt of good news, it's Darrell Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip will drive the No. 88 Quality Care Ford Taurus for Dale
Jarrett tonight in a NASCAR exhibition race in Motegi, Japan.
Jarrett is recovering from gallbladder surgery, which he underwent
Monday in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, however, Waltrip will be unemployed. At the
moment, he has no ride lined up for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like getting a chance to drive the 88 car will be a big
plus for me,'' Waltrip said. ``It's coming at a great time. I need
a little platform here to kind of sell from over the winter as far
as looking for a deal for next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip is one of several drivers still in limbo. Others without
guaranteed 1999 employment include Geoff Bodine, Morgan Shepherd
and Dick Trickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 51 and people have hounded me for the last two years, and
I mean that literally, hounded me to get out of the car and go do
TV and go do other things,'' Waltrip said. ``But that's like me
calling the president of a corporation and saying, `Hey, you need
to retire. You've been there too long. Let somebody else run the
company for a while.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't feel that way. I still feel good. I still want to
race, and I still want to win. My pride is the same as anybody
else's pride. I want to win races and then quit, not lose races and
then quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the pressure, all the motivation, all the things that I
feel are self-imposed. Most of the people that want me to stop
driving or want me to go do other things want that not for Darrell
Waltrip, but for their sake.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Armijo can be reached at mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
