<HEADER>
A2692 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     11-21 0093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Saturday, Nov. 21, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following story
for Sunday:    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOREA (Seoul, South Korea) _ President Clinton and South
Korean President Kim Dae-jung tried to steer North Korea away from
a burgeoning confrontation over missiles and nuclear weapons
Saturday, with promises of fresh assistance backed by warnings of
allied resolve. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 1024EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981121.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2693 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOREA-HNS &LR;      11-21 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOREA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND SOUTH KOREA OFFER CARROT AND STICK TO NORTH KOREA  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ President Clinton and South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung tried to steer North Korea away from a
burgeoning confrontation over missiles and nuclear weapons
Saturday, with promises of fresh assistance backed by warnings of
allied resolve.
</P>
<P>
   The allied leaders said they hoped their carrot-and-stick
approach will persuade isolated, famine-stricken North Korea to
forego additional tests of 3,300-mile-range missiles and permit
immediate U.S. inspection of an underground site suspected of
potential use in North Korea's nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea rejected a U.S. demand Wednesday that inspectors be
allowed to view the suspicious underground site.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States and South Korea will continue
their ``clear eyed mix'' of continuing engagement with North Korea
coupled with ``deterrence against North Korean aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Kim met for the first time since North Korea alarmed
northern Asia by launching a three-stage, intercontinental missile
over Japanese territory on Aug. 31 and then rejected U.S. demands
to inspect the underground site at Kumchangai near North Korea's
nuclear weapons' development complex.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted the unprecedented visit of a South Korean civilian
cruise ship to North Korea this weekend to symbolize the open,
two-way exchanges that the allies seek with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told a joint news conference with Kim that he was struck
by the television news coverage of the ship landing that he saw in
his hotel room after arriving from Japan on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us went into our rooms and we turned on the
television and what was the picture? The picture was the tourist
ship going into the North,'' Clinton declared. ``To us, this was
amazing and it was a very beautiful picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The ship, carrying 780 South Korean tourists who paid $2,500
each, is due to complete an unprecedented four-night, five-day stay
in the North Korean port of Changjon on Monday. The South Koreans
are the first tourists from the south to visit North Korea since
the Korean War started in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   The ship's stopover is the first of a series of visits designed
to generate $150 million for North Korea over the next six years.
The port is gateway to Diamond Mountain, an isolated coastal area
featuring towering crags and steep valleys that is being developed
in a joint venture between South Korea and North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said the image on
television ``offered a visual picture of what the potential
advantages are to this open, engagement policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contrasted the promise of such exchanges with the
looming dispute over ``some hole in the ground somewhere in North
Korea where something might or might not be done, which might or
might not be threatening to us in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``Nothing could ever be put in that hole in the
ground that would give the North Koreans as much advantage, as much
power, as much wealth, as much happiness as more of those ships
going up there full of people from here.''
</P>
<P>
   National security adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger said the
United States could offer potential ``carrots'' to North Korea by
easing Korean War-era sanctions if North Korea scaled back missile
development and missile exports and ``chose to forego clearly and
unequivocally a nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Kim matched their overtures with statements of
resolve. Clinton warned North Korea four times and Kim warned his
neighboring nation twice about the dire circumstances that would
arise if it failed to avoid ``further provocations.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and South Korea waged the Korean War to turn
back North Korean aggression, a conflict that ended with a cease
fire in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which has 37,000 U.S. armed forces stationed
in Korea, is committed to going to war to defend South Korea
against any North Korean attack.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang could jeopardize the thin reed of outside assistance
unless it cooperates with allied demands, Clinton warned. ``It
would be a sad thing indeed if for no good end over the long run,
North Korea were to make it impossible for us to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS - STORY MAY END HERE)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor Berger offered evidence to support American
concern that the underground complex could be used to revive North
Korea's nuclear weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a complex hole in the ground _ put it that way,'' Berger
said. ``I don't want to describe the site. But we believe that the
physical inspection of the site would help us ascertain its
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Charles Kartman, who led the U.S. team to North Korea
last week, said the United States does not have concrete evidence
that the underground site will be used for a nuclear facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is strong information that makes us suspicious, but we
lack conclusive evidence that the intended purpose of the
underground site is nuclear related,'' Kartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that U.S. officials are satisfied at this point that
North Korea has complied with the 1994 accord targeting nuclear
weapons related facilities at Yongbyon.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang agreed with the United States, South Korea and Japan
to suspend its quest for nuclear weapons in return for free
shipments of 500,000 tons of heating oil each year and construction
of two non-weapons producing nuclear power stations at a cost of
$4.6 billion to an international consortium.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has demanded at least $300 million to permit U.S.
inspectors to visit the suspect site. U.S. officials have rejected
the condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
