<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STEINBRENNER'S $600 MILLION CAKE  (JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nobody is supposed to be able to have his cake and
eat it too, but George Steinbrenner is about to do just that. And
it might be a $600-million cake.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Steinbrenner, according to two of his business
associates, is close to agreeing to the sale of a ``significant
portion'' of his 60 percent share in the Yankees to Cablevision
early next year, nothing would change in the Yankee power structure
except for his title.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the Yankees' principal owner didn't even put up
all $10 million when his group purchased the Yankee franchise in
1973, that's a tidy profit without any loss of muscle.
</P>
<P>
   When the sale is finalized, possibly for $600 million, the
Yankees would not be George Steinbrenner's team in the corporate
sense. But the Yankees would still be his team in the control
sense, and control is the name of his game.
</P>
<P>
   Control in deciding how many millions to offer Bernie Williams
or Albert Belle this week in the free-agent auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Control in deciding when to dismiss the manager or the general
manager or the pitching coach or the switchboard operator.
</P>
<P>
   Control in deciding when or when not to listen to his baseball
``people,'' whoever they might be at that moment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to be determined, however, would be how much control he
would have in deciding the future of Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Although Steinbrenner no longer would be the principal owner, he
is expected to have an equally intimidating new title: managing
partner. The sight of him in his blue blazer and white turtleneck
would still be more feared at Yankee Stadium than any or all of
those Cablevision suits and ties.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the now 68-year-old Steinbrenner is in command, he
will remain behind his big desk in his Stadium office up there
behind his royal box. As long as he's the managing partner, he will
be conferring with Joe Torre and his front-office people as well as
exhorting or exiling players.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner wouldn't have it any other way. His identity as the
Yankee boss is his life.
</P>
<P>
   Anything less, any deal that allowed anybody else to outvote him
or overrule him in the operation of the Yankees, would never fit
his ego or his personality. No matter how many Yankee shares
Cablevision owns, no matter how much percentage it supposedly
controls, its suits and ties would be silent partners.
</P>
<P>
   John McMullen, the hockey Devils owner who was once a Yankee
limited partner, has said, ``Nothing is as limited as a limited
partner of George Steinbrenner.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the Yankee deal is finalized, all those Cablevision
suits and ties will discover there's nothing as silent as a silent
partner of George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it's a brilliant business buy for Cablevision. For its
$600 million, Cablevision would be assured of Yankee programming in
a continuation of its 12-year, $486 million contract. Charles
Dolan, the Cablevision major domo, might have had to put up $600
million for the next contract anyway.
</P>
<P>
   If the $600-million pricetag materializes, Steinbrenner would
also raise the financial roof of every major-league baseball
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, baseball's most expensive deal was the $311 million
that Rupert Murdoch, the Australian media mogul, paid for the Los
Angeles Dodgers, but that purchase included Dodger Stadium as well
as real estate in Vero Beach, Fla., the Dominican Republic and
around Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, pro football's expansion Cleveland Browns
franchise brought $530 million, the record price for a sports
franchise in North America.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees about to raise the roof, every major-league
clubowner should drop a thank-you note to Steinbrenner for
increasing the value of every club.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Yankee negotiations reportedly involved the
possibility of Steinbrenner also operating Cablevision's two
Madison Square Garden franchises, the basketball Knicks and the
hockey Rangers. But that might be too much cake, even for
Steinbrenner, to have and to eat.
</P>
<P>
   In his quarter of a century as the Yankees principal owner, his
teams have won four World Series championships, including two in
the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But the stunning success of this year's Yankees, who swept the
World Series for a record total of 125 victories, enabled
Steinbrenner to seek a record price for the franchise while
retaining control of the operation. That's having your cake, with
pin-striped icing, and eating it too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 1043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
