<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAUSD-GIFTED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIGHTEST KIDS IN LAUSD NOT SERVED, MANY SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- For years, a group of parents and teachers have
lobbied for funds to launch a program to help some of the LAUSD's
most forgotten students -- the best and brightest.
</P>
<P>
   Banking on promises that the district would spend $2.5 million
to open centers for its gifted students, parents rejoiced when a
$71 million windfall arrived this year. But then came the shocker
-- the gifted centers didn't make the superintendent's wish list.
The final injustice, they say, came last week when parents weren't
even allowed to speak when the board was deciding how to spend the
extra money.
</P>
<P>
   For the 50,000 LAUSD students identified as gifted, there's only
space for 7,000 very bright children at magnet campuses. Others are
given tougher math and reading books for self-study at home, but
are forced to sit through classes below their level.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, board members have told us that they would help us
if they had the money. Well, now they have the funds. Our kids have
waited too long -- this is our time,'' said Carol Knee, chairwoman
of the district's advisory gifted and highly gifted committee, a
group of parents and community leaders that has worked for three
years to improve the system's education system for very bright
students.
</P>
<P>
   When a San Fernando Valley elementary school bluntly told Lisa
Leonoudakis last year that it was unable to properly educate her
highly gifted daughter, the West Hills mother said she was ``forced
to flee'' Los Angeles Unified and enroll her child in a private
school.
</P>
<P>
   Leonoudakis, like thousands of other parents, have anxiously
awaited the promised opening in 1999 of new academic centers in the
LAUSD for their gifted children -- a promise that is now in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It appears that the centers are the latest victims in the
district budget wars, where employee unions are pressuring the
board to use the surplus for a salary hike.
</P>
<P>
   Board members and LAUSD staff members caution that they have yet
to make any final decisions. But George Kiriyama, a board member
who chairs the LAUSD's instruction committee, said the proposal for
the centers is not a high-profile project and has yet to be
discussed by his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyama said he is relying on Superintendent Ruben Zacarias to
outline instruction priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do it all. He's got to say what stays and what
goes,'' Kiriyama said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed 30 centers for 2,500 children would serve as
demonstration sites, with the goal to implement similar programs at
schools throughout the district. Several colleges, including the
University of California, Los Angeles, the University of Southern
California and Johns Hopkins University had volunteered to
implement and design curriculum and teacher training.
</P>
<P>
   The idea proposes at least three schools to be placed in each of
the LAUSD's nine regional areas, but sites have yet to be selected.
Campuses would be an elementary, middle and high school, all
feeding into each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every child should have an opportunity to achieve up to their
ability, but it's obvious that this is not a priority with the
LAUSD,'' Knee said. ``Some parents already have decided to move
their children to private schools, but some people don't have that
option. As a public school system, the LAUSD should be looking
after the needs of all of its children.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan had been to spend $2.5 million to train teachers and
set up the centers modeled on the district's successful magnet
programs, but without their complex application and admission
process. Last year, the district spent $5.5 million on its gifted
students, as opposed to the $689 million on special education _ a
program that is now under a consent decree because the courts
determined the LAUSD had failed to educate those students properly.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent board meeting where members discussed how to divide
the state windfall, there was no mention of the academic centers
and Knee and her group were not allowed to speak. The board's
actions raised concerns among the gifted-talented committee members
that the matter was off the table completely.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Valerie Fields said while she supports the academic
centers, it is unclear how much money is actually available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until there is a firm grip on how much money there is I can't
vote on any of this stuff,'' Fields said, although she did vote to
approve about $20 million in programs during the budget talks.
Fields also has said she is supportive of a raise for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   John Liechty, assistant superintendent for the division of
instruction, said Zacarias has assured him that he supports the
academic centers and believes it will go to the board before the
end of the year. But Liechty, who has worked with the
gifted-talented advisory committee for years, told the group at a
recent meeting that he too is frustrated by the board's failure to
act.
</P>
<P>
   ``This all has to do with salary negotiations,'' Liechty told
the group. ``I wish I could tell you the politics don't play a part
in education, but it does.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
