<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSASSINATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN EXPRESSES OUTRAGE AT LAWMAKER'S KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The killing Friday night in St. Petersburg of Galina
Starovoitova, a leading liberal politician and tireless defender of
Russia's democratic reforms, shocked her old allies who claimed her
as the latest victim of the country's lethally corrupt political
climate.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, President Boris Yeltsin dispatched his top
law-enforcement officials to investigate the shooting death of the
52-year-old parliamentary deputy, who had been his close associate
during the early years of Russia's transition from communism to
democracy, and served as his adviser on inter-ethnic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   According to local police, Ms. Starovoitova was struck and
killed Friday night by three bullets to the head in the entranceway
of her apartment building off one of St. Petersburg's historic
canals. Her press aide, Ruslan Linkov, was seriously wounded. The
two guns used in the attack, a submachine gun and a pistol with a
silencer, were found at the scene, in the style of Russian contract
killings.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Yeltsin expressed his ``profound anger'' and
said he had taken personal control of the investigation. ``The
shots which cut short the life of Galina Vasileyna wounded every
Russian who cherishes democratic values,'' Yeltsin said. ``A
peremptory challenge was thrown at our entire society.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, interviewed on television, was
visibly shaken as he expressed his outrage at the killing. ``This
banditry must be brought to an immediate end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Starovoitova, a psychologist and ethnographer, was a
spirited and visible leader of Russia's young democratic movement,
who shared many a platform with Yeltsin and the late human-rights
campaigner Andrei Sakharov in the late 1980s and early 1990s. She
was a cofounder of Democratic Russia, and kept a high profile as a
leading if increasingly lonely ``democrat'' long after the movement
fell into disfavor with a disgruntled electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, she had declared herself a candidate for governor
of the region outside St. Petersburg, in elections scheduled
sometime next year. She had also recently remarried, prompting a
string of articles about the personal life of one of Russia's few
prominent women politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians of all stripes _ including the leader of the Russian
Communist Party _ Saturday criticized the killing as a criminal act
that was only the latest example of the lawlessness that has
pervaded public life in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   St. Petersburg, Russia's former imperial capital, has been the
scene of a number of political contract killings in recent years.
The city is also in the midst of a particularly nasty election
campaign for the local municipal council, which has brought forth a
slew of accusations of dirty tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question to be answered is whether this was a case of a
political group getting even with a politician over a particular
fact, or a contract killing on a wider level, aimed at provoking
political consequences,'' said former Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev, in an interview with a Russian news agency. He praised
Ms. Starovoitova as ``learned, courageous and active, a born
politician.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Echo Moskvy, a Moscow radio station, former
Prime Minister Yegor Gaidar, the first architect of Russian
economic reform and a close political ally of Ms. Starovoitova,
said she had received many threats. Reportedly, she never traveled
with a bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was extremely tough in opposing radical nationalists and
Communists in the Parliament,'' Gaidar said. ``She was like a bone
in the throat for them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the St. Petersburg police report, Ms. Starovoitova
and her press aide were shot as they returned late Friday night to
her apartment in St. Petersburg's historic downtown district. Ms.
Starovoitova was already dead when their bodies were found by a
neighbor at 10:45 p.m. In their report, police said they found
$1,700 and 1,000 Bulgarian levs in cash and several credit cards at
the scene, apparently ruling out robbery as a motive.
</P>
<P>
   The killing will be prosecuted under Russia's laws against
terrorism, and the investigation will be carried out by Interior
Minister Sergei Stepashin and Vladimir Putin, director of the
Federal Security Service, who arrived Saturday in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, himself from St. Petersburg, called the killing a
``loathsome'' event. ``It is one of the black pages in our modern
history,'' he said. ``It doesn't do much to improve our reputation,
the reputation of the country as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   At a hastily called meeting Saturday by members of Northern
Capital, a local political movement closely associated with Ms.
Starovoitova, colleagues openly blamed corrupt political forces in
the city for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't doubt that the murder was politically motivated,''
said Viktor Krivulin, a member of Northern Capital. ``She was an
exception among politicians. In the past 10 years, they tried to
find compromising material against her, but she was blameless so
they hated her even more, and they were afraid of her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
