<HEADER>
A2787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLEMONS-E-STREET22-CO     11-21 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMONS-E-STREET22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clarence Clemons: The big man remembers the glory days
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Clarence Clemons is sitting in a cramped
backstage corner of Christines, a Jupiter club where the rock sax
legend holds court every Tuesday evening. He's dripping sweat,
sipping a Cosmopolitan. The first set of the night has gone well.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to talk about The Boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce who?'' Clemons kids a visitor. But the 56-year-old
ex-football player, dubbed the Big Man by his musical colleagues,
knows better. After all, it was as a member of Springsteen's E
Street band from 1972 to 1989 that Clemons earned his fame. And now
that Springsteen is back in the news _ with the release of Tracks,
a four-CD box set, and the announcement of his induction into the
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame _ it's a good time to catch up with the
saxophonist who helped define the Springsteen sound.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the fact that Springsteen paid a little visit to
Clemons' Singer Island home a couple of weeks ago. The two did what
old rock buddies do: Clemons, an aspiring chef, cooked Springsteen
a couple of his specialties; Springsteen joined Clemons on stage at
his other weekly gig on Wednesday night at 251 Sunrise in Palm
Beach (talk about your guest artists!).
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a sit-down time for the both of us, to hang out
like we used to,'' says Clemons. ``He's never been in my neck of
the woods here, so I wanted to show him what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   That included his new band, an all-star team of South Florida
veterans that Clemons is bringing into the studio in a month. His
violinist, Randi Fishenfeld, a country-style fiddler with a
rocker's passion, particularly caught Springsteen's attention.
Clemons doesn't want to ignite speculation about her joining the E
Street Band on a rumored reunion tour, but he doesn't rule out the
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping he would (think about it),'' he says, noting that
Springsteen has featured a violin in the band before.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, all instruments are welcome in the free-for-all
celebration that is the E Street Band. But as the Tracks set
attests, none is perhaps more prominent than Clemons' soul-laced
saxophone. Listening to the anthology's 66 songs, most previously
unreleased, you hear a band coalesce from bar-room beginnings to
stadium-era glory _ with Clemons punctuating one tune after another
with his beefy solos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like reliving your life all over again,'' the
saxophonist says of his first reaction to the set.
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen wasn't necessarily looking for a sax player when
Clemons walked into the Asbury Park, N.J., bar where a meeting had
been arranged by a mutual friend. As Clemons tells it, he opened
the door and a gust of wind literally blew it off in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in and asked him if I could sit, and he was too
scared to say no,'' Clemons recalls with a laugh, imagining how he
must have seemed like the Incredible Hulk. (At 6 feet 3 inches,
he's a towering presence even when the door stays on its hinges.)
</P>
<P>
   The two clicked instantly. ``We were both looking for something
_ the missing element,'' Clemons says, noting how the saxophone was
a regular feature of rock bands in the '50s. The increased emphasis
on the electric guitar changed that. ``It was more powerful and had
more drive,'' Clemons adds. ``The saxophone ... couldn't compete.''
</P>
<P>
   But given Springsteen and the E Street Band's wide range _ from
rockabilly to stadium rock _ a sax was necessary. ``It adds an
urban element,'' Clemons explains. ``You can touch a lot more bases
than you would without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while Clemons may be responsible for tooting his own
horn, it's Springsteen who directs the band. Those well-placed sax
solos are exactly that _ well-placed as part of Springsteen's
design. ``I don't play the sax constantly,'' Clemons says, noting
that he also plays percussion. ``I'm a color to his (Springsteen's)
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Clemons' contributions to Tracks are reflective of the
old-fashioned rock tradition of Little Richard and Chuck Berry. In
early party songs like Give the Girl a Kiss and So Young and In
Love, he doesn't play so much as he growls, giving the music a
sexual edge.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the eight-minute reverie known as Thundercrack.
Clemons expresses amazement that Springsteen could write ``an
opera'' on a subject as trivial as how a woman dances. ``He's a
great storyteller, he takes something so simple and makes it so
complicated,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   By the third disc in the chronologically ordered set, one hears
a more mature, sophisticated Springsteen _ and Clemons' sax
reflects the change. Frankie, a seven-minute bittersweet ballad
that Clemons calls ``a pretty intense song,'' features a pointed,
soaring sax solo just at the end. ``You feel it, you know it's
going to come, you want it,'' Clemons says.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Bands Are, from the second disc, offers what might be
termed the quintessential Clemons solo, big and bold down to the
last eighth note. ``That's my second favorite song (on the set).''
At the same time, he wouldn't mind having another crack at that
solo _ and some others. ``Because when you're doing it on a first
or second take, you're just beginning to feel it,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clemons' favorite song, that honor goes to Sad Eyes from
the fourth disc, a number he doesn't even play on. Clemons simply
enjoys the Roy Orbison-influenced tune. ``Roy Orbison was a big fan
(of Springsteen's). He used to follow us around Europe,'' Clemons
notes.
</P>
<P>
   The big question that remains is whether Tracks will prompt an E
Street Reunion. Clemons is pretty confident. The band already
worked together a couple of years ago when Springsteen recorded new
material for a greatest-hits compilation. (Clemons' sweet sax
playing on Secret Garden was a highlight of the added songs.)
</P>
<P>
   And while the band will not be inducted with Springsteen at the
Rock and Roll Hall of Fame ceremonies _ a technicality because they
were not properly credited on Springsteen's first album _ the
chances are good they will join him on stage for a number.
</P>
<P>
   But anything beyond that remains up to Springsteen. Or as
Clemons likes to say, ``He is The Boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
