u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOONAN-WINDOW-DRESSER     11-21 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOONAN-WINDOW-DRESSER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Storefront designer creates splendor in the glass
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Monday, Nov. 23
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Simon Doonan wanted to visit Palm Beach
last week. He really, truly did.
</P>
<P>
   But there was this big car crash between Miami, where he was,
and here, and traffic was so bad, and he had a party at the Delano
in the evening ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply traumatized,'' he said, once he got to a phone.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way Doonan talks. Dramatic. Thrilling. Deliberate and
English, like he's licking crumbs from his fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   He sounds like a flamboyant window dresser, which is just what
he is.
</P>
<P>
   Doonan dresses the windows at Barney's department store in New
York. Doesn't sound like something that would make a person famous.
Put clothes on mannequins. Sweep floor.
</P>
<P>
   But Doonan has fun. His first big hit in window-dressing was a
group of mannequins in tuxedos sitting among trash cans, with
taxidermic rats scrambling over them. The rats were wearing
rhinestone bracelets around their necks.
</P>
<P>
   At Barney's, Doonan collaborates with artists for his windows.
He does whole-window caricatures of Madonna, Martha Stewart, George
Hamilton. The Hamilton window had a mannequin sunbathing next to a
``Tan-enbaum'' Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's written a book, Confessions of a Window Dresser: Tales
from a life in fashion (Penguin, $40). He's on his book tour.
</P>
<P>
   After apologizing about four times for not visiting, he
submitted to some off-the-cuff questions.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Have you been to Palm Beach before?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Oh, yes. Vera Wang was the first to rave on about it. She
has a pink house there. She's Palm Beach's biggest ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What are you doing next?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Well, my book tour just started. I think this is my 15
minutes of fame and I'm about seven minutes through it. Several
people want the book movie rights.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Will you star?
</P>
<P>
   A.: I'm a bit too old, I think (he's 46). They should cast
someone like Mike Myers. Or they should get someone really butch,
like Clint Eastwood or Jean-Claude Van Damme.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Have you ever starred in one of your windows?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Right now I'm in the windows at Madison Avenue. We have this
funny old resuscitation mannequin, like for CPR. It looked like me,
so we propped it up with a typewriter. It's so much fun _ it's the
ultimate ego trip.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: I saw you were one of the critics for People magazine's
best- and worst-dressed issue.
</P>
<P>
   A.: That didn't necessarily reflect me. I think the people voted
based on good taste, and you shouldn't do that for performers.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Who do you think are the best dressers?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Madonna. She always wears new stuff. Sharon Stone. I like
performers who don't necessarily look chic but have a point of
view. For example, Dolly Parton looks great. Puff Daddy dresses in
a certain amount of excess, and that's great. Too many people are
dressing like junior Vogue editors with little Prada bags. You
should have bravado.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: And who are the worst dressers?
</P>
<P>
   A.: There are some who haven't figured it out yet. Like Emma
Thompson. I'm reluctant to name names because they're Barney's
customers. You could say, `Simon was terrified at saying.'
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Any Palm Beach people you'd like to put in a window?
</P>
<P>
   A.: It would be great to do a crowd scene of Palm Beach
characters, throw them all in.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What would that look like?
</P>
<P>
   A.: A vast living room with huge tables and huge bowls of fruit,
and a ceramic zebra in the corner. Giant ceramic urns. Chartreuse
bamboo with velvet upholstery. And huge ceramic animals everywhere.
Patterns of florals and chintz. Another look could be plexiglass
with beige, like a '70s Palm Beach. I like the really overdone
look.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Why don't you do it?
</P>
<P>
   A.: I don't see why not. I could do Saratoga, Palm Beach, the
Upper East Side _ where the society people spend time. Aspen.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: It's almost Christmas time. Any home decorating tips?
</P>
<P>
   A.: The key is abundance. If you have a wreath with balls, make
sure there are hundreds of balls. If you have a snowman, make it
huge. Avoid plastic light-up lawn ornaments. That's a bit cheesy
for Palm Beach. I do like it myself. You should have a giant
Christmas tree in the yard smothered with lights. And there should
be one dominant thing on the tree. Martha Stewart did popcorn balls
in cellophane. I have to say Martha Stewart does the best Christmas
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What are you doing for New Year's?
</P>
<P>
   A.: I'm going to Peru. My boyfriend is a potter and he has a
little factory down there. We went last year. It's great getting
away from it all, sitting in a shed while parrots fly around.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: What's your favorite outfit?
</P>
<P>
   A.: I have a lot of clothes by Helmut Lang. He cuts well for
small people. A lot of Prada. I'm very trendy.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: How tall are you?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Well, now you're thinking I'm four-foot-three. I am
five-five. My passport says I'm five-four and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Which one is right?
</P>
<P>
   A.: Let's say five-five. I'll go get some elevated shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Q.: Anything else? Want to say `Hi' to anyone here?
</P>
<P>
   A.: To the Palm Beachers, I just applaud their sense of style.
They should never lose that. They should never go to flip-flops.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
