<HEADER>
A2789 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONI-TENNILLE22-COX     11-21 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONI-TENNILLE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennille brings broader comedy to role as `Victor/Victoria'
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Toni Tennille, starring in the national
tour of the Broadway musical, Victor/Victoria? Isn't she the
distaff half of the Captain &AMP; Tennille, last heard embarrassing
President Ford by singing Muskrat Love at the White House?
</P>
<P>
   True, but she once wrote her own musical, an ecology-themed show
called Mother Earth that played Broadway in 1972. Briefly.
</P>
<P>
   It closed after 12 performances, a trauma that kept the
55-year-old Tennille from theater until recently. ``It was very,
very heart-breaking,'' Tennille says by phone from Nevada, where
she was nursing a sinus infection. ``It's been such a long time
since Mother Earth, you'd think I'd be over it by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if that were the end of the story, we wouldn't bother
telling it. During the show's tryout in San Francisco, Tennille met
a keyboardist named Daryl Dragon, nicknamed The Captain because of
his penchant for nautical hats. After Mother Earth tanked, they
became a team in nightclubs and in private. They rose to
Grammy-winning stardom, harmonizing on love songs _ both the
Muskrat variety and the kind that Will Keep Us Together.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon and Tennille still criss-cross the country with their
largely nostalgic act, but more and more she has branched out into
big band concerts and solo albums. And lately, the Alabama-born
songstress began itching to try a musical again.
</P>
<P>
   Victor/Victoria, which opens Tuesday evening at the Kravis
Center, is the gender-bending tale of a down-on-her-luck diva
forced to impersonate a man who dresses and sings like a woman. It
began as a 1982 Blake Edwards movie starring his wife, Julie
Andrews. In 1995, it jumped to the stage, again directed by Edwards
and starring Andrews. Although the show got brutal reviews on
Broadway, every bit as bad as Mother Earth's, Tennille contacted
the producers about replacing Andrews. They opted for Raquel Welch.
But when it came to the national tour, they tapped Tennille.
</P>
<P>
   Tennille says the show has been tightened since New York, but
the prime difference is her interpretation. In contrast to Andrews'
reserved approach, Tennille goes for broader comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I do `Le Jazz Hot' and `Louis Says' as Victor, Victor is
not a woman, Victor is a drag queen,'' she notes. ``So you have to
take the drag queen motto, which is `Why do, when you can overdo.'
So everything is very over-the-top, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does she attempt to parrot Andrews' British accent. Instead,
she decided her character is from the American South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a whole story for her in my mind,'' Tennille says.
``She grew up in a little town in Alabama. Actually, we're using
Eufaula instead of Montgomery, where I was born, because Eufaula is
funnier, Blake thought. Her mother was a classical piano teacher
and her father was a very, very good tenor who had wanted to be an
opera singer, but circumstances prevented him from doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Victoria as being exposed to the new jazz music and
really loving that. Because of her parents, she chooses the
classical side and ends up touring Europe with a very small light
opera company.''
</P>
<P>
   The history is made up, but Tennille says there are similarities
to herself. ``My mother did play classical piano, not that well.
And actually, my father sang with the big bands _ he sang with Bob
Crosby's band _ but he had to give up show business when his father
died. He had to come back to Montgomery and take over the furniture
store.''
</P>
<P>
   She can also relate to Victoria's early desperation to succeed,
or at least make a living as a singer. ``Oh, yeah, because Daryl
and I worked in the clubs for very small money when we first
started out,'' she says. ``In 1972 through '74, right before we hit
it big, we were hauling our own equipment into the club and setting
up and playing for, I don't know, a hundred bucks a night.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, unlike Victoria, who is not above causing a disturbance
in a restaurant to finagle a free meal, Tennille cannot think of
anything so wild. ``I am just the most boring person you will ever
meet. I'm the good Southern daughter. I'm not outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it outrageous that anyone would mistake the striking
redhead for a man? ``I don't think they've really mistaken anybody
who's played the part,'' she says. ``I think I probably physically
am fairly well-suited, because I am tall and I'm skinny and I'm
small busted. So I don't even need that squash-down thing that
Julie had to have to squash her breasts down.''
</P>
<P>
   And Raquel? ``Well, puh-leeze. I mean, I didn't see it, but I
can't even imagine where she put those things when she put that tux
on.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Tennille feels comfortable in the show and once
she shakes her sinus problems, she'll be able to relax and enjoy
the tour. Nevertheless, she has the final date _ June 1999 _
circled on her calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I'm going to do is take two months off,'' she
says with a sigh. ``I'm going to do nothing but hike in the hills,
play golf, see my friends and just enjoy being at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Home is near Lake Tahoe, and July there is ``a golf month,
believe me.'' After two months off, she'll be ready for some
symphony dates and to roll out Captain &AMP; Tennille again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually the year 2000 is our 25th anniversary of doing
Captain &AMP; Tennille,'' she says. ``I can't believe it. It's like,
how is this possible?''
</P>
<P>
   The silver anniversary of the act is also Tennille and Dragon's
silver wedding anniversary. The two events are not coincidental.
``My mother had been after us to get married, because we were
living together for three years,'' Tennille recalls. By the summer
of '75, as Love Will Keep Us Together reigned as the No. 1 song
hit, they no longer had the excuse of being too broke to wed.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, love has kept them together, though Victor/Victoria has
been keeping them apart lately. Dragon tends to fly in and see his
wife every three weeks. While she is busy with the show, he has
been helping Al Jardine of the Beach Boys, acting as musical
director for a new group called Beach Boys Family &AMP; Friends,
putting ``a fresh approach to the Beach Boys sound.'' (Both Dragon
and Tennille played on Beach Boys records in the '70s.)
</P>
<P>
   The not-so-hidden agenda for Tennille's 40-week trek with
Victor/Victoria has been to convince Broadway producers that she
can carry a show. ``I think I'm at the top of my game now,'' she
says. ``I would say the next big challenge would be if I were to
open a show in New York on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   And if one didn't come along that was right? ``Actually,'' she
says, ``I'll just write my own show.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
