<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SEOUL22-COX     11-21 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SEOUL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton urges Korean detente
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Holding out the prospect of a new dawn for
one of the world's last remaining pariah states, President Clinton
lent a dramatic endorsement Saturday to Seoul's efforts to build
new partnerships with communist North Korea, one of the most
reclusive regimes on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done repeatedly in recent days, Clinton called on
North Korea to open a suspected nuclear materials site to U.S.
inspectors and to end ballistic missile test launches, warning that
the matters are ``cause for deep concern.''
</P>
<P>
   He also extended an olive branch to the communist regime in
Pyongyang, however, embracing South Korean President Kim Dae Jung's
policy of erecting cultural, political and commercial bridges
across the Cold War divide that has split this ancient land between
north and south through half a century of enmity and war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support President Kim's policy of gradual engagement with
North Korea,'' Clinton told reporters during a joint press
conference following a summit meeting with Kim. ``I think it is a
wise policy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the most animated moment of the half-hour news conference,
Clinton illustrated the opportunities engagement presents to North
Korea, as symbolized by the journey of a South Korean cruise ship
that is, this weekend, ferrying the first-ever large group of
tourists to travel from capitalist South Korea to the communist
North.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, this was amazing,'' Clinton said, ``and it was a very
beautiful picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contrasted that with the menacing image of a vast
underground military construction site in the North that the White
House suspects is being built to house a nuclear reactor capable of
producing enriched uranium, the raw material for atomic bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could ever be put in that hole in the ground that
would give the North Koreans as much advantage, as much power, as
much wealth, as much happiness as more of those ships going up
there full of people from here,'' said Clinton. ``That is the most
important message I would like to leave with you today.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether to engage with or to isolate states that
don't play by international rules has formed one of the most
enduring policy debates of Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Communist Cuba, for example, remains in a sort of U.S.-imposed
quarantine, diplomatically and economically isolated by sanctions
that have been in place for nearly four decades.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has broad and expanding links to communist
China, however, a model of the approach that engagement advocates
say will deepen U.S. influence and serve to moderate Beijing's more
oppressive instincts.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. approach has been decidedly different for North Korea,
the target of the longest-standing and most comprehensive set of
punitory sanctions the United States has ever imposed on another
country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton embarked on carefully calibrated engagement with North
Korea four years ago, when his administration brokered a deal to
freeze, and ultimately dismantle, Pyongyang's alleged nuclear
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Clinton administration has engaged North Korea
in ongoing negotiations centered on confidence-building measures
that might ultimately lead to a formal end to the state of war that
technically exists between the two Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   On yet a third track, the Clinton administration is conducting
talks with North Korea concerning ways to bridle Pyongyang's
ballistic missile program.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, those efforts represent a sea change in U.S.
relations with North Korea, so much so that the Congress has
mandated a White House review of its policy, a task Clinton has
delegated to former Defense Secretary William Perry.
</P>
<P>
   In aligning himself with Kim's own engagement approach, referred
to in Korea as a ``sunshine policy,'' Clinton appeared to step
closer to working with the unpredictable North, which, despite the
movement of the past several years, remains one of the most
closeted regimes anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It's far from clear whether North Korea's authoritarian regime
is interested in embracing the outside world. While Pyongyang has
agitated for a lifting of U.S. economic and diplomatic sanctions,
the regime is dogged by contradictory fears that opening the
country to outside influences could mark the beginning of the end
of its own authority.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean President Kim, however, has spent his first nine
months in office advocating engagement as the surest route to
dispelling a generation of animosity and distrust between Koreans
on both sides of the border, which Kim hopes to one day see
reunified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have patiently and consistently pushed such a policy,'' Kim
said during a toast Saturday night at a state dinner in Clinton's
honor. ``The result is gradually emerging now. North Korea is
cautiously, but noticeably, taking measures to increase interaction
and cooperation between the South and the North.''
</P>
<P>
   Formed 50 years ago by the Soviet Union as a counter to the
U.S.-backed government in the South, North Korea has been virtually
walled off from the rest of the world through a combination of its
own secrecy and self-imposed isolation and an overarching set of
U.S.-imposed sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has never had official diplomatic relations with the
United States, which has not formally recognized it as a legitimate
state. Americans are strictly forbidden to do most types of
business with North Korea under U.S. laws that prohibit trading
with the nation's enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Some 54,000 Americans died combating North Korea and its Chinese
allies during the 1950-1953 Korean War. And the United States still
keeps 37,000 American troops in South Korea to help guard against
possible attack by North Korea's million-man army, much of which is
combat-ready and forward deployed along the heavily fortified
border that divides the nation less than 30 miles north of Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of its Soviet benefactor seven years ago has left
North Korea virtually alone in an increasingly integrated world,
while the failings of its central controls have exhausted its
economy and driven many of its 22 million people to the brink of
starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to spend Sunday visiting with U.S. troops
in Korea, before leaving later for the U.S. island possession of
Guam. He plans to spend the day there before returning to
Washington Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
