<HEADER>
A2794 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS22-COX     11-21 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gun retailers preparing for shoppers' backlash against new law
 &HT;    By Jim Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Sporting goods stores and other shops that sell
guns are bracing for crowds and complaints this week as shoppers
try to beat a federal law that goes into effect Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   On that date, potential buyers of handguns, rifles and shotguns
must undergo a background check to see if they are permitted to buy
a gun.
</P>
<P>
   The National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS) is
the result of the Brady Act of 1993. Until now, only those who
bought handguns required a background check. Now all guns, except
most muzzle-loaders, will be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This probably couldn't have come at a worse time for gun
dealers,'' said Evan English, owner of the Olde English Gun Shoppe
in Ginghamsburg. ``Not only is it hunting season, but that's also
the beginning of our Christmas shopping season. So it's going to
add to the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun dealers at first will be required to telephone the NICS
center, a division of the Federal Bureau of Investigation, with the
potential gun buyer's Social Security number and other
identification. Later, the FBI says, computers will handle it all.
</P>
<P>
   With the system in place, the number of background checks for
gun purchases will increase to 12 million a year from 4 million,
federal officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a real nightmare, especially in the beginning.''
English said. ``On a busy Saturday afternoon, calls will be coming
in from all over the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   English said he was told some background checks might take up to
three days if there is a glitch in the system or other problem
obtaining records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we'll have to increase some man-hours to make the calls
or even hire someone to do it,'' English said.
</P>
<P>
   English said he is glad one aspect of the NICS program has
changed. Last month Congress rejected a $13-$15 charge for the
background checks, to be added to the price of each gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't going to be very fair,'' English observed. ``Now
it will be a cost absorbed by the federal government. If the
background checks are meant to protect society, then everyone
should be paying for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun dealers hope customers don't take out their frustrations on
store employees, especially if the system rejects them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to be the ones to take the heat,'' said
Jason McNinch, manager of Lev's Pawn Shop, 3551 Salem Ave. ``People
will get mad and I'll be the one who hears about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The law also requires pawn shops to do background checks on
people who pawn a gun, then go back to get it. The same is true for
people selling a gun by consignment at a gun shop.
</P>
<P>
   A gun dealer who sells a weapon without the checks would face
criminal prosecution, loss of his license, a fine, and possibly
prison.
</P>
<P>
   One area dealer, Roger Meyerhoeffer of Crawdaddy's Outdoor Store
in New Carlisle, said he might give up the gun business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't sell all that many guns in a year and I'm just
wondering if it's going to be worth the hassle,'' Meyerhoeffer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyerhoeffer said he thinks the NICS system will drive more gun
sales underground.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will find other ways to get guns if they don't think
they can get by the background check,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criminals aren't going to buy from gun shops, because of the
background checks,'' said Kevin Heeter, a gun enthusiast from West
Alexandria. ``But it's going to be just that much more red tape for
law-abiding gun owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Another gun owner said he thinks NICS could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is potential for crime to increase because of
the new law,'' said Del Schindler, a veteran Dayton trapshooter.
``If criminals can no longer obtain guns legally, they will
probably try to steal guns more.''
</P>
<P>
   Darke County Sheriff Toby Spencer said the checks would be
``harder on the average citizens'' but do little to stop criminals
from getting the firearms they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will work,'' he said. ``There's too many
avenues for criminals to get guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County Sheriff Gary Haines said he didn't expect
criminals to commit more burglaries to steal guns because of a
massive loophole in the Brady Act: Only registered dealers are
affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most gun sales are casual sales,'' Haines said. ``Criminals
don't get guns from gun stores.''
</P>
<P>
   For Brady to work, it would have to be more comprehensive,
Haines said, adding much more regulation _ and curtailing what most
gun owners view as basic constitutional protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it happening,'' he said. ``I think Americans will
not give up that right.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton this month acknowledged a loophole: The
requirement for background checks does not apply to gun show sales
by non-dealers, who must verify the age and address of the person
buying the gun.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered the Treasury and Justice departments to
recommend executive actions within 60 days to close the loophole to
stop 5,000 gun shows throughout the nation from becoming ''illegal
arms bazaars'' for criminals and gunrunners.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates 5 million people a year attend gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Another change in the law _ elimination of a waiting period _
could put guns in the hands of hotheads, some critics suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Once the new system begins, background checks could be conducted
in 30 seconds to three minutes, according to Paul Bresson, an FBI
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   That would eliminate a five-day ``cooling-off period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see where that could happen,'' said Chris Davey of the
Ohio attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Since the handgun background checks became mandatory, such
checks in Ohio have been handled by the attorney general's Bureau
of Criminal Investigation. On Nov. 30 it will turn over those
duties to the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``There never really was a 'cooling off' period,'' Davey said.
``That was a misconception.'' Davey said background checks for
handgun purchases usually took about five days to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Ingram, an associate professor of criminal law and criminal
procedure at the University of Dayton, said he doubted the hothead
theory. ``Most people at gun shows or firearms dealers are not
buying their first guns,'' he said, adding, ``There are other
avenues'' for someone who wants a gun in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   A Fairborn gun owner said he is more concerned with the
potential to create a ``big brother'' file by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of the government going ahead and keeping a file on
people who own guns could create a real problem,'' said Scott
Craft. ``I hope there is no intent to put together a data base.''
</P>
<P>
   Bresson said the law requires records about gun owners to be
destroyed within 180 days of a background check. Those who can't
purchase guns Following are reasons for which a person would not be
permitted to purchase a rifle, shotgun or handgun under the NICS
background check:
</P>
<P>
   A dishonorable discharge from military service.
</P>
<P>
   Renunciation of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Mental defectives/commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Controlled substance abusers.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal/unlawful aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Wanted persons.
</P>
<P>
   Listed in the protection order file.
</P>
<P>
   Listed in the deported felon file.
</P>
<P>
   In U.S. Secret Service protective file.
</P>
<P>
   In the foreign fugitive file.
</P>
<P>
   Any state laws that can prevent the requester from obtaining the
firearm
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-11-20-98 1915E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
