<SLUG> BC-MONICA-SEOUL22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton says he is paying price for scandal
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ President Clinton said Saturday that it was
not his place to suggest a course of Congressional action to punish
him for his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, but he said he is
paying a price whether lawmakers discipline him further or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of suffering,'' Clinton said. ``That is
different from punishment, although it's hard to see the difference
sometimes as you're going through it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton, who has said his fate and judgment rests in the
hands of Congress and, ultimately, the hands of God, stressed that
his personal struggle over the sex and deception scandal has been
separate from his public battles over its fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this long ago ceased to be a political issue or a
legal issue and became a personal one,'' Clinton said. ``And every
day I do my best to put it right, personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, here as part of a five-day Asia swing, made the remarks
in response to a reporter's question at a press conference with
South Korean President Kim Dae Jung, in this country's presidential
residence, the Blue House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply not appropriate at this time, in my view, for me
to comment on what the Congress should do,'' Clinton said, after
being asked whether he had any suggestions as to how he might help
to put the matter behind. ``I trust the American people, and I hope
Congress will do the right thing in a nonpolitical way, if you
will, to get beyond the partisanship and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky, a former White House
intern, is the subject of impeachment proceedings before the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
