<SLUG> BC-ROGER-CLINTON22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Clinton Brothers: Seoul Man
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ President Clinton and his half-brother
Roger shared a moment as rock show Seoul-mates Saturday night, when
the leader of the free world dropped in on a concert to cheer his
younger sibling.
</P>
<P>
   Roger and his rock band were among a list of acts to appear at
what was billed as a U.S.-Korean Friendship Performance, coinciding
with Clinton's two-day visit to the South Korean capital.
</P>
<P>
   The president left a state dinner with President Kim Dae Jung
and stopped off at the Sejong Cultural Center in downtown Seoul,
where he stood backstage and listened as Roger belted out a pair of
songs.
</P>
<P>
   As the U.S. Commander in Chief stepped into the footlights to
give Roger a congratulatory hug, the audience of some 3,900
well-heeled aficionados rose for an enthusiastic ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clintons beamed and waved, looking for all the world like,
well, Seoul brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
