<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2798 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOINO22-COX     11-21 2563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOINO22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio governor at center of complex probe over incenerator
 &HT;    WITH TIMELINE
 &HT;    By Steve Bennish and Ken McCall
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LIVERPOOL, Ohio _ A plume of exhaust from a $160 million
hazardous waste incinerator is wafting far beyond this Ohio River
Valley town, clouding the final days of George Voinovich's eight
years as governor.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-year investigation that is likely to bleed into
Voinovich's first term as a U.S. Senator, federal authorities are
attempting to trace a complex trail. It leads from Waste Technology
Industries' high-tech and highly controversial incinerator to a now
defunct state-funded pollution monitoring agency, to a landfill
needed for construction of a county jail project.
</P>
<P>
   The trail also connects Paul Voinovich and lobbyist Anthony
Fabiano, whose clients included WTI. Fabiano's employment of union
leader Anthony Gallagher led to questionable expenditures during
the governor's 1994 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Voinovich denies any impropriety and has promised to
cooperate fully with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this is all said and done, the governor's integrity will
be totally intact, and I'm totally confident that there will be a
finding of no wrongdoing,'' said state Republican Chairman Bob
Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   The sprawling investigation by elements of the FBI, IRS Criminal
Investigation Division, Department of Labor and a federal grand
jury in Cincinnati appears to be focusing on possible political and
governmental misdeeds in a corner of Ohio far from major city power
centers.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jefferson County seat of Steubenville, Sheriff Fred
Abdalla watches the unfolding saga. The investigation began with
his office and that of county rosecutor Stephen Stern before
federal authorities took up the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Abdalla said he began investigating allegations that former
North Ohio Valley Air Authority director Pasquale ``Patsy'' DeLuca
and employee Vincent Zumpano pressured local industries for payoffs
to settle regulatory problems. NOVAA had an $847,000 annual
contract with the state Ohio Environmental Protection Agency to
monitor air pollution in six counties until September of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``NOVAA was responsible for any industry with a smoke stack in
the Ohio Valley,'' Abdalla said. ``We got information and
allegations there could be possible payoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Former NOVAA board chairman Frank Petrola said he helped
initiate various probes when he became aware of the allegations.
``The tentacles go way out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DeLuca declined comment. ``I have no comment on any of that
stuff, `` he said. ``I have an attorney and am trying to get that
straightened out.''
</P>
<P>
   Zumpano couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bribery conviction
</P>
<P>
   DeLuca hasn't been charged with any offense, but the grand jury
has issued subpoenas seeking documents ``pertaining to'' him.
Zumpano hasn't been charged in this case, but in 1997 he was
convicted of the attempted bribery of a Jefferson County
commissioner and received a six-month prison sentence. The 1993
bribery attempt, caught on tape by sheriff's investigators, was to
secure a jail construction management contract for the V Group, a
Cleveland-based construction firm headed by the governor's brother
Paul.
</P>
<P>
   A V Group spokesman has denied Zumpano represented them. Phone
records and an investigation by Stern's office, however, show that
Zumpano made at least some of the hundreds of phone calls from
NOVAA and other offices where Zumpano worked to the V Group's
Cleveland office phone and fax machine between December 1992 and
December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Calls were also tracked from NOVAA to lobbyist Fabiano, and back
and forth from Zumpano's home phone to Paul Voinovich's unlisted
home phone.
</P>
<P>
   During that time period, calls also were placed from NOVAA to
the V Group's former lobbyist in Columbus, Stern found. Zumpano
began working at NOVAA in 1992 and for 10 years was a member of the
Jefferson County Board of Elections _ where other calls to the V
Group originated.
</P>
<P>
   How far the federal investigation goes is anyone's guess, but
three federal subpoenas served on the Ohio Environmental Protection
Agency in Columbus have sought volumes of memos and correspondence
from the governor's office on down, deep into the bureaucratic
bowels of the state's leading environmental regulatory agency.
Agents have hauled away two boxes of documents from state files.
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. Attorney's Office in Cincinnati has steadfastly
refused to comment on the investigation, a source close to the case
said indictments are not likely to be returned from the grand jury
until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Elections commission complaint
</P>
<P>
   In August, the U.S. Attorney released grand jury testimony that
resulted in two complaints to the Ohio Elections Commission
involving Gov. Voinovich, his brother Paul, and officials from the
V Group and the governor's 1994 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One complaint accuses the governor, his campaign treasurer
Vincent Panichi, Paul Voinovich, lobbyist Anthony Fabiano and the
campaign consulting firm Mamais &AMP; Associates of ``misrepresenting''
a $60,000 campaign expenditure in 1994. The other complaint accuses
Fabiano, his company, ECIC, Inc., the V Group, and V Group Vice
President Frank Fela of improperly using corporate funds for
partisan political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Nichols, president of the International Union of
Electrical Workers in Trumbull County, filed an additional
complaint Thursday alleging campaign finance reporting violations
based on the same transactions. Nichols' attorney is Donald
McTigue, who has represented the state Democratic Party in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   The $60,000 payment was allegedly used to reimburse Paul
Voinovich and Fabiano for payments made to longtime Voinovich
supporter Anthony Gallagher for work on the governor's campaign.
Corporations are not allowed to contribute to political campaigns,
so any campaign work while on the Fabiano &AMP; Associates payroll
would amount to an illegal corporate contribution.
</P>
<P>
   The money was reported by the campaign as an expenditure for
``voter program development'' to Mamais &AMP; Associates, which served
as a conduit for the cash. Panichi told the grand jury Gov.
Voinovich approved the arrangement during a meeting he attended
with Paul Voinovich.
</P>
<P>
   According to grand jury testimony by Fela, Fabiano hired
Gallagher after consulting with Paul Voinovich. Gallagher, a
longtime pipefitters union representative, had been appointed by
the governor in early 1994 to the Industrial Commission of Ohio,
but declined to take the post when his previously ``expunged''
criminal record came to light. Fela said Fabiano and Paul Voinovich
wanted to ``be helpful'' until Gallagher could find another job.
</P>
<P>
   Fabiano paid Gallagher's salary by reducing a $6,000 monthly
``retainer'' he'd been sending the V Group. The reason for the
retainer has yet to be publicly explained. V Group spokesman Tom
Andrzejewski declined to say why Fabiano _ then a lobbyist for WTI
_ needed an architectural and engineering firm on a retainer.
``That's a private business relationship,'' Andrzejewski said,
``and the V Group has a policy of not discussing private business
relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Fela told the grand jury that Paul Voinovich was
``furious'' when he learned his company's retainer had been reduced
by $30,000 during 1994 because of the payments to Gallagher.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Voinovich then asked his brother for reimbursement for the
payments to Gallagher, and suggested the payment be made through
Mamais &AMP; Associates, according to grand jury testimony by Panichi,
Voinovich's campaign treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   A probable cause hearing is scheduled for Dec. 10 in Columbus on
the election complaints but may be delayed by this week's complaint
by Nichols. The commission could act at the hearing, said director
Phil Richter, it could hand the case to a special investigator, or
it could hold more complete hearings at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum penalties for the governor include a $10,000 fine and
loss of state office. It's unlikely, however, that a state law
could be used to take away his U.S. Senate seat. The commission has
no authority to impose fines or penalties either, Richter said. The
case would have to be referred to a prosecutor and taken to court.
</P>
<P>
   Panichi refused to comment on the case. Calls to the V Group
were referred to spokesman Andrzejewski. Anthony Gallagher has
suffered a stroke, according to his wife, and is not available for
comment. Nick Mamais is deceased and Mamais &AMP; Associates is out of
business. Anthony Fabiano could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Voinovich's attorney, David Young, said the governor denies
the representation of facts given to the commission and expects to
be cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, witnesses continue to appear before the grand jury in
Cincinnati and are being questioned by Assistant U.S. Attorney
Kathleen Brinkman, a source close to the proceedings said. No date
for concluding the investigation has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Ohio connections
</P>
<P>
   Bits and scraps left behind in the investigation's wake include
three detailed subpoenas served on the OEPA between August of last
year and May, suggestive snippets of heavily censored grand jury
testimonies from Gallagher, Panichi and others, a likewise edited
account of an FBI interview with V Group Vice President Fela and
two pages from a lengthy statement of facts compiled by IRS
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoenas demand records that could show links among WTI's
incinerator in East Liverpool, a Steubenville area landfill, and a
laundry list of state governor's office and environmental
regulatory officials, Columbus lobbyists and V Group employees.
</P>
<P>
   The recurring theme of the subpoenas is NOVAA, the now- defunct
agency the state OEPA employed for 25 years to monitor air
pollution in Belmont, Carroll, Columbiana, Harrison, Jefferson and
Monroe counties.
</P>
<P>
   WTI's incinerator was one of the largest plants on NOVAA's
monitoring list. In addition, WTI entered into separate
arrangements with NOVAA for additional monitoring and studies.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, which has withstood lengthy and heated protests from
local residents, is owned by the Switzerland-based Von Roll Group.
It employs 184 people and ranks as the seventh-largest commercial
U.S. incinerator, consuming 60,000 tons of waste annually.
</P>
<P>
   WTI officials acknowledge their relations with NOVAA were _ at
least for a time _ antagonistic. They say they hired lobbyist
Fabiano in February 1994 as a consultant to work on ``improving
this relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The way NOVAA's former board chairman Petrola sees it, however,
executive director DeLuca took advantage of WTI's difficult public
position in the community, directing WTI to hire lobbyist Fabiano
for $27,000 a month. In addition, the company paid for additional
NOVAA-connected environmental studies that were not required by the
state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how much WTI paid NOVAA for the additional
monitoring, but in a statement the company acknowledged paying more
than $100,000 for one study that was never completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (WTI) had so much public animosity, they needed a clean
slate,'' Petrola said. ``They paid a ton of money.'' According a
prepared statement by WTI, company officials hired ``a consultant
to manage downward politically toward better relations with a local
agency.'' As for a connection to Paul Voinovich: ``WTI never
attempted to 'go through Paul Voinovich' to curry favor with state
government,'' according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Results of a special state audit underscore Petrola's concerns
about NOVAA. In March of last year, state auditor Jim Petro found
more than $24,000 in funds were illegally collected by NOVAA's
DeLuca in unauthorized severance payments, unallowable travel and
lodging expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The audit also found NOVAA collected special fees directly from
local industries to conduct some monitoring tasks _ an arrangement
unknown to OEPA officials who approved NOVAA's $800,000 annual
state funding.
</P>
<P>
   Employees signed ``individual agreements'' with DeLuca to
perform the services, according to the audit. These fees padded
various NOVAA employees' regular paychecks by $54,000 in 1995 and
$33,723 the first half of 1997, the audit said. The audit also
found NOVAA executive director DeLuca made NOVAA employees work on
agency time to build and staff an entertainment complex he co-owns.
</P>
<P>
   WTI spokesman Raymond Wayne explained company officials approved
additional monitoring in an effort to appease local critics. ``To
paint it as if we were paying off a regulator is inappropriate,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Local critics, many living within sight of the facility, have
seized on the extra studies, saying they call into question the
independence of a regulator paid by the plant it is supposed to be
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel there are still many questions that are unanswered,''
said Alonzo Spencer, one of the plant's most vociferous critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a conflict of interest that is very disturbing,'' said
Sandy Estell, who with her husband and five children lives on a
river bluff 800 feet from the incinerator.
</P>
<P>
   To date, residents say, the most serious incident occurred on a
March 1995 afternoon when a strong odor chased some locals from
their homes. WTI promised NOVAA it would prevent a recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   OEPA's contract with NOVAA expired in September 1997 and was not
renewed. OEPA staffers now have the monitoring job.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal reviews of the plant, including a General
Accounting Office report and an eight-volume U.S. EPA review, have
said the plant overall poses no significant risks to residents.
</P>
<P>
   WTI spokesman Wayne wouldn't comment about the investigation,
but he called WTI ``the most scrutinized hazardous waste treatment
plant in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Final Days
</P>
<P>
   Documents forwarded from the grand jury to the Ohio Elections
Commission indicate investigators are exploring possible
connections between Fabiano, the former WTI lobbyist, and the
governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   An Internal Revenue Service document says Mike Parkes, a WTI
spokesman, told Fabiano that then Voinovich Chief of Staff Paul
Mifsud helped the lobbyist get the WTI contract. Parkes could not
be reached.
</P>
<P>
   The WTI incinerator isn't the only northeast Ohio enterprise of
interest to federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury subpoena to the OEPA targets a landfill connected
to the Jefferson County Jail project. The landfill was needed for
demolition debris from the jail site. The V Group did the
architectural work for the project and eventually received the
construction management contract.
</P>
<P>
   The demolition landfill permit came during a period when OEPA
had declared a statewide moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Grand jury subpoenas request documents from Ohio EPA Director
Donald R. Schregardus, another top OEPA official, Gerry Ioannides;
Gov. Voinovich, his executive assistant, Andy Futey; former chief
of staff Mifsud, and various other state officials, lobbyists,
consultants and contractors.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years as a popular governor, this clearly was not
the way George Voinovich wanted to spend his final days in the
statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Said Republican Chairman Bennett: ``I think the governor is very
disappointed that this all happened now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
