NYT-11-21-98 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981121.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2801 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVINGSTON22-COX     11-21 2344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Era of the `Anti-Newt'
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANDEVILLE, La. _ His first job was cleaning up after elephants
in the New Orleans zoo; some people like to say he has come full
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Livingston (R-La.), who was chosen Wednesday to succeed
U.S. Rep. Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) as speaker of the House, is not
flashy, but he says he will clean up the mess left by the November
elections. He promises no contracts with America and no Republican
revolution, just good management of the day-to-day business of the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people want, demand and deserve good, solid,
conscientious, honest government dealing with the toughest problems
that face the country,'' Livingston said last Saturday at a
barbecue fund-raiser in his congressional district outside New
Orleans. More than 500 supporters paying $100 a couple stood in
line in the rain to shake hands with the man they call friendly,
down-to-earth and above all, honest.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, he is the anti-Newt. The 55-year-old Livingston,
who is 6-foot-5 with a booming voice to match, has the humble goal
of making the metaphorical trains run on time. He'll spend most of
his days in Washington, not on the road spreading the gospel of
conservatism as Gingrich has, and he vows to work long hours and
weekends doing what he does best _ good old-fashioned governing.
</P>
<P>
   After his selection as speaker by the Republicans Wednesday,
Livingston pledged to cooperate with Democrats. ``We Republicans
lose nothing by reaching out to the other side, to talk and listen
and work in tandem with those who may share some of our goals and
dreams,'' he said. He doesn't plan any major agenda changes, just a
radical change in management style.
</P>
<P>
   This much about Livingston is predictable, and comes as a relief
for many people who were tired of riding Gingrich's roller coaster
of inflammatory statements and controversy. Unlike Gingrich, who
became a reviled figure to Democrats and even to a good share of
Republicans, it is hard to find anyone, Democrat or Republican, who
doesn't like or at least accept Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   That appeal goes back to his earliest days as a politician, said
Melvin Bush, who has worked for Livingston since he became a
congressman 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a populist,'' he said. Livingtson's district used to
include several New Orleans housing projects, and Livingston
captured 78 percent of the black vote in his first election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once, he knocked on a woman's door and said, `Hi, I'm Bob
Livingston and I want to work for you,''' said Bush, who imitated
his boss' voice and drew himself up a little taller to tell his
story. ``The woman said, `Come on in, I've got some dishes in the
back and the bathroom's dirty.'''
</P>
<P>
   What struck Bush and other black people in the district was that
after Livingston won, he didn't forget them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went to the black churches to campaign, like many
politicians, but then he'd go back and thank them,'' Bush said.
``Nobody ever did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston has represented the 1st District here for two
decades, running uncontested in the last two elections and winning
81 percent of the vote in the 1994 race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Democrat and I think he's great,'' said Velma Pitre, who
was shopping in Livingston's district last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll get Democrats to buy into programs they would
have been opposed to,'' predicted Suzanne Villa of Mande-
</P>
<P>
   ville.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one Republican is wondering if the party will be
sorry Gingrich is gone once his antithesis takes the reins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Livingston has enormous shoes to fill,'' said former state
Sen. Ben Bagert of New Orleans. ``The Republicans won't even be
able to hang on to the House unless Bob Livingston demonstrates an
ability to clearly articulate a Republican vision for America. My
advice to Bob would be to get up every morning and after you say
your prayers read one of Newt's speeches. Good management is
important, but at the national level, the more important asset for
a leader is to be the ideologue who can articulate.''
</P>
<P>
   That `endearing goofiness'
</P>
<P>
   So if he's not Newt Gingrich, who is he?
</P>
<P>
   At the ``Bob-B-Q'' in Mandeville last Saturday, Livingston
towered over his constituents, shaking hands, remembering names and
hugging friends. There were banners everywhere that read,
``Livingston: Speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Bonnie, stood by his side, smiling and patiently
answering questions from reporters who crowded around her.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Livingston recently went to lunch with Gingrich's wife,
Marianne, to learn what to expect as speaker's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me what was good and what was bad,'' she said. ``She
said the unfair criticism was bad. But Bob comes in without being
the person who caused the other party to go out of office, so he'll
have fewer problems, hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   When a cheerleading squad from a local high school performed a
special cheer for the presumptive speaker, Livingston cheered with
them, pumping his fist in the air and even dancing a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see that?'' Bush said. ``He's always been just like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Linlithgow said Livingston's straight-arrow, slighty
dorky image is no act. His media consultant, Ray Teddlie, calls it
an ``an endearing goofiness,'' and the New Orleans Times-Picayune
called him the ``standard-bearer of the fuddy-duddy wing of the
Republican Party.'' Conservative but ``fun,'' is how Bush describes
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a throwback to an earlier era,'' Teddlie said. ``He is
`Mr. Smith Goes to Washington.' Jimmy Stewart incarnate.''
</P>
<P>
   Teddlie says he may seem like a boy scout, but like a good
Louisianan, Livingston knows when to kick back and have fun. He
drinks beer with the best of them and hits the dance floor when the
Cajun fiddle starts up at his annual crawfish boil, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a big money-raiser, but it's a lot of fun,'' Teddlie
said.
</P>
<P>
   And he's no pushover _ he has a black belt in tae kwon do, and
is now famous for his temper and his occasional House floor
theatrics, such as playing the harmonica or wielding an alligator
skinning knife to illustrate how he would cut the budget.
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't afraid to criticize President Clinton at the
Mandeville event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to challenge President Clinton to lead,'' he said.
``You know, too many times he's been able to sit back and let the
Republican Congress set the tone, and then he snatches it up. We
think it's about time he comes up with his initiatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston is a classic Republican, opposed to abortion, a
fiscal conservative who favors smaller government and reduced
taxes. As chairman of the Appropriations Committee, he cut $50
billion in government spending in his first year. To date, the
committee has cut 300 programs and frozen spending. His favorite
book is ``Atlas Shrugged'' by Ayn Rand, the libertarian classic
that extols the power of the individual.
</P>
<P>
   But Livingston fights proposed cuts in defense spending and is a
friend to business, especially the oil industry, which dominates
the Louisiana economy.
</P>
<P>
   His fund raiser last Saturday said a lot about his congressional
district. It was held in a rather sterile corporate office park and
was attended mostly by whites. The district, whose lines were
redrawn to exclude most of New Orleans, is more than 80 percent
white, suburban and increasingly Republican _ much like Gingrich's
Georgia district. It contains generations-old, blue-collar
neighborhoods and mushrooming subdivisions filled with people
fleeing New Orleans' inner city troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Founding father ancestor
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was born in Colorado but grew up in an old section of
New Orleans off St. Charles Avenue, moving to the suburbs only when
district lines were redrawn to exclude the city. On his father's
side, he comes from an aristocratic line of early Americans that
includes a signer of the Declaration of Independence and an
orchestrator of the Louisiana Purchase.
</P>
<P>
   But Livingston takes no pride in his lineage; the family fortune
was wiped out in the Depression, and his father, an alcoholic, left
his family to fend for themselves when Livingston was 7 years old.
He is now dead. His mother worked and managed to make enough money
to raise Livingston and his sister in what has been characterized
as a ``semi-blue collar'' style.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've become, I owe not to geneology, but to my mother,''
he told a Baton Rouge Advocate reporter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-year stint in the Navy, Livingston worked his way
through school, selling Fuller brushes and working as a welder at
Avondale Shipyards, now Avondale Industries Inc. He received his
bachelor's and law degrees from Tulane, and went briefly into
private practice. But he disliked it and moved to the Orleans
Parish District Attorney's Office _ where he worked for Harry
Connick Sr. _ and later to the Louisiana Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the same as he is now,'' Connick said of his former
employee. ``Affable, aggressive, and he took his job seriously. He
could get a little red-faced once in a while, but outrage shows
interest in what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's supporters like to portray him as a friend to the
common man. They point out that when he ran for Congress in 1976,
he had just $5,000 in the bank, all of which went into the
campaign. Two of his staffers, when asked which of the world-famous
New Orleans restaurants Livingston frequents, shrugged and couldn't
name one. They say he's more likely to eat a Big Mac in the car
than to sit down at Commander's Palace. A big treat is going to his
old neighborhood in New Orleans and eating an oyster po-boy _ fried
oysters sandwiched in crumbly french bread _ at Domilise's. ``I've
seen him pull a discount shirt out of a plastic bag in his
briefcase and put it on,'' Teddlie said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston was elected to represent the 1st District in a
special election in 1977. He lost the original election by 3
percent, but his opponent then resigned in the midst of a voter
fraud scandal. Livingston has held the seat ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's main residence is outside Washington, but he keeps
a town house in Metairie, about 20 minutes from New Orleans. His
three sons live in Louisiana; his daughter, who is adopted, lives
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. David Vitter, a Republican in Livingston's district,
says the would-be speaker's background is one of the most appealing
things about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His coming from a very modest background and getting ahead
through old-fashioned hard work and diligence says a lot about what
he brings to the job,'' he said. ``He is not a country club
Republican in any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But Livingston isn't necessarily reveling in his lack of riches.
He almost resigned in February in part because he knew he could
double or triple his salary if he moved to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Gingrich who talked him into staying. It was
also Gingrich who plucked him from obscurity four years ago, naming
him chairman of the powerful House Appropriations Committee. It is
unlikely that, before 1994, Livingston had any idea he would one
day be third in line to the president. John Maginnis, an expert in
Louisiana politics, said Livingston predicted in 1988 he would
never achieve more than being a low-profile U.S. representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `John, I've been here 10 years, and I have no power,
I'll probably serve 10 more years and still have no power,'''
Maginnis said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the last time Livingston aspired to a higher office,
he buckled under pressure and lost. In 1987, he and Edwin Edwards,
the flamboyant governor who was twice indicted on racketeering
charges in the 1980s, were in a close race for governor. But in a
statewide televised forum, Livingston went blank in the middle of a
sentence and said, ``I've lost my train of thought.'' He lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really stiffed up,'' Maginnis said. ``But in the end, it
was probably the best thing that could have happened to him.''
</P>
<P>
   A $32 million favor
</P>
<P>
   Livingston doesn't forget the people who keep returning him to
Washington. After all, it isn't just his pleasant demeanor that
keeps the voters happy; Livingston is generous to his home state.
He has sent millions of federal dollars and many jobs to his
district and to Louisiana as a whole. He is credited with the
creation of a massive urban drainage program of pump stations and
canals that has cost $100 million in two years. He secured federal
money to extend the streetcar line of Canal Street in New Orleans,
and he pushed for the construction of several new buildings for an
information technology center at the University of New Orleans. His
old employer, Avondale, currently has contracts totaling $2.1
billion in back-ordered work for the Navy and the U.S. Coast Guard,
including options for ships not yet ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Sam Caruso of Slidell recalls fondly a $32 million favor
Livingston did for him a few years back.
</P>
<P>
   NASA moved some computer operations from Slidell to Huntsville,
Ala., leaving a huge facility vacant. There is a law that prohibits
local governments from taking control of federally-owned property,
but Caruso wanted the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Bob,'' he said. ``I said: `Bob, you can put a
particular law in place that overrides a general law. Write a law
that gives us ownership of that federal facility.' I gotta tell
you, he put it together and today, we own that facility. Is that a
good deal or what?''
</P>
<P>
   There's one more reason why Livingston is loved here; not only
is he the opposite of Gingrich, he is also the antithesis of the
stereotypical Louisiana politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has a worse image about politics than the state of
Louisiana,'' said Delton Charles, who is retired and lives in
Metairie. ``You wanna talk about bad politics, you start with
Louisiana. Livingston will bring new respect _ people will see that
not everyone in the state is a bum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
