<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981121.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOROCCO22-COX     11-21 2441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOROCCO22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senses come alive on streets of Morocco
 &HT;    By Tom Peeling
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FEZ, Morocco _ As our tour bus rumbled off the ferry and headed
for the Moroccan border, our Spanish guide had a warning for us:
</P>
<P>
   ``The switches on the walls, the lamps, the toilets ...'' He
paused a minute. ``In many cases, they're decorative.''
</P>
<P>
   Translated: They don't work.
</P>
<P>
   And he was right.
</P>
<P>
   We were midway through a 16-day bus tour when we left the
comforts of Spain and Portugal, crossed the Straits of Gibraltar
and headed into Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Two seacoast towns in northern Africa still belong to Spain, so
our bus with 38 tourists from the United States, Australia, Canada,
England and Syria had to drive a while to get to Morocco's border.
We waited as our tour guide, Adolfo, went into police headquarters.
He was gone a good 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When Adolfo returned to the bus, a policeman came with him. It
was a little unnerving as the officer went down the aisle, checking
each person's passport and the form we had to fill out for each day
of our visit, noting where we were staying and where we would be
headed the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, we were cleared to go, and a Moroccan national guide
joined our tour. He would stay with us for our six days in Meknes,
Rabat, Tangier, Casablanca and our first stop, Fez.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I knew we were headed into a Third World country. We
had been to Venezuela, but that had not prepared us for what we
would see now.
</P>
<P>
   We drove south for five or six hours through winding mountain
roads. We saw our first camels and enjoyed the beautiful pink
oleanders blooming throughout the hills. We marveled at the nomads
living in tents in the fields, watching their flocks and washing
their clothes in the river and hanging them on the bushes to dry.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasts were remarkable. In one little village, we saw men
throwing wheat into the air to separate the chaff from the grain,
right next to an outdoor cafe where a crowd of men gathered around
a large-screen TV watching a World Cup soccer match. A satellite
dish adorned the roof.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived in Fez late in the evening, after a 14-hour day of
travel. As we entered our room, suitcases in hand, we flicked on
the light switch. Nothing. Our first run-in with ``decorative
fixtures.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one electrical outlet in the room, leaving us with a
choice of watching the television or recharging the video camera
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   We arose early the next morning for our tour of the Old Medina,
or market, with Mohammed, our national guide. As we left the hotel,
we were surrounded by young men selling trinkets _ metal plates,
small leather camels, change purses, fez hats and more. Every move
we made over the next six days would be followed closely by the
street vendors.
</P>
<P>
   We entered one of the gates into the Medina, staying close to
our guide. We wound our way over the cobblestone streets for the
next three hours. Stalls lined the huge market, where vendors sold
everything _ food, clothing, pots and pans, jewelry, live chickens.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow ``streets'' were just wide enough for about three
people to pass abreast. But with the merchandise spilling out onto
the pathway and donkeys carrying full loads, single file was
usually the best our group could do. We all feared losing our way;
the Medina has to be the world's largest maze.
</P>
<P>
   We saw two boys who had spilled a bucket of chickpeas on the
cobblestones picking them up and putting them back in the bucket to
be sold.
</P>
<P>
   The cobblestones were wet. We shouldn't have asked. Donkey
urine, we were told.
</P>
<P>
   Our senses came alive. The overwhelming smell of farm animals,
the arguing in French and Arabic, the unnerving sights of flies
crawling on the meat for sale out in the heat and goat heads, fur
and all, laying in rows on the counters.
</P>
<P>
   We had an unofficial guide for our market tour. A boy of about
10 named Omar would tell us to ``watch our steps'' as we went down
stairs, or ``to the left'' or ``to the right'' as we turned. Once
we had passed him, he'd run ahead to the next obstacle and warn us
again. It reminded me of the nomads herding their sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Omar did it all for tips. And he was so cute we just
wanted to take him home with us.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of the Medina is the Qarawiyin (Kar-a-wyn) mosque,
built in 857 (yes, 857, not 1857). Only the Muslim man from Syria
in our group was allowed in, but the rest of us could peek through
the entrances into an area that holds 2,000 worshipers. Walls and
floors were entirely covered with tiny, colorful tiles.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, we emerged on the other side of the Medina, and,
true to Cosmos Tour Co. form, there was Telex, our bus driver. It
was close to 100 degrees that day, so it was wonderful to fall back
into our air-conditioned motorcoach.
</P>
<P>
   We circled the city to get a good look at the wall that
surrounds it, harkening back to the days when neighboring villages
weren't quite so friendly. We passed the Muslim cemetery, outside
the city wall, where the graves all faced east, toward Mecca in
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   We had some free time that afternoon, so Mohammed arranged a
walking tour of the newer part of the city. Many cafes lined the
streets, with men sitting together at tables. In Arab tradition,
men and women did not socialize in the same places.
</P>
<P>
   Each store owner had a photo of King Hassan II hanging over the
checkout area. The king is much beloved in this social monarchy, as
is his predecessor, Mohammed V. In fact, the main street in every
town is named Avenue Mohammed V.
</P>
<P>
   On a bus tour, you see a lot, but you don't spend a lot of time
in each town. After two nights in Fez, we were off to the capital,
Rabat.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived in Rabat around noon and were thrilled to see the
American flag flying over the embassy there. We grabbed a salad for
lunch. We had been warned about eating uncooked vegetables, but it
was hot, and the cold tossed salad looked so good we couldn't
resist. We'd all pay for it a day or two later, when most of
tourists experienced some ``abdominal distress.''
</P>
<P>
   Our last day in Morocco was spent in Tangier, where we visited
the home of the late Malcolm Forbes (it's now a toy soldier
museum). The rear of the home overlooks the place where the
Atlantic and Mediterranean come together.
</P>
<P>
   We rode a camel and learned to hold on tight. You'd better, or
when it goes down on its front knees to let you off, you might find
the ground sooner than expected.
</P>
<P>
   We felt the least comfortable in Tangier than anywhere else on
the trip. First, a man approached us on the street and offered to
give us a ``private tour.'' We said no, but he continued to follow
us for several blocks. We later saw him sitting at the cafe across
the street, waiting for tourists to come out of our hotel.
</P>
<P>
   We ventured out alone very little here. Because we looked more
``Western'' than most folks, we always had the feeling we were
being watched.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, our hotel in Tangier had its ``decorative features''
as well. This time, it was the toilet. The front desk sent the
French maid up to fix it. She looked it over and announced it
``broke.'' End of conversation. But if we used our garbage can to
fill the tank with water, we could get it to flush.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, we left to meet our ferry back to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Our bus pulled up to the customs office, and we all got in line
to show our passports. When it was our turn, my wife and I handed
our passports and registration forms to two men in a glass booth.
One man looked at my form and noted to the other man that where it
said ``Occupation,'' I had written ``Journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men conferred, then the first man asked me the name of
the television station where I worked. I told him I worked at a
newspaper. The two conferred again, as my wife and I got a little
nervous. Folks behind us in line were waiting, and wondering.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the first man asked the questions. What newspaper did I
work for?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Florida, U.S.A.,'' I
said. They talked again, wrote the name of the newspaper down and
finally told us to pass through.
</P>
<P>
   We breathed a sigh of relief, got on the ferry, and watched the
African coast fade into the distance.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Tours: Cosmos and Globus Tours both offer a number of tours to
Morocco, as well as some in combination with tours of Spain and/or
Portugal. See your travel agent for information, or check out
either on the Internet at: http://www.cosmostours.com
</P>
<P>
   Money: The currency of Morocco is the dirham (pronounced
der-um), with an exchange rate of about 10 to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Tips: Don't drink the water. Use bottled water to brush your
teeth as well.
</P>
<P>
   Don't eat anything that's not cooked and served hot, no matter
how tempting the salads may be. Only eat fruit that has been
peeled.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet: One of the better Web sites for learning about
the country is at http://www.rhizomatics.demon.co.uk/travel/
</P>
<P>
   morocco.html
</P>
<P>
   CASABLANCA SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   Casablanca. The name brings to mind romance, intrigue, danger.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't Hollywood, and we didn't find Ilsa, Sam or
Rick's Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   What we found instead was that the little town portrayed in the
movies has 3 million residents today, with another 3 million people
living in the outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   Casablanca is the industrial and governmental center of
Mor-occo. The city, with its huge port, sits on the Atlantic coast
with beautiful beaches.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the city has to be the Hassan II Mosque,
completed in the past few years. It is the largest mosque outside
of Mecca, our guide told us, holding up to 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Casa, as the natives call the city, is the most modern place in
Morocco. Western clothing predominates.
</P>
<P>
   We even broke down and ate at a McDonald's, where my wife,
Becky, had a chance to try out her somewhat rusty French. French is
much more predominant in Casablanca than in the rest of the
country, where Arabic is spoken most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   While beautiful, with pretty promenades and city parks,
Casablanca is really just another big city.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Louie, but it wasn't the beginning of a beautiful
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   BARGAINING SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   I like to think of myself as something of a bargainer.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, if I knew there was any shot of Publix selling me
bananas for 19 cents a pound instead of 39 cents, I'd haggle with
the produce guy.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a car isn't a headache for me; it's a bargaining bonanza.
Antique shows? I'm in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a case of being cheap, although I do know all the $3.95
to $4.95 lunch places in town.
</P>
<P>
   But when I got to Morocco, I soon realized I was out of my
league.
</P>
<P>
   We'd read in the tour book that if you can buy things for 50
percent of the marked price, you're doing great. Don't expect more,
but if you can get more, take it.
</P>
<P>
   Our first experience with the Moroccan way of doing business was
at a restroom stop when we entered the country. A man with a
blanket spread on the ground had his own little flea market going.
He had pens, old coins, other trinkets, and watches and more
watches.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was hurrying to get back on the bus before it left. But
passing up a flea market, no matter how small, is difficult for me.
So much junk, so little time.
</P>
<P>
   I spotted a silver pocket watch with a locomotive, crescent moon
and star on the front. I had to have it. ``How much?'' I asked the
old man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six hundred dirhams,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calculating quickly, I realized that was about $60.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred fifty dirhams,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Since I knew not one word of Arabic, and his four words of
English weren't helping much, it was a limited conversation. After
calling out more numbers, we finally settled on 300 dirhams, or
$30. I tossed him the dirhams, grabbed the pocket watch and ran for
the bus as the door was closing.
</P>
<P>
   As I slid into my seat all smiles, I finally got to take a close
look at the watch. In tiny letters inside it said ``Hong Kong.''
Probably a $15 pocket watch at Kmart back home, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   First lesson learned. Inspect the merchandise first.
</P>
<P>
   Our second chance at spreading some money around this beautiful
country was in the Old Medina, or old market, in Fez. Our guide had
promised to take us to a carpet shop.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a very primitive, dirty exterior, the inside of the
store was gorgeous. Ceilings 25 feet high greeted us. Walls were
covered with beautifully colored tiles. And carpets, hanging or
standing in rolls, were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   After a mass sales pitch to our group, we were individually
given the hard sell.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I had decided in advance that we would bring a nice,
small carpet home for our new wood floors in our Florida room. With
the huge selection at this co-op, it seemed like the perfect place
to buy one.
</P>
<P>
   I called our Moroccan guide aside and asked him if bargaining
was appropriate here. I mean, this was a nice store, not some
roadside flea market.
</P>
<P>
   He assured us that we probably could get about 10 percent off
the price. Being stupid tourists, we believed him, and that's what
we ended up paying.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I found out we might have been able to do much better if
we'd tried. I didn't feel too badly, since I knew some poor
Moroccan woman had slaved 8 to 9 months to make this rug by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Second bargaining lesson: Don't believe what the national tour
guides tell you. It's worse than asking the real estate agent for
the other party how low they'll go.
</P>
<P>
   We had many more chances to bargain during our six days in
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   I bought some small, hand-sewn leather camels for $2.50 each
from a street vendor. (I had to buy three to get him down to that
price, which was 60 percent less than he was asking.) He had chased
me for about four blocks after I had asked him the price.
</P>
<P>
   Third lesson: Don't show interest in an item if you don't intend
to buy it. Some store owners will chase you right out of the store
waving the merchandise at you and yelling prices.
</P>
<P>
   Our biggest surprise was in Casablanca, a large, modern city. We
went into a small department store, and there were Moroccans
bargaining for everything. It was the equivalent of going into
JCPenney and asking if they could do better on the gold earrings.
</P>
<P>
   I found that Moroccans have taken haggling to a new level. I was
in awe.
</P>
<P>
   While walking one day in the capital city of Rabat, we passed a
supermarket. We didn't have time to go inside, but I was sure there
were folks inside getting bananas for 19 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
