<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGSTON-DILEMMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT STANCE COULD DEFINE LIVINGSTON'S TENURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Ill.)  (Eds: See also IMPEACH-WHITEHOUSE) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even before he assumes the speaker's chair in
January, Rep. Robert Livingston, R-La., faces a decision that could
define his tenure as leader of the House and could alter the course
of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   He could go down in history as the man who let Bill Clinton off
the hook. Or he could be remembered as the man who allowed the
impeachment inquiry into Clinton to continue to consume the House
and overshadow any legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   With Newt Gingrich, the current speaker, on vacation, and House
Republicans eager to bid the Gingrich era adieu, the pressure is
building on Livingston to choose his course even before he is
officially elected speaker in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to end unless Livingston steps in here and
takes some kind of leadership role,'' said Laura Nichols, an aide
to Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the Democratic leader. That is also
what some Republicans are saying privately.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment inquiry has defied a tidy solution, barreling
down the track under its own steam even as the public and many on
Capitol Hill scream, ``Stop.'' Livingston himself says he wants it
over by the end of the year. Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of
the Judiciary Committee, has set the same target date. That leaves
the speaker-to-be, who has barely assembled a staff and a team of
advisers, just three workweeks to wrap it up.
</P>
<P>
   But how would he do it? Intervene? Publicly or privately?
Short-circuit the proceedings? Make a deal with the White House and
risk condemnation, as President Ford did for pardoning Richard
Nixon? Or let the ``process'' run its course _ and risk letting
partisanship run amok and being perceived as a weak and ineffective
caretaker?
</P>
<P>
   For the last several months, Capitol Hill has been divided into
two separate worlds. One was impeachment, which got all the
attention. The other was laughingly referred to as ``substance.''
As chairman of the Appropriations Committee, Livingston was
completely outside the impeachment loop, preoccupied with the 13
fiefdoms that oversee the distribution of every federal dollar, and
that this fall became an object of ridicule and horror for
producing a 4,000-page budget that was loaded with pork and that
ceded several items to the president.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was approved at the end of October, quickly followed
by the Nov. 3 elections and Gingrich's surprise resignation.
Livingston was nominated for speaker by his Republican colleagues
just last Wednesday. On Thursday, the Judiciary Committee held its
first impeachment hearings. On Friday, Livingston was still steeped
in the mechanics of his transition, sorting out committee
assignments and chairmanships.
</P>
<P>
   Even without an impeachment inquiry, Livingston has a lot to
think about. He must bring order to an already riven House in which
his party will have a majority of just six votes. Beyond that, he
must captain a leadership team that has been described as a
dysfunctional family. And he will be tested repeatedly by the
do-or-die conservatives from the class of 1994 for whom this may be
the last hurrah. Many are under six-year term limits, making the
coming Congress their last chance to take stands that may uphold
their principles but could undermine their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Livingston has now been catapulted to the
command center of the still-not-dead impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston is a man who likes to leave himself room to maneuver.
He has strong opinions on some subjects and can express them
clamorously, but he can appear enigmatic on others. When his
committee and party were torn apart this fall, for example, by a
debate over whether to give more money to the International
Monetary Fund, he remained aloof.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with impeachment. ``Studied neutrality'' would be a
good description of his forced utterances on the topic. ``If the
Judiciary Committee proves or charges that there is wrongdoing, we
will look at the evidence,'' he said recently. ``I have never
judged this case.''
</P>
<P>
   He has acknowledged that the public does not want the president
impeached and wants the inquiry over. But, as a former federal
prosecutor, he has indicated that the president should be punished
if he committed crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston has generally refrained from moralizing about the
president, providing a sharp contrast to Gingrich, who at one point
said Republicans should condemn the president's conduct in every
speech and who poured millions of dollars into reviving the matter
in commercials just before Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   But a week ago, Livingston did convey some outrage about
Clinton. ``The president of the United States has a responsibility
to the American people to live by the laws, to obey the laws,'' he
said on the Don Imus radio program. ``And if it's proven that he
did not, he's either going to have to be dealt with or he should
voluntarily recognize that he's got a problem. So far, I haven't
heard any singular recognition of his problem. So we'll just have
to let the processes move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Livingston seems uncertain, so do those who have toiled
away inside the world of impeachment. ``Consider the real
possibility,'' one top Republican adviser said, ``that they just
don't know what to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
