u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-COLUMN-XMAS-LIGHTS     11-21 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COLUMN-XMAS-LIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A CHERISHED RIGHT _ UNFETTERED HOLIDAY LIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDMINSTER, N.J. _ This normally genteel township had a people's
revolution the other day.
</P>
<P>
   All right, the uprising did not have the epic sweep of the 1917
storming of the Czar's Winter Palace. The grievance, after all, was
comparatively trivial: a proposed ordinance that would bar
residents from displaying holiday lights more than 30 days before a
holiday and 20 days afterward, with violators facing 15 days in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   But such trivial issues are big deals in small towns. In a place
where lots of people are on a first-name basis with their elected
leaders, people did not want the five township committeemen telling
them when they could showcase their cherished Christmas lights,
blinking shamrocks or incandescent menorahs, particularly because
no one could remember a single fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``People move out of the city and into suburban areas to get
away from the everyday hassles of regulation and foolishness,''
said Bob Merriam, a 30-year resident.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Johnson, who as the Township Committee's lone dissident
became the uprising's Lenin, said the ordinance addressed ``a
nonexistent problem'' while treading on freedom of speech and
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people get elected to public office, they get the feeling
that they have been endowed with the wisdom of Solomon,'' he said.
``They adopt an attitude that, we know what's best for you. It's a
disease of all politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   It was feelings like these that explained why last week's
meeting of the Township Committee _ typically a soporific affair
that draws a half-dozen spectators _ was raucous and overflowing
with 100 Bedminsterites. Johnson's grown children, Kathleen and
Christopher, arrived with strings of Christmas lights laced over
their bodies. Henry Engelbrecht, 73, challenged Committeeman Norman
Lapidus to step outside and settle the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The rhetoric was not the kind usually heard in a township known
for well-bred rich families, including the Forbeses, the Dillons,
and the Frelinghuysens. When advocates argued that the law was
really designed to allow holiday lights _ since anything not
explicitly permitted was implicitly prohibited _ opponents minced
no words in calling the reasoning plain silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say I want to pick my nose,'' Merriam said. ``Because
there's no law saying I can, it's illegal? I'm going to pick my
nose whenever I want to, and I'm going to put lights on my house
whenever I want to.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd's hostility was so intimidating that the four
committeemen who had seen some merit in the ordinance fell over
each other to kill it. Residents will be able to put up Christmas
lights any time they want.
</P>
<P>
   Bedminster is mostly horse country, a gently rolling landscape
whose families have been known to stable their horses in
brass-fitted stalls more elegant than some hotel rooms. But it is
also a township that has felt the heavy hand of government.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the so-called Mount Laurel court rulings intended
to increase low- and moderate-income housing in New Jersey's
suburbs, the township has seen its population triple to 8,400 in
less than a generation _ with most of the parvenus packed
cheek-by-jowl in a warren of condos and town houses known as The
Hills. Overnight, residents have had to wrestle with inadequate
schools and roadways.
</P>
<P>
   That's partly why those regrouping after the lighting victory
are bracing to pounce on even trifling examples of government
overreaching, like another proposed ordinance that would restrict
the height of grass on homeowners' lawns to eight inches.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Don Cross, a burly relative newcomer to town, favored
consideration of the holiday-lights ordinance. He calls opponents
of the measure elitists, curmudgeons, obstructionists and
``nasties,'' flavoring his epithets with a Texas twang that no
doubt helped him land the part of Richard Widmark's double in a
1961 John Ford western. He cautions that there could be disputes
among neighbors over extravagant displays.
</P>
<P>
   But sound reasoning, he said, was lost in the frenzy of revolt.
Now, he laments, his diligent administration will ``be remembered
for a stupid ordinance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We make mistakes,'' he conceded. ``That's why there are
erasers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
