<HEADLINE>
DISAPPEARING IN THE CATSKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With CATSKILLS-JOBLESS)  
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The closing of the Concord Resort Hotel leaves only a
handful of the famous Catskills resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the acknowledged queen of the hotels,
Grossinger's, closed after steadily declining for years, said John
Conway, an expert on Sullivan County history. So did the Pines,
which was in South Fallsburg and, like many of the hotels, became
prominent in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Other names from the past have been closed for much longer. The
Flagler closed in the early 1970s and is now the Crystal Run School
for developmentally disabled children. Four hotels _ the Brickman,
the Windsor, the Gilberts and the Nemerson _ have also been closed
since the early 1970s and are now part of a collection of private
religious centers operated by the followers of an Indian guru,
Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stevensville closed in the early 1980s, Conway said. But its
new owners plan to reopen it in early 1999 as the Swan Lake Golf
and Tennis Resort Center, said Jonathan Drapkin, the Sullivan
County manager. It will join Kutsher's _ whose patriarch, Milton
Kutsher, died last week _ and the Raleigh as the only vestiges of
the region's storied past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
