<HEADLINE>
CAN YOU NAME THE ORIGINAL NFL TEAMS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What were the original NFL teams? _ A.R., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: In 1920, a group of independent pro football teams formed the
American Professional Football Association, which was renamed the
National Football League two years later.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Professional Football Researchers Association,
the charter teams were the Akron Pros, Buffalo All-Americans,
Canton Bulldogs, Chicago Cardinals, Chicago Tigers, Cleveland
Tigers, Columbus Panhandles, Dayton Triangles, Decatur Staleys,
Detroit Heralds, Hammond Pros, Muncie Flyers, Rochester Jeffersons
and Rock Island Independents.
</P>
<P>
   All of these teams were defunct by 1930, except for two Illinois
teams, the Cardinals and Staleys. Today, they are the Arizona
Cardinals and the Chicago Bears. The Green Bay Packers joined in
1921.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Professional Football Researchers
Association, write to 12870 Route 30, North Huntingdon, PA 15642,
or visit the Web site www.geocities.com/Colosseum/Sideline/5960.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know the meaning, but what does ``cut to the chase'' refer
to? _ N.C.F., Plano
</P>
<P>
   A: The expression is a reference to a director or screenwriter's
instruction in a movie _ ``cut to the chase scene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cut to the chase'' was used in moviemaking as early as 1929,
when a filmmaker wanted the story to progress immediately to a
pursuit, Jesse Sheidlower, a Random House editor, writes on his Web
site. ``The figurative use, which is now quite common, is fairly
recent; it seems to date only from the early 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheidlower publishes Jesse's Word of the Day at
www.randomhouse.com/jesse.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to the author Jerry Pournelle? _ M.D., Fort
Myers, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Pournelle at 12358 Ventura Blvd., Box 372, Studio
City, CA 91604.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the science fiction author and technical writer released
the young-adult novel ``Starswarm.'' Although his longtime role as
a ``Byte'' magazine columnist ended this year when the publication
folded, Pournelle continues to write for the foreign editions of
the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   He also publishes archives of his column at
www.jerrypournelle.com.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
