<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday 11/21/98. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Nov. 21, 1998 -- STARR-REVIEW, 11-21 -- In
testimony before the House Judiciary Committee, Kenneth Starr being
forced to defend himself. The main arguments about the behavior and
approach of Starr and his associates concerned how they have
treated witnesses, notably Monica Lewinsky, and whether they leaked
confidential grand jury proceedings. Critics have also raised other
issues, including whether Starr was involved improperly in Paula
Corbin Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit against the president.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW ORLEANS -- Nov. 21, 1998 -- REPUBLICAN-GOVS, 11-21 --
The Republican Governors Association at a meeting in New Orleans
last week. The governors association is calling for a bigger role
in setting the party's tone and national agenda. They say party
leaders have not given them credit for dominating the nation's
governorships -- there will be 31 Republican Governors come
January. (Lee Celano/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 21, 1998 -- BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN, 11-21 --
Terry Landrum, known as Tito Landrum, a solid baseball player in
the 1980s, earned his degree in physical therapy from New York
University, after his baseball career. He would have been an asset
for any baseball team in the front office, or with a television
network. Instead, Landrum has applied the positive values from
sport toward his own education and a useful career in the broader
world. (Jack Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Nov. 21, 1998 -- JAPANESE-NUNS-RITUALS-2,
11-21 -- A Buddhist nun reading a poem during a service at St.
Paul's Chapel at Columbia University, honoring a medieval abbess,
Mugai Nyodai. Abbess Nyodai, a women of noble birth who was taught
by a Chinese Zen master, founded the first Buddhist convent in
Japan in the early 13th century. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 21, 1998 -- JAPANESE-NUNS-RITUALS-1,
11-21 -- Buddhist nuns from Japan scattering paper petals at St.
Paul's Chapel at Columbia University in a ceremony honoring their
spiritual leader, Abbess Mugai Nyodai. Abbess Nyodai, a women of
noble birth who has been dead for 700 years, helped to nurture Zen
Buddhism in Japan. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 21, 1998 -- CALIF-MOTORCYCLE-DOG-2,
11-21 -- Jeremiah Gerbracht, 58, who has impaired hearing, with his
dog, Lady Harley, a Siberian husky, who likes to ride along on his
motorcycle. Gerbracht has been ticketed five times for riding his
Harley-Davidson with Lady Harley hunched on the gas tank. Gerbracht
insists, he has a civil right to take the dog with him, because
Harley is a hearing dog, and he has impaired hearing. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) LOS ANGELES -- Nov. 21, 1998 -- CALIF-MOTORCYCLE-DOG-1,
11-21 -- Jeremiah Gerbracht, 58, has impaired hearing and is at
odds with officials over whether his dog, Lady Harley, a Siberian
husky, can ride on his motorcycle. Gerbracht has gone to court in
the first three cases, winning each time partly because the
language of the vehicle code, which prohibits unsafe riding by
people, does not apply to animals. ``There is absolutely no law
that prevents animals from riding on a motorcycle,'' he says.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
