<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAILEY, REEVES SHARE WINNING ROOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Chan Gailey needed an NFL job, Dan
Reeves came through. When Gailey needed a recommendation, Reeves
came through again. &QL; 
When Reeves needed a friend in Denver, Gailey was there. But at the
same time, Gailey remained tight with Mike Shanahan and John Elway,
who were not friends of Reeves. &QL; 
When the NFL kicks off Week 12 today, the combined record of teams
coached by Shanahan, Reeves and Gailey will be 25-5. Which speaks
highly of the Broncos' staff of the late '80s. &QL; 
But in the Broncos, Shanahan has the defending Super Bowl champion,
so even 10-0 is not a big surprise. At 8-2 in Atlanta, Reeves is
the leading candidate for coach of the year. ``Absolutely,'' agreed
Gailey, who might get some votes himself since the Cowboys are
7-3. &QL; 
Thus far, however, the biggest winner in the NFL is the small
Georgia town of Americus. &QL; 
Need a coach? Go to Americus. &QL; 
``Chan looked exactly like Opie Taylor,'' Reeves said last week,
recalling his high school days in Americus as a summer-league
baseball coach for grade schoolers. ``But I don't know if Opie
could play. Chan could.'' &QL; 
Americus being the hometown of two current NFL coaches (combined
record, 15-5) is rather unique. ``Must have been something in the
water,'' Gailey said. &QL; 
But as the Cowboys approach a critical point in the schedule
(Seattle today and Minnesota on Thursday), Gailey has a quick reply
for his coaching career having reached this stage. ``Dan Reeves
provided the foundation for where I am today,'' he said. ``I will
be forever indebted to Dan.'' &QL; 
Gailey, eight years younger than Reeves, got his first NFL coaching
chance because of Reeves. &QL; 
``Only now, being a head coach, do I fully realize how much guts it
took for him to hire me in Denver,'' said Gailey, who joined the
Broncos staff in 1985 as special teams coach. ``I was a wishbone
coach from Troy State, who had nothing but a defensive background
in coaching. But I told Dan I wanted to learn NFL offense. And he
let me.'' &QL; 
Offense was and is the specialty of Reeves, of Shanahan, who was
Reeves' offensive coordinator, and, of course, of Elway. ``I walked
into a pretty good learning opportunity,'' said Gailey, smiling. &QL; 
Reeves admits the Americus connection helped Gailey land that first
NFL job. ``But most hires in this business are because of people
you are familiar with,'' he added. ``I knew Chan. I knew his father
and his family. I knew what I was getting. I didn't have any doubts
about him.'' &QL; 
In Denver, Gailey worked and watched and learned. An on-going
subplot there was the strained relationship Shanahan and Elway had
with Reeves. &QL; 
``That's something I don't talk about,'' Gailey said. ``Things
happen in this business, and then they build over time. But
everyone involved is a fine person, despite the differences that
developed. It wasn't like a bad guy and good guy kind of thing.'' &QL; 
As the head coach, Reeves was the focal point. With the future
ambition of holding such a job in the NFL, Gailey took mental
notes. &QL; 
``What I came away with was all the things Dan did really, really
well, and then there were things where I said, `OK, I'd have
handled that differently,' &UR; '' Gailey added. ``Dan is very
demanding, no doubt about it.'' &QL; 
Funny, that's the way the portfolio on Jerry Jones also reads. &QL; 
And when Jones developed a sudden interest in January in Gailey as
a head coaching candidate, he obviously wanted a recommendation
from Reeves. &QL; 
``We were in Indianapolis \Rat the scouting combine\S and Jerry
wanted to talk to me,'' Reeves said. ``I had read the names on his
list and heard the rumors, and then suddenly he mentioned Chan. I
was suprised. &QL; 
``But I told him that this was a good person, a solid coach, and
someone who would be perfect for that franchise. The one thing
about Chan is he could work with Jerry. Chan is not an ego guy at
all. I stressed that to Jerry.'' &QL; 
The question about Gailey, since answered, was would he be tough
enough to bring discipline to a team desperately lacking in it? &QL; 
``I never had a doubt,'' Reeves said. ``Chan is from Americus.
Everybody from Americus is tough.'' &QL; 
Going into today's NFL games, head coaches from Americus are also
winning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
