<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FISH-PACKERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARK DAYS FOR GREEN BAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Death Watch lingers, and hovers, like an
ominous fog that you cannot touch or smell or taste. Yet its
presence is undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   The Death Watch first suggested itself in the off-season, and
then took definitive form on a chilly Monday night in Wisconsin,
and then floated darkly to suburban Detroit, and a few weeks later,
made its presence felt on another Monday night, in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   And today, The Death Watch has tickets on the 50-yard line of
the Metrodome in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers, pronounces safety LeRoy Butler, look for ``an
opportunity to show the world we're an elite team.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler could be right. After all, if the 7-3 Packers upset the
9-1 Minnesota Vikings, the NFC Central title, and maybe home-field
edge in the NFC playoffs, is again a coin flip _ and The Death
Watch might have been knocking on the door of the erstwhile champs
prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   But The Death Watch doesn't hang around where it doesn't belong.
And for as often as it has tailed the 1998 Packers, The Death Watch
might as well be given a locker at Green Bay headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In part because of the expectations we all have,'' says coach
Mike Holmgren, ``this year has at times been a struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably started immediately after Super Bowl XXXII, when the
Packers were stunned by two-touchdown underdog Denver. Green Bay
had fully expected a second consecutive world championship, and the
loss triggered instant tumult. The crises, in chronological order:
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren spent the off-season examining an escape from his
contract to become Seattle's coach and general manager. The Packers
stifled his bid, but conceded by giving Holmgren an escape clause
after this season that would allow him to leave for a similar dual
role. Because of that, rumors are everywhere that Holmgren's 1999
home will be in Cleveland or San Diego or Seattle or Washington or
who knows where?
</P>
<P>
   Then team spokesman Reggie White spoke. His off-season address
to the Wisconsin state legislature ripped homosexuality and
virtually every ethnic group in America. GM Ron Wolf tried to cap
the ensuing firestorm by saying of White, ``I believe everyone is
entitled to an opinion. But sometimes it's time to shut your
mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   But the damage to the organization that had long claimed it, not
the Cowboys, deserved to be ``America's Team,'' was done.
</P>
<P>
   Then came personnel problems. Defensive stars Eugene Robinson,
Doug Evans and Gabe Wilkins departed via free agency. White flirted
with retirement. Quarterback Brett Favre, whose addictive
personality could be a time bomb, has thrown 19 TD passes but also
16 interceptions and keeps saying that he considers retirement
after every loss. And when running back Dorsey Levens broke his leg
in Week 2, the Packers' roster was thinner than it's been in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Week 5 loss to Minnesota, a 37-24 decision at previously
fortress-secure Lambeau Field, was a debacle. But at least the
Vikings were recognized as a worthy foe and a potential threat to
the Packers' division throne. In Week 6, Green Bay was defeated,
27-20, by the Lions and their rookie quarterback, Charlie Batch.
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back losses spoiled a 4-0 start, and another 27-20
loss, this one at Pittsburgh, made the Packers seem poised to
deliver their own eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think \Rthe loss to the Vikings\S lingered only because it
was so unusual,'' Holmgren said. ``That was an unusual set of
circumstances. \RBut\S they won fair and square. And now we have
another crack at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay is reaching the final leg of a demanding three-game
road swing. The Packers were at Pittsburgh, were at the Giants last
week, and now oppose a Vikings team that has lost just once at home
to the Packers since Denny Green and Holmgren became head coaches
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade, NFL teams have played three consecutive road
games 60 times. Only 18 teams have emerged with winning marks, with
35 of the teams finishing 1-2 _ which is what Green Bay faces if it
loses.
</P>
<P>
   Favre is on record as saying San Francisco, a 36-22 loser to
Green Bay, is a better team than the Vikings. Green is on record as
saying he's not certain anybody in Green Bay has earned the right
to disrespect his Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our track record over the years, against every
team, I think we've shown well for ourselves,'' Green says, ``And
that's been especially true in our meetings with Green Bay. We're
happy with the way we match up.''
</P>
<P>
   History says Green has room to talk; the standings say he also
has room to breathe. If Minnesota does lose, the Vikings
nevertheless would have a one-game lead with five to play. But if
Green Bay loses, the Packers are three games back with five to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can play,'' Favre says. ``When we put it together,
we can roll as well as anybody. It's just frustrating, tough to put
a finger on, when we don't play like we can.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a mystery. It's The Death Watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 1832EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
