</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MEASURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TEAM NEAR FULL MEASURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys are only two-and-a-half seasons
removed from winning an unprecedented third world championship in
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen current starters have at least one Super Bowl ring. Ten
have all three.
</P>
<P>
   They begin play at Texas Stadium today against the talented
Seattle Seahawks with a two-game lead on their nearest NFC East
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the prevailing theory is these same Cowboys have something
to prove. Though this club is vastly improved from Barry Switzer's
final days, the season has not produced a victory over a team that
currently has a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Irvin hears this theory, grits his teeth, and curses for
emphasis. The Cowboys, Irvin said, should not use today, or
Thursday's game against the Minnesota Vikings, as a barometer to
measure where they stand among the league's elite. He then contends
this veteran team has enough championship mettle that a record
eighth Super Bowl appearance should not be viewed as a preposterous
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Measuring stick? I don't buy into that measuring stick,'' he
exclaimed. ``We don't need to line up against another team to find
out where we are as far as a measuring stick. We've got a whole lot
of guys here that have won a lot of big games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is anybody on this team that thinks that we can't
beat any team by playing our game and not making crucial mistakes
in the crucial moments then they don't need to be on this football
team because they are a poison and that's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Irvin, Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman scowls at those who
don't think this club can reach over its most recent past to claim
one more title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing that maybe we are not respected as we once
were,'' Aikman said. ``That's upsetting to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't blame anyone for thinking that based on what took
place last year and the way that we played. I still think we're a
talented football team and still think we can compete at the level
we once did.''
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Jerry Jones has stopped short of proclaiming his team
is all the way back. But he points out correctly that the Cowboys
have more balance than any of the NFC's top teams. Two-time
defending NFC champion Green Bay has no running game. San Francisco
is soft in the offensive line and the secondary. Minnesota and
Atlanta lack a championship pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, the Cowboys have proved they are among the best
teams in the NFC. They lead the conference in fewest points
allowed, and are one behind Atlanta for the NFC lead in turnover
margin at plus-8.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Cowboys (341.7 yards per game) are fourth in
the conference in total offense behind San Francisco (420.1),
Minnesota (382) and Green Bay (348).
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson, whose 5-5 team is the most
talented the Cowboys have faced since Week 2 at Denver, sees a
star-studded Cowboys roster, and all but wonders if this isn't the
team to beat in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan has done a tremendous job of getting them ready and they
are playing like they used to _ with great confidence,'' Erickson
said. ``Emmitt \RSmith\S is running well, and Troy, I think, is one
of the best quarterbacks in the NFL. With Deion \RSanders\S, they
are playing great team defense. They are pretty close to the
\RCowboys\S teams of old.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys running back Emmitt Smith hears this theory and has the
same reaction as Irvin and Aikman. Smith relishes the underdog
status. If San Francisco, Green Bay, and Minnesota want to
underrate the Cowboys, let them, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no. Keep us where we are,'' he said. ``We are just going
about our business very quietly, winning games. We're not asking
for extra attention. If you guys want to throw us in a category
with a group of teams you consider elite, then that's your
business.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Irvin requests, leave the measuring sticks at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to beat this team to prove to me that I can do
something, or lose to prove that I can't,'' he said. ``I don't need
any team to be a measuring stick. I already found out what it takes
to win, and I found that out over the last eight or nine years of
my career.''  &LR; tagtop:Kevin Lyons, (817) 390-7760
 &LR; tagbottom:lyonsnfl &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
