<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2941 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-ICEHOGS-TEX     11-21 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-ICEHOGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ICE HOGS ARE REBELS WITH A CAUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Craig Ludwig says his souped up snowmobile
does 121 mph.
</P>
<P>
   And the Stars defenseman said his tricked out Chevy Blazer might
be even faster, ``but it's really not for speed. I use that more to
run over things.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his customized Harley-Davidson motorcycle, he'd really
rather not say how fast that's gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be some legal issues involved there,'' he says
with a knowing nod.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig jokes he hasn't mentally advanced much past the age of
17, he's simply acquired better toys. But at age 37, that makes him
uniquely qualified in at least one area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a pretty good hold on what's going through the head of
a 17-year-old kid,'' he said. ``Heck, I've got 20 years of
experience at it. So if they have any questions, they should come
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   With an opportunity to play big brother, Ludwig has spearheaded
a unique fundraiser for the Happy Hill Farm in Granbury, a home for
troubled youth. Today, Ludwig and his business partner Ron Buckbaum
will be leaders of the pack for the first David McDavid Auto Group
Turkey Ride &AMP; Poker Run.
</P>
<P>
   Motorcyle riders will gather at the David McDavid Acura
dealership in Plano at 8 a.m. and then set out on a day-long ride
across the area, stopping at checkpoints to pick up playing cards
and trying to assemble the best poker hands, which will be redeemed
for prizes. The ride will end in the afternoon at the David McDavid
Auto Group in Irving, with a dinner party and carnival that runs
from 11 a.m. until 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig assures no laws will be broken in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we've got to set a good example,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig has the experience to make himself an example. Growing up
in Eagle River, Wis., he wasn't above a little juvenile
delinquency. Let's just say the city police knew him by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my time,'' he said defiantly.
</P>
<P>
   But each time he messed up, Ludwig said someone was there to
pick him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got myself into all kinds of trouble when I was a kid,''
Ludwig said. ``But every time I did, every time when it could have
been worse, I had my mom and dad there to straighten me out. My dad
is one of the toughest disciplinarians you'll ever see, but he knew
I needed that back then.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, there were teachers and counselors in high school
who helped him gain an athletic scholarship to the University of
North Dakota, where he helped the Fighting Sioux to the 1980 NCAA
championship and made enough of an impression to get drafted by the
Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for a few adults, I'd never have gone to school
and I wouldn't be here right now,'' Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to impart the same lessons to the children at Happy
Hill Farm. The working farm houses about 100 youth aged 5-18, who
live, work and study there. It's a place where they can receive a
second chance, Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And sometimes they might need a third chance or a fourth
chance,'' he said. ``You can't give up on kids, because you never
know what their potential is, who they might turn out to be if you
help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckbaum said more than 500 riders have registered and would
like to get more than 1,000. With the carnival attracting
non-riders, the fundraiser could pull in anywhere between $5,000
and $10,000 for Happy Hill Farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of charity he can relate to,'' said Guy
Carbonneau, who is expected to join Ludwig and Stars teammates
Derian Hatcher and Darryl Sydor on the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig's role on the Stars requires him to provide similar
leadership. An alternate captain and one of three remaining players
who moved with the team from Minnesota in 1993 _ Hatcher and Mike
Modano are the others _ Ludwig doesn't necessarily lead by example.
He purposely lives in Colleyville, away from teammates, and often
is one of the first to leave the StarCenter after practice. He also
interacts with the team as much as any player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luds is funny in that he wants his privacy, but he's also the
guy who gets us all worked up,'' Carbonneau said. ``He's the one
who plans the Halloween party. He's the one who runs the football
pool. He knows how to keep us all interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger players in particular have sought his
sunglasses-and-leather form of leadership and tried to keep up with
his high-speed exploits away from the rink. And Ludwig takes
seriously the responsibility of being a role model to players like
25-year-old Matvichuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past couple of years, that's become even more important
to me,'' Ludwig said. ``I think it first hit me with Matty. I mean
this guy can be a great player, and I didn't want to mess that
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk calls Ludwig a strong role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a big brother to me since I broke into the league,''
Matvichuk said. ``I don't agree with anyone who says he isn't a
leader because of what he does off the ice. He's played 16 years in
this league and he showed me the ropes. I think you can tell by the
style I play that I reflected off of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, a young Ludwig received that same kind of leadership
on the Montreal Canadiens from a player with a wild streak of his
own. That player was Bob Gainey, now the Stars' general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a point where you have information that other people
don't have and you want to be able to share that,'' Gainey said.
``For you to be able to give advice to someone who is 22 or 23,
advice that they can use, it's a good feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig, in fact, would like to impart some of his hard-earned
wisdom to the youth at Happy Hill Farm. You could say he looks at
this motorcyle ride as a case of follow the leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine there are times when the kids aren't happy with
where they're at, but it's great that we have places like that,
places that can give discipline,'' he said. ``If I could just take
a crystal ball and hold it up for these kids and show them what
they could be doing 10 years from now, how much difference there
can be in their lives from the things that happen when they're 17,
they'd see that they can make the right decisions and things can
work out right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
