<SLUG> BC-NELLIE-CONNALLY-INTERVIEW-2000(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRTY-FIVE YEARS LATER, ASSASSINATION MEMORIES ARE STILL SHARP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON: President Kennedy's death. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Connally placed her notes in a file drawer and did not refer to
them until 1993, when the Sixth Floor Museum in the old School Book
Depository was to be dedicated. The notes are now at the Lyndon B.
Johnson Library in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The 30th anniversary of the assassination was her first trip to
Dealey Plaza since that fateful day. It was a time made more
poignant because John Connally had died that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it out and it was good,'' she said of her notes. ``I
was surprised that it was so easy to write what I was thinking. I
didn't write them for you or the country. I wrote them for all the
future generations of Connallys. I wanted them to know what their
grandmother, their great-grandmother felt.''
</P>
<P>
   The diary notes are indelibly etched in her memory.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled the scene at Parkland when John Connally was taken
to Emergency Room 2 and the president was rushed into Emergency
Room 1. Nellie Connally waited in a small room adjacent to the one
occupied by her husband. There were no windows; for her, no outside
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was preoccupied with the recovery of John Connally,'' she
said. ``I wanted him to live and I wanted them to find the person
who did this terrible thing. It's hard to believe something like
this happened in our country. It bothers me that the president was
assassinated in my state. We had a tough time getting through
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Connally said she had little rest that weekend despite being
given sleeping pills by doctors. She said she was shocked when she
saw her husband on life support, tubes protruding from his arms and
legs. There were concerns even when surgeons said he was out of
danger and moved him to a two-room suite, with one room reserved
for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``They covered the windows with 3-inch steel in my bedroom,
too,'' she said. ``They painted other windows in the building
black. That terrified me more. For the first time in my life, I was
worried about the safety of my family. It occurred to me that it
would be easy to hurt us. The governor used to say, `You can escape
a lot of things, but you can't escape a gun.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the hours after the shootings, she talked to Defense
Secretary Robert McNamara and to Lyndon Johnson, a family friend
and the new president. She did not have a chance to speak to
Jacqueline Kennedy. But her son, John B. Connally III, then 17,
persuaded Nellie Connally to write a note he would deliver to the
Kennedys at the president's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie Connally stayed at her husband's side at Parkland.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the funeral, the Kennedys stopped their car when they
saw Mr. Johnson, and got out to talk to the president,'' she said.
``My son, John, gave Jackie the note I wrote, and Jackie told him,
`John, the one good thing to come out of this is that your father
will live.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Connally said she cannot remember what she wrote in her note,
but 10 days later, she received ``a very sweet note'' from
Jacqueline Kennedy, who died of cancer May 19, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   She is amused and bewildered by Americans' continued interest in
the assassination, fueled by movies such as Oliver Stone's
``J.F.K.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every November my phone starts ringing,'' she said. ``The
calls used to be for John Connally, but I'm all that's left of the
four principals in that car. I don't know why they call. I haven't
changed my story for 35 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she continues to grant interviews and share her account
of Nov. 22 with print and broadcast media, as well as with
audiences on occasional speaking engagements she makes around the
state. She doesn't know when or if Americans will have closure on
John Kennedy's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``People never get their fill of the Kennedys,'' she said.
``They were a family. He was handsome, she was beautiful and they
had adorable children. It was snuffed out pretty quickly, and we
never totally recovered. The act was horrible, as unbelievable
today as it was then, and I think we feel a little cheated. I was
part of it, and I hope it never happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
