<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2944 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NELLIE-CONNALLY-INTER     11-21 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NELLIE-CONNALLY-INTERVIEW-2000(2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRTY-FIVE YEARS LATER, ASSASSINATION MEMORIES ARE STILL SHARP
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES)-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ She remembers three shots, and then the blood
splattering the passengers in the presidential motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   As the convertible limousine raced to Parkland Hospital that
horrible day in Dallas, Nellie Connally instinctively pulled her
wounded husband, Gov. John Connally, into her lap. She whispered
reassuringly in his ear, not knowing if he was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be still, it's all right, be still, it's all right,'' she told
him, unmindful of her own safety. She was certain that President
Kennedy, who had been sitting in the back seat with Jacqueline
Kennedy, was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Kennedy was saying, `Jack, Jack, they have killed my
husband. I have his brains in my hand,' '' Nellie Connally wrote in
her account of Nov. 22, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years later, Connally recalls the ride in the
motorcade as if it happened yesterday. There are no tears or
awkward silences. She has no difficulty finding the words. She
knows the story by heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a strange little person. I've lived an exciting, busy
life, and I never look back,'' she said recently, sitting on a
favorite sofa in her apartment overlooking the Galleria in Houston.
``John Connally would march forward, and there was me right behind.
For months after the assassination it was a constant for us, but
you can't dwell on something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans remain fascinated with the Kennedy assassination and
will commemorate its 35th anniversary tomorrow. Although the
findings of the Warren Commission determined that Lee Harvey Oswald
was the sole gunman, the House Select Committee on Assassinations
said in 1979 that Oswald had an accomplice who fired but missed.
And John Connally, who died June 15, 1993, at age 75, said he
believed that shots came from two directions.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy theories continue to burn like the eternal flame
at John Kennedy's grave site.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie Connally, however, dismisses talk of a conspiracy. She
had a front-row seat to history, she said. Who would know better
than she about what happened that day?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there was a conspiracy,'' she said. ``It was a
terrible, awful, heinous act, but it is what I always thought it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Connally's recollections of the day are supported by the diary
she kept of the Kennedys' visit to Texas. It was written days after
the assassination, while her husband recuperated at the Governor's
Mansion in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The diary notes were filed and forgotten until 1993, the 30th
anniversary of President Kennedy's death.
</P>
<P>
   Now 79, Idanell ``Nellie'' Brill Connally is a steel magnolia of
Texas, engaging and resilient, a survivor who has not let the
tragic events of November 1993 become a burden. President Kennedy
would probably have said she has vigor, one of his favorite words,
which became part of the everyday American vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation and much of the world mourned the death of a young
president, keeping vigil in front of their TV sets for three days,
the Connallys endured their own ordeal. It was after John Connally
was released from Parkland and began recuperating at the Governor's
Mansion that Nellie Connally impulsively chronicled the events of
Nov. 21 and 22 on a note pad.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote about the Kennedys' arrival in San Antonio for the
start of a whirlwind, 48-hour Texas trip that took them to Fort
Worth the evening of Nov. 21. The Connallys had lived in Fort Worth
during the 1950s and early '60s, and the president spent his last
night there at the old Hotel Texas, now the Radisson Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was scheduled to end the evening of Nov. 22 with a
reception given by the governor in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Connally noted that Jacqueline Kennedy was dressed in a white
suit when she arrived. Connally was pleased that she had chosen a
different color. On Nov. 22, however, she and the first lady both
wore pink, a fashion faux pas that became a footnote in history.
</P>
<P>
   Her notes focused on the motorcade and how pleased she was that
the Kennedys were receiving such a warm reception in Dallas. The
Connallys were seated in front of the Kennedys as the motorcade
entered Dealey Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that day, Texans were being good and the Kennedys were
being good. I was like a mother with her children behaving,''
Connally said. ``I said, `Mr. President, you can't say that Dallas
doesn't love you.' That was just seconds before there was a loud
noise. I looked back at the president and knew something bad
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   One shot, then a second and a third were fired, shattering the
festive air in Dallas, Connally said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can argue with me as long as they want. The first shot
hit the president. The second hit John. The third shot ... and my
eyes saw bloody matter in bits all over the car,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to me that anything could happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, she worried that the governor would be
neglected while surgeons worked feverishly on the president. And
she empathized with Jacqueline Kennedy's loss even before the
official announcement of President Kennedy's death. MORE &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
