<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2946 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-STURBIN-TE     11-21 1769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAR-VIEW MIRROR: LOOKING BACK AT NASCAR SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ During a year when Michael Jordan, Mark
McGwire and the New York Yankees rewrote record books, Jeff Gordon
also has redefined what it takes to become NASCAR Winston Cup
champion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A career-high and record-tying 13 victories accompanied Gordon's
third Cup championship, his second in a row and third in four
years. At 27, Gordon is NASCAR's youngest three-time champion and
the bane//envy of the ego-driven Winston Cup garage area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since his first championship season of 1995, Gordon has won 40
races. Even if he could continue winning at his current
mind-boggling rate of 10 races a year, it would take Gordon 16
seasons to surpass Richard Petty's career total of 200 victories.
Gordon would be 43 then, four years younger than Petty was when he
won No. 200. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Can the sport withstand 16 more years of Maximum Jeff? Can
Gordon keep pace with his burgeoning obligations without burning
out? How many booed introductions can one man smile through? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These likely are moot points. Because NASCAR's 50-year history
indicates that while runs like Gordon's are frequent, they also are
short-lived. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have years like I had this year, I'll race as long as I
possibly can,'' said Gordon, who counted seven poles, 26 top-five
and 28 top-10 finishes among his accomplishments. ``But the
likelihood of that happening for 20 years, I don't see it. It
really has to do with being competitive, being physically in good
enough shape to go out there and do it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've worked really hard on my schedule away from the
racetrack to make sure I don't get burned out. It's my job to make
sure I don't get burned out and do too much.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As annoying and befuddling as Gordon's domination has become for
his racing peers and NASCAR's loyal fans, is it necessarily hurting
the sport? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Petty, NASCAR's first seven-time champion, said Gordon probably
is turning more fans on to stock-car racing than he is turning
away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When you open up the paper and see `Michael Jordan, Michael
Jordan' or `Jeff Gordon, Jeff Gordon,' we pay attention,'' said
Petty, a Cup car owner who watched Gordon match his modern era
(since 1972) single-season record of 13 victories. ``It's just like
baseball. Baseball was floating along and nobody was really paying
that much attention to it, and those guys \RMcGwire and Sammy
Sosa\S got to knocking those home runs. All of a sudden, a bunch of
people started keeping up with it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You create new fans that way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many established NASCAR fans, of course, have spent the better
part of the past two seasons booing Gordon, the No. 24 DuPont
Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo and all things related to
crew chief Ray Evernham and the Rainbow Warriors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line for Gordon, however, is those boos also are a sign
of respect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you win the championship and you win races, the
people that were booing you still have respect,'' Gordon said. ``I
think that's what we were able to do, especially at the end of the
season.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, Gordon never had won a Winston Cup race in
October or November. But beginning with the rescheduled inaugural
night-time Pepsi 400 at Daytona International Speedway on Oct. 18,
Gordon won three of the season's final four races. Gordon's victory
in the ACDelco 400 at North Carolina Speedway on Nov. 1 added the
11th month to his list of greatest hits, and also clinched his
third championship. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's victory a week later in the rain-delayed NAPA 500 at
Atlanta Motor Speedway allowed him to tie King Richard's 1975 mark
and appropriately ring in his latest title with fireworks and
champagne. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And with all questions answered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``To run the way we did \Rdown the stretch\S was definitely a
huge step, something that Ray and the guys really went to work on
in the shop,'' Gordon said. ``That was a major goal of ours this
year.'' &QL; 
 &LR; tagtop:John Sturbin, (817) 390-7760 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
[cj3][15,11,12.3,12.6,10.6]THE ENVELOPES PLEASE &QL; 
[agatea]A roll call of award-winners from the 1998 NASCAR Winston
Cup season: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Tim Flock Driver of the Year Award _} Jeff Gordon, for the
13-victory season that tied him with Richard Petty for the most in
NASCAR's modern era (since 1972). Gordon has bagged over $6 million
in 1998, before heading to the season-ending banquet in New York,
where at least another $2 million will be served. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Leo Durocher//Alice Cooper Mr. Nice Guy Award _} Mark Martin,
for a career-best seven victories and runner-up points finish to
Jeff Gordon. Martin earned a ton of respect for maintaining his
championship focus in the aftermaths of the deaths of his father,
stepmother and stepsister in an airplane crash in early August. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {.MDBO/L'Oreal.MDNM/ Blonds Have More Fun Award _} Jeremy
Mayfield, who bleached his hair after scoring his first Cup victory
at Pocono Raceway in June. But in case Jeremy missed it _ and as
confirmed by former Formula One blondie Jacques Villeneuve _ purple
hair is in now, dude. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Edsel Ford Engineering Award _} Felix Sabates, whose driving
foursome of Sterling Marlin, Joe Nemechek, Wally Dallenbach Jr. and
Jeff Green combined for zero poles, zero wins and one top-five in
their Chevrolets. Recall that Sabates began the season by jokingly
waving a ``Ford Crying Towel'' during the annual media tour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Culligan Man Water Award _} Bruton Smith's Speedway Motorsports
Inc., which was plagued by water, water seemingly everywhere. Rain
delayed both races at Atlanta Motor Speedway; a drop in water
pressure affected the toilets at Bristol Motor Speedway; a drain
backed up at Charlotte Motor Speedway and sent water spewing across
the backstretch; water seeped out of turns 1 and 4 at Texas Motor
Speedway during pole qualifying. Blame it on El Ni$o, Bruton. Or
the /{Star-Telegram./} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Dr. Scholl's Foot-in-Mouth Award _} Crew chief Ray Evernham,
for this beauty of a quote after Ford Tauruses dominated the
inaugural Las Vegas 400: ``No Chevy is going to win the
championship this year. That's done. That's over. They've killed
that. No matter what \Rrules\S changes they make, they can't fix
this now.'' Somehow, Jeff Gordon _ Evernham's driver _ won the
championship and single-handedly helped Chevy clinch the
manufacturer's title. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {The X-Files Paranoia Award _} Jack Roush, for the so-called
``Tiregate'' incident. The multiple-Ford car owner accused Ray
Evernham of treating the Goodyear Eagle radial tires on Jeff
Gordon's Chevrolet with an illegal softening compound, which
supposedly enhanced their patented late-race two-tire pit stops.
NASCAR officials impounded tires from the cars driven by both
Gordon and Mark Martin and found no evidence of fudging with the
rules. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Goody's Headache Powders Award _} Geoff Bodine, who has gone
from NASCAR owner//driver to unemployment line. Bodine, who
purchased the team founded by former Cup champion Alan Kulwicki in
May 1993, has been fired by former partner Jim Mattei. At 49,
Bodine may wind up in the Busch Grand National Series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler Hype Award _} Charlotte-based Cotter
Communications, for its yearlong information blitz that helped
educate a new generation of fans about NASCAR's colorful 50-year
history. The program also gave several of the sport's otherwise
forgotten pioneers and heroes a few minutes of well-deserved
recognition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {Ruben Sierra Village Idiot Award _} To the ``fans'' who
continue to boo Jeff Gordon, a first-class driver and humble
superstar. The guy whipped NASCAR's fiercest competitor _ Mark
Martin _ and everyone else by the rulebook. Deal with it. That
especially goes for the morons who berate Gordon and his wife on
their websites. &QL; 
 &QL; 
[cj3][15,11,12.3,12.6,10.6]What to look for in 1999 &QL; 
[agatea]{1. A glitch-free weekend at Texas Motor Speedway _} Would
be nice. Will the third time be charmed for officials of Speedway
Motorsports Inc., and the renamed Primestar 500? The inaugural Cup
race in Fort Worth in April 1997 was marked by a massive traffic
jam, muddy parking lots and a racetrack that was panned by more
than one prominent driver. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Water seeping out of turns 1 and 4 in April prompted NASCAR to
postpone pole qualifying. A stern warning from NASCAR president
Bill France Jr. to fix the problem areas followed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TMS owner Bruton Smith and Eddie Gossage, the track's executive
vice president and general manager, spent approximately $3 million
to have a new drainage system installed, the tricky turns 1 and 4
reconfigured, the controversial eight-degree ``dual banking''
removed from the turns and the entire 1.5-mile layout repaved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Gossage eagerly are awaiting what amounts to a papal
blessing from the Cup stars in late March. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {2. Thirty-four races in NASCAR's 51st season _} Up one event
from 1998. After four years of playing host to the NASCAR Busch
Grand National Series, the flat, 1.5-mile Miami-Dade Homestead
Motorsports Complex oval in Homestead, Fla., is scheduled for its
Cup debut Nov. 14. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The schedule now stretches from the nonpoints Bud Shootout at
Daytona International Speedway on Feb. 7 to the traditional
season-ending NAPA 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway on Nov. 21. The
1999 season will end two weeks later than it did this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {3. The new Chevrolet Monte Carlo _} Hendrick Motorsports is
developing the superspeedway version of Chevrolet's newest Cup car,
and Richard Childress Racing is working on the short-track
iteration. Once NASCAR approves the final specs, General Motors
officials must settle on an introduction date. An August debut is
under consideration, but Hendrick Motorsports is lobbying for the
Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte Motor Speedway in May. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {4. Tighter rein on in-season testing _} Sort of. NASCAR again
will allow each team seven tests during 1999, but four will be
controlled by the manufacturers. That leaves three so-called
``open'' two-day tests. And the multicar teams again will be
allowed to pool their sacred information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   {5. Fresh faces changing places _} Busch Grand National regulars
Tony Stewart, Buckshot Jones and Elliott Sadler have secured
full-time Cup rides for 1999. Will any emerge to even remotely
challenge reigning champion Jeff Gordon? Don't bet on it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Definitely worth waiting for will be the five Cup races reigning
BGN Series champion Dale Earnhardt Jr. plans to run in 1999, before
joining his famous daddy and the big boys full-time in 2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
