<SLUG> BC-OUT-HOOD-DEER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVES AND LIFESTYLES OF THE WHITETAIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB HOOD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Mike Biggs of Fort Worth has pursued
whitetail deer with a camera for more than 12 years, becoming one
of the nation's foremost wildlife photographers, but it isn't just
his pictures that might push his new book, The Whitetail
Chronicles, to the top of the all-time list of best-selling
outdoors publications.
</P>
<P>
   Whether behind a camera or behind a rifle sight, Biggs has
become one of the nation's leading authorities on white-tailed
deer. His experiences with photographing and recording deer
attitudes, antler growth and behavioral characteristics separate
his works in The Whitetail Chronicles from many other works. His
experiences have, in his own words, made him more than just an
excellent photographer. He has become an authority in almost every
aspect of a deer's life.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs has had more than 7,500 wildlife photographs published,
including approximately 700 magazine and book covers, but his
specialty has been photographing white-tailed deer. He has had more
than 2,000 photos of different whitetails published in numerous
magazines and books.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real final frontier of whitetail enlightenment lies in the
accurate perception of their lives and times _ the true
understanding of how whitetails live, develop, behave and age under
natural circumstances,'' Biggs said. ``We want the knowledge. We
need the mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   The Whitetail Chronicles is a ``first'' for Biggs in that he
deals more with lives and lifestyles of tremendously large
whitetails rather than in presenting a wide variety of white-tailed
deer photographs as he did in his first two books _ Amazing
Whitetails and Whitetails in Action.
</P>
<P>
   In The Whitetail Chronicles, Biggs presents 500 full-color
whitetail photographs, including numerous aging sequences of bucks
in the wild, giving an unprecedented look at the whitetail aging
process and revealing relationships between aging and antler
development that have never been shown before.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the deer in the book were photographed in the wild,''
Biggs said. ``I believe that there is a big difference in how deer
in the wild and deer in penned situations develop their antlers.
Antler development often is determined by social situations, not
just genetics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have done in The Whitetail Chronicles is to present
something I believe has never been done before _ aging sequences of
bucks which I have photographed year after year. Some of them are
bucks that I have re-found six, seven or eight years in a row, and
a few are bucks that I have followed for as many as nine years.''
</P>
<P>
   The aging sequences constitute the heart of the book, but they
by no means are the only important issue that he covers. The book
includes comprehensive information about determining in the field
the age and judging the quality of a live, trophy buck, as well as
a gallery of beautiful and bizarre scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs said that the more man learns about deer, the more
enjoyable it will be to observe and study them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a lot like watching a movie,'' Biggs said. ``We may be
able to enjoy a movie to some extent by its visual effects alone,
but if we understand the characters and the plot, it's always much
more interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Old bucks frequently exhibit limps and scars from battles fought
with other bucks, causing some to become arthritic. But even those
bucks, walking as stiffly as they must, are beautiful animals to
Biggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost impossible to look at a really old buck without
getting a smile on you face just imagining the times that he has
been through,'' Biggs said.
</P>
<P>
   The bucks featured in The Whitetail Chronicles are among 300,000
color photographs Biggs has taken in six states and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pursuit of mature whitetail bucks is altogether exciting,
challenging, frustrating, humbling and rewarding,'' Biggs said.
``As difficult tasks go, this one is pretty much in a league of its
own.''
FYI The Whitetail Chronicles Available from: Mike Biggs Photography
P.O. Box 330787 Fort Worth, Texas, 76163 1-800-433-2102 Price:
$39.95 plus $4 for shipping and handling (Texas residents add $3.63
sales tax per copy)
</P>
</TEXT>
