<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAILEY, REEVES SHARE WINNING ROOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When Chan Gailey needed an NFL job, Dan
Reeves came through. When Gailey needed a recommendation, Reeves
came through again.
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves needed a friend in Denver, Gailey was there. But at
the same time, Gailey remained tight with Mike Shanahan and John
Elway, who were not friends of Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   When the NFL kicks off Week 12 today, the combined record of
teams coached by Shanahan, Reeves and Gailey will be 25-5. Which
speaks highly of the Broncos' staff of the late '80s.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Broncos, Shanahan has the defending Super Bowl
champion, so even 10-0 is not a big surprise. At 8-2 in Atlanta,
Reeves is the leading candidate for coach of the year.
``Absolutely,'' agreed Gailey, who might get some votes himself
since the Cowboys are 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, however, the biggest winner in the NFL is the small
Georgia town of Americus.
</P>
<P>
   Need a coach? Go to Americus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan looked exactly like Opie Taylor,'' Reeves said last week,
recalling his high school days in Americus as a summer-league
baseball coach for grade schoolers. ``But I don't know if Opie
could play. Chan could.''
</P>
<P>
   Americus being the hometown of two current NFL coaches (combined
record, 15-5) is rather unique. ``Must have been something in the
water,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Cowboys approach a critical point in the schedule
(Seattle today and Minnesota on Thursday), Gailey has a quick reply
for his coaching career having reached this stage. ``Dan Reeves
provided the foundation for where I am today,'' he said. ``I will
be forever indebted to Dan.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, eight years younger than Reeves, got his first NFL
coaching chance because of Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only now, being a head coach, do I fully realize how much guts
it took for him to hire me in Denver,'' said Gailey, who joined the
Broncos staff in 1985 as special teams coach. ``I was a wishbone
coach from Troy State, who had nothing but a defensive background
in coaching. But I told Dan I wanted to learn NFL offense. And he
let me.''
</P>
<P>
   Offense was and is the specialty of Reeves, of Shanahan, who was
Reeves' offensive coordinator, and, of course, of Elway. ``I walked
into a pretty good learning opportunity,'' said Gailey, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves admits the Americus connection helped Gailey land that
first NFL job. ``But most hires in this business are because of
people you are familiar with,'' he added. ``I knew Chan. I knew his
father and his family. I knew what I was getting. I didn't have any
doubts about him.''
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, Gailey worked and watched and learned. An on-going
subplot there was the strained relationship Shanahan and Elway had
with Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I don't talk about,'' Gailey said. ``Things
happen in this business, and then they build over time. But
everyone involved is a fine person, despite the differences that
developed. It wasn't like a bad guy and good guy kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As the head coach, Reeves was the focal point. With the future
ambition of holding such a job in the NFL, Gailey took mental
notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I came away with was all the things Dan did really,
really well, and then there were things where I said, `OK, I'd have
handled that differently,''' Gailey added. ``Dan is very demanding,
no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, that's the way the portfolio on Jerry Jones also reads.
</P>
<P>
   And when Jones developed a sudden interest in January in Gailey
as a head coaching candidate, he obviously wanted a recommendation
from Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in Indianapolis \Rat the scouting combine\S and Jerry
wanted to talk to me,'' Reeves said. ``I had read the names on his
list and heard the rumors, and then suddenly he mentioned Chan. I
was suprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told him that this was a good person, a solid coach, and
someone who would be perfect for that franchise. The one thing
about Chan is he could work with Jerry. Chan is not an ego guy at
all. I stressed that to Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   The question about Gailey, since answered, was would he be tough
enough to bring discipline to a team desperately lacking in it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a doubt,'' Reeves said. ``Chan is from Americus.
Everybody from Americus is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into today's NFL games, head coaches from Americus are
also winning.
</P>
</TEXT>
