<HEADER>
A2949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANALYSIS2     11-21 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANALYSIS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How Reeves rebuilt the Falcons
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Falcons are enjoying their best start,
8-2, in the 33-year history of the franchise and wave after wave of
well-deserved national attention.
</P>
<P>
   For all the current acclaim, however, the first stages of
construction of this team were not the least bit glorious.
</P>
<P>
   For about three months after Dan Reeves was hired as coach and
executive vice president in January 1997, it was a zoo at team
headquarters in Suwanee. ``We were going helter-skelter around
here,'' Reeves said. ``If I looked at everything on the whole, it
would just blow you away.''
</P>
<P>
   One night, in the middle of a March '97 storm, Reeves walked out
of his room at the Falcon Inn Hotel, where he was living, and into
his office.
</P>
<P>
   The building was dark. The power was out. There was a commotion
down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the phone trying to get the deal done for (fullback
Bob) Christian,'' said general manager Harold Richardson, whose
title at the time was assistant head coach for football operations.
``I was working by candle, and I couldn't see, and Dan didn't know
what all the hollering was.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Richardson nor Reeves had any idea how good Christian
would be. He has proven to be not only an outstanding lead blocker
for Jamal Anderson, who is third in the NFL with 1,066 rushing
yards, but an excellent receiver and a positive influence in the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who had been fired by the New York Giants, inherited a
3-13 team with, among other problems, a lot of players who didn't
like each other and didn't like their coaches. Even so, Ken Herock,
the former vice president for player personnel, left Reeves with a
head start. In less than two seasons, he and his aides have
assembled a team that is suddenly thinking Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   While 38 of the 53 players on the current active roster were
brought on board in the past two seasons, 10 of the 22 current are
pre-Reeves holdovers. Still, there was a lot of work to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``My priorities were defense and a quarterback,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   The next Falcon quarterback was going to be either Elvis Grbac,
a free agent in San Francisco, or Chris Chandler, shoved aside so
Steve McNair could be the Oilers' starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought Elvis in,'' Reeves said. ``But Chris is the one
that made the most sense because we could trade for him, we were
willing to give up what they were asking (fourth- and sixth-round
draft choices) and the contract was livable, so that we could still
do some other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler became a Falcon on Feb. 27, 1997. Although he was prone
to injury last year, the Falcons are 15-4 when he starts and
finishes games. Last year, his passer rating of 95.1 was second in
the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't do a lot of what we do offensively if it were not
for Chris,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   On March 3, cornerback Ray Buchanan left the Indianapolis Colts
to become a Falcon. His four-year, $13million contract included a
$4million signing bonus and a first-year salary of $3million.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had to make sure it was (an offer) they wouldn't match,''
Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan wasn't coming to Atlanta until he knew Chandler was the
quarterback. During discussions in the weeks before he signed, he
kept asking about the quarterback situation.
</P>
<P>
   Those two moves were the biggest of the first year, but several
others added up to big gains.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons and fullback Craig Heyward couldn't agree,
Atlanta narrowed the fullback search to free agents Lorenzo Neal,
now a backup in Tampa Bay, and Christian, who missed the '96 season
with an injury in Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta planned to draft a cornerback, but the Falcons needed
another one in case the draftee was not ready to play right away.
Richardson, who was in charge of the Broncos' salary cap before
joining the Falcons, knew of Ronnie Bradford, who played in Denver
three years before joining Arizona in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford wound up starting in front of first-round draft choice
Michael Booker. Bradford was better than expected, just as Chandler
and Christian were.
</P>
<P>
   Another player who has worked out better than expected is
defensive tackle Shane Dronett, who was waived in '97 by the Lions
but now starts for the Falcons. He had played half the '96 season
in Atlanta, and defensive line coach Bill Kollar originally voted
against bringing him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize he was here, and Bill had coached him and
didn't like him,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at the film, and I said, `He's better than what we
got.' He played about half the time last year, and that's turned
out to be a good deal. Bill's done a hell of a job coaching him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' first draft produced tight end O.J. Santiago, linebacker
Henri Crockett and left guard Calvin Collins, all starters. It also
produced the worst move of the Reeves era: the second-round choice
of defensive tackle Nathan Davis, who was active for just two games
last year. He quit the team on the second day of training camp this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a bust,'' Reeves said. ``He's probably the reason
that we're doing some of the psychological testing we're doing now
(for potential draft choices).''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had the No. 3 overall pick in that year's draft; if
Tennessee quarterback Peyton Manning had come out early, Atlanta
would have kept the pick.
</P>
<P>
   But Manning stayed, and Atlanta traded that pick and its
third-round choice for Seattle's No. 11 pick in the first round,
plus the Seahawks' second-round pick _ which became running back
Byron Hanspard _ and fourth-round pick _ which became Crockett. The
teams also swapped third-round choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the Manning thing didn't work out, we traded the pick and
picked up some extras that made it easier to live with the picks we
gave up for (Chandler),'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's draft has produced one starter, right tackle Ephraim
Salaam, a seventh-round choice.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to re-sign speedy wide receiver Bert Emanuel, who
signed a big contract with Tampa Bay, Atlanta got a break in May
when San Diego called and offered wide receiver Tony Martin for a
second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta's had an awful lot of good players,'' Reeves said.
``They've lost them, for whatever reasons. Everybody brings up the
Brett Favre deal or Deion Sanders. The Favre deal _ it wasn't like
they didn't have a quarterback at the time. Chris Miller was a
pretty good quarterback, and Brett was young at the time. Their
track record shows that they brought some good people here through
the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, team president Taylor Smith has given Reeves more freedom
to act, and, with the help of his staff, he has. For example, the
move to bring in free agent free safety Eugene Robinson has
stabilized the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   There are still mistakes, however, such as the free-agent
signing of Corey Louchiey, whom Reeves thought could start at right
tackle. But Louchiey strained a hamstring in training camp, missed
two weeks of camp and two preseason games, and was cut. That cost
Atlanta $500,000 in his signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to throw away money,'' Reeves said, ``but that
enabled Salaam and (Jose) Portilla to get some playing time, and I
think they're both good prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   The team blended faster than Reeves could have hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's by far the best chemistry, 10 times better than anywhere
I've been,'' said Chandler, who has played for six NFL teams. ``It
seems like we stick together and do more things together. I just
feel like guys care about one another more.''
</P>
<P>
   The future is not necessarily secure. Fifteen players have
contracts that will expire after this season and 26 after next
season _ although the Falcons will retain ``exclusive rights'' to
many of them. Richardson has started talking to many players _
including Anderson, Dronett, Christian, Crockett and Collins _
about extensions beyond 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Falcons are outpacing expectations and creating new
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal was to be competitive and try to win, but not do
anything that compromised this team three years down the road,''
Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it and say we've got a long way to go. Our ability
in the long run to be a good football team is going to come down to
our ability to make good decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
