</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ADVANCE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons preparing for battle with Bears
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Games like these are the ones that try mens' souls, or
at least test their concentration. When the Atlanta Falcons today
play host to the Chicago Bears, it will on paper beforehand look
like like a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago is 3-7. The Falcons are 8-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears have scored a total of 15 points the last two weeks _
against the Lions and Rams, no less.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have scored 31 or more points six of their past
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Several Falcon players and coach Dan Reeves don't want to hear
about that though. ``We can't overlook anybody,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   There's additional cause for concern because running back Jamal
Anderson, the NFL's third-leading rusher with 1,066 yards, is iffy
with a sprained ankle and foot.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Falcons are familiar with life on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly one year ago, Atlanta was 2-8. The Falcons then won five
of their next six games. Now, almost suddenly, they trail only the
Minnesota Vikings (9-1) in the race for homefield advantage through
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who didn't practice Wednesday or Friday after
suffering his injury in the first quarter of last Sunday's 31-19
win over the 49ers, participated in walk-throughs on Saturday, and
is guardedly optimistic about playing today. If you know Anderson
well, you're betting he plays.
</P>
<P>
   He has never missed a game because of injury, playing in 58
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Anderson plays or not, he knows the perils of this game,
which is expected to draw 58,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk among ourselves, and we look at where the Bears are,
and we know how dangerous the Bears can be,'' he said. ``Anybody
who's been in the league at least two or three years knows that if
you don't prepare, another team will destroy you.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Anderson's sprained ankle and foot, he said, ``It's
something I'll decide on today, before the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight game, the Bears will be without starting
quarterback Erik Kramer, who is having shoulder problems. Chicago
has the No. 13-ranked offense in the NFL, but is a much better team
with Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Steve Stenstrom will start, and the backup will be
rookie Moses Moreno. That's pretty good news for a Falcon pass rush
that has 10 sacks in the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this game shouldn't be as hard to focus on for the
Falcons as one might think.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has had only two home playoff games in 32 years, and the
last one was Jan. 4, 1981, when the Dallas Cowboys ralled in the
final minutes for a 30-27 win.
</P>
<P>
   Several Falcons would like a chance to do something about that
track record. They've won 14 of their last 18 games, and sit alone
atop the NFC West, but if they don't take teams like the Bears
seriously, the value of what they've accomplished so far will be
minimized.
</P>
<P>
   With the next five games coming against teams with a combined
record of 16-34, the Falcons' focus will remain on focusing for the
next month. This is step one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is setting up real nicely for us,'' said free
safety Eugene Robinson. ``We've got teams to play that don't have
great records, so we've got to take advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
