<HEADER>
A2951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-FEATURE22-COX     11-21 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-FEATURE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QB rises from sub to sublime
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. _ Six months ago and 2,000 miles from here,
in a verdant locale as different from this windswept flatland as
one can imagine, Randall Cunningham leaned over a gimme putt on the
seventh hole at the Sandpiper Country Club in Santa Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Just before he tapped in for bogey, Cunningham paused to catch a
snippet of dialogue between the caddie and playing partner Michael
Jordan. The world's most celebrated athlete had blown a smoke ring
from an expensive cigar, and the bagman was curious about Jordan's
cheroot of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael said, `Well, this here's a championship cigar,'''
Cunningham recalled last week. ``And then he said, `Cunningham
wouldn't know anything about this brand of cigar,' in a joking way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed about it. But it kind of opened my eyes to what he
was saying. Michael was sending me a message: `Randall, go and get
yourself a championship.' And now that's exactly what I'm trying to
do. I know now that's what brought me back.''
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon, barely two seasons after he had walked away from
the NFL in disgust and disgrace, and less than two weeks after
arthroscopic surgery to flush out a few jagged hunks of loose
cartilage that had nestled under his right kneecap like a burr
under a saddle, Cunningham can take another giant step toward his
Super Bowl goal.
</P>
<P>
   His Minnesota Vikings (9-1) can secure a playoff spot with a
victory over Green Bay (7-3) and a loss by either Arizona or New
Orleans. Perhaps as important, a Minnesota win almost surely would
relegate the two-time defending NFC champion Packers to wild-card
status and give the Vikings a leg up on becoming the first
dome-based team to enjoy home-field advantage throughout the
conference playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It is a scenario that might have been the same had snake-bitten
starting quarterback Brad Johnson not broken a leg in the second
game of the season and fractured a thumb two weeks ago. But it's
not the situation that would have been predicted for the surprising
Vikings, though, had they been told in training camp that
Cunningham, 35, would be the team's starter for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with all of the other offensive weapons they have, you
could have surmised there would be some sort of dropoff going so
many games with a No. 2 quarterback,'' Packers defensive
coordinator Fritz Shurmur said. ``It's the logical assumption.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cunningham is 7-1 as the starter. It will be difficult for
coach Dennis Green to rationalize returning Johnson to No. 1 status
for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham has thrown 17 touchdown passes with just five
interceptions, and his passer rating of 109.8 leads the league. He
also has controlled his penchant for scrambling and become a
dangerous passer from the pocket. Ambitious game plans designed by
offensive coordinator Brian Billick have made him more adept at
reading defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The metamorphosis has been remarkable. Billick considers
Cunningham's comeback more incredible than that of Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   ``As tremendous as Flutie has been, he only came back from
Canada,'' Billick said. ``Our guy came back from the NFL
graveyard.''
</P>
<P>
   While league MVP honors likely will go to Denver tailback
Terrell Davis, there is support for Cunningham. All 17 Vikings
asked about it Friday cited him as their most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given everything he's accomplished _ and, frankly, everything
that he's been through _ Randall isn't your typical backup
quarterback,'' center Jeff Christy said. ``Still, with some
backups, you don't know if they're going to step in smoothly or
(mess up). But he comes into the huddle and doesn't stutter or
stammer all over himself. Randall is the pro's pro.''
</P>
<P>
   That he is regarded with such esteem represents a dramatic
turnaround for Cunningham, once labeled ``The Pro of Con'' by a
former Philadelphia teammate. During his 11 years with the Eagles,
the only thing as predictable as Cunningham's breathtaking
scrambles were his frequent public outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   Although coddled there by coach Buddy Ryan, Cunningham became
known as a player who typically placed his personal agenda ahead of
the team's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think calling Randall self-centered would be a fair
assessment,'' safety Michael Zordich said. ``He irked a lot of
people with his attitude and some of the things he did.''
</P>
<P>
   The final straw in Philadelphia came during the '95 postseason
when Cunningham left the Eagles during the middle of playoff
preparations to be with his wife in her final week of pregnancy.
His intentions were noble, but the fact he failed to take along a
copy of the game plan didn't go unnoticed by his teammates. When
starter Rodney Peete was injured in the first quarter against
Dallas, Cunningham was forced to play, and he was miserable in a
30-11 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite three Pro Bowl appearances in the late '80s, Cunningham
was widely regarded around the league as an enigma. When he came
out of retirement in 1997 after a year of self-imposed exile spent
installing granite and marble kitchen counter tops in Las Vegas,
some longtime Minnesota veterans doubted the wisdom of Green and
Billick.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the coaches look like geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   If he plays the entire game today, Cunningham probably will log
enough snaps to trigger a clause in his contract that will make him
an unrestricted free agent next spring. He is noncommital about the
future but wouldn't mind staying if the price is right.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Cunningham has to settle for a good five-cent victory
cigar, however, he wants more than anything else to blow smoke at
Jordan the next time they get together.
</P>
<P>
   ``He laid out the challenge for me and, no matter how
good-natured it was, I'm taking it seriously,'' Cunningham said.
``To not get a ring this year would be to fall short of what I've
set out to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
