<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-SCOTT22-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott in search of a shot
</P>
<P>
   By Curtis Bunn
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the NBA ever gets back to the business of
basketball, the Hawks would not have to look far to fill a gaping
hole at small forward. Dennis Scott, a former Georgia Tech star,
has spent much of the offseason and prolonged lockout in Atlanta,
working on his game and reconnecting his ties to the community.
</P>
<P>
   All with hopes of a return. Scott wants to be a Hawk. The way he
sees it, they need each other. Atlanta could use a reliable
perimeter shooter that defenses would have to honor. Scott, who has
made 1,106 of 2,774 three-point shots (40 percent) in his
eight-year career, is considered one of the league's deadliest
long-range bombers. Also, his floor game _ deft passing, quick
hands _ is above average.
</P>
<P>
   The free agent, who split last season between Phoenix and
Dallas, wants a new home to be an old home. Something comfortable,
like a pair of old slippers. Scott, 30, could sign with the Lakers,
as close friend Shaquille O'Neal has been insisting he do. Thing
is, Scott wants Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq keeps telling me to come out there with him, make movies,
win a championship,'' Scott said. ``But I think Atlanta has
championship potential, too. And I love the city. I'm like an
Atlantan. They relate to me because I'm the kind of guy who loves
to go out in the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The professional reason he wants the Hawks is simple, according
to Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know them very well,'' he said. ``I watched against
Charlotte in the playoffs, with Mookie (Blaylock) and Steve (Smith)
needing that third guy on the perimeter with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a guy teams have to guard. You can't leave me. When you
do, everybody knows I can hit the three. And when you don't, it
opens up the inside game for (Dikembe) Mutombo and (Alan)
Henderson. That's something that was lacking for them last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, an integral part of the Tech '89 Final Four team, has
spent a part of the last year atoning for an incident that
blemished his reputation as one of the league's good guys. As
profanity-laced rap music played in the background, Scott angrily
rambled to kids during a lecture at his basketball camp about
acrimonious dealings with the Orlando Magic. Campers' parents were
outraged.
</P>
<P>
   Scott offered vehement apologies and refunded 100 percent of the
campers' fee. ``It was a mistake that I'll always regret,'' he
said. ``I know I've grown as a person from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reginald Kinchen, Scott's former AAU coach and adviser, said,
``Dennis went right back to that same community this year and did a
free clinic. He confronted his accusers head-on. He followed a bad
situation with something good. What happened that day last year was
totally uncharacteristic. Everyone who knows Dennis knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott does not know when the lockout will end, but he'll
continue to work out and take 500 jump shots a day while hoping for
an Atlanta return. And although he's never made less than $2.5
million in his career, it might not take that much to get him here,
according to Kinchen. ``Dennis is willing to prove himself to be in
Atlanta,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great respect for Lenny Wilkens,'' Scott said, adding
to his reasons for wanting the Hawks. ``It'd be an honor to play
for him. At the same time, I know I'd add a lot to the Hawks _ on
the court and in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
