<HEADER>
A2959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTES22-COX     11-21 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some are eager to play for Hawks
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Suppose they actually decide to have an NBA season.
Then what?
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have only four players under contract, plus two
rookies, plus a few likely free agents. At best, that adds up to
eight or nine players, and they still don't have a starting small
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but the answer might be lurking in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   According to his new agent, free agent forward Rick Fox regrets
not taking the Hawks' $1million last season. He opted for the
Lakers instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick is very interested in the Hawks,'' says agent Mark
Portnoy. ``He likes the team, and he thinks he would be a good
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith, one of the Hawks under contract, heard the same
from Fox recently. ``He's really interested in being with us,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Fox would not come here for anything less than a good
payday. The Hawks would need several million dollars in salary cap
room to get him.
</P>
<P>
   One ex-Hawk, Grant Long, is living in Atlanta again and also
sending out signals he wants to re-enlist. Long was shipped to the
Pistons with Stacey Augmon to clear cap room for the signing of
Dikembe Mutombo. The deal was a disaster for the Pistons. Augmon
was dealt to Portland, and Long opted out of the final year of his
contract to become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, Mutombo, Mookie Blaylock and Ed Gray are under contract.
Roshown McLeod and Shammond Williams are the draft picks. Ty Corbin
and Alan Henderson are the free agents likely to be re-signed.
</P>
<P>
   Laettner and the Pistons
</P>
<P>
   Christian Laettner has hired a new agent _ Lon Babby, who has
Grant Hill _ and appears headed for the Pistons. By signing
Laettner while he recovers from an Achilles tear, the Pistons stand
to get him at far less than the Hawks would have paid _ $8.3
million average over six years _ as recently as last February.
Still, Babby says he won't come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons see Laettner as the type of player _ a big man with
a Bill Laimbeer perimeter shot _ who can spread the floor for Hill
and Jerry Stackhouse. Babby says Laettner's value as a player has
not been damaged and that medical clauses will be included in a new
deal.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last season, Hill said he would not want to play
with Laettner. The two were not that close at Duke, but Babby said
Hill wants to win and thinks Laettner would be a good fit.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller Tractor
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks might have something in Michigan's Robert ``Tractor''
Traylor, who is down to about 285 pounds after playing at 325 to
340 in college. Traylor starts his daily workouts at 5 a.m. Why?
``Part of it is discipline,'' he said. ``No matter what the
training camp situation will be, I'll be awake and always ready to
work out. I want to be ready when the time comes and make the best
of my opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubby's sleeper
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky coach Tubby Smith on Nazr Mohammed, who fell to the
bottom of the first round to Indiana: ``I think he's the biggest
sleeper in the draft. How people could pass on him until the last
pick is beyond my imagination. I think Larry Brown and his staff
got the biggest steal. It's been only two years ago that he was
weighing 300-some pounds. Now he's down to 250, 240. His definition
in his arms and stuff is starting to fill out. He's got a great
attitude, intelligence, good manners, good communication skills and
has a knack for making a big play.''
</P>
<P>
   What's in a name?
</P>
<P>
   Heard about Brian Williams' name change? The free-spirited
Pistons center wants to be called Bison Dele, after apparently
having a spiritual revelation while visiting Bangladesh. Agent
Dwight Manley cannot provide a definition for the new name, but he
says that Bison ``is in amazing condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Flop isn't folding
</P>
<P>
   Ex-North Carolina State center Todd Fuller hired former NBA
All-Stars David Thompson and Bobby Jones to work with him during
the lockout. Four times a week for 90 minutes per session, Fuller,
the Warriors' disappointing first-round draft pick in 1996, works
out with Thompson, one of the game's best-ever offensive players,
and Jones, one of the league's best-ever defenders, at Queens
College in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraging word
</P>
<P>
   Rick Burton, director of the Warsaw Sports Marketing Center with
the University of Oregon's business school, says players better
believe the season is in serious jeopardy. ``Owners have charged
David Stern with gaining economic control, and they cannot continue
under the current model. I believe the league is prepared to shut
itself down for the season. There is no incentive for a number of
owners to agree to terms that do not give them the long-term
financial security they seek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stern looks at it this way: `I don't have another (Michael)
Jordan ready, don't have any other player who can drive the league.
My ticket prices are too high, and TV ratings are about as high as
they're going to be. I can't afford to go on with this economic
model.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The owner wants ... a more efficient business. The player is
demanding the right to force the owner to run an inefficient
business.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
