<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The shrinking NFL
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ New England owner Bob Kraft has the blessing of
commissioner Paul Tagliabue to move the Patriots to Hartford,
Conn., but some league officials are concerned about the ongoing
downsizing of league markets. The previous four franchise
relocations involved going from a bigger area to a smaller one _ Al
Davis taking the Raiders from Los Angeles to Oakland, Georgia
Frontiere moving the Rams from Los Angeles to St. Louis, Art Modell
heading from Cleveland to Baltimore and the Houston Oilers becoming
the future Tennessee Titans. The expansion teams in Carolina and
Jacksonville also are small-market franchises. The Jaguars haven't
been selling out this year, and Panthers owner Jerry Richardson
could find out that Charlotte is a college town if his club doesn't
get things turned around in '99. ``Maybe they're ready to resurrect
the old Decatur Staleys next,'' former Pats guard John Hannah said.
Much to the chagrin of Houston businessman Bob McNair, the league
might try to reverse the trend by awarding its 32nd franchise to
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A Krafty guy
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft moves his team any farther south, New York will have
three NFL franchises. He apprised Giants owner Wellington Mara and
Jets owner Leon Hess of the possible move while attending a league
committee meeting Wednesday in New York. The move was not easy for
Kraft, a lifetime Bostonian who has wrangled with the Massachusetts
Legislature to try to keep the team there. Kraft pointed out that
40 percent of Patriots fans live outside the state and noted that
people north of Boston do not buy tickets, preferring to watch
games on TV. ``Foxboro had become a studio from where we televised
the games,'' Kraft said. ``So we're just changing the studio.'' It
cost $6 million to build Foxboro Stadium for then-owner Billy
Sullivan. The blueprints for the stadium in Hartford, as Gov. John
Rowland pointed out, will cost more to draw up.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders ailing
</P>
<P>
   Oakland defensive coordinator Willie Shaw has worked wonders
transforming the league's 30th-ranked unit from 1997 into an elite
group. A season-ending knee injury to cornerback Eric Allen,
however, will test the team severely. It will force Shaw to use
nickel cornerback Marquis Walker as the starter opposite Charles
Woodson. Although Walker has played well in situations, he is small
and lacks deep speed. Starting free safety Eric Turner remains
sidelined with a foot injury, and strong safety Anthony Newman is
less than 100 percent. ``We're going to have to get people to step
up now,'' safety Albert Lewis said. ``We've come too far now to see
it slip away.'' With the injuries, coach Jon Gruden has all but
abandoned plans to have Woodson get some snaps at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe tongue
</P>
<P>
   Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe will appeal the $10,000 fine
levied by the leagueGene Washington for his role in Monday's
embarrassment at Arrowhead Stadium. The appeal hearing figures to
be a short one. Sharpe conceded that he baited Chiefs linebackers
Derrick Thomas and Wayne Simmons for much of the game. ``If I can't
make you upset,'' Sharpe said, ``you're not human. I perfected
this; trust me. I can make anybody upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo general manager John Butler said there was no
disagreement among the staffers on claiming Simmons after his
release by Kansas City. With John Holecek sidelined for a month,
the Bills needed another linebacker for their 3-4 front. Simmons,
whose strength is playing over the tight end, might replace Gabe
Northern in some situations today. ... With tailback Natrone Means
(foot) out of the lineup in San Diego, third-down back Terrell
Fletcher is the starter. Until last week, Fletcher never had more
than 17 carries in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
