<SLUG> BC-FBN-FEATURE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Character flaws Kansas City
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Critics have claimed that the actions of the Kansas
City Chiefs in the closing minutes of Monday night's loss to the
Denver Broncos were the latest signal that the apocalypse is upon
us. To assign such significance to that isolated swatch of football
anarchy is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   It was the abandonment of gridiron civility, not the end of
civilization, that transpired in the waning moments of another
Chiefs defeat. There was no rioting in the streets of Kansas City
that night, only the embarrassment of the debacle that occurred
between the two sidelines. Middle America hadn't gone over the
edge, just one of its favorite professional football teams.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have contrived to attach big-picture social relevance
to the antics of linebackers Derrick Thomas and Wayne Simmons and
defensive tackle Chester McGlockton will better serve with more
meaningful analyses.
</P>
<P>
   One suggestion: Plumbing the depths of the soul and psyche of
Marty Schottenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Among the NFL's most respected coaches, Schottenheimer is the
freshest example of someone who sold out in pursuit of a Super Bowl
ring. Despite a brilliant record that includes 11 playoff
appearances and six division crowns in 13 full seasons in Cleveland
and Kansas City, Schottenheimer never has taken a team to the title
game.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, his teams roll through the regular season and fold in
the postseason. Then the emotional Schottenheimer spends a winter
of soul-searching. Eventually, such a gut-wrenching carousel blurs
perspective and generates selective amnesia.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Schottenheimer, it has purged from his memory
banks this important lesson he had stressed most of his career:
Character counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was always a constant with Marty,'' said Oakland Raiders
defensive back Albert Lewis, who spent the first 11 of his 16 NFL
seasons in Kansas City, including five years playing for
Schottenheimer. ``There were a lot of times where he cut the more
talented player because he felt he was a bad seed. I'm not sure
that's the case there lately. That was always a team with dignity.
(But) what happened the other night was an atrocity.''
</P>
<P>
   What occurred in a Denver offensive sequence kept alive by five
personal foul calls against the Chiefs, all of them seemingly
deliberate, was the logical conclusion of several years spent
acquiring veterans of borderline character. The Chiefs' roster is
dotted with players whose rap sheets are longer than their NFL
accomplishments. The retirement of tailback Marcus Allen created a
critical leadership drain.
</P>
<P>
   Before a 1997 game against Denver, a wild-eyed Schottenheimer
all but invited some extracurriculars by telling his player he
would pay any fines incurred in the game. It was a warning sign
that his fine tapestry was beginning to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is meant to savage Schottenheimer, who at one point
in the hours after Monday's game flirted with the idea of
resigning. By definition, NFL coaches are men of great ego, truest
believers in their own ability to turn misfits into snug fits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Marty,'' former NFL coach Chuck Knox said last
week. ``The pressure of the job has increased so much. Owners want
instant gratification now. It makes you do some crazy things.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
