<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-NOTES22 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No San Francisco treat
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci is being forced to
deal with a growing concern by some younger players that the team
is catering to Jerry Rice by allowing him to remain in the starting
lineup. Although he leads the league in receptions, Rice at this
point in his career has become more possession receiver than deep
threat. Some of them think the team is appeasing Rice to the
detriment of young wideouts Terrell Owens and J.J. Stokes. Mariucci
and receivers coach Larry Kirksey are adamant that Rice retain a
key role, but look for some changes in the receiver rotation and
possibly even the starting lineup. And with quarterback Steve Young
hurting, look for tailback Garrison Hearst to resurface, especially
against a New Orleans defense that loves to rush the passer.
</P>
<P>
   Giants steps
</P>
<P>
   The decision to start quarterback Kent Graham in place of Danny
Kanell reflects the Giants' feelings on the former Florida State
standout. New York will attempt to get a veteran in the offseason,
and don't discount Kerry Collins; the club thought about claiming
him in October. One vet in whom they have no interest is former
Detroit starter Scott Mitchell. The best bet is that either Kanell
or Graham will be released or traded next spring, and finances
could play a part in the decision. Graham has a '99 base salary of
$1.1 million. Kanell is scheduled to earn a base of $2.25 million
next year and has a $650,000 roster bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Dome, sweet dome
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' Dan Reeves and the Vikings' Dennis Green can be
forgiven if they start doing some scoreboard-watching as the season
chugs toward the home stretch. Both coaches can gain a dome-field
edge in the playoffs, and that has been a rarity through the years.
It is widely known that no dome team has advanced to the Super
Bowl. Also, no dome team has been the No. 1-seeded club in the
playoffs or hosted a conference championship. Six dome teams have
played in the conference title game, all on the road, and all have
lost. ``We feel we can play anywhere, but I don't think many teams
want to come to our place, and that's our psychological
advantage,'' Vikings defensive tackle John Randle said last week.
An Atlanta win today and a Minnesota defeat would give the Falcons
the tiebreaker edge over the Vikings for the top spot in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   Bear-ly speaking
</P>
<P>
   Although the Chicago Bears recently signed Glyn Milburn to a
three-year extension, discussions have dragged with some other
players they would like to lock up for more years. One obstacle has
been the franchise's continued push for a new stadium. President
Michael McCaskey has negotiator Ted Phillips crunching numbers on
the facility, and players such as wideout Bobby Engram, who is
having a breakout year, might have to wait a while longer before
they get extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Packing it in
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay general manager Ron Wolf concedes that coach Mike
Holmgren figures to depart the Packers at season's end. ``I think
the pressure may be such that he will be forced to explore one of
those other jobs,'' Wolf said. Seattle, San Diego and Washington
are possibilities for Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona coordinator Marc Trestman will allow quarterback Jake
Plummer to work more out of the no-huddle ``Cactus Gun'' offense
today. Of Plummer's 465 yards last Sunday, approximately 340 came
in the no-huddle. ... Detroit wideout Herman Moore, unhappy with
the team's current direction, hopes to discuss his future with
coach Bobby Ross and general manager Chuck Schmidt at season's
endBrad Blank. ... Rookie tailback Skip Hicks
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
