</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TWO MINUTES WITH: SHELDON KENNEDY
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Team: Manitoba (IHL).
</P>
<P>
   Position: Right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 29.
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Brandon, Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
   Update: Kennedy played 310 games in eight NHL seasons (1989-97)
with Detroit, Calgary and Boston. Nearly two years ago, he went
public with allegations of being sexually abused by his former
junior coach, Graham Jones, who recently was sentenced to 3 1/2
years. Kennedy recently roller-bladed across Canada to raise $3
million for abused children and plans to build a ranch for abused
children. (Web site: www.anaphe.com). He signed a 25-game contract
with Manitoba of the IHL as he attempts to make a comeback in the
NHL. He missed last season with a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   On his conditioning: ``I feel like I'm in great shape. You lose
it a lot faster than you gain it. But every day I step out onto the
ice, I feel a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   On his comeback hopes: ``I'm looking at the game like I've never
seen it before. I figure I can't get any worse as a player than I
was before. I mean, I was in the NHL for eight years. I never
lifted a weight or rode a (conditioning) bike. I didn't even enjoy
the game. But it's different now, and I think those things are
going to boost my game. I've never given myself an opportunity
before to play the game the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   On his psychological healing: ``Just confronting what happened
to me was the biggest key. It's very difficult, if somebody hasn't
been in that situation, to understand the damage that it does to
somebody mentally and the confidence that it drains you of. I've
seen a lot of kids who go from being an A student to not showing up
at class anymore. For me, coming to the rink wasn't fun because it
brought back memories.''
</P>
<P>
   On his roller-blading fund-raiser: ``Once I got out of the fog
of my own ordeal and understood the damage it had done to me, I
guess I understood how much damage (sexual abuse) had done to
people in our society. I looked at the position I was in, and I
thought I could make a huge difference. We didn't have some
scientist in a lab, creating a pill. It's a matter of education.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers update
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers, approximately 8,500 tickets into a drive to sell
at least 12,000 by a league-imposed March 15, 1999, deadline, have
come up with a new enticement to lure buyers. All season-ticket
buyers will receive a replica Thrashers jersey _ approximate retail
value of $80-$125 _ for every two tickets purchased. The offer is
retroactive, so more than 4,000 jerseys already have been
committed. Because the team's jerseys will not be unveiled until
early next year, fans who purchase tickets will be given a
redeemable certificate, which club marketing director Derek
Schiller is quick to remind us would make a lovely Christmas or
Hanukkah gift. Schiller allowed that the promotion will be used to
help sell tickets, but he added, ``The major enticement is we want
to be able to go into our home games and have the majority of the
18,500 people there wearing a Thrasher jersey. We're doing it for
team spirit.'' ...General manager Don Waddell returned from a
recent scouting trip to the West Coast. Among the players he
scouted was Czech forward Patrik Stefan, who is playing for Long
Beach in the IHL. European players have the option of playing in
the minor leagues without losing their draft eligibility, while
Canadian juniors do not. ``I've seen him play three times this
year,'' Waddell said. ``He's a special player. He's got soft hands,
he handled the puck well, and he's an 18-year-old playing with men.
As we sit here now, he'll be one of the top five or six players
taken.'' The Thrashers will select no lower than third in the
amateur draft next June.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
