<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-DEER22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trophy deer deserves a hunter's best shot
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATESBORO, Ga. _ When Ken Brown left home in Columbia County to
attend Georgia Southern College in 1971, it was more than a simple
move from one side of I-20 to the other.
</P>
<P>
   To a deer hunter, it was like landing on another planet. He
found things quite different in the Coastal Plain than they were in
the eastern Piedmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``Availability of food is the big difference between Piedmont
and Coastal Plain,'' said Brown, 45, chief of Georgia Southern
campus police for the last 10 years. ``You don't find any 150-acre
peanut fields in the Piedmont.''
</P>
<P>
   The farms of the Coastal Plain are big, rich with soybeans, corn
and cotton, and to the eyes of a visitor from the Piedmont, the
fields seem to go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Piedmont, where travel areas for deer are fairly
well-defined trails and deer are relatively concentrated, Coastal
Plain deer, with a wealth of food everywhere, are spread out.
</P>
<P>
   Hunting there requires longer shots than the 25- to 100-yard
shots on the Piedmont. One South Carolina gunsmith even developed a
``Lowcountry Bean Field Rifle'' popular in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has hunted the Coastal Plain for about 20 years. Over that
time, he's learned some valuable lessons and developed some strong
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important is matching a good scope with his
hunting rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A $100 scope on a $700 rifle is akin to putting a six-cylinder
engine in a Ferrari,'' Brown said. ``I pay as much for my scope as
I did for my rifle, and I don't scrimp on the rings, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown uses a Leupold 3.5 x 210 with his Browning Stainless
Stalker 7 mm magnum bolt action, and it's mounted with heavy,
stainless rings that will keep the scope lined up even after a
couple of accidental drops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good, hard-working scope in my price range. It has good
glapend in the woods, to throw away that gold at the end of the
evening is a waste,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with the advantage of a good scope and an excellent
rifle, Brown still refuses to shoot at a deer beyond 250 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people can hit a target at 300-400 yards, but there
are not a lot of bullets that will work (on deer at that
distance),'' he said. ``A deer deserves a good killing shot if
you're going to hunt him.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Brown also is picky about his ammunition,
using rather expensive bullets.
</P>
<P>
   For white-tail, he uses a 150-grain Nozzler ballistic round,
which has been good enough to take down a 230-pound-plus,
eight-point buck with a 20-inch inside spread that scored 130 on
the Boone &AMP; Crockett big-game record scale.
</P>
<P>
   For larger game, such as the elk he took recently in New Mexico,
Brown uses a 180-grain Nozzler partitioned round. The elk's antlers
scored 340 on the Boone &AMP; Crockett scale.
</P>
<P>
   Brown advocates practice through the season, not just the
preseason sighting-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only takes a dollar or two to shoot a couple of practice
rounds every couple of weeks,'' Brown said. ``The deer is a
magnificent animal. You owe it to him to make a good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   KEN BROWN'S HUNTING TIPS
</P>
<P>
   _ The best deer rifle: Religion and politics aside, it's
probably the biggest argument in Georgia. He uses a 7 mm magnum.
</P>
<P>
   _ Covering human scent is important to deer hunters. For hunting
clothing, baking soda is the ultimate coverup. ``I use regular
detergent to wash it but use a lot of baking soda in the final
rinse, and I also throw some in the dryer with my (camouflages).''
How much? He slaps his hand on an arm, and soda dust rises.
</P>
<P>
   _ On commercial scents: ``Pine should be at the top of the list
in Georgia. If you smell like a pine tree, you'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Footwear: He uses rubber boots because they are virtually
scent-free, and only while hunting.
</P>
<P>
   _ On camouflage: ``Buy what's on sale and sit still. Movement
and scent have allowed more bucks to die of old age than anything
the DNR has imposed on hunters with rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
