<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two-minute drill with Oakland's DT Russell
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Oakland defensive tackle Darrell Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Topic: Improvement in his second NFL season.
</P>
<P>
   Background: After bypassing his senior season at Southern Cal to
enter the 1997 draft, Russell was the third overall selection. In
his rookie season, he started 10 games. But because of veterans
Russell Maryland and Chester McGlockton, he often played out of
position at end and finished with just 44 tackles and 3 1/2 sacks.
The exit of McGlockton in free agency allowed Russell to move to
tackle, and he is dominating opponents. With 49 tackles and nine
sacks, he is suddenly regarded to be among the NFL's top interior
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Besides playing at your natural position, what's the biggest
difference between last year and this season?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just knowing the ropes, what to expect, makes a difference.
No matter how sure of yourself you are (as a rookie), you're still
like the new kid at school. It's human nature you're more confident
the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you more comfortable at tackle?
</P>
<P>
   A: In my heart, I will always be an end. My first love is
rushing the quarterback. But the focus of defenses has moved to the
inside, and I don't mind being part of that evolution. You get
better matchups playing tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think opponents view you with more respect now?
</P>
<P>
   A: I hope they respected me last year, but it's also a fact that
you have to pay your dues in this league. I'm a more mature player,
more complete, and I hope that earns respect.
</P>
<P>
   Spotlight on . . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ Veteran: The performance of New England quarterback Drew
Bledsoe has suffered with injuries to wideouts Terry Glenn, Vincent
Brisby and Troy Brown. But owner Bob Kraft wants results, not
excuses. If they are to save coach Pete Carroll's job, the Patriots
need a big game Monday night from Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rookie: While everyone is touting Vikings wideout Randy Moss
and Jaguars tailback Fred Taylor for rookie of the year honors,
Colts quarterback Peyton Manning quietly continues to make strides.
The latest came with last Sunday's victory over the New York Jets,
his first fourth-quarter rally.
</P>
<P>
   _ Free agent: To defeat Minnesota today, the Packers will need a
strong performance by nickel cornerback Rod Smith, a journeyman who
began the season in Carolina. At some point, Smith will be in
single coverage against Jake Reed or Randy Moss and that could be a
mismatch for the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coach: Despite last week's loss to Dallas, coach Vince Tobin
has the 5-5 Cardinals in position for their first playoff berth
since 1982. But Tobin must finish strong against a schedule with
six opponents at a combined 20-40 or owner Bill Bidwill could oust
him at year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   San Diego general manager Bobby Beathard would like to keep June
Jones as coach in 1999. In the event he can't, he's already done
some background work on Stanford coach Tyrone Willingham. ... The
deadline for submitting opening bids on the Redskins is Monday.
Team president John Kent Cooke, son of late owner Jack Kent Cooke,
has found an ally in NationsBank chief Hugh McColl and secured
financing. Because this will be a stock sale, the price will be
depressed and that might favor Cooke. ... The singer Seal has
become a big fan of the 49ers and was in the team's locker room at
the Georgia Dome last week. ... Texas' Ricky Williams is still the
top-rated back for most NFL teams, but several scouts claim that
Kevin Faulk of LSU is closing the gap. ... Slow contract
negotiations have been a distraction for 49ers coach Steve
Mariucci, who hopes to gain clout in the team's front-office
shakeup. Vice president Dwight Clark should be freed to join the
Cleveland Browns this week.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs up
</P>
<P>
   As part of his ``Home for the Holidays'' program, Buccaneers
tailback Warrick Dunn will present four houses to single mothers in
the Tampa area Tuesday. Dunn placed the initial down payment on all
of the homes and then worked with local businesses to stock the
houses with furniture and secure low-interest mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down
</P>
<P>
   The day after the Chiefs-Broncos mess, ESPN had Denver
linebacker Bill Romanowski on to address the behavior of Derrick
Thomas, Wayne Simmons and Chester McGlockton. Producers might have
made a better choice. Romanowski was fined in '97 for spitting on
49ers wideout J.J. Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   The list
</P>
<P>
   With 250 carries, Atlanta's Jamal Anderson has been the NFL's
busiest back through 10 games. He is on pace to break Gerald Riggs'
club record for most attempts and to become only the third back in
history to log 400 carries. Here are the top five:
</P>
<P>
   Rushes Player Team Year
</P>
<P>
   407 James Wilder Bucs 1984
</P>
<P>
   404 Eric Dickerson Rams 1986
</P>
<P>
   397 Gerald Riggs Falcons 1985
</P>
<P>
   390 Barry Foster Steelers 1992
</P>
<P>
   390 Eric Dickerson Rams 1983
</P>
<P>
   Stat of the week
</P>
<P>
   In his six-year career, Minnesota tailback Robert Smith has run
for 23 touchdowns. His average scoring run is 25.8 yards, by far
the highest in history among players with at least 20 rushing
scores. Barry Sanders is second, averaging 19.6 yards on 99 scores.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay defensive tackle Warren Sapp on the Bucs' flagging
playoff hopes: ``It's like a `Code Blue' around here. We need to
make a 911 call.''
</P>
