<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hello, I must be going
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Once a highly touted forward from the former
Czechoslovakia, Roman Vopat now must wonder if he smells bad or
something. Vopat started his career with St. Louis and was dealt to
Los Angeles in 1997 as part of the Wayne Gretzky deal. But that was
just a warm-up. When Vopat landed in Philadelphia on Tuesday, the
Flyers became his fourth employer in a span of 20 days. He played
three games in L.A., then was traded to Colorado Oct. 29 for Eric
Lacroix and a sixth-round pick. But he never dressed for a game
with the Avalanche, which shipped him to Chicago for defenseman Cam
Russell Nov. 10. After three scoreless games, the Blackhawks moved
him to Philadelphia for rookie right winger Mike Maneluk. Vopat,
not exactly an NHL success story, has 17 points and 173 penalty
minutes in 85 NHL games, but at least he's handling his vagabond
lifestyle well. ``I don't know what to say, except I hope this is
the final team for me,'' he said. ``I don't think anyone has been
traded as much as I have in so short a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Habs and Hab nots
</P>
<P>
   This should reaffirm how playing for the Montreal Canadiens _
like the New York Yankees _ is either the best or worst place for a
player, depending on how the team is doing. After being part of a
six-player deal with Chicago, former Habs goalie Jocelyn Thibault
said, ``I've been living through some kind of hell. I feel like a
free man right now.'' Mind you, when Thibault arrived in Chicago,
the Blackhawks had not won in 10 games. Montreal's problems are not
at the same level, but the pressure from fans and media is wearing
on the players and coaching staff. A TV camera last week caught
forward Mark Recchi arguing with coach Alain Vigneault on the bench
while Montreal was in a power play.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   After failing to come back from a hip injury, Cam Neely is
discussing the possibility of a front-office position with the
Boston Bruins. ... Former teammate Ray Bourque on Neely's comeback
try: ``I admire him for giving it a shot. He was sitting at home
wondering if he could play or not, and he had the guts to come out
and find out for himself. If it worked out, it was great for
everybody. If it didn't, it was still great for Cam in some ways.
Nobody loses.'' ... Buffalo free agent Donald Audette is so
disenchanted by contract talks that he and his family have returned
home to Montreal. ``If they were willing to sign me, they could
have done it a long time ago,'' he said. ``I'm losing my time, and
they're losing a player. It's not good for either side.'' The main
sticking point: The Sabres will not guarantee all three years of
their offer. ... Felix PotvinNew Jersey has been mentioned as a
possible landing for Vancouver holdout Pavel BureJohn McMullen
</P>
</TEXT>
