<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gretzky star of L.A. story
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In his eight seasons with Los Angeles, Wayne Gretzky
caused two NHL improbabilities: Hockey became cool in the Sun Belt,
leading to expansion in California, Florida, Texas and Arizona, and
the Kings made it to their first Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   But when Gretzky, now a New York Ranger, returned to the Forum
Thursday night , the scene was more reminiscent of Los Angeles life
before he left Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   The game was an announced sellout, but there were several empty
seats at the Forum for Gretzky's final game there. (The Kings are
moving to a new arena next year.) Further, the Kings' 5-1 loss to
the Rangers stretched their losing streak to six games and made
them 1-9-1 since a 4-0 win over New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Wracked by injuries and a schedule that has them playing 21
games in 42 days, more than any other team, the Kings allowed five
goals to a Rangers team that had averaged only 2.3. The Nos. 1 and
2 goalies, Stephane Fiset and Jamie Storr, remain out with injuries
and are joined in sick bay by top defensemen Rob Blake and Doug
Bodger, No. 1 center Jozef Stumpel and winger Russ Courtnall.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were considered a team on the rise coming into the
year, but as coach Larry Robinson said after the Rangers game, ``We
just looked like we were carrying pianos around. They're tired,
dead tired.'' The most fatigued player might be goalie Manny
Legace, who has gone from the IHL to 12 NHL starts but has only a
2-8-2 record to show for a 2.30 goals-against average.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Belt (cont.)
</P>
<P>
   While the Kings have floundered, the often underachieving
Phoenix Coyotes moved seven games over .500 for the first time
since 1991, when they played in Winnipeg. The Coyotes allowed a
league-low 19 goals in their first 13 games. ``We've had a lot of
talent here,'' forward Keith Tkachuk said. ``I think everyone's
just sick of losing. This year, we're ready to play every game.
Guys are getting down, blocking shots.'' Tkachuk, a poster boy for
all that was wrong with the U.S. Olympic team in Nagano, now
claims, ``I'd love to go back.'' Tkachuk had said the trip was a
``waste of time'' after the United States was eliminated from medal
contention. Now he says: ``I said if we didn't win, it was a waste
of time. It wasn't a waste of time being there. It was a great
experience. I want to go back to Salt Lake City, so we can redeem
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly ...
</P>
<P>
   Colorado general manager Pierre Lacroix did not want to be
dragged into a discussion about ex-Avalanche coach Marc Crawford's
candidacy in Atlanta: ``He's a good man and he did a great job for
us. But it's a situation I don't need to comment on. I don't want
to get into a conversation on what might happen with another
organization. We have enough of our own problems here.'' ... Things
are going so well for Phoenix that backup goalie Jimmy Waite went
4-0-1 with a 1.00 goals-against average after starter Nikolai
Khabibulin was injured. ... Colorado is 20-0-7 in the last 27 games
in which Peter Forsberg scored a goal. ... Nashville is
two-for-its-last-33 on the power play. ... During a recent fight
between St. Louis' Tony Twist and Chicago's Dennis Bonvie, the
players told the linesmen not to separate them. ``We weren't done
yet,'' Twist said. ``There were issues to be addressed. I was
looking to knock his head off.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
