<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Writing and quipping about fishing
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde and Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SHELVES
</P>
<P>
   From Izaak Walton's 17th century poetic perspective, to the dry
wit of a contemporary like Ed Zern, authors have been writing and
quipping about fishing. In the newly released book, ``The Quotable
Fisherman'' ($20, Lyons Press), compiled by Nick Lyons, that
writing is well-represented in the 200 pages which contain 350
memorable and jocular quotes from the world's most interesting
fishing writers. The quotes are as varied at the species of fish
inhabiting the world's streams, lakes and seas. Walton may have
called fishing ``the most honest ingenious, harmless art of
Angling,'' in ``The Compleat Angler'' in 1653, but Zern
wisecracked, ``Fisherman are born honest but they get over it,'' in
``To Hell with Fishing'' in 1945. The rainy-day book catches the
essence of angling, divided into 12 distinct chapters, reflecting
nearly every mood that fishing inspires.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S BLAZE ORANGE
</P>
<P>
   If there's one thing Sonny Marsh likes better than hunting it's
Tennessee football. He was in Knoxville for last Saturday's game
against Arkansas and heard a great story from another Tennessee fan
before the game. The fan, Robert Phillips, was breakfasting with
his family in a Cracker Barrel restaurant before the Georgia game
when four men wearing orange hats came in and sat at a nearby
table. Assuming they were Vols' maniacs, he told his daughter,
Sabrina, 17, to go tell them, ``Georgia is going to kick butt.'' A
girl without fear, Sabrina, did it. All four raised their hats and
chorused, ``Deer hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   AUDUBON'S 100TH SPECIAL
</P>
<P>
   Hunters often make the mistake of thinking the Audubon Society
is antihunting. Actually, some members are and some aren't. In its
special 100th anniversary issue, Audubon magazine includes credit
to hunters for the ``spectacular'' restoration of the wild turkey.
It also includes some compelling trivia such as:
</P>
<P>
   _ Elvis Presley was named after Elvis Stahr, former head of the
Audubon Society.
</P>
<P>
   _ The presidents who made Audubon's list of 100 Champions of
Conservation? Richard M. Nixon, Jimmy Carter, Theodore Roosevelt,
Lyndon B. Johnson, Franklin D. Roosevelt and Ted Turner (well, he
says he wants to be president).
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK'S TIP
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who has ever had problems rigging a soft-plastic bait _
whether it's remembering the best way to tie three palomar knots on
a Carolina rig (start with tying the leader to the hook, by the
way) or thinking of new way to rig a jerkbait _ the Modern Plastics
Rigging Guide published by TTI Companies ($2.95; 334-567-9788) of
Wetumpka, Ala., can help even on the lake. The guide is a laminated
8x11 sheet of cardboard that outlines 13 different rigs, six of
which are effective on a Southern favorite, the black bass.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
