<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-RDP22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deer given to hungry
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde and Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hunters donated 262 deer to the Wildlife Resource
Division's Hunters for the Hungry program during the first
collection weekend, Nov. 8-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an all-time high number of deer donated to the Hunters
for the Hungry program during the first weekend,'' said WRD
Director David Waller. ``The number of deer donated to this program
has continued to grow as more and more hunters learn about the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   The first weekend's results totaled more than half WRD's goal of
500 deer donated for the program this year. Hunters have another
opportunity to donate a deer to the program Thanksgiving weekend,
Nov. 28-29.
</P>
<P>
   Drop-off locations will be open 9 a.m.-8 p.m. and include: Bass
Pro Shops, Shackleford Road, Exit 39A off I-85; Social Circle, Exit
48 off I-20; Lexington, Oglethorpe County Farmer's Market; Locust
Grove, exit off I-75, east side of interstate; Cedar Creek WMA and
B.F Grant WMA check stations _ Saturday only; Gainesville, Jesse
Jewel Parkway at I-985.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Hunters for the Hungry, contact the WRD
Game Management Office at 770-918-6416.
</P>
<P>
   Mud on your feet
</P>
<P>
   Every four or five years, Georgia Power makes it difficult to
launch your boat at Lake Sinclair, but that's not necessarily a bad
thing. By drastically lowering the lake's water level _ it's
currently down about 6 1/2 feet, ``which is a lot for Sinclair,''
according to Comer Gheesling at Little River Park _ the power
company allows home and business owners a chance to fix docks and
seawalls, and complete other structural maintenance. And while
boat-ramp access is limited by the low water (the private ramp at
Sinclair Marina is the only one open that Gheesling knows of), the
fishing success has definitely risen. In a local bass fishing club
tournament last weekend, for example, all 28 boats caught a limit.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey Weekend stripers
</P>
<P>
   The North Georgia Striper Club has found an angler's way to work
off some of that Thanksgiving turkey, and it's become one of its
favorite events. Around 30 boats are expected for the fifth annual
Thanksgiving Classic striper tournament Saturday on Lake Lanier.
``Typically, our holiday tournaments (Thanksgiving and Christmas
weekends) are our most popular,'' said tournament organizer Mike
Maddalena. The tournament, which launches and weighs in at
Hammond's Fishing Center in Cumming, runs 5:45 a.m. to 3 p.m. The
entry fee per two-man boat is $50, including $5 for the big fish
award, and there is an 80 percent payback. Registration begins at
5:15 a.m. For information call 770-501-0675 or 770-887-6083.
</P>
<P>
   Charity fishing event
</P>
<P>
   Chuck LaMar, former assistant Braves GM and now GM for the Tampa
Bay Devil Rays, held his first Chuck LaMar's Mercury Marine Grand
Slam Celebrity Fishing Tournament recently. It raised $100,000 for
the Pediatric Cancer Foundation. A Grand Slam consisted of redfish,
sea trout and snook. Those three plus a tarpon were the Super Grand
Slam. Bill Acree, Braves traveling secretary, won the celebrity
redfish division with a 26-incher that was photographed and
released. Braves GM John Schuerholz, former Braves reliever Rick
Camp and fishing show host Orlando Wilson, were among the 40
celebrities competing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
