<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GRAF'S MARKED WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also TEN-CHASE) 
(mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About the softened and vulnerable Steffi Graf I have
been hearing so much about; does this evolved persona of the tennis
legend really exist? Lindsay Davenport, wisely suspicious, played
it conservatively deferential, not giving Graf any more incentive
than she already had Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never intimidated when I go out on the court, but it is
very tough to play her indoors,'' said Davenport, merely the
world's No. 1 player, before her Chase Championships semifinal
against Graf at Madison Square Garden. Then, just as Graf was about
to punctuate Davenport's observation with an exclamation point, a
cranky hamstring intervened and Davenport survived, 6-1, 2-6, 6-3,
into Saturday's final against Martina Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it didn't hurt,'' Davenport said of Graf's bad timing.
``I won the last three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport didn't sound much like No. 1, before and after, with
her judicious pre- and postmatch strategy against Graf. Already
beaten by Graf in the final of a Philadelphia tournament last
Sunday, Davenport, 22, wasn't about to do the teen-age thing, like
Hingis last summer. Hingis wrote the German off as an expensive
museum piece, claiming Graf ``is old'' and ``her time has passed.''
Graf shrugged off the comments at the time, biding her time, until
last week's Philadelphia quarterfinals, where Graf turned her third
set against Hingis into a 6-0, hit-and-run collision. Hingis and
the other young legends in their own minds will think twice about
dismissing her until Graf decides she is finally done.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Graf struggle back from her numerous injuries these
last three weeks, seeing her eyes narrow in the tense moments at
the Garden, told me she had not battled a body rebelling against
years of overextension just for a farewell tour. Reports of a
mellower, more emotive, soon-to-be 30 Graf notwithstanding, she
seems to be out there with her old blinders on, with the intention
of being the best, not pretty good. No surprise, it's what she
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I don't have to answer any more questions why am I
doing it, why am I trying,'' she said. ``I think it speaks for
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't recall anyone advising Graf to retire, with the
exception of Hingis, though I suppose Graf might have decided that
Hingis was speaking for the tour, or at least that part of it under
20. Now, unless Graf's tender limbs seriously betray her, they are
all marked women, even Monica Seles, the ultimate victim.
</P>
<P>
   When Graf rallied from being one lopsided set down to catch the
tiring Seles in what even Davenport called ``unbelievable tennis''
Thursday night, there was this great buildup of crowd emotion for
the soap opera's grand dames. From the start of the third set, it
was clearly a matter of time before Graf put Seles away, and you
could sense the anticipation for the moment when the star-crossed
champions approached the net for, as it turned out, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   As the winner, it was the perfect opportunity for a softer
version of Graf to surface, with a warm pat of her opponent's back,
if not an arm around Seles' shoulder. The handshake, instead, was
brief, cool, a turnoff. It left me feeling far less sentiment for
Graf than the enormous respect she deserves.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a clear indication that these two have a ways to go
before they share bagels in the locker room, the higher place
Martina Navratilova and Chris Evert evolved to late in their
rivalry. Of course, they, for the most part, had only each other to
worry about, not the growing number of contenders Graf has returned
to hunt. The top 10 of women's tennis has never had such a colorful
mix of teen-age and young adult contenders. Graf this week had to
defeat the Wimbledon champion (Jana Novotna) and Seles for the
privilege of facing Davenport, winner of the U.S. Open, while
falling short of a showdown with the Australian Open champion,
Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have survived this far, so we will see what comes up next,''
Graf said. ``I do not have any other goals than to play well, no
expectations whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she talked herself into that, after straining the right
hamstring at 0-30 in the sixth game of the third set, Davenport
seemingly sagging as much from the intensity of Graf's gaze as her
whip forehand and punishing backhand slice. Graf won the next
point, but not many after that. ``How did it look?'' she said, to
the question of diminished mobility.
</P>
<P>
   In such a defiant tone is the message that Graf will fight on
against medical odds because she still believes that there is no
one better. Seles, still struggling with the meaning of it all,
still refusing to get back into pre-stabbing shape, often seems to
be playing just to play. It is difficult to imagine Graf hanging
around very long that way.
</P>
<P>
   She will need those blinders, her iron resolve that doesn't
leave much room for bagels or hugs. This is how Steffi Graf became
great. This is how she held her ground, how she has come back.
There is no such thing as Ms. Nice Graf, and won't be, until she
lays down her racquet for good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
