<HEADLINE>
COACHES CAN'T GIVE PLAYERS CREATINE, BUT THEY CAN SELL IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Coaches cannot give a nutritional supplement
like creatine to their student-athletes, according to University
Interscholastic League rules.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean they can't ``sell'' it.
</P>
<P>
   The league's amateur rule prevents athletes from receiving
everything from T-shirts to free meals, but athletes may
voluntarily purchase those items from boosters or coaches or
whomever is selling.
</P>
<P>
   And coaches can sell those things, including creatine, at a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make it available to the kids because we get it at cost and
then the kids can buy it for less than they'd have to pay at a
health food store,'' said Pottsboro head football coach Rick
Cullum, who estimated that 25 percent of the players in his Class
3A program take creatine. ``We don't make a profit off it. In fact,
we probably lose money. I don't think you should make a profit off
the kids, but I know people who do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some representatives at the annual UIL Legislative Council
meeting last month don't think coaches should sell it at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of whether creatine is legal or illegal,
but the role of the coach in promoting it,'' UIL associate athletic
director Cynthia Doyle said. ``Our position is that coaches should
not provide anything to students in this manner. If a coach cannot
dispense aspirin to students, why should they be providing these
products?''
</P>
<P>
   The use of creatine and other nutritional supplements, including
the controversial androstenedione, is not prohibited by the
National Federation of State High School Associations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the federation issued a position statement in August
urging coaches to dispense supplements ``with extreme caution and
in accordance with policies developed in consultation with parents,
health-care professionals and senior administrative personnel of
the school or school district.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing health and safety precautions, liability risks and
ethical concerns, the federation's statement says ``school
personnel and coaches should never supply, recommend or permit the
use of any drug, medication or food supplement solely for
performance-enhancing purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the UIL abides by National Federation rules, the league
began the process of formulating a similar, if not stronger,
position at its annual Legislative Council meeting last month.
</P>
<P>
   The debate that emerged was not about creatine, but about the
fact that coaches can sell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is the long-term effects of creatine, which hasn't
been out long enough to have concrete, scientific studies on it,''
explained Granbury athletic trainer Mark Gilbert, president of the
Southwest Athletic Trainers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Especially when the products are not regulated by the Food and
Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Supplement supporters contend that, in rural areas, students
wouldn't have access to the products if coaches couldn't distribute
them. Like Pottsboro's Cullum, they say that, without the discounts
coaches receive for resale, the high retail price would put
supplements out of reach for some students.
</P>
<P>
   But if a coach is selling the product ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are not people who have the right to say no to the
commanding adult,'' Don Hendrix, Crosby schools superintendent and
UIL athletic committee member, told ``USA Today''.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, individual school districts decide whether coaches
can sell supplements to their students.
</P>
<P>
   Following the UIL meeting, athletic committee chairwoman Dr.
Jill Shugart, the Garland schools superintendent, returned to her
district and issued a notice prohibiting district coaches and
trainers from selling supplements.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the only action taken by the UIL is asking coaches to
refrain from distributing the substances from an ethical
standpoint, the UIL's Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   The league isn't asking students to stop taking supplements;
they're merely asking coaches to stop selling them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we lost perspective when we put so much emphasis on
winning that kids can no longer compete without going above and
beyond a balanced diet?'' Doyle asked. ``Does everything have to be
legislated before coaches see that \Rselling supplements\S is not
the right thing to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer should be apparent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
