<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Driesell scores 700th victory
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The exclusive club of NCAA Division I coaches who won
700 or more games Saturday gained its 11th member.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 38 years after he won his first game as a college coach,
Georgia State's Lefty Driesell secured career victory No. 700 at
GSU's Sports Arena as his Panthers defeated North Florida 84-74
with a crowd of 1,108 looking on. It was Driesell's third try at
win No. 700, losing to Florida International in the final game of
last season and Georgetown in the season opener Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just glad to finally get it over,'' said Driesell, in his
second year at the university in downtown Atlanta. ''But as I said
before, I've never made a shot or got a rebound. I've been
fortunate enough to have some good players, good assistant coaches
and some presidents who believed in what we were doing. They
deserve the credit. All I've done was by lead by shouting and
stomping my feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in that debut in November of 1960, when Driesell guided
Davidson to a 65-59 over a Wake Forest team led by basketball
analyst Billy Packer, No. 700 came against a Division II opponent
of the obscure variety.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't come easily. Playing without sophomore point guard
Kevin Morris, who did not find out until Friday that he had
sustained a fractured left foot in the Georgetown loss two days
earlier, Georgia State trailed North Florida 50-38 with 14:02 left
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of Morris, who will be sidelined three to five
weeks, the Panthers had only eight players dressed. Small forward
Chad Searcy was forced to start at the point, where he struggled in
a major way throughout the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kevin is our leader and he runs the offense and plays great
defense,'' said the 66-year-old Driesell, who was out of coaching
two seasons after leaving Maryland. ''With him out, we didn't quite
know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior forward Maurice Robertson, after watching his team
flounder about in the first half, was the force that staved off
defeat during the final 20 minutes, when the Tennessee transfer
scored 18 of his 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were missing Kevin, but I kept telling the guys that we
were going to win if we kept our composure,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Henry Nieves, a freshman walk-on from Lawrenceville, who
helped hold the Panthers together down the stretch. Nieves scored
only six points, he ran the offense sufficiently enough from the
point and added to his effectiveness with six steals.
</P>
<P>
   ''He doesn't have a scholarship, but after the way he played, I
might have to give him one,'' Driesell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers were led in scoring by Anton Reese and center
Torquin Gresham, who scored 25 points each. Their sentiments at the
end were the same as Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just proud to be a part of No. 700,'' Robertson said.
''That's something historic.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
