A2985 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA22-COX-COX     11-21 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA22-COX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Direction, degree of NATO activity in Bosnia discussed at forum
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In assessing the current state of the Dayton
Peace Accords, which ended the war in Bosnia three years ago, the
tough word of the agreement turned out to be not ``peace'' but
``accord.''
</P>
<P>
   That was evident Saturday at the University of Dayton, where
more than 30 ambassadors, ministers and experts gathered to debate
what role the North Atlantic Treaty Organization should have in
creating a lasting, multiethnic society in the troubled Balkan
country.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone agreed NATO should do more, but more of what?
The possible answer produced a wide range of divergent views.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now Bosnia is doing more to shape NATO than NATO is in
shaping Bosnia,'' said Susan Woodward of the Brookings Institution
in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The workshop, which concludes today, was sponsored by UD's
Center for International Programs, which received a $50,000 grant
to study how to implement the Dayton Peace Accords. Attending were
representatives from Bosnia, Croatia, Yugoslavia, Slovenia,
Macedonia, Hungary, Albania, Romania, Germany and Bulgaria as well
as U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balkans are a barometer of the health of Europe,'' said
Mircea Geoana, ambassador to the United States from Romania.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomat Richard Holbrooke, the chief designer of the
accord who received an honorary degree from UD on Friday, conceded
in a speech that the accord had flaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he accepted the terms, Bosnian President Alija
Izetbegovic said, 'This is not a just peace, but it is peace my
people need,' `` Holbrooke said Friday, recalling the negotiations
at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The peace has held, thanks in part to an international NATO army
that includes U.S. troops. However, several tenets of the Dayton
Accord remain unresolved:
</P>
<P>
   _ The capture of war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   _ The return of some of the more than 2 million refugees
displaced by the war.
</P>
<P>
   _ The final disposition of towns such as Bracko, which connects
the two halves of the Serb section of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   State department official Michael Lekson said Friday that 34 war
criminals were in custody, 29 are at large and 18 have been
acquitted by the international tribunal at The Hague. However,
Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic said the war criminals in
custody were ``small fish,'' compared to suspects like Radovan
Karadzic who are still operating in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops have been reluctant to use force to capture war
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Some participants said NATO should be the instrument to
introduce Western values and democracy to the region. As NATO is
looking to expand to include other countries, it is looking more
like a permanent force in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Bennet of the International Crisis Group in Sarajevo
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The European community has no foreign policy,'' he said. ``It
does have an economic policy, which is paying for what Richard
Holbrooke agrees to. Democracy does not work in a region with three
clear and distinct ethnic groups. If one group gets 50 percent plus
one, it dominates.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
