 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
QUESTIONS ABOUT IMPEACHMENT FOLLOW CLINTON TO ASIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   By NANCY MATHIS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEOUL, SOUTH KOREA _ President Clinton said Saturday he already
has experienced ``a lot of suffering'' because of his relationship
with a White House intern and urged Congress to ``do the right
thing'' as it considers impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, asked if he should face some sort of punishment,
declined to say what Congress should do. The president, here on an
official visit, faced reporters during a news conference with South
Korean President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, again I say, there has been a lot of suffering _
that is different from punishment, although it's hard to see the
difference sometimes as you're going through it,'' Clinton said,
speaking in quiet measured tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this long ago ceased to be a political issue or a
legal issue and became a personal one. And every day I do my best
to put it right, personally,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee began its impeachment inquiry of
Clinton last week as the president traveled to Asia. Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr, the panel's only witness so far, charged
Clinton had abused the powers of his office in trying to cover up
perjury in a civil deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's 12-hour appearance in the highly partisan forum prompted
his ethics adviser, Sam Dash, to quit in protest because the
independent counsel had adopted an aggressive advocacy for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as the committee voted to expand the impeachment inquiry,
key House Republican moderates, Peter King of New York and John
Porter of Illinois, announced they would vote against articles of
impeachment if brought to the floor by the panel. They estimated 15
to 50 Republicans would join them, assuring defeat for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides appear to be groping for ways out of the political
dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, after initial denials, admitted in August to an
``improper relationship'' with Monica Lewinsky and to trying to
cover up the affair. The president, under fire from members of his
own party, later apologized for the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply not appropriate at this time, in my view, for me
to comment on what the Congress should do,'' Clinton said. ``I
trust the American people and I hope Congress will do the right
thing in a nonpolitical way, if you will, to get beyond the
partisanship and go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls repeatedly show the public opposes
impeachment but supports some punishment such as a censure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Starr's ``long-awaited acknowledgment'' that
there was not enough evidence to pursue charges in other issues
under his jurisdiction, such as Whitewater, a ``positive thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr four years ago began investigating whether the president
and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton benefited improperly in their
land development venture in Arkansas. Starr also investigated the
firing of White House travel office employees and the White House's
improper handling of Federal Bureau of Investigation files.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, even half a world away, faced questions about the
Lewinsky scandal. In Japan, where he began his trip on Thursday, an
Osaka housewife asked how Clinton apologized to his wife and
daughter. The woman added that she doubted she could forgive her
husband if he had had an affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I did it in a direct and straightforward manner, and I
believe they did, (forgive him) yes,'' Clinton said the studio
audience at the Tokyo Broadcasting Systems participating in a town
hall meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
