<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWESTERN BELL PUSHES TO ENTER MISSOURI LONG-DISTANCE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   _ KANSAS CITY, Mo., _ Southwestern Bell
Telephone Co. on Friday asked the Missouri Public Service
Commission for permission to offer long-distance service to its
local customers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Competitors large and small heckled the application, saying
Southwestern Bell has yet to fully open its local markets to
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Like other regional Bell telephone companies, Southwestern Bell
is prohibited from offering long distance until it proves to
regulators that it has opened its local markets to competition.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, the company and its competitors have been
waging a public-relations and regulatory battle in five states over
that question.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was no exception. Sprint Corp., AT&AMP;T Corp., MCI WorldCom
Inc. and Birch Telecom lined up in opposition to the application in
Missouri, saying the company had yet to comply with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell insisted that its local markets are open, but
that competitors are cherry-picking lucrative business customers
while ignoring the residential market.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri is the last state in its five-state region where
Southwestern Bell has filed a long-distance application.
</P>
<P>
   It has met with little success elsewhere, but company officials
contend that it has a good shot at approval in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very strong application,'' said Priscilla
Hill-Ardoin, the company's president in Missouri. ``We cannot
control our competitors' business decisions, but we have done our
part by fully opening our markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Reactions to similar applications in other states, however,
suggest that Southwestern Bell may be further from approval than it
thinks.
</P>
<P>
   State utility commissions in Kansas, Texas and Arkansas only
recently gave Southwestern Bell's long-distance applications thumbs
down. And an administrative law judge in Oklahoma made an informal
recommendation against approval.
</P>
<P>
   Each state has a slightly different process and made different
recommendations to the company. But the shortcoming most often
cited was the company's failure to provide functional electronic
operations systems, which allow competitors to switch customers
from one company to the next, order installations and repairs and
handle billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have centralized systems that handle the entire region,''
said Ellen D'Amato, vice president of state external affairs at
Sprint. ``If they were deficient in Kansas two months ago, I can't
believe they've complied in Missouri by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell says it has learned from its experience in
other states. Hill-Ardoin said she has confidence in the Missouri
commission and expected approval within 120 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in a test in Missouri,'' she said. ``We
have spent one ton of money to open our markets, and we invite our
competitors to meet us in the marketplace, now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 1925EST &QL; 
