<HEADLINE>
CONDUCT OF CHIEFS COULD COST KC, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   _ KANSAS CITY, Mo., _ If Derrick Thomas
thinks this week's suspension is personally expensive, it may be a
pittance compared to what Monday night's embarrassment at Arrowhead
will cost the area economy and the Chiefs ownership in the years
ahead.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been contended often in this corner of the newsroom that
big-league sports has incalculable economic value because it
showcases the community. There's no way of telling, for instance,
how those television portraits on Monday Night Football in recent
years have helped boost the gross community product.
</P>
<P>
   All that can be said with any certainty is it's the sort of
advertising money can't buy, which has undoubtedly boosted tourism
and enhanced local commercial life. The reason it has had this
effect is because Kansas City always comes off perfectly positive
in every respect, from the team's performance, to the fans'
behavior, to the city's beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Until last Monday night, that is. The reciprocal of good
nationwide PR is that it can turn around and bite you in a painful
place if the images transmute into something ugly. It's difficult
to imagine, say, that the other city by the bay ever reaped any
economic benefit from the thuggish performances of its football
teams over the years. Leastways, nobody ever wrote a song about
leaving their heart in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Within the scope of a few minutes Monday night, a few members of
Kansas City's pro football team undid seven years worth of positive
prime-time image building in a most horrific way. It was as though
the spirit of the old Raiders at their most boorish had taken over
the bodies of those in Chiefs uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Night Football returned to Kansas City in 1991 after the
Chiefs' slide from mediocrity to awful had resulted in prime-time
banishment for most of the 1980s. On that auspicious evening the
Chiefs covered themselves with glory and a young Derrick Thomas had
one of his best games as a pro.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the era of Monday Night Football banishment will begin
anew is an open question at this point, but things certainly don't
look very good.
</P>
<P>
   It must be assumed the National Football League and ABC will be
leery of risking the same sort of prime-time fiasco next season and
will take a cautious wait-and-see approach to the Kansas City
problem. Beyond this consideration, Monday Night Football usually
doesn't feature bad teams, and the Chiefs are very close to
backsliding to their abysmal '80s state.
</P>
<P>
   If worse were to come to worst, Kansas City stands to lose many
more opportunities to put the community's best foot forward for a
national TV audience. The opportunity cost of such a development
can't be precisely known, but we do know this: The 1990s have been
a great decade for the Kansas City area. Part of it has been a good
national economy. But another intangible part of it _ thanks to the
resurgent Chiefs _ also has been the result of lots of national
exposure as a good place to live and do business.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do developments portend an economic hit for the
community, but Chiefs owner Lamar Hunt also will find the
profitability and value of the franchise diminished considerably if
the team reverts to '80s form.
</P>
<P>
   It's only a game, but the stakes go far beyond W's and L's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 1926EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
