<HEADLINE>
VIDEO RECREATES LOVED ONES' LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   OLATHE, Kan., _ Some people seek special
ways to give thanks for a life, even amid the sorrow of death. And
the desire for that kind of thanksgiving was shared by Tom and
Jayne Coones of Olathe, Kan., last October when their 10-year-old
son, Jared, died of leukemia.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He was the most precious child we could have asked for,'' said
Tom Coones, a manager with Yellow Services. `` We wanted very much
to express our feelings about the wonderful years we had with him.
But we weren't sure how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day after their son's death they found an answer in a
simple brochure they read at the Memorial Chapel of Olathe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It suggested making a videotape,'' said Jayne Coones. ``And we
both knew immediately that's what we wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The funeral home's manager, Bennie Smith, explained that the
video would be created by a man named Bill DeMay, who, he said, was
particularly good at it. He then advised them to go home and choose
the photographs and music they wanted used in the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``That turned out to be an emotionally draining task,'' said Tom
Coones. ``We finally chose about 150 photos, but we didn't get it
done until late on the day before the visitation. By then I was in
a panic, not knowing how anybody could pull it all together in just
24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   They delivered their material to the funeral home about 5 p.m.
and were told that DeMay would call them that evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really expected him to say he couldn't guarantee anything,''
said Tom Coones. ``We'd worked with other video makers, doing tapes
for the Leukemia Society, and with them it was always meet the
deadline or forget it. But when Bill called, he wasn't like that at
all. He seemed to understand exactly what I felt. He told me,
`Don't worry. I'll get it done for you. I promise.' ''
</P>
<P>
   DeMay, who is 56 and who works full time as the photography
manager for the local (negin itals here)Auto Trader(end itals),
picked up the Coones' photos at 5:30 that afternoon and raced back
to his Olathe home to start the job.
</P>
<P>
   He does his video work in a cramped, equipment-filled den now
converted to an editing studio.
</P>
<P>
   He began by reviewing the photographs. ``Bennie Smith from the
funeral home told me something of the Coones' story,'' DeMay said
last week. ``So I knew a little about the family. But I never
really know what I'm going to find or how I'll feel when I begin a
project. I only know that making videos like this is always more
than just a job.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMay, a former real-estate salesman, began working with video
production years ago, making tapes for sales meetings and company
Christmas parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the start I loved going into an editing studio and
putting a tape together,'' he said. ``It enriched my life so much
that it became a passion.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, deciding to produce his own work, he invested more than
$7,000 in video cameras, lights and a complex, computerized editing
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me almost a year to master the system,'' he said.
``Many times I was tempted to quit. But I kept at it.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, a year ago, noting the increased use of videotapes in
the funeral business, DeMay approached several funeral homes about
doing their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would just be an interesting technical and
creative exercise,'' he said. ``I found it was much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The families I work with are hurting terribly, and I know
that. Some people can detach themselves, but I found I can't. And
so I sit alone for hours working with their pictures, seeing their
lives unfold, and it becomes very painful. Sometimes I just sit
there and cry.''
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981121.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3005 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAR-JOURNAL-2NDTAKE-     11-21 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-JOURNAL-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   OLATHE, Kan., _ sit there and cry.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After reviewing the Coones' photos, DeMay went to work, first
deciding how to shoot each photo on videotape and then using the
images to build an emotional rhythm, an active visual story, by
synchronizing hundreds of precise music and photo transitions.
</P>
<P>
   DeMay's level of craftsmanship has already impressed others in
the photo industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most commercial studios produce are really just
videotaped slide shows,'' said Michael Johns, the manager of LeBon
Photo in Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Bill DeMay does much more than that. He employs
documentary techniques, zooming in and out of still photos, panning
across them, using interesting overlaps and dissolves for
transitions. He does real image choreography, and that's very
impressive to me.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMay worked straight through the night on the Coones video. But
at 8 the next morning, just hours before the visitation was
scheduled, the 17-minute tape was not finished to his satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to my job, but I kept thinking about the video,'' he
said. ``Jared Coones was quite a little guy. And seeing all those
family photos showing the great love his parents and his sister,
Meghan, felt for him, I wanted that tape to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to focus on anything else, he took time off and went home
to continue polishing the video. In all, he spent more than 20
sleepless hours at his editing console before delivering the tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw it, I was truly surprised at how beautiful it
was,'' said Tom Coones. ``People at the visitation kept commenting
about that, about all the joy and love that were so evident in the
tape. One of my co-workers, who had never even met Jared, told me
later that he thought about the video all night long. He said that
after seeing it he felt like he knew our son.''
</P>
<P>
   That reaction to DeMay's work is not unusual. Last March, for
example, Rick and Linda Kelley, also of Olathe, asked DeMay to make
a memorial tape for the funeral of their daughter, Courtney, who
died of cancer at age 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed at how well it turned out, particularly given the
short time Bill had to work on it.'' said Rick Kelley. ``He
obviously put his heart and soul into it. These days most people
just go after the buck, the almighty dollar, but Bill was truly
concerned with quality. And he reached out to us; he was
emotionally involved.''
</P>
<P>
   More involved, perhaps, than even his clients know.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Bill was making that tape for the Kelleys,'' said
funeral director Bennie Smith, ``he couldn't even describe it to me
without crying.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMay's involvement with his clients is evident in still another
way. He charges between one-quarter and one-half of the industry
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's fascinating to me,'' said Bennie Smith. ``Here Bill
is running a business, doing some of the best work around, yet
money doesn't seem to be a major issue for him at all. He's kind of
unique.''
</P>
<P>
   During the six weeks since their son's death, Tom and Jayne
Coones have often sought comfort in the tape Bill DeMay made for
them.
</P>
<P>
   At least once each day, Jayne Coones kneels before the
television set in her living room to watch again as images of her
son appear and fade into others, chronicling his life from the day
he was born.
</P>
<P>
   As she watches, she often cocks her head to the side as though
seeing something beautiful for the first time, and then a rapturous
smile spreads across her face. Only the sorrow in her eyes reveals
the complexity of her emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing the tape helps me get past the memory of the last, hard
months,'' she said. ``It gets me back to remembering happier times.
It's good to do that, I think, to remember the happy times.''
</P>
<P>
   For DeMay, the Coones project is still vivid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making that video broke my heart,'' he said. ``Most people
never know how deeply I feel about the work I do. I'm just the guy
who produces the video. But I know what these tapes mean to
families, and that's the greatest satisfaction of all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
