<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      11-21 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME HOUSE MEMBERS SEEK COMPROMISE ON IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After an icy standoff, House members have quietly
begun reaching across party lines in the first tangible sign of a
quest for a bipartisan compromise to the impeachment case against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With the House speaker-elect, Bob Livingston, eager to end the
inquiry and the Democratic leader, Richard A. Gephardt, open to
several alternatives, rank-and-file members of both parties
initiated informal conversations last week on a wide range of
possible exit strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The development is significant because until recently, only a
tiny number of House Republicans had been willing even to privately
broach the possibility of short-circuiting the impeachment process.
Every GOP lawmaker in the House and 31 Democrats voted last month
to launch the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers and congressional aides in both parties said
resistance began to fade last week, as Republicans elected a new
leadership team and the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr,
raised no new allegations against Clinton when he testified as the
only major witness in the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've started talking to moderate Republicans, and most of
them want to resolve this matter and bring it to closure,'' said
Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Lowell Democrat who serves on
the House Judiciary Committee. ``The potential to reach an
agreement is there now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Livingston and Gephardt each expressed desire in a
meeting last week to resolve the process before the end of the
year, the search for an escape route is complicated by a maze of
political ramifications, procedural possibilities, and
constitutional concerns. The GOP conservatives who control the
Judiciary Committee have given no indication they will cede
jurisdiction of the matter until they vote on articles of
impeachment, as early as Dec. 15. The panel is expected to approve
articles of impeachment for action by the full House.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, White House officials, who routinely participate in
major negotiations on Capitol Hill, generally have sidelined
themselves for fear that if they lobby too vigorously for a
compromise they might be seen as trying to thwart the impeachment
process, and Clinton could suffer a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Congress that is going to have to arrive at a bipartisan
solution,'' said Ann Lewis, White House communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the road to a possible compromise continues to widen as
House Republicans say an increasing number in their ranks either
oppose impeaching Clinton or want to avoid casting a vote on the
issue that could hurt them in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   The estimates of House Republicans who oppose removing Clinton
from office ranged last week from ``more than 20,'' by
Representative Christopher Shays of Connecticut, to ``15 to 40,''
by Representative Peter King of New York, to ``as many as 50,'' by
Representative John Edward Porter of Illinois. All three lawmakers
are Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   With the GOP holding a 228-207 edge in the current House
session, the defection of as few as 20 Republicans would likely be
enough to defeat articles of impeachment in the full House.
Democrats expect all but a handful of Southern conservatives to
vote against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the recent elections were an indication that the
public wants this over with very soon,'' said Representative Jack
Quinn, a New York Republican. ``I believe the interest to impeach
the president is running out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   If the House fails to resolve the issue in the current session,
the Republican advantage will slip to 223-212 when the next
Congress convenes in January, further reducing the chances for
Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The life of the inquiry is only as long as the life of this
Congress,'' said a senior aide to a Republican lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   The possible outcomes appear to be boundless. ``There are plenty
of ideas,'' said another GOP congressional aide, ``but there is no
magic solution that will have universal appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, a Newton Democrat who serves on the
Judiciary Committee, said Gephardt is willing to join Republican
leaders in ending the process by co-sponsoring a resolution that
criticizes Clinton for misconduct in his sexual affair in the White
House with a former intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Livingston has not agreed to formal negotiations on a
possible compromise, and he is not expected to do so until the
Judiciary Committee has voted. His staff did not return phone calls
on Friday, but other House Republicans said Livingston is concerned
about being seen as interfering with the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several conservative Republicans have warned that it
might constitute a conflict of interest if Livingston intervenes
because, as House speaker, he will be third in line to the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gephardt is eager to proceed. ``At some point, the
speaker-elect is going to have to exert some leadership to get this
over with once and for all,'' said Gephardt's spokeswoman, Laura
Nichols. ``It's not clear yet that he has really stepped up to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties balked at one of the most prominent
compromise proposals, to censure and fine Clinton, after numerous
scholars recently told the Judiciary Committee that censuring and
imposing a financial penalty on a single person, even the
president, exceeds the constitutional authority of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, resolutions of censure and reprimand are official
congressional sanctions reserved for members of the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   However, Congress routinely passes resolutions expressing a wide
variety of views about individuals. Just as the House passed a
resolution in the 1970s wishing former President Harry S Truman
happy birthday, Frank said, the House could wish Clinton ``an
unhappy birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank, who is seen among many House members as a master of
legislative compromise despite his partisan public image, said he
favors a resolution that would express disapproval of Clinton's
actions.
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives are likely to react angrily to any proposal
aimed at killing the impeachment process. And many other House
members who are considered open to a compromise believe Clinton
should pay a substantial financial penalty to offset the $4 million
cost of Starr's investigation during the eight months the president
publicly lied about his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Yet without the votes to pass articles of impeachment, any
disciplinary action against Clinton could be killed by a House vote
or a variety of procedural causes. They ranged from a motion to
table the articles to a motion to send them back to the Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unfortunate thing is that many of us think the president
should be admonished,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Republicans on the Judiciary Committee are running the
risk of having him get off scot free by pushing for impeachment
when they know they don't have the votes in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders, citing concern that a divisive debate could harm
the national interest, also could decide not to bring the articles
to the floor for a vote, although that scenario is considered
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ann Scales of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
