<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-USC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA BEATS USC, 34-17  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif._ It was what a UCLA-Southern California
football game is supposed to be: high stakes, great atmosphere,
standout performances.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in front of 88,080 at the Rose Bowl on a brilliant
Saturday afternoon, the Bruins turned four Trojan fumbles in the
first half into 13 points to race out to a 17- point halftime lead
before cruising to a 34-17 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept UCLA (10-0, 8-0 Pacific 10) solidly in the
picture for the Fiesta Bowl and a shot at the national
championship. The Bruins came into this game No. 2 in the Bowl
Championship Series standing, which will determine the Fiesta Bowl
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Bruins' freshman tailback, DeShaun Foster, who stole
the show by rushing for 109 yards and scoring four touchdowns,
including an electrifying 66-yard dash that broke the game open in
the second quarter. After USC (7-4, 5-3) had pulled as close as
27-17 and limited the Bruins to 3 yards on offense in the third
quarter, UCLA turned to Foster. He delivered, scoring on a 1-yard
plunge to put the Bruins back ahead by 17 points with 13 minutes 9
seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered UCLA defense, ranked 91st in the nation, came up
with a big performance. Along with forcing six turnovers, the
Bruins sacked the USC freshman quarterback Carson Palmer six times.
Four of those sacks were by the senior outside linebacker Brendon
Ayanbadejo.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA also had local bragging rights on the line in the 68th
meeting of the two schools. The Bruins defeated the Trojans for the
eighth consecutive year as they also looked to get their 20th
consecutive victory over all, dating back to last season. And even
as the largely partisan Bruin crowd began chanting, ``Eight more
years! Eight more years,'' their team had larger aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   It was an entertaining first half despite the numerous
turnovers. The senior Bruin quarterback Cade McNown threw an
interception on his first pass attempt of the game. That eventually
led to a 36-yard field goal by the Trojans' Adam Abrams. But McNown
came out firing on the next offensive series, slinging a 42-yard
pass to Danny Farmer that the senior flanker juggled in the air and
came down with at the USC 20-yard line. The drive was culminated
with Foster's first touchdown, a 4-yard scoring reception with 8:41
left in the opening quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Leading by 14-3 early in the second quarter and driving after
USC's second fumble, a McNown pass intended for Brad Melsby bounced
off the flanker's hands and into the hands of the USC linebacker
Chris Claiborne, who returned the ball 66 yards down to UCLA's
4-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Palmer lofted a 4-yard pass to the senior wide
receiver Mike Bastianelli to make the score 14-10 with 12:10 left
in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Much like they have all season, the Bruin offense struck
quickly. Less than a minute later, Foster turned a second-down run
off left tackle into a 66-yard scoring dash down the left sideline
that put UCLA up by 21-10. Two more Trojan fumbles led to two UCLA
field goals and a 27-10 Bruin lead at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   With the Trojan defense containing McNown and the offense in the
third quarter, USC put together a 15-play, 62-yard drive that
resulted in a 1-yard scoring run by the junior tailback Petros
Papadakis to pull the Trojans as close as 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   McNown did not have his best performance Saturday afternoon,
completing 12 passes in 20 attempts for 146 yards and two
interceptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 2018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
