<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOREA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MODERATES TONE IN SPEAKING OF IRAQ, NORTH KOREA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.  R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ Confronted with nuclear and security threats from two
renegade states, President Clinton chose the carrot over the stick
Saturday, urging calm in the face of Iraq's latest moves and
appealing to North Korea to embrace engagement rather than
hostility.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Iraq's refusal Friday to provide documents requested
by UN weapons inspectors, Clinton cautioned, ``I think it's
important that we not overreact here on the first day'' of resumed
inspections. ``I want to make sure we know exactly what the facts
are.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a striking departure from the White House's previous hard
line, just a week after Clinton called off airstrikes against Iraq
when Baghdad agreed to cooperate fully with UN inspectors charged
with finding and destroying suspected chemical, biological and
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the reaction seemed prudent when Iraq did not
object to a surprise search by the UN inspection team.
</P>
<P>
   The president's muted response on Iraq mirrored his enthusiastic
support Saturday for South Korea's policy of trying to engage its
hostile Stalinist neighbor, despite signs that North Korea may be
boosting its ar-sen-al of missiles and planning to resume nuclear
production.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to be following the message of patience
counseled by his South Korean counterpart, Kim Dae Jung, a longtime
advocate of democracy who, like Nelson Mandela or Vaclav Havel, was
a longtime political prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   Kim spent years in opposition and survived five assassination
attempts, from agents running him over with a dump truck to
scheming to drown him or chop him up.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Kim has chosen to hew a path of engagement rather
than conflict with the North. But recent signs of continued
hostility by North Korea are calling into question the success of
that ``sunshine policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's moderate tone in seeking access to inspect suspicious
sites in Iraq and North Korea follows a softer delivery on the
president's international economic message as well. In Japan and
South Korea in the last three days, Clinton departed from his
administration's pattern of forcefully badgering Asian nations for
economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday Clinton said if Iraq objects to providing certain
documents because they think they have ``nothing to do with matters
covered by the UN resolutions, they ought to say that, and then we
should immediately resolve it.''
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel Berger told reporters that the
UN Security Council is reviewing whether Iraq is meeting its
obligations. If Iraq is defaulting, he said, ``we obviously are
prepared to act.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, concerns have also risen over North Korea's
preparation of an underground facility that could be used for
nuclear production, and its refusal to let inspectors visit the
site. Saturday, Seoul reported that a northern spy vessel attempted
to enter South Korean waters Friday, the latest of several marine
incursions.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from South Korea's presidential palace, just 17 miles
from the most heavily militarized border in the world, Clinton
urged North Korea to keep its promise to halt nuclear weapons
production, warning that ``further provocations will threaten the
progress we have made.''
</P>
<P>
   US special envoy Charles Kartman, who days ago spoke of
``compelling evidence'' that North Korea was preparing a nuclear
facility, Saturday backtracked, saying the United States lacks
``conclusive evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Seoul's foreign minister, Hong Soon Young, cautioned that a
fight over a suspected but unconfirmed nuclear program could easily
anger the mercurial leadership in the North and prompt the North's
leaders to abandon their 1994 agreement to halt plutonium
production.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also made a direct appeal for cooperation to North
Korea's reclusive leader Kim Jong Il during a press conference
carried live on CNN. North Korea's leader is said to watch CNN
religiously.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a television clip of South Korean tourists
traveling on a cruise ship to North Korea on a landmark visit a few
days ago, Clinton called it a ``beautiful picture.'' He contrasted
that with the grim image of a ``hole in the ground'' that the
United States and South Korea worry is the beginning of a nuclear
installation in the North. Clinton said economic cooperation and
cultural exchange between the Koreas could yield far more than a
military buildup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could ever be put in that hole in the ground that
would give the North Koreans as much advantage, as much power, as
much wealth, as much happiness, as more of those ships going up
there full of people from here,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But many South Koreans, such as Chang Sung Hee, 33, question the
wisdom of a policy to engage a government so isolated and
unreasonable. ``We're sending tourists to their mountain at the
same time they're sending submarines to us?'' she asked. ``Do we
have any idea what we are doing?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked Saturday why the White House was not threatening swift
military action against North Korea over weapons inspections, as it
has repeatedly done with Iraq, a senior administration official
said the situation in North Korea was not as urgent. Even if the
hole in the ground is intended for a new nuclear facility, the
official said, it would be five to six years from completion.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the US commitment to defending the Korean
peninsula, however, the president today will visit US military
training centers near the demilitarized zone. The United States
keeps 37,000 troops stationed in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ended the evening last night by stopping in on a
US-Korean ``friendship concert'' that featured his brother, Roger
Clinton. The younger Clinton sang ``On Shaky Ground,'' an odd
choice given the troubles Clinton is facing in Washington. The
brothers embraced before a standing ovation from the 3,900 guests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 2019EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981121.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3021 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TENN-KY-NYT &LR;      11-21 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-KY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE BEATS KENTUCKY, 59-21  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The Tennessee Volunteers didn't stop Saturday
at kicking a team that was down. They buried the Kentucky Wildcats,
59-21, and with every touchdown cemented their hold on the title of
the best team in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   They rumbled for 237 rushing yards, exceeding their 217-yard
average, which was already the nation's 14th best, despite losing
perhaps the best running back in the country six games ago. Their
quarterback, Tee Martin, threw for one touchdown and ran for
another and got Tennessee off to its best start (10-0) in 42 years.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who was expected to run from the shadow of his
predecessor, everybody's all-American and the most recent Volunteer
savior, Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteer defense, which had given up an average of 12
points a game in its last eight games, defused the Wildcats'
high-powered offense, sacking the Heisman Trophy candidate Tim
Couch six times for 43 yards despite missing its all-America
linebacker Al Wilson, who was nursing a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   In overcoming one obstacle after another, including having to
come from behind against snake-bitten Arkansas last week, Tennessee
has shown that is the best of the still-unbeaten teams. The voting
polls and the ranking computers are certain to count this
performance the best of the day, and the Volunteers will remain in
the top spot of the new Bowl Championship Series standing. The top
two teams in the standing are supposed to meet in the Fiesta Bowl
in Tempe, Ariz., on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   In 7-4 Kentucky, they beat a high-quality opponent convincingly
_ Martin and most of the Tennessee starters were pulled in the
beginning of the fourth quarter _ while UCLA and Kansas State
needed strong efforts to repel challenges from Southern California
and Missouri, respectively. The Vols have a season-ending game next
week at Vanderbilt and then likely will face either Arkansas or
Mississippi State for the Southeastern Conference championship on
Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky defense, at least, opened the game as if it might
be able to bounce back from a traumatic week of funerals, police
charges and late-night practices. The week began horribly for the
Wildcats last Sunday when their starting center, Jason Watts,
wrecked his pickup truck, killing Couch's best friend, Scott Brock,
a student at Eastern Kentucky, and the Kentucky defensive lineman
Arthur Steinmetz.
</P>
<P>
   Watts was charged with manslaughter and drunken driving when
authorities discovered he had a blood alcohol content of 0.15
percent, which is above Kentucky's legal limit. Couch served as a
pallbearer at Brock's funeral during the week, and the Kentucky
team traveled to the service for Steinmetz.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, it looked as if the Wildcats' defense might
provide the emotional lift that Coach Hal Mummme was seeking. The
undersized unit had given up an average of 378.1 yards a game, but
it held the Volunteers to two field goals even though Tennessee
started drives inside the Wildcats' 40-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Couch and his ``Air Raid'' offense, however, showed signs of
mental exhaustion. Couch missed on his first four passes and was
hammered to the ground by blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   He got on track on the Wildcats' third possession. On
third-and-9 at the Kentucky 19, Couch zipped a ball to Kevin
Coleman, who was racing down the right side of the field, for 24
yards. Couch completed five of his next seven passes and put
Kentucky in the end zone on a 3-yard touchdown pass to Lance
Mickelson. Kentucky had the lead, 7-6, for the first and only time
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   From there the game deteriorated into a highlight reel
flickering with images of the orange-clad Volunteers running up and
down the field in perhaps Tennessee's most dominating performance
of the season. Martin went arm to arm with Couch, outthrowing him
by 177 yards to 174 in the first half on 12-of-18 passing. Martin
would finish 13 of 20 for 189 yards and add 54 yards rushing;
Couch, playing from behind, would be 35 of 56 for 337 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Martin took Tennessee 74 yards on perfect 3-of-3 throwing,
including a 41-yard bomb to Peerless Price, who reached over
cornerback Eric Kelly with one hand and gathered the ball in at the
19-yard line. On third-and-goal from the 1, Shawn Bryson rammed it
over left tackle for the touchdown. The fullback, who had 63 yards
and two touchdowns in the first half, then caught a cross-field
pass from Martin for the 2-point conversion.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers had claimed a 14-7 lead and the momentum to roll
over the exhausted Wildcats. Tennessee did it with explosive yet
surgical strikes. Martin launched a missile that traveled 65 yards
in the air to Cedric Wilson, who was standing all alone in
Tennessee's orange and white checkerboard end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee did it with punishing ground drives, too. Bryson, one
of 24 Tennessee seniors who have compiled a 42-5 record over four
years, chugged between tackles and up the center of the field for a
58-yard touchdown romp.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the first half ended, Tennessee had rolled over
Kentucky for 326 total yards _ on its way to 466 for the game _ and
38 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
