<SLUG> BC-FBC-KSTATE-MISSOURI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS BEATS MISSOURI, 31-25  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSH WRIGHT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ Kansas State can now say it has switched places
with Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation was completed Saturday when the Wildcats
survived the same November scare that the Cornhuskers got from
Missouri last year. No. 2 Kansas State (11-0 over all, 8-0 Big 12
North) held off a Missouri drive in the final minutes to pull off a
31-25 victory at Faurot Field.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri (7-4, 5-3) started its final drive at its own 1-yard
line with 3 minutes 4 seconds to play and marched to the Kansas
State 37 with 1:45 left. But four straight passes by Corby Jones
fell incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept alive Kansas State's national championship
hopes. The Wildcats, who are 11-0 for the first time, were ranked
third in the latest Bowl Championship Series poll.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, which is ranked 19th, suffered its 35th straight loss
to a top-10 team. The Tigers dropped a 45-38 decision to top-ranked
Nebraska last year in overtime, and has four losses this year to
top-10 squads _ Ohio State, Nebraska, Texas A&AMP;M and Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   The battle between Jones and Michael Bishop, two of the best
quarterbacks in the Big 12, played out marvelously. Bishop rushed
23 times for 104 yards and completed 13 of 26 passes for 157 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Jones finished with a season-high 249 yards passing, completing
nine in a row at one point. The senior quarterback's favorite
target was the walk-on John Dausman, who had a career-high 169
yards on 6 catches.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats scored 14 points in the first four minutes of the
second half to erase Missouri's 13-10 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Marlon Charles keyed the first scoring drive,
running 55 yards on the first play of the half. Bishop punched it
in three plays later to give the Wildcats a 17-13 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri had to punt on its next series, and David Allen
returned it to the Missouri 11. Frank Murphy scored from 9 yards
out, and the Wildcats were up, 24-13, before the Tigers knew what
hit them.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy had two touchdowns, rushing for 65 yards on the day.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri took a 13-10 lead at the half in the unlikeliest of
ways _ passing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   A die-hard running team, the Tigers went up on a 20-yard pass
from Jones to Kareem Wise with 1:23 remaining in the second
quarter. It was the 17th straight game in which the Tigers have led
at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State led 7-0 after taking its first drive 62 yards for a
touchdown, scoring on a 10-yard pass from Bishop to Gavin Peries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
