<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOTBALL-CONNECTICUT-     11-21 1876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-CONNECTICUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CONNECTICUT GOT AN NFL TEAM IN HARTFORD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ If Governor John Rowland learned anything when
the National Hockey League Whalers pulled out of Connecticut after
attempts to build a new stadium for the team collapsed in 1997, it
was this: Dealing with owners of pro sports franchises can become
personal.
</P>
<P>
   It was something Massachusetts politicians already knew.
</P>
<P>
   There was no goodwill between Rowland and Whalers owner Peter
Karmanos Jr. They disliked each other. And the governor did not
blink when the team threatened to desert the city and leave a
gaping hole downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karmanos never developed any kind of personal rapport or
relationship with broader Hartford or Connecticut _ political or
otherwise,'' said Democratic Senate Majority Leader George Jespsen.
``He was using the negotiations with Connecticut as leverage for
negotiations with other cities. ... That left a very sour taste.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft, who owns
Rand-Whitney Containerboard, a southern Connecticut cardboard box
mill, developed a friendship with Rowland as a result of that
business over the last four years. They have had dinners together.
They have chatted at the Capitol. They have jointly attended
charity events and Kraft has frequently had lunch at the governor's
mansion in West Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   It was partly that relationship, built on trust, that allowed
Rowland and Kraft secretly and quickly to develop a plan to move
the football team to Hartford while personality conflicts and
parochialism killed chances of a new stadium in Foxborough, Mass.,
where the Patriots currently play.
</P>
<P>
   They were also desperate. Kraft badly wanted a modern playing
facility for his team and Rowland needed a dramatic development
victory to help Hartford's downtown restoration efforts and improve
poor urban neighborhoods across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Yet how Rowland and Kraft arrived at a successful collaboration
also has much to do with the governor's willingness to share power,
listen, and make others feel important, political talents his
supporters say Rowland has perfected. It just happened that they
were exactly what Kraft was looking for among Boston's political
leaders but never found.
</P>
<P>
   One of Rowland's strengths, his many allies say, is that he is
personable. Stories abound about such things as Rowland walking
into a Putnam antiques shop with his wife, Patricia, striking up a
conversation with a dealer, and later sharing a beer with the man
at a tavern across the way where the UConn Huskies were playing on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, much of his political process is based on instinct,
loyalty, interpersonal relationships, and never forgetting a favor
_ all of which are important in a small state full of would-be
powerbrokers with long memories. Those who know Rowland best say
trust is the cornerstone of most of his relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium talks between Rowland and Kraft first turned serious on
Nov. 9 during a secret meeting at the low-profile Host Hotel in
Sturbridge _ symbolic for being nearly equidistant between
Foxborough and Hartford. How secret the talks remained became a key
test of the mutual trust the two men had developed.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rowland had casually dropped into conversations with
Kraft the idea of luring the team to Hartford, the team owner never
focused on the overtures until after the Connecticut Legislature
approved funding for a $1 billion downtown redevelopment project
known as Adriaen's Landing along the Connecticut River last May.
Just around the time Massachusetts House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran
was putting the brakes on any hopes of a stadium compromise in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was an article in the New York Times that same month
in which Kevin Sullivan, the Senate president pro tem, was quoted
calling the end of the legsislative session a ``lovefest,''
explaining how the state's politics, with a young Republican
governor at the helm, had moved to a nonpartisan middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, who felt acrimony mounting on Beacon Hill over the
stadium, read the story and was intrigued by Connecticut's state of
political cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   There were casual conversations between Kraft and Rowland over
the summer. Conceptual talks. Football was starting. The election
was coming up. But shortly after Rowland won, defeating Democratic
US Representative Barbara Kennelly by the largest plurality in
state history, the phone rang in Jonathan Kraft's office.
</P>
<P>
   It was Brendan Fox, the governor's legal counsel who is the same
age as 34-year-old Jonathan Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said let's get together and start talking,'' Jonathan
recalled. ``It wasn't about public posturing in the media. It was
about trying to focus on getting a business deal done. (Rowland)
got the business side down then switched into political gear.''
</P>
<P>
   So the younger Kraft and Fox had four half-day meetings in the
Brimfield conference room of that Sturbridge hotel, hammering out
details of what would become a $350 million stadium deal. An
agreement was close. But the elder Kraft and Rowland still had not
met face-to-face to discuss it or even had a conversation about the
terms.
</P>
<P>
   So the Krafts drove to a deserted airplane hangar that belongs
to a Rowland supporter in Plainville. For nearly two hours, they
literally stood among antique cars and the second-to-last DC-3 ever
manufactured. The governor and the Krafts ironed out some
differences on improvements around the proposed stadium site, the
number of club seats and luxury boxes in the 68,000-seat facility.
As it turns out, Kraft scored on those points, extracting one of
the most lucrative deals in NFL history. The Connecticut deal not
only provides Kraft with an ultra-modern stadium and free land on
which to build a hotel, but guarantees payments for any premium
seating that goes unsold, a potential $175 million subsidy over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert wanted to look the governor in the eye and know our
season ticket holders were being taken care of,'' Jonathan Kraft
said. ``And Rowland wanted to look Robert in the eye and know that
if he agreed to the deal they were coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Unbowed to any superstition, the two men shook hands on Friday,
Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the job of selling the proposal to state legislators
and getting Kraft's signature on the tentative agreement before
Massachusetts lawmakers woke up and realized their football team
was in the middle of a quarterback sneak.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, Rowland had already begun quietly debriefing
lawmakers, but some reporters saw Rowland squiring Kraft around the
Legislative Office Building adjacent to the Capitol and word began
to leak of a possible deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's good,'' Sullivan said of Rowland, ``this is what he
does best and that is to make people feel part of a team. But when
he's bad, it's when he goes into a bunker and draws a line in the
sand. I don't see that happening in this case because everyone has
such an interest in making this work. That in itself should keep
everyone ... on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartford Mayor Michael Peters, a Democrat, said Rowland's office
kept him informed that talks were ongoing. But he was only apprised
of the details on Wednesday, 24 hours before the press conference
announcing the deal was finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that was fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say to me, `Mayor how come you weren't
involved as much as you should have been because you're the mayor
of the City of Hartford?' Let me tell you something, if I know
somebody's doing the right job and they're working on behalf of the
city, I wouldn't want too many people in that room either for fear
of screwing up the deal,'' Peters said. ``I think the governor
handled it absolutely perfectly. ... I think he's fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rowland was not so well-liked by the Democrats earlier in
his term, when, sworn in at 37 in 1995, he was the state's youngest
governor ever.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Democrats _ then a minority _ were more
combative and Rowland was more conservative, fighting a
minimum-wage increase and campaigning against abortion.
Connecticut, the richest state in the nation per capita, also has
the most stringent welfare reform law, which Rowland touted in
campaign literature. The governor became embroiled in a few
low-rent ethics investigations _ stemming from the state leasing
his wife a Chevy Suburban and two of his children helping
themselves to state-owned camping equipment. But he came through
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Rowland supports abortion rights and he recently signed a
new $6.10 per-hour minimum wage law. He has also made improving
Bridgeport, New Haven and Hartford _ three of the country's poorest
cities _ a priority much in the way of an urban Democrat. And he
golfs with he leader of the more liberal House of Representatives,
Democratic Speaker Thomas Ritter.
</P>
<P>
   In Ritter's office on the top floor of Connecticut's tallest
building, sits a rendering of a stadium designed in 1993. Five
years ago the Legislature passed bonding for a new stadium but its
attempt to lure the Patriots to Hartford were foiled when Kraft,
who lives in Chestnut Hill, bought the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time with Kraft (Thursday) and he was really
blown away with how really well we all work,'' Ritter said. ``We're
all in the office. We're joking. He couldn't believe that all of us
were together. That really struck him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland defeated Kennelly earlier this month by stealing her
party's traditional issues, such as education, property tax relief
and improving working-class cities. Basically, the Democrats agree
with his vision, his plan, and his style. There's nothing much left
to fight about anymore, legislators say.
</P>
<P>
   There are some cynics, though, who contend Rowland changes his
mind to fit public opinion. An editorial cartoonist for the
Hartford Courant frequently draws him with a weather vane on his
head. But Rowland has certainly become more moderate with age,
although at 41, he is still the nation's youngest governor.
</P>
<P>
   His political career began in earnest when he was 23, elected to
the Legislature as a Republican from a Democratic district in
blue-collar Waterbury, where he was a Catholic high school
wrestling star.
</P>
<P>
   The Villanova University graduate held the post for four years
before making the leap to Congress, defeating a three-term
incumbent. In 1990, he ran for governor and lost to Lowell P.
Weicker Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But he found a $400,000 private-sector job as a business
consultant and then ran again in 1994. He won. This time, as a
Northeast Republican with broad-based appeal, much like the
Massachusetts Governor Paul Cellucci and his predecessor William
Weld.
</P>
<P>
   That appeal is evident even on the lonely after-hours streets of
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Said Patrick Smith, a tour guide-interpreter at the old State
House in Hartford: ``I'm not a big supporter of John Rowland. I
never have been. But I'm impressed with what he's done. He's
impressed me as a good businessman, a good negotiator. I'm
impressed with him swaying people to see what Hartford is really
like.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Globe correspondent Shira Springer contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
