</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-LIBRARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD KENNEDY LIBRARY TAKE A MORE OBJECTIVE APPROACH?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John F. Kennedy's striking figure and trademark
cadence, echoing through the halls, follow visitors on the
bittersweet trip of nostalgic idealism that is the John F. Kennedy
Library tour.
</P>
<P>
   Here, by Dorchester Bay, Kennedy's legend lives on unsullied. To
this day, the 35th anniversary of his assassination, a steady
stream of admirers comes to the library to recall three dramatic
years. Special exhibits, such as the one last year devoted to
Jackie Kennedy, swell attendance; this year, it has ebbed by 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But for some historians, the man honored within these walls
seems more saint than mortal. And for an electorate grown more
accustomed to all-too-human presidents and all-too-human Kennedys,
the library tour can seem a nostalgic trip back in time, to an era
when presidential records were scrubbed clean by the waters of
history.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these scholars, say the nation would be even better
served by broadening the missions of all federally funded
presidential libraries to discuss the mistakes, dilemmas, and
frailties of the chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should do more and want to do more,'' said Martin
Sherwin, a history professor at Tufts University. ``I would want
both the museum and the library to provide as sharp a view of the
past, both in the strengths and weaknesses of the Kennedy
administration and of the president himself, as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibits now pay little more than cursory attention to the
failed Bay of Pigs invasion, Kennedy's escalation of US involvement
in Vietnam, the assassination of South Vietnam President Ngo Dinh
Diem, and clandestine efforts to oust Cuban leader Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   On a global map where the flashpoints of the early 1960s are
highlighted, a caption under Cuba states that ``President Kennedy
accepted the CIA plan'' developed under President Dwight D.
Eisenhower for the Bay of Pigs invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Further text, which can be read to reflect nobly on a reluctant
warrior, states that this ``humiliating setback for the new
president'' was one for which ``he quickly accepted full
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby text on Vietnam says that it was Eisenhower who initiated
US military involvement, and that Kennedy dramatically increased
troop strength in response to a deteriorating political situation
there.
</P>
<P>
   The display acknowledges ``tacit'' administration approval of
the coup against the corrupt Diem regime, but states that the South
Vietnamese leader refused a US offer of safety before his
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   These assertions, and all others in the exhibit, pass the muster
of historical accuracy, museum spokesman Thomas McNaught said. But
accuracy without amplification is not as rich, the scholars
contend.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's undisputed victories _ the presidential debates with
Richard Nixon, the Cuban missile crisis, the Peace Corps, and the
pioneering space program _ are noted in much greater detail in a
meandering exhibition, where the president's stirring rhetoric is
never far from earshot.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the library's visitors _ 264,655 came in 1997 _ it
recreates the sense of hope that was Camelot. For others, it plays
like a cast album of ``Camelot,'' a perfectly preserved keepsake
from the early '60s, spinning on through time.
</P>
<P>
   Such a presentation probably should be expected, presidential
scholars say, in a city where Kennedy family influence remains
strong and respected. But President Kennedy, an avid reader of
history, may have welcomed a more candid overview of his
administration, suggests Alvin S. Felzenberg, a Washington-based
lecturer and writer on the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should the (museum's) mission be to glorify its principal, or
to illuminate the period, or to have the public working its way
through public-issue debates?'' Felzenberg asked. ``I'll say it's
all three of them.''
</P>
<P>
   McNaught said the facility makes ``no apologies'' for its
portrait of Kennedy. ``This is a museum and a library devoted to
President John F. Kennedy, and we are going to put the best face
forward without trying to reshape and rewrite history.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding lengthy text panels that probe the wisdom of Kennedy's
moves or delve into complicated issues such as the Cuban revolution
and US sentiment toward communism is an ``unreasonable''
expectation, McNaught said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say to historians'' who critique the display ``that
the museum is not the best place to trigger those kinds of
conversations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other presidential libraries, however, have taken steps in that
direction. The Franklin D. Roosevelt Library in Hyde Park, N.Y.,
examines that president's knowledge of the Holocaust. And in the
Lyndon B. Johnson Library at the University of Texas in Austin,
references to the Vietnam War and domestic protest clearly
demonstrate that Kennedy's successor sparked divisive national
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never a substitute for balanced, honest history,''
said Robert Dallek, a Boston University professor who wrote a
two-volume biography of Johnson and is working on a book about JFK.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Johnson Library,'' Dallek said, ``I found them eager
to put the best possible face on the man, his career and his
presidency. But they didn't neglect the inner-city riots and that
there was dissension over the Vietnam War. It's not a strictly
balanced portrait,'' but the museum does show that ``it wasn't
simply a golden era or a time of universal endorsement of Johnson's
presidency and leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy family has been criticized for the slow release of
White House tapes on the Cuban missile crisis and for severing
cooperation with authors writing unflattering books on the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Historians question whether the family's wishes also account for
maintaining the museum's starry portrait of JFK. McNaught said
decisions can be made independently of the family _ by curator
Frank Rigg, library archivists, and historians _ and that the
exhibit changes constantly. As a result, he said, the picture to
visitors is not unblemished. McNaught cited as examples documents
showing discontent among black leaders about Kennedy's pace on
civil rights, as well as evidence of Nixon's criticisms of Kennedy
during the 1960 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the library sponsors a range of lectures and
seminars on public issues. And its community-education programs may
be the most ambitious of any of the nation's 11 presidential
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   To McNaught, however, the purpose of the museum is more than
storing documents, displaying memorabilia, and sticking to the
historical record. The exhibit is also designed to convey the sense
that Kennedy ignited a spirit of purpose among Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about John F. Kennedy that the public will always
remember was his idealism, and his ability to give voice to that
idealism and inspire the American people to something that was
greater than themselves,'' McNaught said. ``I do think the museum
accomplishes that well.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Fidler of Chelmsford would agree. Visiting the museum for the
first time last week, Fidler said the exhibition helped him recall
the 1960s, when he was a young man.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the museum should question Kennedy's performance,
or draw attention to personal flaws, Fidler adamantly opposed such
changes. ``I think a presidential library is a repository of
history,'' he said. ``It's a place to reflect, not a place to open
old wounds and further divide the nation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
