<HEADER>
A3028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESEARCH-STANDARDS-BO     11-21 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEARCH-STANDARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERSIGHT OF SCIENTIFIC RESEARCH CALLED FAULTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saying the existing system for protecting people in research
fails to do the job, a congressional committee and medical
ethicists called last week for an independent national board with
the power to enforce rigorous standards and prevent harm.
</P>
<P>
   Citing psychiatric research abuses detailed in a Globe series
last week as adding impetus to efforts to create such a board,
legislators and ethicists said the move is urgently needed because
of the rapid pace of research and the poorly funded and overworked
state of research review boards.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Christopher Shays, a Republican from Connecticut,
plans to file a bill next year to create such a board, said
Lawrence Halloran, staff director and counsel for the House
Subcommittee on Human Resources, which is chaired by Shays.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is going to be the centerpiece of our legislation,'' said
Halloran, adding that the Globe's findings are helping to propel
the committee's efforts. ``Mr. Shays sees more than ever a need for
a permanent national bioethics panel,'' Halloran said, to set
training and research standards, and to serve as a central registry
of review boards and research.
</P>
<P>
   Some medical ethicists want such a panel to go even further, by
having the authority to sanction researchers deemed to have acted
unethically.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have real live penalties for violating the rights
of subjects _ like fines and jail,'' said George Annas, chairman of
Boston University's health law department, who plans on drafting
legislation to create a board able to impose sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jay Katz, a Yale University professor emeritus of law,
medicine, and psychiatry who was the first to call for such a
national board, agreed: ``If you don't have any teeth in the
regulations, that creates problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe series detailed how psychiatric researchers for the
past 25 years have conducted a series of ``challenge'' and drug
withdrawal studies in order to examine the biology of the disease,
not treat the patients' illness. Mentally ill patients in challenge
studies were given a stimulant such as amphetamine to stir symptoms
of their psychosis; in withdrawal studies, patients were taken off
their medication so they could be observed as their symptoms
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Many past efforts to ensure the ethics of research have been
ineffective, authorities noted.
</P>
<P>
   A policy adopted by the International Committee of Medical
Journal Editors, requiring researchers to indicate whether they
conducted their studies in accordance with ethical standards, has
not prevented the challenge studies from being published.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a very effective mechanism for the
regulation of research,'' said Leonard Glantz, professor of health
law at Boston University School of Public Health. ``Journals are
too distant from events that went on. It's sort of
after-the-fact.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 bill to criminalize unethical research, filed by Senator
John Glenn, the Ohio Democrat who is leaving office next year, has
languished. The Human Research Subject Protections Act he proposed
would have penalized researchers who failed to get proper informed
consent and ethical review in all experiments, whether publicly or
privately funded.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 20 years, federal commissions have repeatedly
called for special research protections for people with mental
illness, without success.
</P>
<P>
   A presidentially appointed National Bioethics Advisory
Commission last week recommended such protections be adopted, but
some legislators, ethicists, and mental health advocates worry that
its proposals either do not go far enough or will be largely
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran, the House committee counsel, said he was particularly
concerned that the advisory commission did not take a strong stance
on research that exacerbates psychotic symptoms, or on safeguarding
the rights of people with mental illness who do not have the
capacity to consent meaningfully to take part in research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing they couldn't advance the ball on those
subjects,'' Halloran said.
</P>
<P>
   Adil Shamoo, a University of Maryland bioethicist and editor of
the journal Accountability in Research, said he viewed some of the
advisory commission's report as positive, but ``I think
fundamentally it's flawed. They did not prohibit the worst-case
scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Shapiro, National Bioethics Advisory Commission chairman
and president of Princeton University, said last week that while
the commission only has authority to recommend regulations to the
White House, ``we hope that the report will be convincing to enough
people, that people will be inclined to take these recommendations
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatric researchers, on the other hand, have objected to the
advisory commission's recommendations as going too far and
threatening to paralyze research that could help improve
understanding of and treatments for mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in a letter to the commission, Dr. Robert W.
Buchanan of the Maryland Psychiatric Research Center, which has
conducted some of the challenge studies, said some of the
commission's recommendations ``reinforce concerns'' among
researchers that the commission is ``antipsychiatric research.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Shapiro: ``You never 100 percent satisfy anyone. Either you
ask too much or you ask too little. This is our best judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   But for medical ethicist Annas, who in the 1970s served as a
consultant on the first national commission to call for special
protections for people with mental illness, that is not good
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need an agency to do something, to protect human subjects,
to hold researchers accountable,'' said Annas, adding that the
Globe series is helping to push the calls for a strong national
board. ``It's time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
