<HEADLINE>
SEMINOLES BEAT GATORS, 23-12  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Florida Coach Steve Spurrier smugly said
before Saturday's game that winning here wasn't necessarily on his
coaching wish list.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now it should be.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida State Seminoles (No. 1 in the New York Times's
computer ranking and No. 5 in the Associated Press poll) used a
vise-like defense and several big plays from wide receiver Peter
Warrick to vault past Spurrier's Gators, 23-12, before a Doak
Campbell Stadium record crowd of 81,614.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd got some unexpected pre-game entertainment, when the
two teams scuffled at midfield and three players were ejected.
</P>
<P>
   The victory left Florida State at 11-1 and still in the national
title race, while sending Florida (9-2) home with more shattered
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier, the most successful coach in Gator history, is now
0-4-1 here. In fact, Florida (No. 6 Times, No. 4 AP) has not won
here since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles, who were behind throughout the first half, moved
ahead to stay early in the third quarter. And the points came
courtesy of a Florida defender.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Outzen threw the ball directly to Gator strong safety
Marquand Manuel, but it squirted through Manuel's hands and was
seized by Warrick, who zigzagged by cornerback Bennie Alexander to
complete a 32-yard touchdown play.
</P>
<P>
   That put Florida State ahead by 13-12, and a trick play finished
off Florida early in the final period. Warrick took a handoff from
running back Jeff Chaney and passed to the wide-open split end, Ron
Dugans, for a 46-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   A 41-yard field goal from Sebastian Janikowski with 4 minutes 31
seconds left was window dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State benefited from the pre-game scuffle, which stoked
the crowd into a screaming mob. Florida's starting senior
cornerback, Tony George, was ejected, while Florida State lost two
players not even listed on the depth chart, linemen Ronald Boldin
and Josh Baggs.
</P>
<P>
   On the game's second play, Seminoles free safety Dexter Jackson
intercepted a Doug Johnson pass and returned it 33 yards for what
appeared to be a touchdown. But cornerback Mario Edwards was
detected holding receiver Natis Karim.
</P>
<P>
   The teams exchanged punts before the Gators found a weakness,
moving 81 yards in just three plays. A 15-yard pass to tight end
Erron Kinney, with 15 yards tacked on for a personal foul, got the
visitors started. The drive ended suddenly, with Johnson looking
right and finding wide receiver Travis McGriff alone for a 50-yard
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators had another opportunity seconds later, but could not
capitalize on Outzen's fumble. The sophomore quarterback, starting
just his second college game, was stripped of the ball by tackle
Reggie McGrew, who was playing despite a sprained ligament in his
lower back.
</P>
<P>
   That set up Florida at the Seminoles' 19-yard line, but a
third-down pass by Johnson was intercepted by Sean Key.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second quarter, the Seminoles appeared to
benefit from a questionable call. Outzen was sacked by McGrew,
sending the ball bouncing into the end zone. Gators tackle Gerard
Warren fell on it for an apparent touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But several Florida State players landed on Warren and the ball
ended up being cradled by Seminoles tackle Ross Brannon for a
Florida safety.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators did not seem to let that bother them. They promptly
drove to the Seminoles' 5-yard line before settling for Jeff
Chandler's 22-yard field goal and a 12-6 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
