<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FISH-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES COULD SALVAGE COWBOYS' GOLDEN MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Imagine it: Tony Dorsett and Emmitt Smith,
both 12,000-yard rushers, on the field, together, at the same time!
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate in Cowboys Fantasy Football? Sure. And it could be
the ultimate in reality, too.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Cowboys whiffed on an opportunity to pair the
two best running backs in their history when Smith surpassed
Dorsett as the franchise's all-time leading rusher. It would have
been a golden moment, a snapshot of a lifetime, had owner Jerry
Jones thought to have Dorsett as his guest at Texas Stadium that
day against the Giants, poised to pass the torch to his successor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea why I wasn't invited,'' Dorsett said.
``Normally, that's kind of standard in sports. Billy Sims was there
when Barry Sanders broke his records in Detroit. It's kind of a
snub.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Jones and some members of the previous generations of
Cowboys are back to where they were almost a decade ago, when he
was perceived by old-timers as an egomaniac with no understanding
or respect for the rich history of the Cowboys. The ghosts of Jones
vs. Tom Landry and Jones vs. Tex Schramm are being resurrected by
Jones vs. Dorsett, which has evolved into a game of ``Did Not, Did
So.''
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't Jones invite Dorsett? Jones says, ``I thought it
would be a distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Counters Dorsett: ``He's had movie stars and princes and lots of
friends on the sideline. I don't see how I would've been more \Rof
a distraction\S than them.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Jones: ``We didn't have Drew Pearson there for Michael
Irvin breaking records and we didn't specifically invite Roger
\RStaubach\S when Troy \RAikman\S broke passing records. It just
hasn't been our policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Counters Dorsett: ``We've got two guys with 12,000 yards. That
may be as significant a record as the Cowboys will have.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Jones: ``If I had it to do over again, I would've invited
Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Counters Dorsett: ``Oh, sure. I'm supposed to trust the man
who's made other promises to me and not kept them? With all the
things that have happened, I have a hard time trusting the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett was a business partner in Cowboys Sports Cafe, the
Valley Ranch restaurant that Jones once declared off-limits because
the NFL expressed ``bad element'' concerns about some of the
restaurant's patrons. Dorsett says the ban came only one week after
he'd been assured by Jones that there would be no such measure
taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Jerry Jones put me out of business,'' Dorsett says.
</P>
<P>
   Personal problems aside, Jones had lots of reasons to avoid
inviting Dorsett to the game, led by his long-held concern for the
perception that he relies on the coattails of the old Cowboys to
hide present-day Cowboys warts.
</P>
<P>
   Personal problems aside, Dorsett had lots of reasons to be at
Texas Stadium on his own. He is, after all, a season-ticket holder.
Staubach was at the game, by his own volition. So were dozens of
other ex-Cowboys who don't need gold-engraved invitations to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   Still, any chasm between old and new is sad, and which side is
more wrong (''Tony's a baby''/''Jerry's a jerk'') is debatable, if
not immaterial. It's understandable that Dorsett wants to be
coddled; that's what professional athletes are accustomed to. And,
it's unfair to accuse Jones of disrespecting the past; of the 10
men in the Ring of Honor, all are old-generation and four were
inducted by Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Can this marriage be saved? Yes. Here's my plan:
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who could use any edge available for the
Thanksgiving Day game against the talented Vikings, finally extend
the invitation to Dorsett _ and Don Perkins, Calvin Hill, Duane
Thomas and Herschel Walker. And in a nationally televised pregame
ceremony, the six greatest running backs in Cowboys history (not to
mention NFL history) share a joyous and noteworthy spotlight, with
Smith and Dorsett as the centerpieces.
</P>
<P>
   The country receives a heck of a show. The Cowboys receive an
emotional boost. Smith receives his ``torch.'' Dorsett receives his
due. And so do the rest of the fellas. Just outside of camera
range, Jones basks in the feel-good glow. And decadelong wounds are
healed.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry, you have a lot to be thankful for, including Tony Dorsett
and the generations of Cowboys that came before him. So thank him.
Thank them all.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers game 25.8 _ The definition of a breakaway threat,
Minnesota's Robert Smith averages 25.8 yards per touchdown run, the
highest in NFL history among players with at least 20 rushing
touchdowns.
Trivial pursuit When was the last time Marty Schottenheimer, an NFL
head coach for 14 years, lost five consecutive games? Never, until
this season. The Chiefs have dropped consecutive games against New
England, Pittsburgh, the Jets, Seattle and Denver. The Chiefs have
a chance to break the streak today at San Diego, but at 4-6 and
unraveling from the inside, they are in danger of suffering a
losing season _ something else that Schottenheimer's never
experienced.
Quotable ``We have the capability of being the greatest group of
wideouts on one team, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Vikings wide receiver Cris Carter on the receiving trio that
includes himself, rookie Randy Moss and Jake Reed.
Check out ... The officiating fallout from the Cowboys-Cardinals
game. The Cardinals have nobody _ not even the officials who failed
to flag Kevin Smith for interference in the end zone on the final
play of a 35-28 loss _ to blame but themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The three-step review of how the Cardinals screwed up their own
chances in the final seconds:
</P>
<P>
   1. Rob Moore's 58-yard catch-and-run. Once he got to the 5-yard
line, he wanted the touchdown and tried to bull into the end zone,
gaining no yardage against two Cowboys tacklers and wasting
valuable seconds. Had he gotten out of bounds, more than 30 seconds
(and four plays) would have been available to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   2. Jake Plummer's stop-the-clock spike. The clock is down to 20
seconds. The Cowboys defense is scrambling, confused, tired,
scared. I'll never know why offenses don't plan for these
situations. The Cardinals spiked the ball, thus wasting first down.
They were left them with only two plays.
</P>
<P>
   3. Moore vs. Kevin Smith in the end zone. Was it interference?
Who knows? Was Plummer's throw two feet too low? Definitely. Had
Plummer thrown the ball higher, Smith's involvement in the play
would have been incidental, Moore would have scored a touchdown and
the Cardinals would believe the game was pristinely officiated.
AFC Buzz Linebacker Chad Brown has played for the Steelers and the
Seahawks. As the Cowboys try to learn the strengths and weaknesses
of the Seahawks, their Sunday visitors to Texas Stadium, Brown
contrasts and compares. ``The Seahawks are run as a corporation,''
Brown said. ``They're not run like a family, like the Steelers are.
With the Steelers, if \Rowner Dan\S Rooney was out sick on payday,
we didn't get paid because he had to sign the checks. There's
obviously a little higher budget here, and it makes this nice. ...
With the Steelers, you had to turn in your old jock to get a new
jock.'' ... How is the AFC-centric CBS pregame show faring in Fort
Worth-Dallas? Insiders at KTVT/Channel 11 say its locally produced
``In The Huddle'' show featuring Eric Dickerson, Craig James and
Gil Brandt recently earned a 3.0 share. Then on came the network
show, which drew a 2.1 ... Baltimore at Cincinnati: The Bengals,
losers of five consecutive games and seven of their past eight,
bench quarterback Neil O'Donnell, bypass backup Jeff Blake and
start third-stringer Paul Justin. ... Maybe Chiefs players wouldn't
feel free to take cheap shots if, as alleged, coach Marty
Schottenheimer hadn't long ago issued a bounty on Broncos players.
I'm told the NFL investigated such charges last year, and after
Monday night, the league should be motivated to investigate again.
... Denver has outscored opponents 114-13 in first quarters. ...
Look for the Jets to work out a new contract for quarterback Vinny
Testaverde. ... What happened to Tennessee owner Bud Adams'
announced plan to conduct a contest for fans to pick the new name
of his franchise? Instead, Adams has decided to just handle it
himself. Thus, the Tennessee Titans, which Adams says fits his
desire to have the nickname reflect the team's new home. I don't
get it, but welcome to the wacky world of Bud Adams. ... By the
way, Jets at Oilers is actually Titans at Titans (the Jets' 1960-62
nickname vs. the Oilers' future nickname).
NFC Buzz Arizona quarterback Jake Plummer's numbers in his past
three second halves: 44 of 66, 606 yards, four touchdowns and no
interceptions. Sounds great. But if he has ``arrived'' as ``the
next Fran Tarkenton,'' what's he doing down 28-0 in the first half?
Plummer's rating in his past three games is a very good 95.5.
Great, except his rating through Week 7 was a lousy 63.1. ... You
want parity? Green Bay is the only 1997 division champion that won
last Sunday. ... Greg Hill remains the Rams' leading rusher despite
being out since Week 3 with a broken leg. ... Arizona at
Washington: The Redskins played the Cards tough two weeks ago,
losing, 29-27, and have won two consecutive game at home,
outscoring foes 49-17. ... The Cowboys have swept their four
division road games for the first time since 1983. ... Saints at
49ers: San Francisco has outscored New Orleans 87-7 in past three
meetings. ... The 3-7 Lions have not won on Sunday afternoon. Their
three victories have been prime-time games. ... More evidence the
Cardinals don't get it: During last week's game against the
Cowboys, a member of the Bill Bidwill ownership family was a guest
on the Cardinals radio network to announce the club's plans to sell
tickets to any Cardinals home playoff game. I bet the phones didn't
exactly light up; Arizona was behind, 28-7, at the time. ... The
Eagles have only two touchdown catches this season, none of which
were caught by wide receivers. ... The Packers hope to get runner
Dorsey Levens back from injury next month. ... Detroit's Barry
Sanders needs one touchdown to become the sixth player with 100.
... Friends of Steve Mariucci say the 49ers coach is irritated at
how slowly his contract renewal is moving, but the word is he will
get an extension through 2005.
</P>
