<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDBACKS GAIN IN JOHNSON DERBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Signing Todd Stottlemyre has made the Arizona Diamondbacks a
serious threat to sign free-agent pitcher Randy Johnson. In fact,
Arizona may be the clear-cut favorite. If so, the Rangers could be
hurting.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' two obstacles going into the process were
being in the National League and being a last-place team. Johnson
told the Rangers he wants to play on an American League team that's
competitive and is located west of the Mississippi River.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks are still in the National League, but signing
Stottlemyre sends Johnson a signal they're serious about winning as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to do things to become competitive sooner rather
than later,'' Diamondbacks owner Jerry Colangelo told Arizona
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' main advantage remains Johnson's residence in
a Phoenix suburb and his desire to pitch close to home. Johnson has
three children, and sources close to him say he's serious when he
talks about the importance of being near his family.
</P>
<P>
   Economics will also be a factor, but the second-year
Diamondbacks have yet to flinch in that area. Baseball officials
are still amazed Colangelo gave Jay Bell $34 million over five
years last year when nobody else was offering anything close to
that.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson spent the weekend in Southern California visiting the
Angels and the Dodgers. But the Angels are getting close to signing
Mo Vaughn, which would likely take them out of the running for
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, backed by Fox television's deep pockets, should
make a strong run at Johnson, especially if they can trade Eric
Karros or Gary Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers remain in the running, but general manager Doug
Melvin may have to start looking at alternatives. There are few
that are attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Belcher, Pete Schourek and Bob Tewksbury are among the best
of the remaining free agents, and Ismael Valdes, Pat Hentgen and
Joey Hamilton are the pitchers most likely to be available for
trade. But that means giving up players in return.
Random observations: Rangers minor-league outfielder Mike Zywica
won the Arizona Fall League batting championship with a .330
batting average. He also led the league in runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Zywica would earn a bigger honor if he ever makes it to the
major leagues. Of the thousands of players who have played in the
big leagues, Zywica would be absolutely last alphabetically. That
would put him in exclusive company. Hank Aaron is first.
</P>
<P>
   The most exciting competition in the off-season is for the
coveted title of Worst Contract Given Out. Brian Bohanon's
three-year, $9 million deal with the Colorado Rockies was the early
leader but was quickly overtaken by the Boston Red Sox. Baseball is
still stunned that Jose Offerman was given $26 million over four
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, being publicly criticized in New York for their
interest in Albert Belle, have increased their efforts to re-sign
Bernie Williams. There is a five-year, $60 million offer on the
table, and Williams' bargaining power decreased when the Dodgers
signed Devon White and the Rockies re-signed Darryl Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan, who picked a great time to have a career year, has
narrowed his choices to the Yankees, Mets, Orioles and the Braves.
Look for the Orioles to win if they re-sign Rafael Palmeiro, too.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals and Colorado Rockies are both interested
in Kevin Brown, but both aren't enthusiastic about meeting his
demand for a six-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   If Belle dumps the White Sox and goes elsewhere, that will give
them the money to re-sign popular third baseman Robin Ventura.
Otherwise, they'll avoid big-name free agents and stick to their
youth movement.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers, in exchange for dropping his demand to be traded,
is talking about a deal in which he pitches for the Oakland
Athletics next year then gets to become a free agent. He currently
has an option for 2000 that would kick in if he pitches 160 innings
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians have talked to Toronto general manager Gord Ash
about Roger Clemens, but general manager John Hart told Cleveland
reporters, ``I asked Gord if he was going to move him and he said,
`Not at this time. We're building around him.' Gord made it very
clear they're not going to move him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Twins, who must cut their payroll to $17 million,
have been approached by a number of clubs about Brad Radke, who
general manager Terry Ryan said is not available.
</P>
<P>
   If Ricky Bottalico comes back strong from last year's elbow
problems, then the Cardinals have made a terrific deal in getting
him for outfielder Ron Gant.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Brian Giles to emerge as an offensive force if the
Pirates allow him to play every day. They got him cheaply by giving
reliever Ricardo Rincon to the Indians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
