r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BAYLOR-TEXAS-ARLI     11-21 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BAYLOR-TEXAS-ARLINGTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR'S LATE RALLY FOILS UTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Baylor basketball players said they could not
easily handle another close loss, not for a third time and not
again at the Ferrell Center.
</P>
<P>
   Down the stretch, UT-Arlington did its part to help out the home
team yesterday in Baylor's 64-59 men's victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks blew a four-point lead with 3 minutes, 46 seconds
left by going scoreless on five consecutive possessions. UTA (0-1)
went 1-for-4 from the free-throw line in the closing minutes, and
junior forward Dewayne Marable finished a 1-for-13 day by missing
two outside shots in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (1-2), after close losses against Arkansas State and
Louisiana Tech, picked up its first victory with 1,405 in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   UTA let slip away what would have been its first Division I,
season-opening victory since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, we had our chances,'' UTA coach Eddie McCarter
said. ``Down the stretch, we've got to make plays, we've got to hit
shots and we have to make our free throws. We didn't do those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   UTA was down 39-30 early in the second half before fighting back
to 50-49, coming within one on a Marable 18-footer.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks forward Donald Harris hit a breakaway layup and was
fouled on UTA's next possession. His free throw was good, and UTA
took a 52-50 lead with 5:30 left. Another Harris layup with 3:46
left made it 56-52.
</P>
<P>
   The game switched in Baylor's favor during a one-minute stretch
that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Harris fouled out at the 2:37 mark, and Baylor guard Tevis
Stukes took a pass from Kish Lewis and nailed a 23-foot jumper to
pull within 57-56. Baylor's defense took over from there, and the
Bears went 8-for-10 from the line in the final 1:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got down, we didn't go up in the shell in this game
like we have in the other two,'' Stukes said. ``We had to fight
hard. I wanted the ball in my hands in the that situation. Win or
lose, I want the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The pass from Lewis on the Stokes 3-pointer was an example of
how Lewis, a 6-foot-7 senior, hurt UTA all day.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis finished with 13 rebounds and 20 points on 7-for-13
shooting. Stukes had 17, and Jamie Kendrick scored 10 as Baylor
outrebounded UTA, 44-31.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Washington led UTA with 20 points; Harris scored 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was the worst game we've played of the three so
far,'' Baylor coach Harry Miller said. ``I saw some good things,
but I'm not seeing any consistency.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
