<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTCARDS FROM THE LEDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was several weeks before the official announcement that
University of Texas running back Ricky Williams would be the Doak
Walker Award winner last December when Darrell Royal picked up the
phone and called the Doaker himself.
</P>
<P>
   Royal, knowing his old friend was probably wincing at the sight
of Ricky's dreadlocks, had a specific reason for his call. He
wanted to assure Doak that this kid was something special, both as
a player and as a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dunno,'' Walker said, unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm voting for him,'' Royal replied. ``I just wanted you to
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at the awards ceremony, Walker and his wife, Skeeter,
were captivated by Williams. After Walker was paralyzed in that
terrible skiing accident, Skeeter said Williams wrote or called
every week until her husband died.
</P>
<P>
   This story comes from Texas assistant athletic director Bill
Little, who got it from the horse's mouth, Royal himself. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The only flaw we've seen is that he can't hit the curveball.''
_ Terry Bradway, Kansas City Royals head of personnel and scouting
director, quoted in last week's issue of ``Sports Illustrated'' and
referring to Williams' going-nowhere baseball career in the
Phillies' farm system. ...
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of ``SI'', take a look at pages 10-11 in this
week's Leading Off section. No way anyone can look at that sequence
of four photos and not understand that the Cowboys' Kevin Smith was
guilty of flagrant pass interference and/or defensive holding on
the Cardinals' Rob Moore on the final play of last Sunday's victory
against Arizona. End of debate. ... Revo's Insider of the Week To
those who tried to compare Will Clark's departure for three games
from the Rangers at the end of May and the Rangers' subsequent
explanation that it was a ``personal matter'' with the cover-up of
the Michael Irvin scissors affair at training camp in Wichita Falls
in August, hope you read last Sunday's story about Clark's son,
Trey, being diagnosed as autistic.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Clark abruptly left the team in Tampa Bay and
returned to Texas to be with his family. ``That day he came to me
in my office and told me he had to go back to Texas,'' manager
Johnny Oates says, ``is the only time I've ever seen Will cry.''...
</P>
<P>
   How did American League rookie of the year Ben Grieve first
learn to hit? When he was 2, father Tom handed him a Wiffle Ball
bat, blew up balloons and let the toddler start swinging. ``He
started to hit left-handed,'' Tom, now the Rangers' TV analyst,
recalls. ``We didn't teach him and we didn't stop him.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Former Mavs media guru Kevin Sullivan, under a new arrangement
with Ross Perot Jr., says he'll stay on the company payroll while
actually working for the 2012 Olympic Committee helping put Dallas'
bid together. Longtime assistant Tony Fay replaces Sullivan with
the Mavs. ...
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, there's speculation that 42-year-old quarterback
Warren Moon needs to get his act together again soon _ like today
against the Cowboys _ or find himself riding the bench for the rest
of the season with his $5 million nonguaranteed contract for next
season a moot point. ...
</P>
<P>
   Former Cowboys linebacker Darrin Smith will start today for the
Seahawks and brushes off suggestions that his former team's 7-3
record is merely a product of playing in the weak NFC East.
``They've beaten the teams they were supposed to beat, with the
exception of Chicago,'' Smith notes. ``They beat three teams we
beat \RArizona, Philadelphia, Washington\S, so if you say anything
\Rbad\S about them, what does that say about us?''...
</P>
<P>
   NBA super agent David Falk, responding to commissioner David
Stern's charges that he and other agents are at least part of the
problem behind the labor dispute that threatens to shelve the
season: ``There's a misconception that I'm running the thing, but
I've barely lifted a finger. Now, of course, I'm going to get
involved.'' That is not good news. ...
</P>
<P>
   And Falk on client Michael Jordan's involvement in the labor
negotiations: ``I've heard that some people feel these negotiations
will lure Michael to keep playing. I think his involvement has
given him an added stature in the league, if that's even possible.
In any case, Michael is too intelligent to let labor negotiations
determine whether he comes back or not.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   The ``St. Louis Post Dispatch'' says Stars winger Brett Hull
turned down a chance to play in Chicago at the advice of former
Blues general manager Ron Caron, who was paraphrased in the
newspaper, saying, ``\RBlackhawks'\S Owner Bill Wirtz was erratic,
rookie coach Dirk Graham was untested and the lineup was a mess.''
...
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that when the police are dead wrong about something _
like mistakenly arresting the Hampton University women's basketball
coach, her husband and her assistant for running an alleged con in
a Lubbock Wal-Mart parking lot _ they have such a hard time
apologizing? Fear of lawsuits, perhaps? Wrong is wrong, but the
Lubbock police will let the city's mayor try to soothe the hurt
feelings while maintaining that they were just doing their jobs.
...
</P>
<P>
   Former Rangers pitching coach Tom House has interviewed for the
pitching coach's job in San Diego, now that Dave Stewart has left.
House has spent the past couple of years working for the Padres as
their international consultant, mostly in Japan. ...
</P>
<P>
   OK, so we're all in agreement that the Rangers' Juan Gonzalez
was the American League's MVP in 1998, and Sammy Sosa was the
National League's MVP. Now we can we also all agree that
``baseball's'' MVP was the Cardinals' Mark McGwire? I believe ``70
home runs'' trumps any argument to the contrary. ...
</P>
<P>
   Our national football writer, Wendell Barnhouse, had faxed a
letter to Kansas State coach Bill Snyder after last weekend's
K-State-Nebraska game pointing out the unfairness of allowing
quarterback Michael Bishop to speak to only ``Sports Illustrated''
after the game. Much to Barnhouse's surprise, Snyder phoned him
personally to apologize and then, at his weekly press conference
Tuesday, apologized to the writers there and brought Bishop in for
interviews.
Revo's rimshots
</P>
<P>
   Let me get this straight: Ken Caminiti turned down a three-year,
$21 million offer from Detroit to accept a two-year, $9.5 million
offer with Houston? Either Caminiti thought the Tigers were paying
with Canadian dollars or he flunked Business 101.
</P>
<P>
   Had a pleasant enough trip to Lubbock last weekend for the
Texas-Texas Tech game, but then, I wasn't hanging around the local
Wal-Mart, either, thank heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Spotted in Vegas, with a bandage on his hand: Dennis Rodman.
Friends say not to worry, it's just a sprain to his shooting hand,
and when it comes to rolling dice, he's ambidextrous.
</P>
<P>
   John Blake's fate may be decided when University of Oklahoma
regents meet today in Norman. No, he won't be asking Troy Aikman to
appear as a character witness.
</P>
<P>
   _ Old buds Bill Parcells and Jimmy Johnson conspiring to share
information about injured Patriots receiver Terry Glenn? Nah. They
wouldn't do that, would they? Not where anyone could ever prove it,
they wouldn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
