<SLUG> BC-FBC-NORTH-TEXAS-NEW-MEXICO-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNT WINS, BUT MISSES ON SHARE OF BIG WEST TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GENE MENEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ As soon as North Texas tight end Brian Futrell
recovered a New Mexico State on-side kick to secure a 19-11 victory
yesterday, the Eagles players turned their attention to Boise,
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles became the biggest fans of the Boise State Broncos
this side of Idaho. With a Boise State victory against Idaho, North
Texas (3-8 overall, 3-2 Big West Conference) would have earned a
four-way share of the Big West title and would have owned the
tiebreaker over the other three teams for a possible bid in the
Humanitarian Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Broncos fan right now, big-time,'' UNT senior center
Phillip Armour said immediately after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Said UNT linebacker Jeff Rodgers: ``Most of us will go to our
apartments right now and watch the ticker on ESPN2 and see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. Idaho edged Boise State, 36-35, in overtime,
making a two-point conversion that won the Vandals (8-3, 4-1) the
Big West title and the Humanitarian Bowl berth.
</P>
<P>
   For North Texas, the leftovers were not so bad. Before 7,432
fans at Fouts Field, the Eagles played possibly their best
defensive game of the season in defeating the Aggies and, as a
result, tied Nevada for second place in the Big West _ its best
finish since the school joined the conference in 1996. The Eagles
were picked to finish last.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we could today,'' UNT coach Darrell Dickey said
after finishing his first season at the helm. ``It is something for
us to build on _ finishing as high as we did in the conference.''
</P>
<P>
   The UNT defense held the Aggies (3-8, 1-4), ranked No. 7 in the
country in rushing offense and No. 13 in total offense, to their
second lowest scoring output of the season. The Eagles also forced
four turnovers, which matched the defense's best of the season, and
stopped New Mexico State twice in the second half on fourth-down
plays inside the UNT 11-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas limited New Mexico State running back Denvis Manns,
one of just three Division I-A players to rush for more than 1,000
yards in four different seasons, to 131 yards. UNT running back
Ja'Quay Wilburn ran for 162 yards on 26 carries and also caught a
26-yard touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've faced the best \Rrunning backs\S in the country, and he
\RManns\S was another good back,'' said UNT linebacker Jeff
Rodgers, who tied free safety Phillip Littlejohn with a team-high
nine tackles. ``But I've got all the confidence in the world in our
defense, especially against the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was probably our best effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Big plays helped the Eagles build a 16-3 halftime lead. A
41-yard pass from Chase Corley to receiver Kendrick Hollie set up a
29-yard Garrett Courtney field goal to tie the score at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles got the ball back at the Aggies' 29-yard line after
sophomore Derek Gordon, a Marcus High School graduate, blocked an
Andy Kohl punt _ Gordon's second punt block in two games. Three
plays later, Wilburn turned a simple dump-off pass along the right
sideline into a 26-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   On the Eagles' next drive, Wilburn ripped off a 48-yard run that
set up another Courtney field goal, and Littlejohn set up
Courtney's third of four field goals with an interception of K.C.
Enzminger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw the ball right to me,'' Littlejohn said. ``That was a
Larry Brown pick.''
</P>
<P>
   North Texas' average starting position in the first half was the
Aggies' 45-yard line.
Extra points
</P>
<P>
   North Texas has won its final home game of the season for the
past six years. ... UNT blocked a punt, blocked a field goal and
recovered a pooch kick against the Aggies. All came in the first
half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
