<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECOND CHANCE IS REWARD ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If only the NHL could award three Masterton Trophies this
season, then maybe John Cullen, Paul Stewart and Milos Holan could
receive their due.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, none is expected to take home the league's award
given for perseverance and dedication to the game. Stewart is a
referee, and Cullen and Holan aren't playing in the league. Still,
their stories of overcoming illness to return to the ice is what
the Masterton is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was diagnosed with colon cancer this summer, and yet he
is back skating in the NHL after an operation in June to remove the
cancer. Cullen and Holan each had bone marrow transplants and are
trying to recover from the shock and damage done to their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Cullen, who started the season with the Tampa Bay Lightning, is
skating with the Cleveland Lumberjacks of the International Hockey
League. Holan, who tried to come back with the Mighty Ducks of
Anaheim in training camp, is skating in Europe. Both are long shots
to play in the NHL this season, although Cullen likely will be
given every chance by the Lightning to return to the team.
</P>
<P>
   And that's all he's asking. Cullen turned down an offer to
become an assistant coach, and instead accepted his demotion to
Cleveland. Already, he has tied a Lumberjacks' mark by recording
seven points (two goals, five assists) in a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hockey Gods are on my side,'' Cullen said. ``Every bounce
was going my way.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's hoping the bounces of life continue to also fall onto
his stick.
</P>
<P>
   Stars trainer Dave Surprenant said these athletes might have a
better chance of surviving cancer than the average Joe. Being in
good physical shape is an obvious key to fighting any disease.
Being in touch with diet and exercise also seem to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``With most people, exercise is something you have to make time
for,'' Surprenant said. ``These people are paid to stay in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Having constant medical attention, as athletes do in the form of
trainers and team doctors, also is helpful in early detection,
Surprenant said. Although Stewart, 43, didn't worry about testing
until he saw ``Today'' show host Katie Couric speaking about the
cancer of her husband, Jay Monahan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was her sadness that catalyzed me into going to the
doctor,'' Stewart said. ``It was the week my son was born. My wife
and I were watching TV, and with all of the symptoms that were
being ticked off, I kept looking over at her and saying, `I have
that one. That one. That one.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stewart said he would like to be someone who gets the
message across _ not only that cancer testing is critical, but the
disease can be beat. Cullen also has accepted the role of
spokesman, as has Holan.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as all three don't mind telling their stories,
they'd rather tell stories of hockey accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes on, the novelty will wear off, and what will be
important is that wherever I go, I will be a referee,'' Stewart
said.
SLAPSHOTS Christmas shopping Canucks general manager Bryan Burke
was in Dallas Friday night for the Stars-Islanders game and to stir
the pot, hoping a possible trade of holdout winger Pavel Bure for
unsigned Isles winger Ziggy Palffy could be in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Burke confirmed he chatted with Islanders general manager Mike
Milbury.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the deal makes no sense. The Isles won't pay Palffy $6
million a year, but would be willing to pay Bure $8 million? Burke
guaranteed on Friday the Canucks will pay no part of Bure's salary.
Cam can't Former Bruins great Cam Neely has elected to remain just
that _ a retired NHL superstar. Neely, 33, canned a comeback
attempt last week when his arthritic right hip began acting up
during workouts in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't have any relief at all from the pain, you have
to wonder if you can really play again,'' Neely said. ``The only
thing I was lacking out there was conditioning and a right hip.
Skillwise, I feel that I could play this game.'' Kennedy rebounds
Anyone who has followed the saga of Sheldon Kennedy has to be
cheering for the 29-year-old forward. Kennedy went public two
seasons ago that he was sexually abused by his junior-hockey coach,
Graham James, setting off a maelstrom in Canada as James was jailed
and the entire junior-hockey system was turned on its ear.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy eventually washed out of the NHL, but this past summer
completed a 136-day, 5,000-mile in-line skate across Canada,
raising $3 million to help sexually abused children. Friday,
Kennedy returned to the ice with the Manitoba Moose of the
International Hockey League and scored the game-winning goal in a
5-2 victory against the Kansas City Blades.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 6,000 in Winnipeg gave him a standing ovation. The
week ahead Tomorrow
</P>
<P>
   Sharks at Stars: The Bryan Marchment saga continues. Sometime,
somewhere, a Stars player is really going to pop this guy.
</P>
<P>
   Friday
</P>
<P>
   Canucks at Red Wings: Two of the NHL's winningest coaches _ the
Red Wings' Scotty Bowman and the Canucks' Mike Keenan _ duke it
out.
</P>
<P>
   Oilers at Flames: The Battle of Alberta is one of the most
enjoyable rivalries in the league.
</P>
<P>
   THE BUZZ Eastern Conference The Sabres have some sort of hex
over the Maple Leafs, running their unbeaten streak against Toronto
to 6-0-3 with a 4-1 victory Friday night. That's not good news in
Toronto when you consider the teams will meet six times this season
after meeting only twice a year in the past. ``I don't think it's
any special success that we have against them,'' Sabres winger
Matthew Barnaby said. ``It's just the way it goes some nights.
Against the Maple Leafs, they all seem to go in.''... The Tampa Bay
Lightning has allowed five goals in a period eight times this
season, already matching a team record. Tampa has lost four
consecutive, outscored 27-5 in the process. ... Capitals left
winger Richard Zednik was suspended for four games for
high-sticking Toronto defenseman Daniil Markov. He will not be
available for the Capitals when they play Friday against the Stars
at Reunion Arena. ... Wayne Gretzky left The Forum on a fabulous
note, helping the Rangers to a 5-1 victory against the Kings in his
final appearance at the arena in which he worked his magic for
eight seasons as a member of the Los Angeles Kings. ``I found my
myself daydreaming in between shifts, thinking of all the fun times
here and how hard everyone in the organization worked to sell
hockey here,'' Gretzky said. Among the big nights there, Gretzky's
biggest was scoring his 802nd career goal in 1994 to surpass Gordie
Howe on the NHL's all-time list. ... Lightning winger Andrei
Nazarov was suspended seven games for cross-checking Cam Russell.
It is the longest suspension given by Colin Campbell, the NHL's
newest director of discipline. ... The Flyers are shopping Chris
Gratton, Dainius Zubrus and Alexandre Daigle and are said to be
interested in the Oilers' Ryan Smyth, the Flames' Theo Fleury or
the Canucks' Pavel Bure. Gratton has the most value. He's young,
and his contract for the next four years averages $1.5 million a
season.
Western Conference NHL scoring is actually up, meaning rules
changes implemented in the summer could gradually be working. In
50-game increments, this is how scoring has gone since the start of
the season: 4.7 in games 1-50; 5.0 in games 51-100; 5.3 in games
101-150 and 5.7 in games 151-200. That's a season average of 5.2
total goals per game _ lowest since 1956. Still, expect the league
to exceed last season's 5.27 goals-per-game average. ... The Kings
are 1-9-1 over their past 11 games, but expect to soon see the
return of goalies Stephane Fiset (groin), Jamie Storr (groin),
Jozef Stumpel (ankle) and Doug Bodger (hand). ... Ducks winger
Teemu Selanne has missed five games with a thigh strain and isn't
close to returning. ... Kings winger Matt Johnson has been
suspended indefinitely, and could receive at least a week off from
the grind of the game. Johnson cross-checked the Rangers' Jeff
Beukeboom in the face last week and is awaiting a conference call
tomorrow with Colin Campbell. ... Keith Tkachuk knew what was on
the line. After all, you don't hold out on the fans, demand a big
new contract and then come in and play terrible. The Phoenix
Coyotes winger said getting off to a fast start was important not
only to the team, but to himself. ``A lot of the focus was on me
and a lot of eyes were on me. To get paid the kind of money I'm
getting paid, you've got to do well,'' Tkachuk said. So far, he has
with nine goals through 13 games and a league-best plus-15 rating.
... Canucks coach Mike Keenan had to wait through two false alarms,
but he finally recorded his 500th victory last week. In fact,
Keenan thoroughly enjoyed a 5-0 whipping of Colorado that broke a
15-game Canucks winless streak (0-12-3) against the Avalanche. ...
Keenan's 500th victory tied him with former Montreal coach Toe
Blake for fifth place in NHL history. Only Scotty Bowman (1,062
wins), Al Arbour (781), Dick Irvin (693) and Billy Reay (542) are
ahead of him.
</P>
</TEXT>
