<HEADLINE>
DEVILS TIE PANTHERS, 3-3  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils found themselves two men
short for two minutes midway through the third period, but they
escaped unscathed thanks to the heroics of Scott Stevens, Scott
Niedermayer and Ken Daneyko.
</P>
<P>
   The three defensemen were on the ice for the entire two-man
disadvantage, and along with goaltender Martin Brodeur, they
deserve a great deal of the credit for the Devils' 3-3 tie against
the Florida Panthers Saturday afternoon at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys did a heck of a job,'' Brian Rolston said of his
three teammates. ``They were really on top of their game. And Marty
made the saves when we needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   With Stevens leading the way, the three defensemen were superb
as penalty killers. The Panthers scored only once during eight
manpower advantages.
</P>
<P>
   After killing the two-man penalty situation in the third period,
with the score tied at 3-3, the three defensemen and Brodeur were
given a standing ovation by the crowd of 16,033. The Devils got
some rest during the penalty as a result of a television timeout
and a timeout called by Coach Robbie Ftorek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scotty anticipated well a couple of times and got the puck
down ice,'' Ftorek said about Stevens. ``Nieder forced a couple of
turnovers, and Dano did a good job cutting down the passing lane.
They did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Daneyko agreed with his coach's assessment of Stevens and
Niedermayer. ``The two Scotts were tremendous,'' Daneyko said.
``Both Scotts did an excellent job not getting caught out of
position. But to kill a penalty like that you have to rely on your
goalie, and Marty was there to shut them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur faced 25 shots in the game, none in overtime. His most
crucial moments came when the Devils were down two men, which
started at 8 minutes 59 seconds of the third period. Vadim
Sharifijanov and Lyle Odelein both were penalized for slashing.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur found himself on his back, on top of the puck, at one
time during the disadvantage, but he also got help from the post
once on a shot by Viktor Kozlov.
</P>
<P>
   All six goals in the game came between the fourth and the 15th
minutes of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Brylin opened the scoring for the Devils with his second
of the season, at 3:44, but the Panthers took the lead on goals by
Dave Gagner and Ray Whitney 40 seconds apart. Denis Pederson and
Petr Sykora regained the lead for the Devils at 3-2, before Rob
Niedermayer scored what turned out to be the last goal with 5:37
left in the second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
