u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARROLL-     11-21 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARROLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDITIONING ISN'T PROBLEM SAYS CARROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The hot seat wasn't sizzling much under Pete
Carroll this past week.
</P>
<P>
   The sizzle instead was over the Patriots' move to Hartford in
2001, and for that, owner Bob Kraft did his embattled coach a huge
favor by directing attention away from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, in fact, spent more time talking about a move he may
not even be part of than what the Patriots must do to change their
fortunes this season.
</P>
<P>
   He spent more time talking about the mood of a sellout crowd
Monday night at Foxboro Stadium than what the Miami Dolphins may
try to do against the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   But one issue that never seems to go away is the injury report.
And somehow Carroll takes the heat for that as well.
</P>
<P>
   He's charged with not being tough enough. Being too soft. Not
getting players back on the field. Not lighting a fire under them
to participate in the offseason conditioning program.
</P>
<P>
   Because a few regulars _ Vincent Brisby (hamstring), Willie
McGinest (groin), Zefross Moss (ankle), Todd Collins (groin), and
Mark Wheeler (knee) _ will not dress Monday night, and because
others such as Terry Glenn (hamstring), Chris Slade (ankle), Henry
Thomas (ankle), and Chad Eaton (thigh) will be playing hurt,
Carroll is still being asked why so many injuries have cropped up.
</P>
<P>
   The coach doesn't believe the difference in training and
practice styles between him and Bill Parcells is the reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the best participation in our offseason workout that we
had in the last four years,'' said Carroll. ``When a guy falls on
the back of his leg like Troy Brown did _ one of the most flexible
guys we have _ maybe his leg would have been broken if he wasn't in
such great shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the knee injury Wheeler gets is less than what it would
have been had he not been in great shape. Zefross Moss _ a guy
comes flying across the line of scrimmage and dives across his
legs. Maybe this is a case of these guys surviving these injuries,
and we have felt all along these guys would return.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn had good practice sessions Friday and Saturday and is
expected back Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Brisby, who missed a month after breaking a finger, was placed
on injured reserve with a hamstring injury suffered in the Buffalo
game last week. Anthony Ladd was activated off the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   McGinest also will sit out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie was here (for the conditioning program) the whole
time,'' said Carroll. ``There seems to be a makeup on individual
guys that we're going to try and figure out some other solutions.
When a guy gets injured by accident, there's nothing you can do.
There's no explanation for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that we reported in great shape. Our offseason program
was strong, but maybe we need to apply special help in these unique
cases. I know our trainer, Ron O'Neil, reported that we missed the
least amount of minutes to injuries last season.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll believes in the practice method adopted by the Packers,
49ers, and Broncos of working out in pads one day a week (sometimes
two) and sees very little differences from the practice work of the
previous regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it could be a factor,'' said Carroll. ``We're
not that far different. We have more repetitions and snaps during
the week than they did. We do all of the same things in the
offseason. We do all the same things with training in-season.
That's all the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just the timing, it just hit us.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is seen by some as more compassionate than Parcells, who
has a reputation of getting injured players back on the field
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about compassion,'' said Carroll. ``We've got guys
with torn tissue. We can test the muscles now and see there's
bleeding in there. We have guys with six screws in their finger
trying to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like they're trying to play with bumps and bruises.
If that was the case, we'd get them out there. But these guys are
legitimately hurt. They have medical problems that can be seen with
tests, and those are things you can't rush back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to get our guys back now. We knew we would
eventually and that we'd have a team of guys back.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has a few more hours to enjoy his time off from the hot
seat. But Monday night, before a national television audience, the
coach will be back on it.
</P>
<P>
   One closing piece of Hartford-related news: The Patriots'
season-ticket waiting list soared by more than 3,000 Saturday. The
team already had about 7,000 on the list before the announcement
that they would move in 2001. According to Patriots spokesman Don
Lowery, about 90 percent of the additions were residents of
Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 2156EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
