<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3069 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-21 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IMPRESSIVE CLIMB IN THE IVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They know down, and they now know up, and there is no question
which one they prefer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were 0-7 in the Ivies last year,'' said Yale captain
Corwynne Carruthers. ``We beat 'em. It doesn't get any sweeter.
This is a program in transition, and we're back now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were picked eighth in the Ivy League and Harvard was picked
first,'' pointed out linebacker Peter Mazza. ``For us to go from
where we were at preseason, No. 8, to do what we've done is
phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yale football is back where it belongs,'' declared Carruthers,
whose team regained the all-important bragging rights in college
football's most hallowed rivalry with a 9-7 decision over a Harvard
team that will always recall this game as the coulda/shoulda/woulda
game of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things happened out there I never thought I'd see,''
sighed Crimson coach Tim Murphy, whose team's winning streak in The
Game was snapped at three.
</P>
<P>
   He was undoubtedly thinking of his veteran quarterback electing
to pitch to a trailing tailback for what turned out to be a 1-yard
loss when he could have walked into the end zone himself.
</P>
<P>
   Or the missed 19-yard field goal attempt that soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   Or his kick returner stepping out of bounds at the Harvard
8-yard line following the Yale touchdown when it looked as if the
worst that was going to happen was a runback to the 30.
</P>
<P>
   Or his quarterback fumbling the ball to Yale at the Harvard 15,
a play that set up the game-winning 27-yard field goal by Mike
Murawczyk (imagine the Scrabble triple-word possibility here) with
3:04 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Or he might have been wondering if he has ever lost a game, at
any level, to a team that could manage only eight first downs, four
of which came on its only touchdown drive.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're Harvard, you're going to say you lost. You
certainly aren't going to give Yale the satisfaction of saying it
won.
</P>
<P>
   If you're Yale, of course, you won the most important game on
your schedule, and you did so with a display of athletic nobility
that would have thrilled old Walter Camp himself. You're not going
to bother yourself worrying about your almost nonexistent offense.
You won't talk about having to punt 11 times. You will talk about
your stout defense, and rightly so.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the greatest defensive performances I've ever
seen by any team,'' gushed second-year Yale mentor Jack Siedlecki.
``Our defense, in the second half, well, I don't know if I've ever
seen a team on the field that long make so many clutch plays. They
came through today, series after series.''
</P>
<P>
   With this victory, Yale finishes 6-4 and winds up tied with
Brown for second in the Ivies at 5-2. Last year Yale was 1-9
(beating only 1-AA Valparaiso) and had that 0-7 bagel in league
play. This represents Yale's first winning season since 1991, when
it likewise went 6-4. The Bulldogs beat Princeton, as well as
Harvard, which makes them ``Big Three'' champs. In New Haven, this
is all a very big deal.
</P>
<P>
   It is a strange team. In all six victories, Yale has allowed the
other team to score first. No one has an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we have to be behind every game,'' said
Siedlecki. ``But we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Siedlecki had a good feeling about this season since last
spring. The Yale tradition is to elect a new captain shortly after
the Harvard game. Siedlecki asked if he could deviate from
tradition and have the players elect a captain in the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we just did not have any demonstrated leadership at
that time,'' Siedlecki explained. ``I thought it would be a good
idea if we waited until spring.
</P>
<P>
   When the balloting was held, the winner was a 6-foot-2-inch,
295-pound mass of energy named Corwynne Carruthers, a middle guard
who ascended to the post with one obvious public distinction. He is
the first Canadian (Peterborough, Ontario) ever chosen as Yale
captain.
</P>
<P>
   The selection pleased the coach very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corwynne is our hardest worker,'' explained Siedlecki. ``He
bench presses 475 pounds. For them to select him told me they were
interested in being like him. That's when I started to feel good
about the team.''
</P>
<P>
   When you have already won five games when the other guy scores
first, you are unlikely to be fazed when you are losing by a measly
7-0 entering the final period. And when you manage to score _ a
9-yard pass from Joe Walland to fullback Derek Bentley _ and then
have the extra point blocked, you say to yourself, ``It's no big
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We trail in every game,'' shrugged Capt. Carruthers. ``Even
when we had the extra point blocked, we knew we had it.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Steve Petrie's high snap caused the extra point to be
blocked, leaving Yale 7-6 in arrears, Siedlecki knew he had to do
some serious coaching. ``I walked over to Steve and Mike
(Murawczyk) and I said, `It's going to come down to you two.'''
</P>
<P>
   The wait was short. For once return man Damon Jones stepped out
of bounds on his own 8, you could feel the obvious momentum shift.
On third and 5 at the Crimson 13, quarterback Rich Linden rolled
right. Cornerback Ben Blake rocked him, freeing up the ball. Jeff
Hockenbrock flopped on it at the Harvard 15.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays produced little, and so Murawczyk, a sophomore who
had already kicked a team-record 11 field goals, was brought in to
attempt the biggest kick of his life. It was a no-doubter, right
down Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Was Siedlecki nervous as the ball was being snapped?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he acknowledged. ``You run all the scenarios
through your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't mention scenarios to Murphy. This game scenarioed him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he said, ``is one of those days I wish I had gone for
my MBA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
