</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HARVARD-YALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YALE HAS LATE KICK FOR VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The history of this annual gridiron ritual between Harvard and
Yale has been laced with the unusual and populated by unlikely
heroes, and sometimes the ordinary game ends up one to savor for
the team that seemed to be on the way to defeat. Saturday's
edition, in bright sunlight and swirling winds before 27,787 at
Harvard Stadium, had its unusual moments, its hero who was given a
second chance, and a grand moment for the Elis to relish.
</P>
<P>
   After Mike Murawczyk's extra point that would have tied the game
for Yale with 5:36 left was blocked by Joe Weidle, the second
chance came when Crimson quarterback Rich Linden was hit by Ben
Blake as he tried to sweep to his right and cut up field. Linden
fumbled, Jeff Hockenbrock recovered, and on the ensuing fourth
down, Murawczyk kicked a 27-yard field goal with 3:04 remaining to
lift the Elis to a 9-7 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   This was a special moment for the seniors, who had lost three
straight years to Harvard, and it completed the transition from an
0-7 Ivy team last year to a 5-2 league record this year, good for a
share of second place with Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I had a chance,'' said Murawczyk. ``Extra points
should be automatic, but we had a high snap on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Petrie's snap indeed was a little high, and Weidle rose to
the occasion and blocked it. That prompted a conference on the
sideline among Yale coach Jack Siedlecki, Murawczyk, Petrie, and
holder Ken Marshner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Calm down _ there's nothing we can do about it,'''
said Murawczyk. ``The coach came up and said we were going to get
another chance. I was pretty much sure we would. We did it when it
counted, and that's all that mattered. It's not that I had an
option. I had to keep confident.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was the largest to see The Game in Harvard Stadium
since 1990, but there wasn't much to arouse the spectators in a
lackluster first half. The Elis didn't have a first down in the
first quarter (10 yards total offense), as a Crimson defense led by
tackle Chris Nowinski was on fire. The statistics at halftime
showed the visitors with just three first downs, 53 yards total
offense. The Crimson (4-6, 3-4) had eight first downs and 121
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Joe Walland, who had been Yale's offensive spark in
dramatic victories over Brown and Princeton, struggled in the early
going. But he produced when he had to, leading a 71-yard
fourth-quarter drive by completing 7 of 9 passes. He uncorked a
9-yard touchdown pass to a wide-open Derek Bentley, but Murawczyk's
kick was blocked.
</P>
<P>
   After the Crimson had forged a 7-0 lead on Linden's 1-yard
plunge at 9:24 of the third quarter, they were subsequently stopped
on three bids from less than 2 yards out. Mike Giampaolo's
chip-shot field goal attempt was wide left, but the lead stood into
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After Linden's pass for a first down was dropped by Josh
Wilskie, another Giampaolo attempt from 33 yards was blocked by
Yale captain Corwynne Carruthers. Giampaolo had converted 6 of 7
attempts coming into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Walland went to work on the touchdown drive that lifted the
sagging hopes of the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in pressure situations with the clock,'' said
Murawczyk. ``I knew were were going to have another chance. At
least I was hoping I would have another chance, because it wouldn't
be a way to go out.''
</P>
<P>
   Siedlecki, who replaced the legendary Carm Cozza last season,
has seen his team virtually come full circle in his second season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally beat them,'' said Carruthers. ``We got the fumble,
and we knew we'd win it. We were trying to get into a groove
passingwise, and we finally did it on that drive. We knew we had to
score, and we did. We've been down all year, trailing in every
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Elis wound up with just eight first downs and
176 yards in total offense, Walland (16 of 33 for 147 yards) and
Murawczyk came up big when it counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just weren't executing our plays,'' said Walland. ``We
tried to run, and it wasn't working. After a while, we settled down
and we had to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was tough. It was tough throwing the ball. On my
first play, on a wheel play, I threw it 5 yards out of bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Walland adjusted, the defense kept coming up strong, and
Murawczyk had his second chance, the Crimson came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to believe in yourselves,'' said Siedlecki. ``It
took a little longer. We had to get behind again. We've been behind
in every game, but we played with tremendous emotion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
