u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-WES     11-21 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-WESTVIRGINIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST VIRGINIA ROUTS BC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORGANTOWN, W.Va. _ They were forlorn figures as they sat next
to each other at the end of Boston College's bench, draped in
hooded winter coats. Lost in their own thoughts, BC senior
quarterback Scott Mutryn said he and senior running back Mike Cloud
spoke nary a word between them as they sat and helplessly watched
the final 7:41 of their careers tick away in Saturday's 35-10 loss
to West Virginia before a crowd of 40,573 at Mountaineer Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words really can't describe ... and words can't even begin to
explain the way we felt and what was going through our heads,''
said Mutryn, who presided over a team that began the season with so
much promise after a 3-0 start, but stumbled in a six-game losing
streak and wound up 4-7 for the second year in a row after
Saturday's season-ending conference loss. ``We've both gone through
different seasons, but he had an outstanding year and you can't say
enough about what he did. We're very proud to see where he came
from and what he'd done the previous four years to come out and
have a year like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud became not only BC's but the Big East's all-time rushing
leader when he ran 28 times for 179 yards (and a 21-yard touchdown
in the second quarter) that helped him surpass Troy Stradford
(3,504, 1982-86) as the school's career leader with 3,597 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud finished the season with 308 carries for 1,776 yards, both
conference records, but added another to his glittering resume when
he supplanted West Virginia's Amos Zereoue, who rushed for 143
yards on 32 carries and TDs of 47 and 30 yards, as the league's
career rushing leader _ if only for a week. Zereoue, who has 3,569
yards, has one game left Friday at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Despite cutting remarks made earlier in the week by Zereoue, who
said in so many words that Cloud did not rank as the league's best
back, Cloud took the high road when asked about his head-to-head
duel with the junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the Mike Cloud-Amos Zereoue game,'' Cloud insisted.
``It was Boston College against West Virginia and our defense did a
great job in holding him down. And like I said, it's not a one-man
game, it's a team game.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first quarter, it became abundantly clear that West
Virginia was a better team, but not one without flaws.
</P>
<P>
   The Mountaineers, who got 312 yards passing from junior
quarterback Marc Bulger, raced to a 12-0 first-quarter lead off a
pair of 83-yard drives that were capped by a 47-yard TD by Zereoue,
who had 12 carries for 100 yards in that quarter alone, and a
1-yard plunge by fullback Anthony Green. But West Virginia kicker
Jay Taylor failed to convert both PATs, leaving the door open for
the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   But BC stubbed its toes, too, when John Matich had a 25-yard
field goal blocked by Scooter Davis, a costly mistake that led to a
13-play, 83-yard drive capped by Green's TD.
</P>
<P>
   After Cloud broke the school's career rushing record with his
21-yard TD, Zereoue answered by capping a five-play, 71-yard drive
with a 30-yard run. Taylor finally found the mark on the PAT to
give West Virginia a 19-7 lead with 2:15 left before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   That's when it really got ugly.
</P>
<P>
   On BC's next possession, Perlo Bastien blocked a Jason Malecki
punt. The ball rolled towards the BC goal line with several
Mountaineers in hot pursuit, but Carlos Moore alertly kicked it
through the end zone. Moore was charged with an illegal kick
penalty, resulting in a safety that gave West Virginia a 21-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On West Virginia's next possession, Taylor was charged with the
same penalty when he dropped a punt snap and tried to kick the ball
illegally. BC took over at the West Virginia 11, but came away
empty when Matich missed a 28-yard field goal attempt to the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the times that's a function of a better football
team, with better people making plays against you,'' said BC coach
Tom O'Brien. ``That's the first time this year we've had a (field
goal) kick blocked and the end of the half was about as ugly of an
end of a half as you'd want to see. And they got us on a couple of
blitzes there ... and then we get down there on the 5 or 6-yard
line and get a late-hit penalty; just a lot of stupid things.''
</P>
<P>
   Matich finally connected on a 22-yard field goal, capping a
nine-play, 58-yard march, but Bulger, who spread the ball to seven
receivers, fired a 31-yard TD pass to Antonio Brown just before he
was blasted by the blitzing Pedro Cirino. Bulger then put the game
out of reach, 35-10, in the fourth when he lofted a 10-yard pass in
the corner of the end zone to Shawn Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   After turning it over on their next series, Mutryn and Cloud
were relegated to the sideline, where they sat and watched in
silence as their careers came to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a moment that we both wanted to ourselves and
there was no way to describe how we were feeling,'' Cloud said.
``It was just mixed emotions. I think it was just a moment where we
sat and reflected on things.''
</P>
<P>
   But both seemed to share the same fervent wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish,'' Cloud said, ``I had at least one more year
left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
