<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-CAMNEELY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NEELY, NO COMEBACK, NO REGRETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The official end to the Cam Neely comeback came a little less
than a week ago when Neely announced that the pain in his hip
wouldn't allow him to continue to progress toward a return in the
National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   For that week, though, it allowed everyone a chance to fantasize
that the former 50-goal scorer might suit up in his familiar No. 8
again and fire blistering slap shots off the right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Tallas had known Neely only peripherally; the goalie played
one game for Boston in Neely's final season, a couple of weeks
after Neely had played in his last game in Anaheim. In the last
week, Tallas learned what every goalie in the NHL had learned
throughout Neely's 13-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me those shots hurt,'' said Tallas's agent, Jay Fee,
who also represents Neely. ``He said he still had an awful lot on
his shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes forward Gary Roberts could sympathize with Neely. It
appeared his career was over when he suffered a severe neck injury
that forced him to sit out the 1995-96 season. But Roberts returned
last year to score 20 goals and 49 points in 61 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping he would make it because I went through the same
thing,'' said Roberts, who scored a career-high 53 goals with
Calgary in 1991-92, the same year Neely was limited to just nine
games after colliding with Ulf Samuelsson in the 1991 playoffs.
``He's still a young guy and I'm sure that he thought that if he
didn't give it a shot, he might regret it down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Neely said he has no regrets. He played 13 seasons, which is
longer than many play. His commitment and work ethic should serve
as an inspiration to the young players in the league now.
</P>
<P>
   What his future holds is anyone's guess. However, one of his
most enduring qualities has been his willingness to say what he
thinks, and you could do far worse than hiring Neely as a broadcast
analyst. During a cameo stint on Channel 38 a couple of seasons
ago, Neely didn't mince words when talking about the game he was
watching.
</P>
<P>
   What was most sad about Neely's original retirement was the
regret he carried to the lecturn in the Legends restaurant at the
FleetCenter. That has certainly changed. The other day, Neely
talked like a man with more in his life than hockey. He has a
terrific wife and a new baby boy. And he has something he really
needed: closure.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Good guy  &UR; Colin Campbell &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is now wearing the black hat as
the league's chief disciplinarian, said he doesn't mind anyone
questioning his decision-making. What drives him nuts is people
complimenting him at the expense of his predecessor,  &UR; Brian
Burke &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now in the GM seat in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing worse for a coach than to have a new coach
come in and criticize what the other coach did, saying, `I'm going
to do it differently,''' said Campbell, drawing an analogy to his
former line of work. ``It's not that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell thinks Burke did a terrific job in his five years
running the league's supplementary discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (commissioner  &UR; Gary Bettman &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; came in and changed the
whole system around, Brian was the hockey man,'' said Campbell.
``He had a different way and different background than I did and he
did a great job. I had the opportunity to see him work first-hand
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comparisons are certainly unfair. The pressure lasts 12 months
a year, 24 hours a day, it's a constant. For five years, Brian did
an excellent job. Some people would say he didn't play the game at
the NHL level, but he had a feel for every aspect. He played
college, he played in the AHL, he was an agent, an assistant GM,
and a GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot from Brian and he helped me more than anyone
in the transition.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as Campbell is enjoying his new role, he said it's
impossible to win. In his opinion, most of the criticism of Burke
comes from people with an ax to grind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years in that job, you're not going to make a lot of
friends, you're going to make a lot more enemies,'' he said. ``It's
like being a traffic cop. It's either no ticket or write a ticket,
they're not going to say thanks for no ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``When discussing a suspension with Mr. Bettman, he said, `No
one is going to be happy about a suspension, no one is going to
thank you.' He's right.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Hard to figure the decision-making in Tampa. Belmont native
 &UR; Paul Mara &LR; , &UR;  &LR; taken with the No. 7 overall pick in 1997, was the
last defenseman cut from the club, and he's back with his junior
team in Plymouth of the Ontario League (5 goals and 11 assists in
13 games). He had an impressive training camp and ran the
Lightning's power play during the exhibition season but wasn't good
enough to stay? Hmmmm. Consider that blue liners  &UR; David Wilkie  &LR; and
 &UR; Michal Sykora  &LR; were sent down to Cleveland. Wilkie cleared waivers
and reported. Sykora has balked, saying he might go home to the
Czech Republic. Meanwhile, the Lightning gave up an Eastern
Conference-worst 66 goals in 18 games, an average of 3.66 ...
Another local product, former Boston University standout  &UR; Jeff
Kealty &LR; , &UR;  &LR; has found a home in Milwaukee. He was released from
Colorado's camp, hooked on with Nashville as a tryout, then did
well enough to be assigned to Milwaukee's IHL club. In 13 games, he
has 2 goals and 8 points and is among the top four in ice time ...
Vancouver coach  &UR; Mike Keenan  &LR; earned the 500th win of his career in
Thursday's 5-0 victory over the Avalanche. It was the first time in
16 tries that the Canucks had beaten Colorado ... Don't blame
 &UR; Roman Vopat  &LR; if he's afraid to put away his suitcase. The center
has already been traded three times this season, and it's only
November. He began with Los Angeles, was dealt to the Avalanche
Oct. 29, then shipped to Chicago Nov. 10. Last Tuesday, he was
moved to Philadelphia for  &UR; Mike Maneluk  &LR; ... Nice to see  &UR; Milos
Holan  &LR; back playing hockey. The former Flyers and Mighty Ducks
defenseman is skating for HC Vitkovice of the Czech Republic. Just
over a week ago, he played his first game since 1996. Holan has
been battling leukemia for two years, undergoing chemotherapy and a
bone marrow transplant. He was cut by the Ducks after preseason
camp. ``I'm the happiest man on earth now,'' said Holan, 27. ``I
have the same feelings as when I first played in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   You think things are bad here? Go to Montreal and see how last
week's blockbuster trade is being viewed north of the border. In a
word, the feedback has been brutal. According to a TV poll, 90
percent of viewers opposed the deal that brought goalie  &UR; Jeff
Hackett &LR;  and defensemen  &UR; Eric Weinrich  &LR; and  &UR; Alain Nasreddine  &LR; from
Chicago for goalie  &UR; Jocelyn Thibault  &LR; and defensemen  &UR; Dave Manson
 &LR; and  &UR; Brad Brown &LR; . One Montreal columnist referred to Hackett as
``sieve of the month.'' ...  &UR; Phil Esposito &LR; , &UR;  &LR; former Lightning
general manager, is working as a studio analyst for Fox Sports
News. Esposito, who was fired by new ownership two games into the
season, will commute from Tampa to Los Angeles. ``I like the Tampa
area too much to leave it, at this time anyway, I love it,''
Esposito said. ``It will be tough on my family but it's something I
want to give a shot.'' Esposito worked in TV as a color analyst for
the Rangers before becoming that club's GM in 1986 ... It's never,
ever boring in Montreal, at least when it comes to hockey. There
was a report out of that city that coach  &UR; Alain Vigneault  &LR; and
forward  &UR; Mark Recchi  &LR; were jawing at each other during Tuesday's
5-4 loss to Carolina. Recchi wasn't out for the power play, which
was thought to be the reason for the exchange. However, Recchi said
it was a misunderstanding. ``If you really want to know why I was
in an ugly mood,'' said Recchi, ``it's because with this (flu)
thing, I'm not helping the team. Not one bit. Another reason was
that I had just been hit from behind pretty hard _ a pretty cheap
hit. But believe me, I didn't have a conversation with Vigneault.
No way.'' Recchi actually has pneumonia ... Oft-injured Ottawa star
 &UR; Daniel Alfredsson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been out of the lineup more than a
week because of an eye injury suffered against Edmonton, is back
riding the bike and hopes to be in the lineup Monday night against
the Canucks. Alfredsson was bored out of his mind waiting for his
injury to heal. Some days, he said, he was sleeping for as many as
15 hours a day. ``I've never slept that long in my life,'' he said.
``It's no fun sitting around. I didn't feel like a hockey player. I
haven't even been able to work out. I've just been watching TV and
sleeping.'' ... This afternoon, the Bruins' alumni team will face
the Canton Youth Hockey Coaches at the Metropolis Rink in Canton
(Route 138 South off Route 128) at 4 p.m., with proceeds going to
the Canton High School girls' ice hockey program.
</P>
</TEXT>
