<HEADER>
A3081 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATRIOTM     11-21 2536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATRIOTMOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BUSINESS, THERE IS PROFIT AND LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; What Thomas Finneran and many in the Commonwealth learned last
week is that a businessman is a businessman, even if he sometimes
sounds like a televangelist when talking about the city where he
grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Kraft is a guy who once (a week) said he grows misty-eyed at
the thought of his beloved Boston Braves leaving him behind for
Milwaukee in 1953. Judging by what he did last week, he's gotten
over it.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is a Boston guy, but he's not a goofy guy. He's a Boston
guy, but not a blind guy. He's a Boston guy, but not an idiot. And
so, faced with the choice of raising $200 million of his own
capital to build a stadium in Foxborough that would not have been
what he wanted, or being handed $350 million in Connecticut to have
the state build one to his specifications, he took the money and
ran. If he could get some of his highest-priced players to do as
well, they wouldn't be 5-5 at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   This does not qualify as shocking. It is what good businessmen
do, and Kraft is nothing if not a good businessman, as he has
proven both before he bought the Patriots in 1994 and since. It is
not about emotions and never was, despite all the talk about misty
eyes and departed franchises and ``public trusts'' since the day he
``saved the team'' for his ``hometown.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, if this is the end, Kraft saved the team but not for
his hometown, unless there's going to be a change in his biography
along with the change in stadium address.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Billy Sullivan went broke ``saving the team'' for
his hometown. He didn't sell when it would have been wise to sell,
and he didn't move when it would have been wise to move it, and he
ended up in Foxborough only because he'd been thrown out of every
stadium in Boston. Billy Sullivan saved the team. Bob Kraft moved
it to Hartford, and Hartford isn't Hingham.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's decision was a good business move for the Kraft
family, one Bob had been counseled to make by his family and his
financial advisers while he continued to search for a way to keep
the team in Massachusetts. It made sense both for the future
viability of the Patriots in a sport in which owners are hell-bent
on wasting their money every offseason, and because the
Commonwealth of Finneran clearly was not going to fork over the
kind of infrastructure assistance Kraft needed to build a
state-of-the-art stadium that would be easy to get into and out of
for his high-end customers.
</P>
<P>
   So Kraft ended up with a $550 million windfall on the deal (the
$200 million he doesn't have to raise, plus the $350 million
stadium he's getting) for driving down the Mass Pike and I-84 a
couple of hours. That's on top of the sudden jump in the value of
his franchise for making that kind of move.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is said to have overpaid when he laid out $178 million for
the Patriots, $25 million for the stadium, and picked up enough
past debt to put his cost at $206 million. While he may well have
overpaid at the time, he now holds a franchise that will be worth
something in the same $500 million range as the new Cleveland
franchise once Kraft gets settled into his risk-free stadium in
Connecticut. Add to that the constant revenue stream from TV and
the bonanza expansion-franchise fees he's getting from Cleveland
and whoever wins the Los Angeles-Houston sweepstakes (bet on LA, by
the way), and Kraft has done the kind of deal that makes him what
he is today: a rich guy with a football team that should be called
the Hartford Actuarial Tables, not the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many in the sports business, when Kraft pulled the gun
out of his pocket, it was not to lay it on the table for effect. It
was to fire it, which he did when he signed the agreement with the
state of Connecticut that will lead the Patriots to Hartford in
2001 if the Nutmeg State can raise the cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   Before it's over, it is a move that will mean bad karma for
Kraft. In Hinduism, karma is the total effect of one's actions
during the successive phases of one's life that determines one's
destiny. Looked at that way, Kraft has gone from the kid crying
over the loss of the Braves from his hometown to the man who leaves
kids crying for the loss of the Patriots from their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody will have to pay for that one day, because they always
do. Not financially, for sure, because Kraft is covered on that,
but the fact is he was always covered on that. He was always going
to be a rich guy with rich kids in a big house regardless of
whether the Patriots played in Foxborough or not. Now he's a richer
guy with richer kids in a bigger house in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   But Kraft didn't look that happy when the deal was being signed,
and maybe that's because he's more his father's son than he is like
the people who advised him to move. Maybe he understands what this
will really mean for him ... that one day an older Bob Kraft will
be walking up State Street or down Federal Street, his shoulders
hunched to the wind, and he'll pass a couple of young guys on the
rise in rep ties and well-pressed suits who will mumble, ``That's
the guy who moved the Patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   That's his legacy now.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   After a dismal 1-3 start, the Oilers made a subtle offensive
change that coach  &UR; Jeff Fisher  &LR; contends has been an integral part
of a resurgence that has them at 6-4. Tennessee has won five of its
last six and achieved one of Fisher's principal preseason goals. He
wanted desperately to improve on last year's 2-6 division rec-ord.
His team is 5-1 in the AFC Central, and a big reason for the
turnaround was a decision to go almost exclusively to a one-back,
two-tight-end set six weeks ago. ``After three or four weeks, we
moved to more of a one-back set with two tight ends and detached
one of the tight ends to utilize more movement,'' Fisher said.
``That has helped us recognize things up front. It's also helped us
to a certain extent to stay out of those eight-man-front defenses
at times. We're a zone-oriented offense run scheme. When you're
utilizing a zone scheme, you've got to be able to spread people out
to allow your back to cut back. By opening up the formation a
little bit with our tight ends, that's helped us the last six
weeks.'' ... Kraft's decision to push the commissioner's office to
``investigate'' tampering charges against  &UR; Bill Parcells  &LR; for his
phone call to  &UR; Drew Bledsoe  &LR; is another example of pettiness and
cloudy thinking. Kraft really couldn't care less about the Bledsoe
call, but he believes Parcells has tried to tamper with several of
his soon-to-become free agents through subtle conversations, and he
hopes this will be a warning to the Jets. But all he really
accomplished was to make Parcells seem even bigger in the Patriots'
locker room, a place in which his image has already swollen to
unmanageable proportions. It is time to let sleeping dogs lie. It
is time even to let a wide-awake dog lie. The success of the
Patriots is no longer determined by Parcells, but the team's
obsession with him may contribute to its failures if it continues
... Baltimore's  &UR; Ray Lewis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who led the NFL in tackles last
season with 210, became the highest-paid linebacker in football
Thursday at the age of 23. With another year to go on his present
contract but the right to terminate the deal he signed in 1996
because he reached various incentives, Lewis agreed to a four-year,
$26 million extension that includes a $7 million signing bonus.
That pushes him past  &UR; Junior Seau &LR; , &UR; Levon Kirkland &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Ted
Johnson &LR; . Here is what the Patriots are getting from Johnson for $5
million a year and what Lewis has done for the Ravens. After 38
games, Lewis is averaging 11.3 tackles a game. Johnson, in 42 games
(he came into the NFL a year before Lewis), is averaging 8.6 a
game. A year ago, Johnson was credited with 127 tackles to Lewis's
league-leading 210.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is nothing if not sales-oriented. The Oilers will still
have a derrick on their helmets Sunday, but by mid-December the
league will have its new ``Titans'' logo on merchandise, in time
for the holidays. The game may not be as good as it was 20 years
ago, but the T-shirt sales are higher ... Foxborough resident  &UR; Joe
Tolland  &LR; continued his statistical breakdown of the Patriots'
drives and found some surprising good news when he analyzed the
team's opening drives of the second half. On those 10 series, the
Patriots have produced 30 points (to zero in the first half), with
16 first downs, going three-and-out only four times. Meanwhile,
they have held opponents to zero points, with 12 first downs, and
forced them to go three-and-out four times in early second-half
efforts. Not surprisingly, Bledsoe's performance reflects the
disparity. On the game-opening drives, he is 9 for 26 passing; on
the second-half opening drives, he is 23 for 38. This led Tolland
to come up with perhaps the best idea of the season: ``They should
scrap the idea of scripting the opening plays of the game and meet
20 minutes prior to the game in the locker room and develop the
first series in the same way it's done at halftime,'' he joked ...
It may be difficult for the Patriots to anticipate what the
Dolphins' pass defense will have in mind Monday night. In the first
two games of the season, a fourth of Miami's 12 sacks came from
defensive backs and linebackers, but the Dolphins have produced
only 16 sacks over the next eight games, with only three coming
from their secondary or linebacking corps. Although that indicates
the Dolphins' blitzing has slowed some, it does not mean they
aren't putting heat on the quarterback. Opponents have completed
only 51.3 percent of their throws against the swift-moving defense
_ Bledsoe went a miserable 13 of 33 in Miami's victory last month _
and the Dolphins have held opposing quarterbacks to a rating of
59.1, one of the lowest in the NFL. Only two Miami opponents have
converted more than 40 percent of their chances on third down; the
Patriots were at 27 percent in the first meeting, well below their
already dismal 39.2 conversion rate ... Miami's offense has not
been anywhere near as productive as it was when  &UR; Dan Ma &LR; - &UR; rino  &LR; was
still alive, but coordinator  &UR; Kippy Brown  &LR; has the Dolphins doing
fewer things with less mistakes, and it has led to a 7-3 record. If
it works again Monday night, the Patriots will be virtually out of
the playoff picture with more than a month to go and the Dolphins
will have a stranglehold on the division. Brown uses only 35-40
plays a game. Under previous coordinator  &UR; Gary Stevens &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the
Dolphins sometimes would come into games with more than 100 plays
on their list, which was an impossible undertaking if execution is
your aim.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Denver's  &UR; Terrell Davis  &LR; is having what could be the greatest
season ever by a running back. He has 1,330 yards and 17
touchdowns, which is on pace to break both  &UR; Eric Dickerson's
 &LR; record of 2,105 yards and  &UR; Emmitt Smith's  &LR; record of 25 touchdowns
... Raiders coach  &UR; Jon Gruden  &LR; continued to work rookie cornerback
 &UR; Charles Woodson  &LR; as a wide receiver during practice and is
threatening to use him there to add punch to the passing game.
Gruden mentioned the idea a week ago before the Seattle game but
did not act on it. Woodson, the former Heisman Trophy winner,
caught 11 passes at Michigan last season and averaged 21 yards a
catch. The Raiders have only nine touchdown passes this season, in
part because of the injury to quarterback  &UR; Jeff George  &LR; ... One
reason for the Raiders' remarkable turnaround from last year's 4-12
debacle is that they are now on the right side of thin margins of
victory. Oakland is 5-1 this year in games decided by 3 points or
fewer. The previous two seasons, with  &UR; Joe Bugel  &LR; as head coach,
they went 1-9 in such games ... Word among college scouts is that
the Dolphins have spent an inordinate amount of time looking at
Central Florida quarterback  &UR; Dante Culpepper &LR; . With Marino 37 and
the Dolphin offense limping along, Culpepper could make for an
interesting shift, because he is considered a giant-sized Houdini.
He is bigger than  &UR; Steve McNair  &LR; and some say more elusive, which
is saying something since McNair ran 71 yards for a touchdown last
Sunday after avoiding a blitz. At 6 feet 4 inches, 240 pounds, and
with a strong arm and fast feet, Culpepper may be gone by the time
Miami drafts ...  &UR; Steve Lofton  &LR; may not have been good enough to
find work as a cornerback in New England, but he's starting Sunday
for the Panthers in place of injured  &UR; Doug Evans &LR; . This season has
been a nightmare for Evans, who just came back from one injury only
to separate his right shoulder and be lost for a month. After
signing a five-year, $22.5 million free agent contract in the
offseason with a $7.5 million signing bonus, Evans has been like
the rest of the Panthers: a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dana Stubblefield &LR; , &UR; Dan Wilkinson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Sean Gilbert  &LR; have
been cited as the biggest failures of last season's free agent
class, but what of the 49ers' signings of defensive end  &UR; Gabe
Wilkins  &LR; and cornerback  &UR; Antonio Langham &LR; ? Neither starts any
longer, despite Wilkins's five-year, $20 million contract and
Langham's $16.9 million deal. On a team whose defense has slipped
from first a year ago to 17th, those signings have been killers.
San Francisco has fallen behind by at least 16 points in each of
the past three games and four times in the past five weeks. The
49ers went 2-2 in those games, coming back to beat Indianapolis and
Carolina but losing to Green Bay and Atlanta ... Not every free
agent is a bust. When the Oilers made  &UR; Craig Hentrich  &LR; the first
million-dollar punter, some thought they were crazy, but Hentrich
leads the NFL with a 47.5-yard gross and 40-yard net and has also
made a significant difference on kickoffs. A year ago, Tennessee
had only four touchbacks. This season, Hentrich has launched 21
touchbacks on 46 kickoffs ... No wonder Lions coach  &UR; Bobby Ross
 &LR; lost his mind recently. His team is 2-7, losing the games nearly
everyone in the NFL wins.  &UR; Barry Sanders  &LR; has rushed for more than
100 yards six times this season. The Lions have lost four of those
games. The other 29 NFL teams win 81 percent of the time when a
running back rushes for 100 yards ... It may be too late to salvage
the Buccaneers' season, but defensive lineman  &UR; Warren Sapp
 &LR; admitted he's been part of the problem after coach  &UR; Tony Dungy
 &LR; showed Sapp film of him running down several quarterbacks from
behind last season, when he weighed 276 pounds. Sapp says he
started the year at 315 pounds after a bit too much celebrating of
his six-year, $36 million contract. He's now down to 295 and
playing better ...  &UR; Rod Woodson  &LR; seems to have found new life in
Baltimore after appearing to be finished last season in San
Francisco. Woodson has adjusted his stance at the line of
scrimmage, now facing receivers head-on instead of playing with his
body turned, as the 49ers favored. He has five interceptions, which
ties him for second in the NFL. More significant, a year ago he had
a dozen interference calls. This year he has none.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
