<HEADLINE>
MISSED MOMENTS MAKING ME A BASKET CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA lockout is lurching toward December. Washington Wizards
owner Abe Pollin says the lords of the game are ready to ``gut the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Celtics were into their schedule, they'd be playing host
to the Vancouver Grizzlies tonight, probably carrying a 4-5 record
into the game.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I miss the NBA. I miss the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   I miss ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Wondering what outfit Pervis Ellison will be wearing when he
sits at the end of the bench in street clothes. Not since bowser
Alaa Abdelnaby stole Celtic money have we had such sartorial
splendor from the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Rick Pitino lying and laughing ... laughing and lying.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Jersey Red telling us about his latest phone call from Mo
Vaughn (it's sort of like Tim Johnson talking about napalm in the
morning back in 'Nam).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The dulcet tones of Pufessor Cedric (``that's Doctor Ebonics,
to you, sir'') Maxwell describing yet another Celtic loss on the
radio. (Stop right there, you outraged Cam-bridge-/Brookline/Newton
letter writers. It was our own Howard Manly who dubbed Max
``Pufessor Ebonics'' on these pages last year.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Thanksdad Gaston standing in his high-priced loge seat and
yelling at the officials.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Red Auerbach sitting next to Thanksdad and pretending to
listen to the owner's opinions about basketball.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Leo Papile doing the Steven Seagal thing and telling us the
stories behind the stories of NBA players he has coached.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The Ripoff Brothers parking lot, and the $20 I get to put on
my expense account.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Tommy Heinsohn's tender take on the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Antoine Walker's shot selection, his no-look defense, and his
Chris Canty celebration dances while the opposition fast-breaks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Tommy Nunez and Hue Hollins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Freddie ``Tag'' Tenaglia performing the anthem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The nitwits of the Parquet Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Nitwit fans mugging for the Jumbotron scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The insufferable Alan Dershowitz trying to look important.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Commissioner Bob Ryan, at courtside, insisting that none of
 &UR; today &LR; 's immature players could ever top the selfishness of Elvin
Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Larry Bird coming to town with the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Danny Ainge coming to town with the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Dave Cowens coming to town with the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Kevin McHale coming to town with the Timberwolves. Think of
what McHale would tell us about his new governor, Jesse ``The
Body'' Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The brilliance and candor of Bob Cousy's TV analysis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Greg Minor's vigorous defense against his deadbeat dad rap.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Hideous halftime promotions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The parquet floor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Pitino taking over the upstairs at Fours after a big win.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The Crunch 'N' Munch Man.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Kenny Anderson icing his knees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The empty seats in the opening minutes, and the closing
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Bob Lobel doing the Mike Wallace thing on ``The Rick Pitino
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Globe game stories by Michael Holley and Peter May.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Ticket scalpers on Causeway Street when the Bulls, Lakers,
and Pacers come to town.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Eddie Lacerte and Arnie Scheller healing the wounded.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The ushers and security folk who've been working Celtic games
for a million years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Red getting extra satisfaction whenever the Celtics beat the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Ron Mercer playing like a 10-year veteran _ not bad for a
young man who looks like he could be older than Bobby Murcer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; M.L. Carr walking around, smiling, high-fiving everybody, and
promoting his latest book project.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Francis O'Bryant attending to details in both locker &UR;  &LR; rooms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; Red's cigar, in the locker room, after the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
