A3083 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     11-21 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT HITS LOTTERY IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About a dozen years ago, when late Patriots owner Billy Sullivan
was conducting one of his many fire sales, I asked one of the
rejected suitors, ``What happened? You told me the deal was done.''
</P>
<P>
   His response: ``We thought Sullivan wanted a deal. Then we
learned what he wanted was a Pig Package.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A `Pig Package'? What's that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our group gave it that name when he became so greedy that we
just had to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, I received a call from that same suitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just read your story this morning about the Kraft deal in
Hartford,'' he said. ``If that goes down, that will be the all-time
Pig Package.''
</P>
<P>
   A story in Saturday's Globe detailed the financial breakdown of
the memorandum of understanding between Patriots owner Bob Kraft
and the state of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The details were read to three NFL owners, who requested
anonymity. All agreed that it is the greatest financial deal any
National Football League owner has ever received.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this thing goes through,'' said one owner, ``he will make
more money than any other team in the league. This is a lot like
the Cleveland deal and the Baltimore deal. But this is better. He
will net about $50 million a year out of this thing. Good luck to
him. It will help the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, in his own stadium in Foxborough, took in roughly $40
million-45 million a year. This is money generated through tickets,
concessions, parking, signage, novelties, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers in the Connecticut arrangement indicate that Kraft's
intake will double, to $90 million-$100 million per year. Ten
percent will go to the state of Connecticut. The rest is his.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, there are some generous perks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The state will give Kraft $15 million to build a training
facility in the area.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The state will give Kraft the land to build an NFL Pavilion,
i.e. theme park.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ &LR; The state will give Kraft the rights to the primary hotel
that will be attached to the new convention center, which will be
built as part of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft can sell these rights to a major hotel chain, such as
Hyatt or Hilton, and make millions more without spending a cent.
</P>
<P>
   The state will also put aside a total of $190 million over the
next 30 years for so-called capital improvements to the new
stadium. But as one NFL owner suggested Saturday, ``That's money in
theory that is being set aside for another new stadium in 30
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft paid $160 million in January 1994 to purchase the
Patriots. He purchased Foxboro Stadium out of a bankruptcy court
for roughly $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   In pro football, under the current collective bargaining
agreement, 64 percent of revenues go to the players in salary.
However, that does not include luxury box revenue ($12.5 million a
year in Hartford) and, according to one owner, stadium signage,
which in Hartford he estimated would yield $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kraft can put that money, about $20 million a year, in his
pocket and not share it with anyone (except the state of
Connecticut),'' the owner said.
</P>
<P>
   That number does not include parking revenue because the
memorandum did not delineate how much money will be generated from
that. But Kraft will receive 90 percent of that, whatever it is.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has said he has to move out of Foxborough because he is
not making money, and his family would have to sell the team ``out
of the region.'' So, by moving it to Connecticut, he is saving it
for New England.
</P>
<P>
   He said the other day that he has the lowest revenues in the
league. This brought a chuckle from a couple of his peers. One said
Kraft's revenue ranked ninth or 10th (out of 30 teams). Another
said it was 12th. A third said, ``They used to be somewhere between
five and 10, but they dropped back with the new stadiums in Tampa,
Cleveland, and Baltimore.''
</P>
<P>
   The most outstanding part of Kraft's incredible Connecticut deal
is the state guaranteeing money toward the sale of luxury boxes and
preferred seats.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore, St. Louis, and Washington, three new stadiums,
there are no government guarantees on the sale of these boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut will spend up to $10 million per year to cover club
seats not sold over 4,000. In other words, if Kraft can't sell
2,000 of the 6,000 club seats, the state will pay him for the empty
seats.
</P>
<P>
   The state will have $7.5 million a year to give Kraft for empty
luxury boxes, after the first 50 are sold. If Kraft sells 50, and
the rest do not sell, the state has to pay him $7.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Connecticut has yet to approve the package, but it
is supposed to be a slam dunk. The governor has lined up some
legislative heavy hitters to push for passage.
</P>
<P>
   A few years back, I remember talking to John Shaw, the president
of the Los Angeles Rams (soon to be the St. Louis Rams). We talked
about his negotiations with the politicians on a lease in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gotten more,'' he said, ``but I didn't push for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked him why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if the deal is that good, if they give you everything
you want, then the politicians will probably vote it down,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 2207EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981121.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3280 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FENG-SHUI-OFFICES-NYT     11-21 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENG-SHUI-OFFICES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET ORIENTED: THE ART OF ZEN IN THE WORKPLACE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN:Business, Lifestyle Editors)   (This quirky 525-word ``separate buy'' story is from the November
issue of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been into the ``a'' domestic/general
news, ``f'' financial news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
  
 By RESHMA MEMON YAQUB  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever walked into a room that just felt really good? You couldn't
explain why, but everything felt right. The energy just worked.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are _ even if the person who arranged the room didn't do
it on purpose _ the place had good feng shui.
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui is the ancient Chinese art of arranging a balanced
environment to create a positive flow of energy. Popular for years
among decorators, it's now moving into the office, according to a
new book, ``Feng Shui at Work,'' by Kirsten Lagatree, who says it
can have dramatic results in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Put your furniture in the proper place, hang the right things in
the right places on your walls, and seat your employees
strategically _ then watch as the office becomes a more comfortable
place to work, relationships among co-workers improve, and your
business grows.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with your desk. It must face the door. Like much
with feng shui, this is rooted in common sense. If your back is to
the door, you'll be caught off guard when people walk in, says
Lagatree, and you won't be able to keep an eye on things. Sit
catercorner from the door with two walls intersecting behind your
desk to stay in visual and physical command of the space.
</P>
<P>
   Having either side of your desk up against a wall blocks energy,
says Steven Post, CEO of the San Francisco-based Geomancy/Feng Shui
Education Organization. The path of movement around your entire
office should be smooth and unencumbered, says Post. Doors should
almost never be blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Clutter stops the flow of energy. ``Clutter is a series of
postponed decisions,'' says Lagatree. ``You are surrounded by
things that are calling for your attention, so you're never really
concentrating on the thing in front of you at that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Strive for Zen surfaces in your office, says Hope Karan Gerecht,
a feng shui consultant in Baltimore. That means at least half the
vertical and horizontal surfaces should be clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mind needs a place to rest and relax as it is
problem-solving and creating,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Think carefully about the objects you surround yourself with,
says Gerecht: ``Everything around us is creating our lives on a
daily basis.'' Is an item something that pleases you? Or something
you're using because you have it?
</P>
<P>
   Also, don't keep anything broken in your office; it saps energy.
The office should have a feeling of life energy, whether you create
it with plants, fish, or color.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a desk your own size. A big desk may look impressive, but
if it dwarfs you, you'll feel lost, and you may have trouble
expanding your business.
</P>
<P>
   Mirrors are the aspirin of feng shui. Hang mirrors to reflect
anything you want doubled, like a view of water. Don't, however,
let them reflect the top of your desk, unless what you're looking
for is a doubling of your workload.
</P>
<P>
   And never situate an employee beneath or directly facing an exit
sign. ``It gives the subconscious command for them to exit,''
explains Gerecht. ``Even if they stay, a part of their psyche may
feel uncommitted.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Reshma Memon Yaqub is a staff writer at
``WORTH.'') &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 525-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267
or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
