<DOCNO> NYT19981121.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3297 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVOLUTION-WALL-STREE     11-21 1673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVOLUTION-WALL-STREET-400&AMP;add-NYTSF-WORTH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY WALL STREET IS ABOUT TO CHANGE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Editors)   (This ``separate buy'' financial story is from the November issue
of ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be
purchased from New York Times sales representative NIRDI RELIS in
New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at
212-499-3382.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS TWO HELPFUL OPTIONAL TRIMS, AT 400 (225 WORDS) AND AT 725
(200 WORDS). TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 1,400 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``f''
financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By MICHAEL PELTZ  
 c.1998 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As New York City's largest used-book seller, Strand, at the
corner of 12th Street and Broadway, is a place where Manhattanites
go to browse through treasures of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few flights up in the same building, however, the
employees of Wit Capital have their attention fixed almost entirely
on the future.
</P>
<P>
   Wit, a registered broker-dealer, is a pioneer in the use of the
Internet to trade stock.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike online brokerages, which communicate with customers via
the Net but execute trades on the traditional exchanges, Wit is
attempting to create a whole new way for companies to sell stock to
investors and for investors to buy and sell directly with one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by 37-year-old Andrew Klein, Wit was little known on
Wall Street when it opened for business in September 1997. That
changed abruptly last spring, when Robert Lessin, one of Wall
Street's best-connected mergers-and-acquisitions bankers, left his
position as vice-chairman of Salomon Smith Barney to become Wit's
chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, other topflight investment-banking pros, including
Matthew Carbone from Salomon and William Tkacs from Cowen &AMP; Co.,
joined the 43-year-old Lessin.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ronald Readmond, formerly vice-chairman of Charles Schwab &AMP;
Co., announced that he was signing on as Wit's president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   What drew the likes of Lessin and Readmond to Wit was nothing
less than an opportunity to revolutionize the process of capital
formation _ or, as Lessin puts it, to ``democratize'' Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to the extent that Wit or some other organization like
it one day succeeds, Wall Street's role as a middleman between the
owners and users of capital could be profoundly altered _ and
perhaps sharply diminished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within ten years I think we'll see the death of the floor on
the New York Stock Exchange and possibly the end of open-outcry
trading,'' says Bill Burnham, the senior analyst of electronic
commerce at Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be fewer exchanges globally, and individual retail
investors will have access to 24-hour trading worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street isn't exactly quaking in its boots just yet, and
Wit, for its part, has a long row to hoe just to survive as a
business, let alone threaten the established positions of the major
Wall Street firms.
</P>
<P>
   Its true significance at the moment is as a harbinger of the
upheaval that lies ahead for the Street. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Internet will make such dramatic change possible (and
inevitable) because it is the first medium capable of creating a
public market _ an electronic version of a trading pit or stock
exchange, where multiple participants can get together to trade.
</P>
<P>
   Wit founder Klein was among the first to recognize this. As a
young securities lawyer for Cravath, Swaine and Moore in New York
in the late 1980s, he was exposed to the huge fees that Wall Street
firms command _ particularly the sums spent as companies attempted
to raise capital through initial public offerings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Klein resigned his lucrative job at Cravath to start a
microbrewery. Two years later, he took Spring Street Brewing public
in the first Internet-based IPO, raising $1.6 million for Spring
Street _ without any help from investment bankers _ from 3,500
individual investors. Many were fans of Wit beer, a spicy, cloudy
concoction akin to Belgian wheat beer.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1996, Klein launched the first Web-based trading
mechanism that enabled investors to buy and sell Spring Street
shares. A month later, he formed Wit Capital, borrowing the name _
and distinctive red exclamation-mark logo _ from the beer.
</P>
<P>
   His goal for Wit: ``To include individual investors in the
capital-raising process and create a better way for people to buy
and sell stocks,'' he says. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though little more than a year old, Wit has already participated
in more than 30 IPOs of common stock. It also recently won its
first assignment as an ``e-manager'' _ a term Klein coined to
describe Wit's role as the co-manager charged with distributing an
allotment of IPO stock through the electronic-brokerage community. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Initial public offerings have long been a source of frustration
to individual investors because Wall Street firms have
traditionally used their clout to reward only their favored
customers with allocations of new shares.
</P>
<P>
   Lessin notes, for example, that this was a common practice at
his former firm, Salomon Smith Barney, which reserved only a tiny
percentage of shares for the firm's retail customers _ even though
a retail broker at Solomon might have as much as $60 million under
management.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, when Wit co-manages an initial public offering, it
offers shares on a first-come, first-served basis both to its
clients and to those of other online brokers that join its
electronic syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Lessin and Klein also say that, by reducing underwriting fees
and broadening the base of prospective customers, Wit's process
provides a better deal for corporations issuing stock.
</P>
<P>
   As Klein learned when he took Spring Street public, the Internet
can be used to identify buyers who are more likely to feel some
loyalty to the issuing company and view their purchase as a
long-term investment, as opposed to an opportunity to make a quick
buck by flipping the stock (reselling it quickly on the open
market). &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the long term, Wit's success will hinge to a large degree
on its ability to deliver as an e-manager. It received a major vote
of confidence in August when EarthWeb, the Internet-based
online-services provider, agreed to place Wit smack alongside
bulge-bracket underwriters J.P. Morgan and Bear Stearns as a
co-manager of its initial stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   To win many more such assignments, Wit still needs to persuade
other online brokerage firms to join its e-syndicate. As of
September 1, it had reached agreements with Quick &AMP; Reilly,
Suretrade, Datek Online, and Wall Street Access.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. and E*Trade may prove more difficult to
crack because they already offer customers at least some access to
IPOs through relationships with more traditional investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   An equally important test of Wit's business strategy is just
beginning as the company unveils its next, and by far its most
ambitious, project _ the Digital Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   The DSM is a sophisticated Internet-based trading system
designed to allow individual investors to negotiate directly with
one another and buy and sell stocks within listed bid-asked spreads
in much the same way that institutional investors have long been
able to do.
</P>
<P>
   The concept itself is simple. DSM lets investors call up an
order book that includes the official bid and asked prices, as well
as indications from other investors who want to buy or sell a given
number of shares at various price points in between. Investors can
accept one of the existing orders, enter a new order, or try to
negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   Wit modeled this system after the private
electronic-communications networks _ such as Instinct _ that
institutional investors, dealers, and market makers have long used
to trade stocks with one another.
</P>
<P>
   Investors should like the look and feel of the Digital Stock
Market, but a larger question is whether it will be able to attract
the order flow that markets need to run smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Atkin, president and CEO of Instinct, has seen other
technically advanced trading systems disappear into obscurity for
this very reason. ``Building the technology is only a quarter of
the battle,'' he says. Retail investors, says Atkin, want to know
that when it's time to sell there will be buyers ready and waiting.
</P>
<P>
   To provide that assurance, Wit, which has only 7,500
active-brokerage accounts of its own, is looking to broaden its
base of potential buyers and sellers by forming partnerships with
other firms.
</P>
<P>
   It is in talks with a number of electronic brokers, hoping to
entice them to use its Digital Stock Market by agreeing either to
split fees or to share equity stakes in the new market.
</P>
<P>
   One firm unlikely to participate: Datek Online, which already
operates a small-scale trading network for Nasdaq stocks, called
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Klein and Lessin have high hopes for the Digital Stock Market.
Even if it fails, they believe the paradigm shift that has already
begun in the capital-raising process is unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   As capitalists, they would like to cash in on this change as
well _ and perhaps if they succeed, they'll one day find their
story told in a book on sale downstairs at Strand. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Michael Peltz is WORTH's financial editor.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
