<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-KENTUCKY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE ON ITS GAME, DEFEATS EMOTIONALLY DRAINED KENTUCKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ A measure of Tennessee's determination to
cling fiercely to its top-dog status occurred early in the third
quarter yesterday, when the Volunteers rose up and stopped Kentucky
three times from the 1-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Vols were holding a 31-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats finally scored _ barely _ on fourth down, but it
was of little help. The Vols (10-0, 7-0) cruised almost
effortlessly to a 59-21 triumph before a crowd of 107,252 at
Neyland Stadium to strengthen their position as the No. 1 team in
the Bowl Championship Series standings and The Associated Press
poll.
</P>
<P>
   It was also their 14th consecutive victory over Kentucky (7-4,
4-4), and secured a berth in the Southeastern Conference title game
on Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had great concern for the Kentucky offense, but our defense
may have played its best game,'' Vols coach Phillip Fulmer said.
``Maybe our offense did, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the circumstances of the week had some effect. You
have to feel for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky coach Hal Mumme also referred to the tragic events of
last Sunday, when a truck driven by Wildcats center Jason Watts
overturned and Kentucky football player Arthur Steinmetz and
Eastern Kentucky student Scott Brock were killed. Watts, who is
hospitalized, has been charged with manslaughter because of his
blood alcohol content.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a week of emotions surrounded by tragedy,'' Mumme
said. ``There's no way to describe it. It's been sad, a week of sad
losses. We didn't play well, focused, or with emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   They did, however, play with a certain reckless abandon. On six
occasions, the Wildcats gambled on fourth down in their own
territory. They failed five times, presenting the Vols with an
added flurry of points on short drives.
</P>
<P>
   But the Vols, who rolled up 466 yards and scored on eight
consecutive possessions, scarcely needed help. Using a pressure
defense to contain Kentucky's high-octane air attack, they cruised
to a 38-7 halftime lead and coasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we wanted to do was put pressure on \RKentucky
QB\S Tim Couch,'' Fullmer said. ``We were sometimes blitzing an
extra linebacker, sometimes not _ but we wanted to hurry him and
keep him off balance. He's so good, you have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch (35 of 56, one interception) threw for 337 yards but was
sacked six times and rarely had an opportunity to throw downfield.
The Kentucky ground game, meanwhile, weighed in with 39 yards
rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee quarterback Tee Martin (13-20-0) threw for 189 yards
and ran for 63 more, directing a versatile Vols attack that
Kentucky's ``Black Flag'' defense couldn't handle.
</P>
<P>
   The Vols broke it open in the second period, when Martin fired a
55-yard pass to Cedrick Wilson to make it 21-7, followed quickly by
a 58-yard bolt from fullback Shawn Bryson that stretched the lead
to 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Kentucky shattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of pressure on them with the pass rush, and that
was a big difference,'' linebacker Chris Ramseur said. ``We knew
they had a second-string center in there, and we capitalized on
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked a little confused out there, but I guess you'd say
they all looked like they really didn't have that fire in their
eyes.'' Extra points The winner of the game is normally awarded
possession of the Beer Barrel, a large beer keg that has served as
the game's trophy since 1925. In the wake of the fatal,
alcohol-related accident Sunday, the barrel did not make an
appearance this year. ... Tennessee set a school record for season
attendance this year, drawing an average of 106,914 fans per game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
