<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KANSAS-STATE-MISSOURI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 2 KANSAS ST. OUTLASTS MISSOURI TO STAY UNBEATEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ Kansas State quarterback Michael Bishop did not
turn in a performance yesterday that is likely to cause any Heisman
Trophy voters to erase Texas' Ricky Williams from the top of their
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the Wildcats likely cause the Bowl Championship Series
computer to leap them past Tennessee or UCLA, both of whom won
convincingly yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But both Bishop and his team simply did what they have done for
19 consecutive games _ win.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop accounted for 261 yards of total offense and two
touchdowns as Kansas State held off Missouri's spirited bid for a
program-shaking upset and escaped packed Faurot Field with a 31-25
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, 11-0 and ranked No. 2 by The Associated Press, now
can sit back with their first-ever undefeated regular season and
await the Dec. 5 matchup in the Big 12 Championship against South
Division winner Texas A&AMP;M (10-1, 7-0), which yet must face
traditional foe Texas on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to be 11-0,'' Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It beats losing one, two or three,'' Wildcats coach Bill
Snyder said. ``I think it's a pretty special achievement for our
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of undefeated football teams in the country
and probably not a lot from year to year. So to be one of the very
exclusive group is something I appreciate for our players. They're
proud of it, and I am, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Between now and the league championship game, the BCS will
release two more sets of weekly rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've proved we're good enough to be 11-0 right now,''
Wildcats defensive end Joe Bob Clements said. ``It's hard to say
we're better than other teams because we haven't played them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I can say we're better than the 11 teams we've
played on the day we played them. It's up to other people to decide
where they want to put us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats did not assure themselves of a continuing place in
the debate until Missouri quarterback Corby Jones overthrew two
receivers running deep across the middle on a fourth-and-15 at the
Kansas State 42 with 1:15 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Jones won the statistical war with Bishop, accounting for 249
yards passing and 63 running. But he wasn't good enough for
Missouri (7-4, 5-3 Big 12).
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole week we were determined to come out and shock the
world,'' said Missouri wide receiver John Dausman. ``We almost did
it. But almost doesn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dausman, who is a backup, shocked a vaunted Kansas State
defense, ranked No. 2 nationally in pass efficiency, by catching
six passes for 169 yards. Included was a 20-yard touchdown pass
from Jones that closed the Tigers to 24-22 six seconds into the
fourth quarter. A two-point pass attempt _ necessitated because of
a missed kick after the second touchdown _ failed.
</P>
<P>
   But in a game of shifting momentum and big plays, Kansas State
responded. The Wildcats went 37 yards in eight plays after a short
punt. Frank Murphy scored after recovering his own fumble in the
end zone after losing the ball at the one with 8:28 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The best Missouri could do was a 29-yard field goal from Brian
Long with 5:49 to play after failing to get into the end zone from
first-and-goal at the 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our football team played an excellent game,'' Missouri coach
Larry Smith said. ``Kansas State is an excellent team, and it was
one of those games where you get a chance at the end. But it came
down to that, and we didn't have quite enough to get us in the end
zone one more time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
