<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS THROWING RIGHT PITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Fact: The Diamondbacks' .246 batting average was the
worst among the 30 major league clubs last season.
</P>
<P>
   Additional facts: Teams with seven of the top eight staff ERAs
in the National League had winning records. In the American League,
it was five of the top six with winning records.
</P>
<P>
   Another fact: Of the remaining 16 clubs, only two others (Texas
and the Chicago Cubs) managed to win more games than they lost.
</P>
<P>
   When the inaugural Diamondbacks season ended and the team had
lost 97 of its 162 games, finishing with the third-worst record in
the majors, managing general partner Jerry Colangelo, during a
state of the franchise summation, cited the importance of pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's not quite time to erect a statue of Colangelo for some
grand revelation, but at least it didn't take long for the big
cheese to discover what this ballclub needs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Colangelo began addressing the club's most pressing
need when he lured Todd Stottlemyre to the Valley. &QL; 
Braves have right idea &QL; 
Sure, it took 32 million reasons for Stottlemyre to decide to sign
his name on the bottom of a four-year contract. Whatever the
rationale, it's a move in the right direction for an organization
that seems hellbent on contending sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator among all successful clubs starts and
ends with its starting rotation. Say what you want about the
Atlanta Braves and the fact that they have only one World Series
championship to show for their run this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look below their postseason failures, and arguably the
best rotation in 30 years leaps out as the primary reason for the
Braves' success in the 1990s. Sheer muscle is impressive to look at
in the middle of July, but it gets you nowhere in October.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado had the best batting average and St. Louis hit the most
home runs in the NL. Players from each club watched the playoffs at
home. Seattle socked more home runs (234) than any club in the
majors. The Mariners barely managed to elude the AL West cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' AL-best batting average was supposed to be a major
concern and obstacle for the Yankees in the first round of the
playoffs. Yankees pitchers stopped the Rangers, who managed to
score one run in three games while batting .141.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pitching first, second and third that matters most,'' St.
Louis pitching coach Dave Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks recognize that the quickest way to contend is
by building a rotation worthy of striking fear into opponents.
Stottlemyre may seem like a .500 pitcher, but this is a guy who has
gained the reputation as a big game pitcher because of his passion
for winning.
</P>
<P>
   Is $32 million more than a pitcher with a 123-110 career record
should be receiving? Absolutely. But in an era where there is such
a premium on pitching, it's what the market bears that determines
salaries. Detroit had offered $28 million for four years for
Stottlemyre. St. Louis was willing to go as high as $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   If it took an extra $1 million per season to land a top pitcher,
then the Diamondbacks made the right decision. Throwing Stottlemyre
into the mix with Andy Benes and promising left-handers Brian
Anderson and Omar Daal gives Arizona an envious rotation. &QL; 
Confidence is key &QL; 
In baseball, it all comes down to the mental side of the game. The
separation of talent between the top players and the bottom-rung
players is basically small. Confidence plays a far bigger role in
this game than is generally recognized.
</P>
<P>
   When Atlanta's players take the field with Greg Maddux, Tom
Glavine or John Smoltz on the mound, they've mentally notched a
victory before the first pitch is thrown. Those pitchers combined
to win 59 percent of the games they started.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's top three starters _ Darryl Kile, Pedro Astacio and
Jamey Wright _ won 34 percent of their starts. Don't forget, the
Rockies' .291 average was the best in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   One final fact: Pitching wins ballgames, plain and simple. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-21-98 2314EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
