<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIBAULT HAPPY TO LEAVE MONTREAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing for the fabled Montreal Canadiens can be a lot like
following Pavarotti to the microphone at a karaoke bar. You're
constantly being compared to previous greatness, and if you can't
cut it, the fans and the media let you have it.
</P>
<P>
   Take goalie Jocelyn Thibault. He kept his opinions to himself
while he was in Montreal the past two-plus seasons, but he didn't
shy away from bashing the contemptuous atmosphere there after last
week's trade to the Chicago Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been living through some kind of hell. I feel like a free
man now,'' Thibault said. ``People eat hockey there. When they sit
down at breakfast, they talk hockey. When they sit down at lunch,
they talk hockey. When they sit down at dinner, they talk hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   It was doubly rough on Thibault, though, because he was the
goalie the Canadiens got in exchange for trading St. Patrick Roy to
Colorado in that unforgettable Dec. 6, 1995, trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get traded for a legend, they expect you to play like
a legend, even at 20 or 21,'' said Thibault, 23, who visits the
Valley on Tuesday. ``I did my best, but I guess it wasn't good
enough for the people there.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith, who scored the Stanley
Cup-winning goal for Montreal in 1986, knows what it can be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I was there when I was in my prime rather than at the
beginning of my career or at the end of it,'' Smith said. &QL; 
The magic bus
</P>
<P>
   A funny thing happened on the Detroit Red Wings' bus from
Calgary to Edmonton last week. As Coach Scotty Bowman stepped onto
the bus to leave the team hotel to the airport, a bellman came
running out with a note saying the team's charter flight had been
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the plane had been hit on the tarmac by a truck that
cleans toilets, ripping a huge hole in the fuselage. The Red Wings,
Bowman informed his team, would have to bus it all the way to
Edmonton _ a three-hour trip with the bus completely packed, one to
a seat.
</P>
<P>
   After losing six times in eight games, they responded with a
huge 6-2 win over the Oilers the next night, prompting associate
coach Dave Lewis to say, ``That bus trip was a great remedy. It was
just what the doctor ordered. We got back to basics, back to where
we came from. Back to our roots. It was like being back in
juniors.''
</P>
<P>
   No one actually saw the hole in the plane, of course, which
prompted the rumor: Did Bowman, the master motivator, cook up the
whole story and bribe the bellman? Sounds like something he might
pull. &QL; 
Rough boys
</P>
<P>
   If it seems there have been an alarming number of suspensions
and fines doled out this young season, there have. Colin Campbell,
the NHL's new director of hockey operations, has been a busy, busy
man handing out the discipline.
</P>
<P>
   After slapping Tampa Bay's Andrei Nazarov with a seven-game
suspension Thursday for cross-checking Colorado's Cam Russell in
the face, Campbell dished out 17 different fines and a total of 46
games in suspensions, including lost pay. Last year at this time,
the league had issued only nine fines and a total of six games to
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers will grow on Monday. That's when the Kings' Matt
Johnson has his hearing with Campbell in New York to discuss
Wednesday's ugly incident when Johnson knocked out the Rangers'
Jeff Beukeboom with a sucker punch _ a forearm shiver to the back
of the head. Expect him to get seven to 10 games, minimum. &QL; 
The real me
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver Canucks Coach Mike Keenan, who on Wednesday became
just the sixth head coach in NHL history to capture 500 career
wins, said his reputation as a no-nonsense, too-intense,
power-hungry, money-spending, player-bashing enigma is a
media-manufactured myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a label that will be with me for some time,'' he said.
``I know it's good copy, but people have a three-second exposure of
you and they think they know you. The image perpetuates itself, and
it isn't even true.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes forward Rick Tocchet played for Keenan in Philadelphia
and knows him well. He respects him, too. But listen to Tocchet
long enough, and at least part of ``Iron Mike's'' reputation seems
well deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's a great guy, but he's always been his own man,''
Tocchet said. ``Most coaches today _ I should say a lot of coaches
_ ask around and get a lot of advice before they do anything. Not
him. He makes a decision and runs with it, whether it's right or
wrong. He'll be the first guy to tell you he's made his share of
mistakes, but hey, his record speaks for itself.'' &QL; 
Goin' mobile
</P>
<P>
   In a span of only three weeks, 22-year-old forward Roman Vopat
found himself traded three times and playing for four different NHL
clubs. Los Angeles dealt him to Colorado, which moved him to
Chicago, which shipped him to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget, he originally was drafted by the St. Louis
Blues and played briefly for the Roadrunners after being traded to
the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' Vopat said of his recent wild ride. ``I
can't even say how I felt. I was 19 and thought I was going to stay
in L.A., but I got traded after two years. Soon as you get traded,
you get traded again? Three times in three weeks? That hurts.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
