<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS MAY HAVE TO CRAWL BACK TO YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The market for All-Star center fielder  &UR; Bernie Williams does not
appear to be anything near the feeding frenzy agent  &UR; Scott Boras
had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   With the news that Williams had turned down the Yankees' offer
for a five-year deal worth $60 million, the stark reality is that
Williams may find himself with no suitors.
</P>
<P>
   A list that started with Los Angeles, Colorado, Texas, Arizona,
Baltimore, Boston and the Yankees almost has dried up to the point
where Williams may find himself having to take far less money than
he envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   Boras insists that his client has a seven-year offer on the
table. If so, Williams better jump at it soon. The Diamondbacks
have not made an offer and have their eyes set on  &UR; Randy Johnson
over Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and Rockies went in different directions when they
signed center fielders of their own _  &UR; Devon White and  &UR; Darryl
Hamilton, respectively. Baltimore insists it will not make an offer
to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Boston and the Yankees, who have said the five-year,
$60 million offer is as high as they will go. Take away  &UR; Pedro
 &UR; Martinez's six-year, $75 million contract (which was more to cover
tracks for the departed  &UR; Roger Clemens) and history indicates the
Red Sox will not go as high as Boras and Williams would like.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, imagine being Williams and playing for the Red Sox
next season. Say Boston stumbles, which can happen considering the
career years they had from  &UR; Tim Wakefield and  &UR; Bret Saberhagen and
the loss of
 &UR; Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   If the Red Sox bumble their way to a sub-.500 record, whom will
the testy fans turn their anger towards? General Manager  &UR; Dan
Duquette will quietly hide in his perch high above Fenway Park
while Williams will be in center field every day, in the open for
all the booing to rain down on him.
</P>
<P>
   Williams should think again about that Yankees offer. Remember,
there's no place like home. &QL; 
Godzilla lives &QL; 
Japanese fans attending one of the seven games between All-Stars
from U.S. and Japanese leagues must have thought the fabled green
reptilian monster was attacking their shores again.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland Indians Manager  &UR; Mike Hargrove put out a lineup for
one of the games in which the starting lineup had combined for 349
home runs last season. The starters:  &UR; Andruw Jones (31),  &UR; Nomar
Garciaparra (35),
 &UR; Carlos Delgado (38),  &UR; Sammy Sosa (66),  &UR; Manny Ramirez (45),  &UR; Vinny
 &UR; Castilla (46),  &UR; Javier Lopez (34),  &UR; Jason Giambi (27) and  &UR; Damion
Easley (27). &QL; 
No Gambler here &QL; 
 &UR; Kenny Rogers, who two weeks ago exercised his right and demanded
that Oakland trade him, has changed his mind after learning that he
will not be eligible for free agency until 2002 if he is traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping we're able to work something out in a day or two
with Kenny so that he will return to Oakland next year,'' Athletics
General Manager  &UR; Billy Beane said. ``I think it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was 16-8 with a 3.17 ERA for the last-place A's. The
left-hander changed his mind once he discovered that Oakland was
not going to hold him to his 2000 option and he could file for free
agency after next season. &QL; 
Our kind of guy &QL; 
This is from a paid obituary that ran in both the ``Seattle Times''
and ``Seattle Post-Intelligencer'' last week. It reads, in part:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dick Upton, 71, from Seattle died on Veterans Day. He was a
knowledgeable and passionate baseball fan who enjoyed
second-guessing (Mariners GM)  &UR; Woody Woodward. He finally succumbed
quickly after hearing about the  &UR; Paul Spoljaric for  &UR; Mark Leiter
trade, which occurred just a few days earlier. He was quite a guy.
</P>
<P>
   He left his first wife to play on  &UR; Eddie Feigner's fast-pitch
softball champs; he drove the team bus for the Tri-City Atoms for
22 years before finding his niche in car rental business. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Guess they're happy where they  &UR; are: The Tampa Bay Devil Rays,
losers of 99 games in their inaugural season, have made exactly
zero trades since the four expansion draft day deals they made on
Nov. 18, 1997. By the way, every one else has made at least one
trade in that span.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finally, one for the Rocket: With four sons,  &UR; Roger
 &UR; Clemens had vowed to pass each one a Cy Young Award trophy. Now
that he has won his fifth, it seems he'll get to keep one for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Pepe Frias.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Honest, I pitch in the majors: Tampa Bay reliever
 &UR; Scott Aldred appeared in 48 games last season without recording a
victory, loss or save. The previous record for securing non-vital
stats belonged to  &UR; Mike Flanagan, who appeared in 42 games in 1992
without a decision or save. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Texas'  &UR; Rick Helling became only the second 20-game winner in the
past 20 years to receive no Cy Young Award votes. Helling joined
Kansas City's  &UR; Dennis Leonard, a 20-game winner in 1980 who was
shut out of the Cy Young balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati combined to go 6-26 against the NL's division
champions _ Atlanta, Houston and San Diego. Against the rest of the
league, the Reds were 71-59.
</P>
<P>
   If Cleveland is successful in signing free-agent second baseman
 &UR; Roberto Alomar, the Indians will have a combined 18 Gold Gloves up
the middle when you include catcher  &UR; Sandy Alomar, shortstop  &UR; Omar
Vizquel and center fielder  &UR; Kenny Lofton.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels are furious with the Dodgers, who want to
shorten their annual preseason Freeway Series from three games to
one in order to bring in the Yankees for a two-game series. The
Dodgers want the Angels to be a standby, just in case the Yankees
back out of the deal. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Now that  &UR; Ken Caminiti is officially gone, San Diego is turning its
attention toward  &UR; Robin Ventura, who would love to play for the
Padres. San Diego, of course, wants Ventura to come as cheaply as
possible, which, in current terms, would be no less than $8 million
per season.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets have discussed the possibility of trading for
Milwaukee All-Star second baseman  &UR; Fernando Vina, who nearly went
to Atlanta before the Braves got a better deal from Cincinnati two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs are taking a long look at third baseman  &UR; Sean
Berry, who became very available last week when Houston signed
 &UR; Caminiti. Berry hit .314 with 13 home runs for the Astros while
earning $1 million. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
