<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-SEASON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU CAN'T STOP LEAKS FROM HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - If an autopsy were performed on Arizona State's
season, the first thing uncovered would be a weak heart.
</P>
<P>
   There lies the key clue of how a team some fingered for the
Fiesta Bowl is in danger of its first losing season since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Others became evident: injuries, unrealistic expectations,
unfulfilled potential. But the glaring personality trait to arise
from ASU's 5-5 start is that it is a team that cracks under
adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever think it's been a question of this team caring or
wanting to win,'' ASU Coach Bruce Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Caring isn't always enough, and the 1998 Sun Devils appear to be
everything the 1996 team wasn't. That group found ways to win. This
team finds ways to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Never underestimate the right mix of personalities. ASU lacks
the leadership that players like Jake Plummer and Pat Tillman
brought, athletes who practically willed those around them to play
better.
</P>
<P>
   This team's shortcomings were apparent from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sun Devils played evenly with Washington during
much of the season opener, they collapsed down the stretch and were
unable to stop the Huskies on a fourth-and-17 play with less than a
minute remaining. Quarterback Brock Huard connected with tight end
Reggie Davis for a 63-yard scoring play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just found a way,'' Huard said afterward. ``Maybe we just
believed in ourselves more.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder acknowledged that it took days for the Sun Devils to
recover. They went up to Brigham Young following a poor week of
practice, and it showed. The offense managed just six points as ASU
lost by 20.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils beat North Texas, 34-15, in an uninspiring effort
and played better in defeating Oregon State, 24-3. But Snyder
admitted he still had concerns about the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not where we believe we can be,'' he said. ``We're
not putting together enough consistent efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the most telling statistic about ASU's emotional state is
that its losses always come in pairs. A defeat seems to wipe out
the team for a good seven days.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to Washington was followed by the humiliating defeat to
BYU. A loss to Southern California was followed by a humiliating
defeat to Notre Dame. This doesn't fare well for Friday's game
against Arizona, since the Sun Devils are coming off a loss to
Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ASU can only hope a bye week will negate that statistic.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder wasn't prepared for this personality trait, nor was he
prepared for what else came his way:
</P>
<P>
   Injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Every team faces them, but the Sun Devils continued to get
kicked where it counts.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback J.R. Redmond has been limited much of the season
because of toe and ankle problems. Quarterback Ryan Kealy is coming
off arthroscopic surgery on his right knee. And the secondary . . .
where do you start?
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils lost top reserve Courtney Hysaw during camp and
James Dunn early in the season. Starting strong safety Christon
Rance, who was beginning to grow comfortable in his role, missed
ASU's last two games because of a knee injury and will not play
against the Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Kyion Grayes has been suspended from the team, and a thigh
contusion has limited Courtney Palmore.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the Sun Devils' starting secondary,
primarily free safety Mitchell Freedman and cornerback J'Juan
Cherry, has been so banged up this year that it rarely practices.
That only hurts.
</P>
<P>
   ASU has several other players in those positions that hardly
play, suggesting that the Sun Devils need to do a better job in
evaluating numbers and talent while recruiting the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore jinx.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy had a tough act to follow _ his own _ considering his
standout freshman year, but his struggles this season have been a
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Having a team collapse around him may have been too much of a
burden for Kealy to bear. He admitted that he put too much pressure
on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped going out there and having fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unrealistic expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Having the national championship game in Sun Devil Stadium was
just too tantalizing for some.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder acknowledged that he had concerns about his team in the
preseason but was thrust into an awkward position: How do you say
you're not that good when everyone else says you are?
</P>
<P>
   ``There were things I saw,'' he said. ``But it's a difficult
situation when there is so much preseason attention your way.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder's biggest concerns were on defense. Junior college
transfers Junior Ioane and Erik Flowers have big-time potential,
but they didn't transfer until spring, and the coach feared their
development would take awhile.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Larry Johnson for academic reasons was going to hit
the linebacking unit hard.
</P>
<P>
   He was right on both accounts. But he probably never dreamed
just how costly it would be. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
