<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3352 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-NO-HUDDLE-A     11-21 1495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NO-HUDDLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS TOY WITH NO-HUDDLE OFFENSE  
 PLOY COULD HELP PLUMMER CURE 1ST-HALF BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Cardinals don't plan to ask Jake Plummer to
drop back and chuck the playbook into the Potomac River.
</P>
<P>
   They are not ready to scrap their offense for sandlot plays.
</P>
<P>
   They just want to run it quicker when they visit the Washington
Redskins this afternoon. About two quarters quicker.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for the Cardinals (5-5), who hope to go above the
.500 mark for good in their quest for an NFC wild-card playoff
spot, has been their lifeless first-half offense.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half of the past three games, they've been almost
unstoppable. Last week they outscored the Dallas Cowboys, 21-7, in
the second half as Plummer passed for 314 of his 465 yards using a
no-huddle attack. In the second half of the past three games,
Plummer is 44 of 66 for 606 yards, four touchdowns and no
interceptions after digging first-half holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could play the third quarter first,'' said wide
receiver Rob Moore. &QL; 
First-half fix? &QL; 
That gives rise to suspicion that the Cardinals might have found
the key to unlock their early-game woes. That and the fact that
they practiced the no-huddle all week. They've fed the rumor mill,
dropping hints that they will use it early in hopes of keeping the
Redskins' defense off-balance, in turn boosting their own
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Or it all could be a carefully crafted smoke screen, only a ruse
to give the Redskins one more thing to think about while preparing
on their practice field.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals might really be more intent on running the ball
down the middle of the Washington defense. After all, in a 29-27
comeback win over the Redskins in Sun Devil Stadium two weeks ago,
the Cardinals rushed for a season-high 187 yards, their most in 38
games. But then, Plummer set a club record by completing 15
straight passes after halftime in the comeback. He also passed for
a Cardinals rookie-record four touchdowns against the Redskins last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Boomer Esiason, not using a no-huddle but getting
the team in and out of the huddle fast and using a quick count,
dinked and dunked the Redskins for a Cardinals-record 522 passing
yards in an overtime win.
</P>
<P>
   If it turns out that the only huddle the Cardinals call this
week is the one to decide whether to use the no-huddle, that would
be great fun, according to Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Backup quarterback) Dave Brown put it perfectly when he said
the no-huddle is organized chaos,'' Plummer said. You're out there
running around. You know the plays. The defense is getting tired
because those guys are not even in their stance yet when you snap
the ball. They're waiting for their call to come in. You can create
some confusion, some panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun. It's a good mix-up if you're doing it well like we
had to last week.'' &QL; 
Bills benefited &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There certainly is precedent for playing no-huddle the entire
game. The Buffalo Bills in the early 1990s went to four straight
Super Bowls using it in their K-Gun Offense. The difference is the
Bills ran essentially a two-minute offense with minimum changes of
personnel packages. The Cardinals run their regular offense, making
changes in personnel groupings according to down-and-distance
situations.
</P>
<P>
   The K-Gun took the Bills to four straight Super Bowls, but they
didn't win any. That's important to note, said Cardinals backup
center Mike Devlin, who played for Buffalo during that era.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an offense that can help you beat average teams, but good
teams have enough depth to deal with it. That's what I thought,''
Devlin said. ``At Buffalo it was beautiful to see, beautiful to be
in it. The best thing is that by the third and fourth quarter,
except for the really good teams that could bring in waves and
waves of people, it wears down the pass rush to almost nothing. Not
many teams in the NFL are two or three deep now.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer is not yet to be confused with Bills quarterback Jim
Kelly, the trigger man of the K-Gun. Moore, Frank Sanders and Eric
Metcalf, however, arguably are as effective as Buffalo wide-outs
Don Beebe, Andre Reed and James Lofton. Surprising Cardinals tight
end Johnny McWilliams still isn't quite a Pete Metzelaars. And
running back Adrian Murrell, while capable of making more out of
little, isn't in a class with the Bills' Thurman Thomas. &QL; 
Good for Plummer &QL; 
Yet the no-huddle does seem to fit the skills and psyche of Plummer
and his offensive players. He is at his best when moving, whether a
designed rollout or a scramble. He could draw the plays in the
dirt, according to Anthony Munoz, a Hall of Fame offensive tackle
who now is an analyst for ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have a young quarterback as mobile as Jake that
can do so many things on the move, create plays, I think you need
to do a little more of that,'' Munoz said last week on KTAR-AM's
``620 Sportsline.'' ``You need to be on the cutting edge,
especially as specialized as defenses are adjusting to the
offensive personnel. I think this is a way to keep a defense off
balance. It was obvious the Cardinals were able to do that late in
the second half of the Dallas game. They were down, they didn't
have anything to lose, they said, `Let's go out and have fun.' Jake
put up some great numbers. They were one score from tying that
thing up and going to overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a matter of how you use it. There is a lot of
perception that it's a hurry-up offense. It's really a matter of
getting to the line, locking that defensive linemen into his
stance, looking it over, and giving Jake the opportunity to call
it. There are very few downsides. The pluses outweigh them. Jim
Kelly was very successful doing that. It needs to come back,
especially with what is going on with defenses now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin thinks that assessment is reasonable
but not necessarily an indication of what the Cardinals will do
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Jake has the ability to make plays when things
break down around him,'' Tobin said. ``I don't know that running a
no-huddle makes him more prone to making those kind of plays. He's
got the option when a play breaks down of scrambling and doing all
the things he's capable of doing whether the play was called in the
huddle or at the line of scrimmage. It's what happens after the
snap that's relevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The no-huddle helped us last week, but last week was a unique
situation. We were 28 points behind. Their defense probably played
a little different than if it was 7-0.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin faced Kelly and the K-Gun in the AFC while Tobin was
defensive coordinator at Indianapolis. He gained further insight
into the no-huddle after Ted Marchibroda, who was offensive
coordinator at Buffalo when the K-Gun was installed, moved over to
the Colts staff with Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot like the run-and-shoot, which is out of the league
right now, in that when you run it, usually yardage went up and
scoring went up,'' Tobin said. ``The flip side was the other team
scored more. When you have three-and-outs you use very little time
off the clock, which puts the other team's offense on the field
more than it normally would be.'' &QL; 
Team effort &QL; 
Plummer wouldn't necessarily be on his own to read the defense and
call a play at the line. With the radio receiver in his helmet,
offensive coordinator Marc Trestman, no stranger to the no-huddle
himself, still has input. The objectives would be moving quickly to
prevent the defense from making situational personnel adjustments
and simply tiring out the pass rushers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched Buffalo's success with it, and when I was at
Cleveland in 1989 we used it the final month of the season,''
Trestman said.
</P>
<P>
   When he was quarterbacks coach at Detroit last season, Trestman
picked the brain of Lions backup Frank Reich. As Kelly's backup for
the Bills, Reich came into an AFC wild-card playoff game against
Houston in 1992 facing a 35-3 deficit. He rallied the Bills to the
greatest comeback in NFL playoff history, a 41-38 win in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank gave me insight,'' Trestman said. ``Their no-huddle was
different than what we're doing here in that they stayed in the
same personnel grouping. If we continue to do it, when we do it,
we'll move personnel around and force defenses to turn over their
personnel, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Trestman acknowledges the no-huddle could be an effective tool
in engaging his offense earlier in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes the pace and flow of the game,'' Trestman said.
``It creates somewhat of an uncomfortable environment for the
defense. They're changing quicker. They've got to be alert to
personnel changes. We're all creatures of habit. When you take a
player out of his normal environment, you could create that
uncomfortable sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we feel we can change the pace of the game with the
no-huddle, we will.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
