<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3353 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONA-SEASON-AZ     11-21 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-SEASON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S UNDERRATED SHIP COMES IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON - Unknown in August. Undefeated in September. Unlikely
after a loss in October. Unbeaten since then.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Arizona, underrated until now.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats (10-1, 6-1 Pac-10 Conference) rank among college
football's biggest surprises. For evidence, you need look no
further than the national polls.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona started at No. 24 in the Associated Press preseason
poll. Today the Wildcats are No. 8, which, ironically, was Arizona
State's starting point.
</P>
<P>
   They've climbed 16 spots. Only No. 9 Arkansas has come further.
The Razorbacks weren't ranked at all in the hazy days of August.
</P>
<P>
   How did it happen?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, not even Arizona Coach Dick Tomey, could have guessed
that his 1998 team would arrive at this week with a chance to
become the school's first to win 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Cochise near Douglas, Tomey was searching for a few big
men. He talked about a committee approach to the defensive line. He
grew testy with skeptical questions about plans to use two
quarterbacks, Keith Smith and Ortege Jenkins. His leading running
back, Trung Canidate, didn't participate in camp because of an
injury.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Tomey walked off Cochise College's practice field,
looked at the faraway mountains and talked about the view's
``beautiful tapestry.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounded as if he were taking one last look at it all. His job
was on the line, and there were whispers about who would succeed
him. Mediocrity was predicted. The Wildcats figured to be a
crushing bore.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't, for a mix of reasons that includes luck,
unprecedented offensive creativity in the Tomey era, smarts at key
positions, gamesmanship and timing. In large part, the last of
those has made it all work. Except for 10 minutes at the end of a
55-28 loss to UCLA, Arizona's timing has been Swiss-clock perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is a key. If ASU's season-opening loss to
Washington was a knockout blow, Arizona's early games were tuneups
that allowed a talented young fighter to gain experience and
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats' first two games were on the road. But what a road.
This was college football's Club Med, with stops at Hawaii and
Stanford. But there were rocky moments.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii, still winless, actually threatened in the first half
before Arizona won, 27-6. A weak Stanford also made the Wildcats
look vulnerable in the early moments before succumbing, 31-14.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, each game provided hints of what was about to
happen. A sure sign of promise was the season's opening kickoff.
Chris McAlister returned it 100 yards for a touchdown. In a sense,
the Wildcats have never looked back since then.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister was one of the few certainties amid all the unknown.
The preseason All-American has lived up to the billing. In the
early games, Arizona was allowed to grow around the core of talent
that McAlister represents.
</P>
<P>
   With each game, it became evident that some of Arizona's skilled
offensive players had been either overlooked or forgotten. There
was Jeremy McDaniel, who didn't play last season because of
injuries and academic problems. He was almost impossible to stop in
the early going, and he is still one of Arizona's big-play artists.
He leads Pac-10 receivers in touchdowns with nine.
</P>
<P>
   By the time opponents remembered McDaniel was back, Dennis
Northcutt grew from a complementary receiver into a dangerous one
all unto himself. In addition to a spot among the league's top 10
receivers in total receptions and yardage, Northcutt is third in
the conference in all-purpose yardage with a 141.3 average.
</P>
<P>
   The Northcutt-McDaniel combi nation helped make a success of the
Smith-Jenkins rotation. They were consistently open for receptions,
regardless of who was throwing the pass. It could have been Ortege
Smith or Keith Jenkins, for all it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there was the emergence of a linebacker who caught
Tomey's attention at the end of last season's 7-5 finish. Then,
Marcus Bell had potential. In a 35-11 victory over Iowa on Sept.
19, he became a star with a jarring third-quarter hit of the
Hawkeyes quarterback. Today, Bell leads the Pac-10 in tackles with
10.7 a game.
</P>
<P>
   With McAlister in the secondary and Bell established at
linebacker, the evolution continued along the defensive front.
Tomey had known entities along the front in Daniel Greer and Joe
Tafoya. But during a defining 31-28 victory at Washington, he
discovered a player who had arrived in Tucson without credentials
as a high-profile prospect.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Keoni Fraser was playing high school football in
Hawaii. On Oct. 3 in Seattle, the freshman was made one defensive
stop after another in a gane that featured Jenkins' famous
game-winning flip into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Then and since, there have been Eli Wnek, Mike Robertson, Idris
Harroon and Ben Alualu. The committee is working beyond
expectations, if not belief. It was the key to six sacks, and
perhaps a 27-23 Arizona victory, last week at California.
</P>
<P>
   The flaw in Arizona's season has been the fourth-quarter
collapse against UCLA on Oct. 10. Yet, here again, there was good
timing. The Wildcats were able to recover the next Saturday at
Corvallis, Ore., with a 28-7 victory over a relatively weak Oregon
State.
</P>
<P>
   Then they were able to conduct midseason maneuvers against an
overmatched Northeast Louisiana. A 45-7 whipping over a former
Division II school was the perfect way to prepare for Oregon on
Halloween. The work paid off. Arizona was never better in a 38-3
whipping of the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   The last piece in the puzzle was Canidate, the junior from
Central High School who left no doubt a stress fracture in his left
foot had finally healed.
</P>
<P>
   Canidate broke loose for a 71-yard touchdown run against Oregon.
Since then, he has scored on runs of 75, 45 and 54 yards. His 6.3
yards per carry leads the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Canidate's explosive emergence has made anything look possible.
In Arizona time, almost everything has been. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
