r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-WOLF-AZR &LR;      11-21 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-WOLF-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM CAN'T AFFORD NOT TO DIAL WOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - There are weekends when they see each other on the
roof of Sun Devil Stadium. They might shake hands, they might share
a smile, but the conversation always starts and ends the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You in shape?'' Bob Ferguson, the personnel boss, asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Joe Wolf answers.
</P>
<P>
   And then Wolf, a Cardinal-in-waiting, an ex-employee who hasn't
lost the itch, spends another week waiting for the phone call that
never comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're banking on their starters staying healthy,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Vision. It always comes back to vision.
</P>
<P>
   So here are the Cardinals, clinging to the final playoff spot,
hoping to keep their season afloat, on the road for the next two
weeks, sniffing the postseason for the first time since arriving in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   And here are the Cardinals, sitting on their hands, reacting
with crossed fingers and a tenuous wish that their depleted
offensive line can stay healthy for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's been a long time, and the Cardinals may not fully
grasp what they're chasing. But this is not how to embrace a
playoff push.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six quarters, the much-maligned offensive line
finally has stood up to the criticism. In the past six quarters,
the offense has scored 50 points. Together, they have delivered
overdue compensation to their friends on defense.
</P>
<P>
   But now there are bumps in the road. Bumps threatening to expand
and swallow the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Graham awoke with fluid in his left knee this week. Chris
Dishman is two weeks removed from a strained neck injury. Lomas
Brown is 35 years old. Lester Holmes has been inconsistent. James
Dexter is fine.
</P>
<P>
   They all will play today, and the coaching staff will pray for
the best. Because Anthony Clement, the rookie who could've made a
difference, is gone for the season. Because Matt Joyce, the first
backup at both tackle and guard, will miss at least two weeks with
a broken hand.
</P>
<P>
   One injury, and the postseason might rely on Jerome Daniels or
Mike Devlin or Jon Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Feel good about that?
</P>
<P>
   Last season in Dallas, Brown was injured during warm-ups. The
Cardinals turned to Wolf, who was more than adequate as a
substitute left tackle. In his NFL career, he has played every
position on the offensive line except center. He says he's in
shape, and after attending training camp in Flagstaff, he already
knows the framework of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``All season, I've been lifting, running, the whole works,''
Wolf said. ``The only thing I'm missing is the contact. As for
learning the offense, it would take maybe two nights to look at.
We're not talking rocket science here.''
</P>
<P>
   But we are talking another dent in the payroll. A whopping
$120,000 for the rest of the season. For a team that is $3 million
under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes it odd,'' Wolf said. ``If they weren't in
the running, like last year, you'd understand them playing the guys
they have to see if they can play or not. But when you're in a
playoff run for the first time ever in the Valley, you think they'd
do something. You think they'd want to be covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if one of the starters goes down, Wolf's phone will
be ringing off the hook. Or in the words of Vince Tobin, you don't
make decisions until you're forced to make decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Why not act now? Why not plan for disaster?
</P>
<P>
   Vision. It always comes back to vision.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins are on a roll, a Joe Nedney field goal removed from
a three-game winning streak, a team that has won its past two home
games by a combined score of 49-17. Beating the embarrassed Chiefs
in two weeks at Arrowhead Stadium is a tall order. And in three
weeks, a man who knows how to dismantle the Cardinals like no other
_ former assistant coach Jim Fassel _ brings the Giants to Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   This will not be easy. This is no time to just hope for the
best.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Wolf would cost $20,000 a game for the next six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals would rather throw pennies in a wishing well. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
