</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEYTON'S PLACE: AMONG TOP ROOKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Peyton Manning still makes silly mistakes that a $48 million
quarterback can't make.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Indianapolis Colts rookie has thrown 20
interceptions, an NFL high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to myself, `I can't throw that again. I can't throw that
pass that late,' '' Manning said.
</P>
<P>
   He has become a good listener.
</P>
<P>
   Ten games into the season, Manning, the first pick overall in
the 1998 draft, already has tied a league rookie record with
touchdown passes in seven consecutive games. He has thrown for 11
scores in the past five games.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, the 6-foot-5, 230-pounder from Tennessee, holds team
rookie records for completions (209) and yards (2,289) and is on
pace to finish with 3,662 yards, which would be an NFL rookie mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you've heard about the guy, his work ethic, his
character, his intelligence, his ability, his leadership . . . he's
better than you heard,'' Coach  &UR; Jim Mora said. ``He reminds me of a
throwback guy. No ego. Tough. Wants to win. Competes. If you put a
pair of black high-top football shoes on him like  &UR; Johnny Unitas
used to wear, he'd look pretty comfortable in them.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Manning threw three touchdown passes and drove the
Colts 80 yards in the final minutes to beat the New York Jets,
24-23.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the Colts' second victory, but it signaled Manning's
coming of age.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems a lot more relaxed, confident, poised and calm,
especially in critical situations,'' Mora said. ``He has that
mental and emotional makeup that serves him well in tough
situations. I think this will be a big boost for his confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, San Diego Chargers rookie quarterback  &UR; Ryan Leaf sits
on the bench, demoted for his two touchdowns and 13 interceptions
and his behavior off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, who has 15 touchdown passes, doesn't think sitting and
watching would have served any purpose for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the best way to learn is to make mistakes,'' he
said. ``You come into the league with high expectations of how fast
defenses are, how complex defenses are. But you have to face live
bullets to find out just how fast the free safety is, that you put
too much arm on that pass to get it by him. You say to yourself,
`You can't float the ball. Drive that ball.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it can be tough, and (losing) is all new to me. I was
34-5 in three years as a starter in high school. I lost only six in
college. I had a lot of negative experiences early this season.
Sometimes it can get you down. Your confidence could get down, and
you never get over it. But I've just kept working and believing
that good things would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   How much has Manning improved? He has learned to get rid of the
ball and has been sacked only twice in the past six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games started off at 100 mph for me,'' he said. ``Now it's
about 75 mph.  &UR; Steve Young,
 &UR; Brett Favre, John Elway are probably at 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to play. That's the only way you get better. I'm not
using this year as a crutch or a waiting period to get to next
year.'' &QL; 
Silent protest &QL; 
``Cincinnati Enquirer'' columnist  &UR; Paul Daugherty has a suggestion
for frustrated Bengals fans, tired of having the AFC's worst record
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   He said fans should take their protest beyond renting a
helicopter to fly over the practice field and asking for the
dismissal of team owner  &UR; Mike Brown, Coach  &UR; Bruce Coslet and
offensive coordinator  &UR; Ken Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Daugherty suggested that the fans boycott today's game between
the Bengals (2-8) and the Baltimore Ravens (3-7).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an inarguable sanity to it,'' Daugherty wrote. ``It's
the same sanity that says if you don't want a headache, then stop
banging your head against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile,  &UR; Paul Justin, the former Arizona State and Rattlers
player, will be the team's fourth starter at quarterback in the
past 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   Justin, 30, has leapfrogged from third string to first past
 &UR; Neil O'Donnell and  &UR; Jeff Blake.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've shown up to this point, most of the time, is not
the Cincinnati Bengals,'' Justin said. ``Hopefully, we can turn it
around this week. But I don't put any extra pressure on me. I
learned a long time ago it doesn't do any good.'' &QL; 
Memories linger &QL; 
The Patriots are moving out of the worst stadium in the NFL,
Foxboro Stadium, formerly known as Schaefer Stadium and Sullivan
Stadium, to a $350 million facility in Hartford, Conn., in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping that the first time it snows there, the Patriots
don't find an ex-con to climb aboard a snowplow and clear the way
for a game-winning field goal try.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens at Foxboro Stadium the next two
seasons, the place always will be known for  &UR; Mark Henderson, on
leave from prison, driving his snowplow onto the field 15 years ago
to give kicker  &UR; John Smith a better chance to beat the Dolphins,
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, former Dolphins Coach  &UR; Don Shula won't refer to
then-Patriots Coach  &UR; Ron Meyer by name because of that play.
</P>
<P>
   Shula remembers another game in Foxboro for the ``funny smell''
in the room where he held his post-game news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it was turpentine or paint thinner,'' Shula said.
``They had us in a broom closet for the press conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, the lights went out as  &UR; Adam Vinatieri was
about to kick a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right before we kicked,'' Vinatieri said. ``I had taken
my steps back and everything. I gave (holder  &UR; Tom Tupa) the nod,
and Tom turned and was set to say, `Set,' and bam, the lights went
out. Fifteen minutes went by. I went to the sideline, put my jacket
on and everything. It was weird.'' &QL; 
Breakout game? &QL; 
When Minnesota beat Green Bay earlier this season, Vikings rookie
 &UR; Randy Moss had five catches for 190 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next four weeks, he had only 10 receptions for 136
yards and no scores.
</P>
<P>
   He rebounded to catch four passes for 99 yards and a score in
last week's victory over the Bengals. In fact, he celebrated the
touchdown by leaping so high into the stands that his knees wound
up on top of the restraining wall at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nothing,'' said Moss, who will renew his rivalry with
the Packers today at Minneapolis. ``That's all expected.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't found too many NFL defensive backs he respects.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Bengals secondary, Moss said, ``They didn't do
nothing. It's the same week after week. . . . They were poor, as
usual.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)PNI.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
