r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAYING-STREAK-LADN     11-21 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAYING-STREAK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA MONICA SEES SEVENTH SLAYING IN SIX WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. -- A man was shot to death on a street near
a Santa Monica park early Saturday morning, marking the city's
seventh homicide in six weeks, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gary Gallinot of the Santa Monica Police Department said the
victim, who appeared to be in his mid-30s, still hasn't been
identified. He was shot once in the torso at 2:15 a.m. and died at
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinot said another man, 36-year-old Terry Holt, was seen by
witnesses fleeing from a car that police saw speeding away from the
crime scene. Holt was questioned by police and later arrested on a
no-bail parole violation unrelated to the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinot said the latest shooting doesn't appear to be related
to any of the six other killings. Investigators also said the
shooting did not appear to be gang-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate we've had so much at one time,'' Gallinot
said. ``We're actively pursuing each and every one of these
investigations. We're doing everything we can to apprehend the
responsible parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Saturday's shooting occurred in the 2000 block of
Virginia Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   A Santa Monica police officer was patrolling Virginia Avenue
Park when he heard gunshots. The officer pursued a car speeding
away from the scene, and a man found near the vehicle was detained
for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Gallinot said police don't know if the man was involved in the
shooting and aren't sure what the motive was.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Monica recorded only one homicide in 1997. At least four
of the slayings this year are believed to be gang-related.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, crime is at the lowest level it's been since the
1960s in Santa Monica,'' Gallinot said. ``However, we have seen
seven homicides in the last six weeks. We live in an urbanized
society surrounded by one of the largest metropolitan areas in the
country. Crime does occur.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing spree began Oct. 12 when Omar Sevilla, a 22-year-old
gang member from suburban Culver City, was shot. About two hours
later, Horst Fietze, a German tourist on vacation with his wife,
was killed during a street holdup.
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, gang member Juan Campos, 28, was shot to death
in a Santa Monica liquor store.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 27, Michael Juarez, 27, and his brother Anthony, 18 from
San Luis Obispo County to the north, were killed at a clothing
store their cousin, a former Santa Monica gang member, had recently
opened.
</P>
<P>
   And on Nov. 1, police arrested a transient suspected of killing
another transient, Jim Henders, 28, on the beach near Ocean Park
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
