<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3360 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU/UA-HUSKIES-AZ     11-21 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU/UA-HUSKIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON GAMES PROVING GROUNDS FOR UA, ASU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 and NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A flip and a strip.
</P>
<P>
   Although both plays took a matter of seconds, they made dramatic
impacts on the direction of Arizona's and Arizona State's seasons.
And both were game-ending plays against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   One worked, one didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats vaulted into the national spotlight with Ortege
Jenkins' game-winning flip into the end zone at Seattle's Husky
Stadium on Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils fell out of the national championship race when
Huskies quarterback Brock Huard hit tight end Reggie Davis with a
63-yard game-winning pass with 28 seconds remaining in the season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Mitchell Freedman, who had been one of ASU's most
reliable defensive players, tried to strip the ball from Davis _
who had gotten past Phillip Brown _ instead of tackling him and
possibly holding Washington to a field goal. He failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss wasn't the absolute difference in our season,'' ASU
Coach Bruce Snyder said, ``but I think it may have impacted how the
team subsequently handled itself in big game situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats-Huskies game will be remembered for one play that
Arizona Coach Dick Tomey says has defined his team.
</P>
<P>
   Before kickoff, Arizona had a 4-0 record that was built on a
soft start to a 12-game schedule. Tomey wasn't certain about his
team. Was it tough enough?
</P>
<P>
   Tomey learned it was with Jenkins' heroic play and all the big
ones that preceded his somersault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turning point came with the mind-set we showed at
Washington,'' Tomey said. ``OJ's play was the key, but we showed
real persistence throughout that game. There were injuries. We gave
up a touchdown off a fumble within the opening minute. But we kept
coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' acrobatic move has been played and replayed. The
Highlight Hall of Fame is the next stop.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the play is described as a 9-yard run with four
seconds left in a 31-28 Arizona victory. But the numbers do a
disservice. It was so much more in so many different ways.
</P>
<P>
   First, the play itself:
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins took the snap and dropped back to about the 20-yard
line. He looked for receiver Dennis Northcutt or tight end Mike
Lucky. Both were covered. Jenkins then took off. He ran straight
ahead and, at about the 4-yard line, leaped head over heels. It
appeared that three Washington defenders tipped his feet just
enough to allow him to do a full 360-degree flip. He landed like
that other Tucson gymnast, Kerri Strug.
</P>
<P>
   If he hadn't landed in the end zone, Jenkins could have
continued running. That's how good his balance was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used my basketball skills to jump over those guys,'' said
Jenkins, a reserve guard on the Wildcats 1997 national championship
team.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a 55-28 loss to UCLA, the No. 8 Wildcats have been
jumping up the national polls ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's heartbreaking defeat seemed to sap the life out of the Sun
Devils.
</P>
<P>
   They looked flat in the following week's 26-6 loss at Brigham
Young and unimpressive in a win over North Texas on Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder noticed right away something was wrong with his team
after the Washington defeat at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not overcome the hangover until midweek,'' he said.
``It's the bounce in their step. I can taste it, smell it. And it's
not the third-string guys. It's the ``players.''''
</P>
<P>
   ASU dropped from No. 6 to 14 in the Associated Press poll after
the game. It wouldn't be long before they were out of the polls for
good.
</P>
<P>
   It was a heartbreaking defeat because the offense had clicked
against Washington. Quarterback Ryan Kealy passed for 302 yards and
three touchdowns and didn't throw an interception. In many ways,
the Sun Devils outplayed the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Until the end. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
