<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981121.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-21 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3383 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-RICE-HNS &LR;      11-21 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-RICE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Late miscue bursts Rice's bubble
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. _ For the third time in three years, the
Rice Owls were poised on the precipice, playing in a game with
championship implications in November. Win and they are in; lose
and they fall out of consideration.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the other key games in 1996 (a 49-0 loss at BYU) and
1997 (a 31-14 loss at Utah), the Owls had Saturday's game at No. 20
Air Force in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Rice held a two-point lead with less than nine minutes remaining
and long-suffering Rice fans were starting to become wide-eyed with
anticipation. But Air Force linebacker Mike Tyler stepped in front
of a Chad Richardson pass, ran down the left sideline and scored on
a 26-yard interception return with 8:27 left. The run for PAT was
successful and Air Force held on for a 22-16 victory before 47,647
at Falcon Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler had torn the anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee
this year and must have surgery after the season. He also had
hyperextended the knee two series before his game-deciding play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to beg the trainers to let me back in the game,'' Tyler
said. ``I knew somebody had to make a big play for us. It's been
that way all season, and I guess it was my turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler and safety Charlton Warren thought a slant pass to wide
receiver Jason Blackwell was coming _ which had been successful in
the first quarter _ and faked a blitz before dropping into
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force won the Western Athletic Conference Mountain Division
by beating Rice, and will play Pacific Division champion BYU on
Dec. 5 in Las Vegas in the WAC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   To add insult to injury, the Owls would have gone to the WAC
title game with a win because Tulsa upset Wyoming 35-0, which would
have given Rice the necessary tiebreakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a kick in the gut to hear that (Tulsa) score,''
said Rice offensive guard Charles Torello.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force coach Fisher DeBerry said he used film as motivation
to get his team ready for the Owls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed our team a movie (Saturday) morning,'' DeBerry said.
``It was the league's advertisement for the WAC playoff game. And
Air Force wasn't even in it. So that shows you nobody in the WAC
expected us to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice players were philosophical abou tthe outcome, refusing to
blame anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hold Chad accountable for us losing the game,''
Torello said. ``We had numerous opportunities to win the game. It
wasn't Chad Richardson's fault. I firmly believe that. We didn't
take care of business so there is nothing we can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The game started well for Rice, as the Owls took the opening
kickoff and drove 76 yards on 16 plays before fullback Jamie Tyler
scored on a fourth-and-one for a 7-0 lead. The drive took 9:15,
which was the longest drive for Rice in coach Ken Hatfield's five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rice held Air Force on its initial possession, one in which
quarterback Blane Morgan suffered a left ankle injury. Doctors said
he suffered a third-degree medial sprain and is doubtful for the
Dec. 5 game. Backup Cale Bonds replaced Morgan and struggled at
first.
</P>
<P>
   On their second series, the Owls drove from their 20 to the Air
Force 12 before Derek Crabtree kicked a 27-yard field goal for a
10-0 lead to silence the Air Force crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons changed the tenor of the game, as they drove 93
yards on 18 plays to score on a one-yard run by fullback Spanky
Gillam to draw to within 10-7 with 1:08 remaining in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force took the lead in the third quarter on a four-yard
touchdown run by Bonds. The 11-play drive was aided by a 15-yard
roughing-the-passer penalty on Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was a (bad) call,'' Rice linebacker Rashad
Reynolds said. ``But they capitalized off of it. Bonds also did
well. Morgan was out, but they still had the same blockers in
there, and I thought their blockers did a great job. Bonds kept his
poise and stayed in the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice trimmed the deficit to 14-13 on a 40-yard field goal by
Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   Owls defensive back LonDee Smith then intercepted a Bonds pass
at the Rice 48 to stop an Air Force drive. Rice capitalized by
driving to the Falcons' 23 before Crabtree added a career-long
41-yard field goal for a 16-14 lead with 12:19 remaining in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Tyler's subsequent interception brought a painful end
to the Owls' season.
</P>
<P>
   Rice had other opportunities in the game, as Richardson
overthrew a wide-open Leroy Bradley streaking down the right
sideline, and cornerback Adrian Sadler dropped a would-be
interception that hit him in the hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been that kind of year,'' said Hatfield of his Owls
(5-6). ``Nobody gave us a chance; we were 21-point underdogs
against Air Force. We took the opening drive and scored. We did
some things. But we made one bad play to let them back in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But without Chad's throwing early, we wouldn't have been where
we were. We've been one play away all year long _ except for the
Texas game _ but no team plays harder than us. No one. It's just
been that kind of year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
